<HEADLINE>
FORD IS SAID TO BE BETTER; BUSH ALLOWED IN FOR VISIT
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for final rewrite. Note byline change.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Former President Gerald R. Ford's doctors said
Thursday that they were ``very pleased'' with his medical progress
since he was admitted to Hahnemann University Hospital on Wednesday
because of a stroke, and they expressed confidence that he would
make a full recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's doing much better,'' Dr. Robert J.
Schwartzman, the hospital's chief neurologist, reported at a midday
briefing. ``He's walking, his balance is better, his left hand has
returned to normal. He's still having some problems with his tongue
and a little bit of slurred speech, but he's in good spirits and
doing much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford was making such good progress that hospital officials
permitted Gov. George W. Bush of Texas to visit him for 20 minutes
shortly before noon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked great, sounded good,'' Bush said as he left the
hospital to prepare for his speech on Thursday night accepting the
presidential nomination at the Republican National Convention. ``He
told me to practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, 87, was in Philadelphia to attend the convention when he
became ill. He first went to Hahnemann Hospital around midnight on
Tuesday, shortly after receiving a warm reception from delegates in
the convention hall. After walking in on his own at the hospital,
he told doctors he was suffering acute facial pain. He was told he
probably had a bad sinus infection and was given some antibiotics
and released.
</P>
<P>
   But after a sleepless night, Ford returned to the hospital at
about 9 a.m. Wednesday, again walking in on his own. The symptoms
were worse, he told doctors, and besides pain included dizziness,
numbness and an inability to speak without slurring words.
</P>
<P>
   Tests indicated that he had suffered at least one mild stroke
since the weekend in the rear portion of the brain that controls
basic functions like balance, speech and swallowing. He was
admitted to the neurological intensive care unit and given a blood
thinner that breaks up the kinds of blockages that often form to
cause strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials insisted Thursday, as on Wednesday, that they
had made no serious medical error late Tuesday when they told Ford
that his facial pain had probably been caused by a sinus infection.
They said they saw nothing that indicated any cause other than
that, and they reported that Ford had said that all he needed was
pain medicine, not hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was treated appropriately and discharged as per his
wishes,'' said Dr. Wayne Satz, the head of Hahnemann's emergency
room.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's spokesman, Calvin McDowell, added what appeared to be
another important detail regarding Ford's initial visit. He said
that just before discharging Ford, hospital officials advised him
to undergo a head scan, but that he declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The activities that evening were totally controlled by the
president,'' McDowell said, adding that the Ford family had no
complaints about the hospital's care of the former president and
considered it ``nothing but fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   If Ford continues to make good progress, hospital officials said
late Thursday, he might be released in about five days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
