<HEADER>
A2430 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-GOP-CONVENTION-SPI &LR;      08-04 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONVENTION-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ACCEPTS GOP NOMINATION; VOWS NEW LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The torch was passed to a new generation of
Bushes on Thursday night as Texas Gov. George W. Bush, son of a man
who was in the White House eight years ago, accepted the Republican
presidential nomination and promised to ``use these good times for
great goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the Clinton-Gore administration has ``coasted through
prosperity'' and ``squandered'' opportunity abroad with ``a steady
erosion of American power and an unsteady exercise of American
influence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current president embodied the potential of a
generation,'' he declared. ``So many talents. So much charm. Such
great skill. But, in the end, to what end? So much promise, to no
great purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had their chance. They have not led. We will,'' Bush
said, a phrase that evoked roars each of the three times he
repeated it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush presented an agenda dominated by four promises: Rebuilding
America's military strength; reforming Social Security by allowing
some payroll taxes to go for ``sound responsible investments'';
reducing income taxes ``for everyone, in every bracket,'' as well
as abolishing the inheritance tax; and holding educators
accountable by applying standards for schools that receive federal
dollars. If public schools don't perform, parents would be given
vouchers with which they could send children to private schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grant me a mandate, and I will use it!'' Bush declared.
</P>
<P>
   Bush drove home what has been an orchestrated theme of this
week's Republican National Convention, that a conservative party
often identified with wealth has become, in the GOP nominee's
words, ``the party of idealism and inclusion.'' Pennsylvania Gov.
Tom Ridge, in introducing Bush, went so far as to talk of a ``new
Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly with its stress on education, the Bush agenda is
also designed to entice swing voters _ suburbanites,
upper-middle-class women and Hispanics in particular _ back into
the Republican fold after voting for Clinton in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education is OUR issue,'' Texas state Sen. Florence Shapiro
declared Thursday at a luncheon honoring the nominee's wife. Laura
Bush pledged that early childhood education, preschool development
and family reading will be her top priority if she becomes first
lady.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats argued that the GOP nominee's program puts emphasis in
the wrong place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can test kids all we want, but unless class sizes are
workable and the learning environment is safe, there will be no
gains to measure,'' Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., said Thursday
night. Murray is chief Senate sponsor of the Clinton
administration's plan to put 100,000 new teachers in America's
schools.
</P>
<P>
   But the upbeat Bush counterpunched against criticism already
coming from his foe. He heaped scorn on Vice President Al Gore's
``risky scheme'' rhetoric _ used to describe Bush's Social Security
plan _ without mentioning his opponent's name. He lampooned a Gore
blooper in which the vice president claimed to have invented the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my opponent had been there at the moon launch, it would
have been a `risky rocket scheme','' Bush said to rising audience
laughter. ``If he'd been there when Edison was testing the light
bulb, it would have been a `risky anti-candle scheme.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And if he'd been there when the Internet was invented, well .
. .'', Bush added.
</P>
<P>
   The hall rocked. At the relentlessly positive GOP convention,
only Bush and vice presidential nominee Dick Cheney were allowed to
unleash delegates' pent-up dislike of the Democrats in the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ``now leads the party of Franklin Delano Roosevelt, but the
only thing he has to offer is fear itself,'' Bush added. ``That
outlook is typical of many in Washington _ always seeing the tunnel
at the end of the light.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Texas oilman, who experienced ups and downs in
business before his success in politics, traced his optimism back
to the dusty town in which he was raised and returned after an
education at his father's alma maters, Andover and Yale.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Midland, Texas, where I grew up, the town motto was `the
sky is the limit' . . . and we believed it. There was a restless
energy, a basic conviction that, with hard work, anybody could
succeed, and everybody deserved a chance. ... Neighbors helped each
other. There were dry wells and sandstorms to keep you humble, and
lifelong friends to take your side, and churches to remind us that
every soul is equal in value and equal in need.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush concluded a four-day, feel-good convention at which the
conservatism of GOP faithful was muted by confidence that American
voters will restore Republican control of a White House that is
rightfully theirs.
</P>
<P>
   The Bushes showed that they have supplanted the Kennedys as
America's closest equivalent to a royal ruling family.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Bush and his wife Barbara sat in the galleries
surrounded by three generations. The elder Bush saluted his son.
Candidate Bush described his father as ``the last president of a
great generation'' and added: ``Dad, I am proud to be your son.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida Gov. Jeb Bush announced the votes of the Sunshine State
GOP delegation for his brother's candidacy. And Jeb's son,
24-year-old George P. Bush, whose mother is Mexican American, spoke
to the convention in both Spanish and English.
</P>
<P>
   While talking about poor children and ``poverty schools'' to
show his compassion, Bush also used his acceptance speech to
underscore his strong conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   He delivered a carefully worded affirmation of Republicans'
opposition to abortion, emphasizing elements of the pro-life agenda
that win majority support in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will lead our nation toward a culture that values life _ the
life of the elderly and the sick, the life of the young and the
life of the unborn,'' Bush proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know good people disagree on this issue, but surely we can
agree on ways to value life by promoting adoption and parental
notification, and when Congress sends me a bill againt
partial-birth abortion, I will sign it into law.''
</P>
<P>
   The promise was greeted by a 25-second ovation, the longest of
Bush's speech.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates also roared approval at Bush's promise to fulfill
a dream of Ronald Reagan's _ space defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the earliest possible date, my administration will deploy
missile defenses to guard against attack and blackmail,'' Bush
pledged.
</P>
<P>
   He implied that he is willing to scrap the 1972 U.S.-Soviet
anti-ballistic missile treaty. ``Now is the time not to defend
outdated treaties, but to defend the American people,'' Bush said.
Ex-Secretary of State Henry Kissinger, an architect of the treaty,
applauded in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Bush made some promises to low-income Americans. He promised to
lower the bottom income tax bracket from 15 percent to 10 percent,
and pledged to give low-income Americans tax credits to buy private
health insurance ``they need and deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Other issues got but a brief mention.
</P>
<P>
   The environment merited two sentences. Bush, who has taken fire
for air pollution in his home state of Texas, said corporations are
responsible ``to leave the air and waters clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, a longtime champion of firearms owners' rights, pledged he
would ``protect our children'' by ``strictly enforcing our gun
laws.'' He pledged no new initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seemed to be saying that many of the nation's problems can
be solved by uplifting its spirit. ``An era of tarnished ideals is
giving way to a responsibility era,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans live on the sunrise side of the mountain. The night
is passing. And we are ready for the day to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
