<SLUG> BC-DIRTY-BEACHES-LADN </SLUG>
 
SHORELINE POLLUTION ON THE RISE IN L.A. COUNTY BEACHES &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIK NELSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Despite Los Angeles' $28 million effort to stop
beach pollution, a national environmental group has found that
county beach closures tripled last year, with the worst problems in
Santa Monica and Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The Natural Resources Defense Council on Thursday singled out
the Regional Water Quality Control Board for violating the Clean
Water Act and has filed an administrative petition with the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency to force the local agency to clean
up its act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clean Water Act's been on the books for 30 years, and we
still have hundreds of beach closures and advisories,'' said David
Beckman, a senior attorney with the environmental group, who
attributed the beach closures to stormwater runoff high in
bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism accompanied the NRDC's release of ``Testing the
Waters: A Guide to Water Quality at Vacation Beaches.'' The
166-page report found that California had the largest number of
beach closures and health advisories in the nation, with 3,547 in
1999, up from 3,273 the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   During the same two years, Los Angeles County health officials
issued 460 advisories and closures, up from only 147 in 1998. Long
Beach had the most such incidents with 71, followed by Santa Monica
State Beach with 27 closures and advisories in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Beckman said the additional closures and advisories have more to
do with increased monitoring under California's right-to-know law
than it does higher bacterial counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the more you look at it, the more you find
it,'' Beckman said.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County didn't have the most closures in 1999. That
distinction went, for the second year in a row, to Santa Barbara
County, which had 1,392 closures and advisories.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring Ventura County had 257 closures, up from 237 in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Beckman acknowledged that the city, county and water board are
spending millions of dollars to divert Los Angeles stormwater
runoff into sewers for treatment during dry months, but said such
measures were but a ``Band-Aid'' that doesn't address the causes of
urban runoff.
</P>
<P>
   That was evident in the health advisories and closure orders
issued by Los Angeles County health officials for beaches in Santa
Monica and Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't divert it during the winter because the sewage
treatment plants would be overwhelmed; they're already at
capacity,'' said Steve Fleischli, executive director of Santa
Monica Baykeeper, an environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the NRDC filed an administrative petition with the
U.S. EPA to compel the water board to enforce runoff rules. Beckman
said action on the petition, which is being considered by federal
officials, could take years.
</P>
<P>
   But Dennis Dickerson, the water board's executive officer, said
the agency has been short-staffed, but is now anticipating enough
state funding for 15 new inspectors to step up enforcement. The new
positions will come from a $5 million state fund started last month
to combat runoff pollution. Dickerson said he didn't know exactly
how much the Los Angeles water board will receive.
</P>
<P>
   The new inspectors will visit about 3,000 industrial sites in
the area, many of which do not have proper industrial stormwater
permits, and issue violations against them. The board is also
creating development regulations aimed at treating the initial
runoff from new construction, which Dickerson said carries more
pollutants than later runoff.
</P>
<P>
   And city Bureau of Sanitation Director Judith Wilson said her
agency collects $28 million a year from a special fee tacked onto
city property tax bills that is earmarked for stormwater programs.
</P>
<P>
   Those include sending inspectors to literally sniff out illicit
sewer lines that feed into stormwater pipes. In one case,
discovered about a year ago, builders of a shopping mall in South
Central Los Angeles missed a sewer hookup by 8 inches and tapped a
stormwater line instead. The illegal flow lasted for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Other measures include using catch-basin inserts to screen or
filter pollutants, telling downtown business owners along Skid Row
not to hose vagrants' waste into storm drains and running ad
campaigns advising residents to pick up after their pets, lest more
bacteria wash into the Los Angeles River.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
