<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2440 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-PEARLJAM-CONCERT-TEX     08-04 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEARLJAM-CONCERT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEARL JAM TAKES STAGE FOR FIRST TIME SINCE ROSKILDE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By STEFAN STEVENSON 
 c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. _ Pearl Jam, the Seattle rock band that has
faced multiple hurdles during the past nine years, cleared its
biggest obstacle Thursday night before 20,000 fans at the GTE
Virginia Beach Amphitheater.
</P>
<P>
   It was 33 days ago that nine fans were crushed to death while
Pearl Jam performed at the Roskilde Rock Festival in Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   The band cancelled the remaining two shows on its European tour,
and it wasn't clear until mid-July whether their booked and mostly
sold-out U.S. tour would happen.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Pearl Jam began the first leg (Aug. 3 through
Sept. 5) of the U.S. tour with a renewed passion heightened by the
tragic events of this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Vocalist Eddie Vedder led the band in an inspirational set that
opened with ``Long Road,'' a heartbreaking ode to lost loved ones.
Vedder paid tribute early to those lost in Denmark, changing a line
in ``Long Road'' from ``for you'' to ``for them.''
</P>
<P>
   No long speeches eulogized the deceased; the music and lyrics
did the mourning. Each prophetic phrase was laced with agony and
irony. It became clear early on that the audience came to support
the band, especially Vedder.
</P>
<P>
   No extra security was evident, and none was needed. No one had
been seriously injured at a Pearl Jam show before June 30, and
Thursday night, the crowd seemed intent on celebration rather than
mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came with my friend all the way from Detroit,'' said Chris
Langrill, 23. ``If they didn't think they could have played the
kind of show they're capable of playing, they would have cancelled
the tour. I think they love their fans so much, even in the face of
the tragedy, they wouldn't let them down.''
</P>
<P>
   When the tragedy occurred in Denmark, Pearl Jam was forced to
cut short the song ``Daughter.'' Thursday night, they turned it
into a sing-along. Vedder asked the crowd to help the band ``start
anew'' by singing, ``It's OK, you got to run and hide away.'' His
tactic turned the song into a rousing uplifter.
</P>
<P>
   Vedder, the often-misunderstood icon, stayed in Spain all of
July, reportedly in secluded turmoil and letting a beard grow.
Thursday night, he appeared visibly shaken through the first six
songs; the crowd genuinely seemed to help him to shed that early
anguish.
</P>
<P>
   By the closing crowd pleaser, ``Yellow Ledbetter,'' the band
seemed to be finding relief in the performance and the reaction of
the devoted fans.
</P>
<P>
   Guitarists Mike McCready and Stone Gossard, bassist Jeff Ament
and drummer Matt Cameron, along with Vedder, are touring in support
of ``Binaural,'' the album the band released May 16.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 0017EDT &QL; 
