<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2442 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-TV-NOTEBOOK-1STLD     08-04 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-TV-NOTEBOOK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPEECH AND A PRODUCTION, MADE FOR SOUND BITES
</HEADLINE>
 (SUBS for rewriting; SUBS headline)  
 By CARYN JAMES  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush had an on-screen audition Thursday night for the
role of president, commandeering a chunk of network time as
presidents do, to give an extended speech. In the surprise-free
zone of this convention, the only question lingering was How
convincing a performance would he give.
</P>
<P>
   That is not a frivolous question in a television-driven
campaign, when a candidate's ability to act like a president on
camera may go further than any number of issue-oriented appearances
on ``Meet the Press.'' In those terms, Bush resembled an actor who
had studied hard, learned his lines and was determined to give the
best reading he could under circumstances that did not play to his
strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has always been and is still better in situations of casual
intimacy, chatting with Larry King. Thursday night his brow was
furrowed and he seemed to squint into the camera (blinding lights
or an effort to read the Teleprompter seemed like plausible
reasons), which made him look as if he were trying exceptionally
hard to be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, was what most commentators said he had to do.
As Bob Schieffer said on CBS in the minutes leading up to the
speech, ``The main message is: He's ready.'' And, as Peter Jennings
put it on ABC, ``It's a cliche for a reason: The most important
speech of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   He seemed stiffest in his delivery when reciting the lines that
had all too clearly been written to become the sound bites,
especially in the refrain, repeated three times: ``This
administration had its chance. They have not led. We will.'' He
seemed far more comfortable and convincing on screen when he spoke
emotionally, notably when acknowledging his parents.
</P>
<P>
   Speeches rarely make good television, but that can be overcome
if the candidate's delivery is dynamic enough to leap off the
screen. Bush's wasn't, but at times he showed the flicker of a
connection between him and the camera that suggested he was just
beginning to master this part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The networks and cable channels led up to the speech in
different and very telling ways. NBC and its cable channel MSNBC,
along with CNN and Fox News Channel, presented the treacly video
biography of Bush made by the Republican National Committee. In
this gushy video, his Mom and Dad say he's great. He is seen as
governor surrounded by schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ABC and CBS put things in a far more intelligent context by
presenting their own, more balanced biographical features. They
gave Bush full credit for a quick rise to success, but also raised
the tougher questions about him.
</P>
<P>
   As the CBS report put it, ``Is George W. Bush prepared to lead
the most powerful nation on earth?'' Where the video showed him
extolling the virtues of freedom, the CBS and ABC reports included
tape of the pop quiz in which he failed to name world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   After all the network complaining about what an infomercial this
convention was, a little reporting was the least a network could
do. Simply labeling the video as a Republican National Committee
production and letting it run only emphasized that television
producers seem to have thrown up their hands in surrender over the
whole affair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
