<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA CHAMP RALLIES, TRIPS TEXAS CHAMP FOR DIXIE MAJORS TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EULESS, Texas _ Hernando County, Fla., almost gave a Dixie
Majors World Series title away last night.
</P>
<P>
   But one of its star players, Chris Cole, made sure that didn't
happen. Two innings after the state champion from Florida committed
three errors in a four-run Lufkin inning, Cole, the team's catcher
and a Florida State signee, clinched the game with his third home
run of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Cole hit a two-run shot over the right-field fence in the sixth,
giving Hernando County a 7-6 victory against Lufkin at The Parks at
Texas Star. Hernando County reliever Patrick Ryan saved the victory
for starter Jason Dunn in the top of the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a high fastball inside, and \RLufkin reliever Chris
Crain\S left it where I could handle it,'' said Cole, who hit over
.600 in the six-day tournament. ``After the first two innings I
thought it wasn't going to be a 7-6 game, but at least we didn't
have to bat in that last inning.''
</P>
<P>
   After drawing the bye into last night's championship game,
Hernando County took advantage of the rest by building a 5-2 lead
after the second inning. Lufkin was in its second game of the day,
after defeating Louisiana, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fourth inning, Lufkin scratched its way back into the
title game. Lufkin went up 6-5 when Justin Purvis hit a single down
the first base line that scored Brett McDaniel.
</P>
<P>
   Hernando County committed four errors in the game, three in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get three sawed-off grounders and we let them back in it,''
said Florida coach Tim Sims, who was on the last team from Hernando
County to win a Dixie Majors title in 1983. ``We created momentum
for them. We had two pitchers that were going to throw strikes and
make them put it into play.''
</P>
<P>
   Crain kept Florida from scoring in the bottom half of the fourth
and the fifth. But in the sixth, Dee Brown led off with a single to
left before Cole hit the game-winning home run a few pitches later.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Leslie closed out the inning without giving up a run,
but the damage was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the tired team, and they were the rested team ... that
was the advantage that they had,'' Lufkin coach W.A. Dempsey said.
``We jumped on them, they come back and we come back and have the
lead. We make one bad pitch and it goes out of the ballpark. That's
just baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   In eliminating Louisiana, Lufkin scored three runs in the bottom
of the seventh to win. Cody Deal hit the game-winning single off
Louisiana starter Allan Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Lufkin starter Wade Fitzgerald picked up the victory, after
giving up two runs on three hits in seven innings.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
