A2445 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBO-BULLPENS-BOREDOM-     08-04 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BULLPENS-BOREDOM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIEF FROM BOREDOM: CREATIVE DIVERSIONS HELP LIVEN BULLPENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Baseball, to put it politely, is a sport with
the occasional less-than-thrilling moment.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to work up much enthusiasm for batters stepping
out of the box, interminable throws to first base, visits to the
mound, and pitchers who don't throw strikes.
</P>
<P>
   OK, sometimes it's downright boring.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult, if not impossible, to stay interested in every
pitch of every game.
</P>
<P>
   That holds true whether one is watching from the stands, the
living room, the press box _ or the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, ennui can set in even among a team's relievers while
waiting for their turn to come into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be focused on every out,'' Rangers left-hander Mike
Venafro said. ``You're a spectator for the first four innings or so
unless you're a long reliever. You cheer, and you have
conversations that normal fans would have.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, cheering and conversing are ways to pass the time.
But there are stories about other more interesting, more creative
ways to while away the innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those rumors may be true,'' Venafro said with a smile on his
face. ``I definitely can't divulge anything. I really don't know
what goes down there.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the zany things that used to go on in bullpens are well
documented.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were always practical jokes,'' said Rangers pitcher
Kenny Rogers, who spent the first four seasons of his career as a
reliever. ``You'd light somebody with hot foots. If they'd nod off,
you'd cut their shoelaces up, tie them together if you could.''
</P>
<P>
   In old Arlington Stadium, where the pitchers were stuck in a
sunken bullpen down the first-base line, a hungry reliever with no
place to go might bribe a fan with a baseball in exchange for a hot
dog or nachos.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of thing isn't as common today. In a modern facility
such as The Ballpark in Arlington, a reliever with the mid-game
munchies can easily go to the clubhouse without going across the
field.
</P>
<P>
   And the prevalence of television, with cameras frequently
pointing toward the relievers, makes it tougher to conduct
practical jokes and participate in zany stunts.
</P>
<P>
   Tougher, but not impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a couple of bullpens that have cameras in them, and
I've heard of certain relievers going as far as trying to dismantle
these cameras or rewire them,'' Venafro said.
</P>
<P>
   Venafro also has heard of, ahem, certain relievers doing other
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Underneath a lot of stadiums, there's a lot of empty space,''
he said. ``It is rumored, that in the olden days, guys used to ride
behind golf carts and skate around on their spikes, doing slalom
work or working on their off-season skiing techniques. That's
rumored to have happened long ago. Golf carts are way too fast now;
that would be too dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as it would be dangerous to explore in an unfamiliar
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a challenge to discover the workings of a
ballpark,'' Venafro said. ``You go to exciting parks like Anaheim,
which is Disney; very exciting. You've got all kinds of fountains
and things down there, and you always want to try to figure out how
they work. I've heard of guys probing around a little bit to see
how high the fountain can go. We really don't condone those sort of
things here with the Texas Rangers. I think when Doug Melvin puts
this bullpen together that he's really not attracted to guys like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Such adventures _ sorry, rumors _ are infrequent. But the
Rangers relievers have other methods to pass the time on a daily
basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have little things that they do that, while having a good
time and keeping things loose, it keeps them involved in the
game,'' bullpen coach Larry Hardy said. ``The whole objective is to
pass the time while at the same time watch the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Just what those little things are is more closely guarded than
nuclear secrets at the Los Alamos lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell you, but then I'd have to kill you,'' closer John
Wetteland said.
</P>
<P>
   An intrepid spy did dig out a little information, however.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, the leader of the relief corps, has devised an
elaborate set of rules. Deviation results in swift punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody gets caught not acknowledging a hit or something
that has advanced the runner, they get head slaps,'' Hardy said.
</P>
<P>
   Head slaps?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's to keep you in the game,'' Doug Davis said. ``John
definitely holds you to that. He wants to make sure everybody is
into the game. He really doesn't slack off about it at all. He
never lets anything go.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland won't divulge specifics, but said the rules serve a
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though they're fun, and funny, and seem at times
ridiculous _ and they are _ there is a whole underlying thing that
goes along with the rules and the punishments and everything
else,'' he said. ``That is to one, be attentive to what's going on
in the game; two, to think of others before you think of yourself;
and three, to be gentlemen. Those are the three things that all of
these rules stem from.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to be always on to the game. But what most relievers
have found throughout the years, is if you get sucked into the
game, it's tiring. This is a way to be sucked into the game to make
it a fun thing rather than a chore.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
