<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-RICE-365&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONSANTO PLANS TO OFFER RIGHTS ON ALTERED RICE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a bid to foster support for biotechnology and
save lives, Monsanto Corp. will make available patent rights to
genetically altered rice that could help stave off malnutrition in
poor nations, the company's president said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrik Verfaillie, the president and chief executive of the St.
Louis-based company, said Monsanto will forgo licensing fees for
its ``golden rice,'' a modified strain that is rich in beta
carotene, an essential source of Vitamin A.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of golden rice is to bring Vitamin A where people
suffer,'' Verfaillie said in a telephone interview. The development
of the rice, he added, ``clearly demonstrates that biotechnology
can help not only countries in the West, but in the developing
world as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, about 200 million children suffer from Vitamin A
deficiencies, and about 1 million children succumb to diseases
partly caused by a lack of adequate defenses. Hundreds of thousands
more go blind each year, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Monsanto's unusual offer, which was first reported in Friday's
editions of The Washington Post, will cost the corporation
financially, Verfaillie acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   But it appeared aimed in part at countering a tide of negative
publicity over the proliferation of genetically altered crops.
Skepticism toward such products is especially acute in Western
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The company's offer was applauded by the developer of golden
rice, Ingo Potrykus, a Swiss professor. In remarks to the press,
Potrykus said he would seek to persuade other companies to follow
Monsanto's lead and provide life-saving biotechnology to poor
nations free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   The rice, named golden for its yellowish hue, is rich in beta
carotene, the same substance that give carrots their color. The
body converts beta carotene into Vitamin A, which becomes an
essential nutrient that boosts the immune system and wards off
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Monsanto, a large agricultural biotechnology firm that is a unit
of Pharmacia Corp., announced in April that it had decoded the
genes of rice.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The company and its competitors have come under criticism from
environmentalists and some science groups for their work on
genetically modified crops, which the critics say could damage the
environment and prove dangerous for consumption. Thursday's
announcement could help blunt some of the criticism if the move
lives up to its promise of saving the lives of otherwise
malnourished children around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Some groups that have been critical of biotechnology companies
have questioned whether the widespread distribution of golden rice
is necessarily a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent statement quoted in The Post, the Rural Advancement
Foundation said that ``critics are concerned that the advent of
golden rice's `quick fix' for Vitamin-A deficiency oculd kneecap
other low-tech and more cost-effective initiatives _ among them, to
reintroduce the many vital-rich food plants that were once chap and
available.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation added, ``Rather than nurture a strategy that
encourages biodiversity, golden rice could promote monocultures and
genetic uniformity. This is the wrong stratHegy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 0031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
