<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2448 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GOP-BUSH-SPEECH-1STLD     08-04 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUSH-SPEECH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER TWO MONTHS OF REFINING, BUSH FINDS JUST THE WORDS TO MATCH
HIS STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 1st and 4th grafs removing reference to planned text; SUBS
3rd graf with speech taking longer than planned; SUBS 8th graf to
replace ``the advance test'' with ``it''; SUBS 12th graf with
Bush's performance; SUBS last graf   to update) 
By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ If it had been up to his speechwriter, Gov.
George W. Bush would have opened his remarks Thursday night by
thanking the delegates here for ``the honor of this hour.''
</P>
<P>
   But that felt too lofty to the Texas governor, too fancy and
formal. And so, as he scribbled in margins, sounded out sentences
and ushered the most important address of his political career
through 17 drafts, Bush deleted the last three words of that
phrase, ending the sentence with ``honor.'' It was closer to the
way he normally spoke, and closer to the way he felt.
</P>
<P>
   He used the last few weeks before his big moment to nip, tuck
and condense the speech from about 4,300 words to about 3,900, even
though the former length was well within the range of convention
tradition. Bush believed that shorter was better, and truer to who
he was. He also exhibited a bit of prescience, because his
methodical delivery and the frequent applause extended his
appearance on stage beyond what he and his aides had originally
estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the generally worded proposals and beneath the
emphatically stated priorities, Bush's speech Thursday night was in
many ways a glimpse into the way he thinks and feels. According to
the campaign's chief speechwriter, Michael Gerson, and other aides
who worked with Bush on the remarks, he tended to elect simple
statements over ornate locutions, the epigrammatic over the
elongated, words he felt comfortable saying over words that
challenged him, clarity over ambiguity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted images, he wanted things shorter, he wanted things
more concrete,'' said Gerson, who has been writing Bush's biggest
speeches for nearly a year and a half. The campaign did not, as is
sometimes the case, recruit outside help for this address. Like
most endeavors in Bush's political world, this process was kept
close to home, among the tried and trusted.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not practice it in front of focus groups or strangers,
advisers said, although he did practice it often over the last two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He read it aloud in front of senior campaign officials, taking
pointers from Karen Hughes, his communications director, and Mark
McKinnon and Stuart Stevens, who make the commercials for the
campaign. He toted a teleprompter into the living room of a private
house in Cincinnati and then into the dining room of the
Pennsylvania governor's mansion in Harrisburg, subjecting friends
in both places to his trial runs.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's speech may well be a hallmark of Bush's maturation as
a candidate, in that it reflects a degree of diligence and level of
preparation not always evident on the campaign trail over the last
year.
</P>
<P>
   He looked at the first draft two months ago, and ordered changes
and more changes until the end. He pestered aides well outside of
office hours with his latest thoughts. As Gerson spoke with a New
York Times reporter over breakfast early last week, his cell phone
rang, and it was the boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirteen is just spelling errors and punctuation,'' Gerson
told Bush, explaining what had been corrected and amended since the
12th draft. ``We'll make sure that we get 14 ready for the
teleprompter.''
</P>
<P>
   After hanging up, Gerson said that Bush, who had called from his
Texas ranch, wanted the reporter to know that ``he's been thinking
so hard, the deer have started talking to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Those animals were apparently urging concision, simplicity,
``making our eloquence more direct,'' as Gerson said. What Bush and
his campaign strategists wanted was something that balanced the
formality of the occasion with the informality of his personal
style, and the difficulty of that task was made apparent in Bush's
delivery Thursday night, which was not as natural as he undoubtedly
wanted it to be, and which tested the limits of his abilities as an
orator.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush was very much a part of the production.
</P>
<P>
   He pruned an array of phrases near the top. At the end of a
sentence that began ``together, we will,'' Gerson attached a
lengthy litany of goals. Bush distilled them into a single phrase,
``renew America's purpose'' that echoed existing slogans from his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gerson initially offered several paragraphs of examples of the
sacrifices of the World War II generation, which Bush had wanted to
honor. Bush was not content until the tribute had been boiled down
to a few sentences and a central sentiment: That these brave men
had ``stormed beaches, liberated concentration camps and delivered
us from evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerson, trying to make the case that good times are as crucial
as bad, wrote that ``a time of crisis is a test of strength, a time
of prosperity is a test of vision.'' But that was neither active
nor specific enough for Bush, who kept pressing and pressing until
Gerson came up with this: ``Prosperity can be a tool in our hand,
used to build and better our country, or it can be a drug in our
system, dulling our sense of urgency, of empathy, of duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the theme that the baby boom generation had squandered
some of its opportunities and surrendered to irresponsible impulses
was present from the first draft, Bush wanted that notion turned
into a motif, with recurring allusions to a privileged generation's
unrealized obligation to give something back.
</P>
<P>
   Inasmuch as Bush can be said to have intellectual obsessions,
this had always been one, but there was another reason to hammer
home this argument. It represented an implicit indictment of
President Clinton, and an implicit pitch to start anew in the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Although Thursday night's speech was much more than a culling
and cobbling together of Bush's stump speeches to date, the
candidate did revert to familiar phrases.
</P>
<P>
   An early draft by Gerson included the sentiment that
``congregations are responsible not only to worship, but to
serve.'' Bush was not accustomed to using that first word, and one
of the first times he read a version of the speech aloud he
spontaneously changed it to ``churches, synagogues and mosques,''
words he had used in dozens of previous remarks. Aides duly
inserted the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to be able to say the words in a comfortable way,''
said Hughes, who provided extensive help with the editing. Hughes,
who has worked with Bush since 1994, knew his voice as well as he
did, and often came to Gerson to single out the same passage the
governor had as something that did not sound like him.
</P>
<P>
   But as involved as the governor was, he did not let the gravity
of the task eclipse the levity to which he is perpetually inclined.
</P>
<P>
   When he walked onto the convention stage on Wednesday to check
out where he would be standing for his big moment, he made a widely
grinning, grandly gesticulating show of pointing to ushers, waving
to supporters and calling out familiar names, even as his
straight-faced entourage busily went about checking the lighting
and sound.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday afternoon, when reporters asked about Bush's
latest thoughts on the speech, he said he had given a more
important speech ``when I asked my wife to marry me.'' Bush took a
nap in the afternoon, because the scheduled time for the beginning
of his remarks shortly after 10 p.m. was past his usual bedtime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 0033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
