<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PAC-10-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERS OF THE PAC? UW VOTED NO. 1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TED MILLER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It took Rick Neuheisel just two years to make the
University of Washington the top Dawgs in the Pac-10 _ at least in
the media's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Washington nipped USC by three votes as the media's choice to
win the 2000 Pac-10 crown in the annual preseason poll, while
Washington State was relegated to the 10th position for the second
consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   The vote tied the second-smallest margin between first and
second since the inaugural preseason poll in 1961. Washington (275
total points) received 16 first-place votes to 11 for USC (272).
</P>
<P>
   Oregon, picked third, received one first-place vote, while No. 5
Arizona State had two.
</P>
<P>
   The honor inspired ambivalence in Neuheisel, who led the Huskies
to a 7-5 record in his first season as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to say, hey, great, it's a positive for our
program that people believe Washington football is on the way
back,'' Neuheisel said. ``That said: I can't wait to go and tell my
team this doesn't mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a point.
</P>
<P>
   The media has correctly picked the eventual champion in just 17
out of 39 polls, and only two times in the past seven years. Seven
different teams have won the Pac-10 title in the past eight years.
In four of the past seven years, the eventual conference champion
was picked to finish in the bottom half of the league.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's champion, Stanford, which was picked eighth before
the 1999 season, was voted seventh this year, despite returning 15
starters from the team that played in the Rose Bowl. It was only
the second time since 1978 that the defending champs were predicted
to finish in the conference's bottom half the following year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really want my reaction?'' Stanford coach Tyrone
Willingham said with a grin. ``I think it's consistent with what
has gone on most years ... and I'll leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal also had the widest range of votes, ranking as high
as second and as low as 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Washington State has compiled a 1-15 conference record since
appearing in the Rose Bowl following the 1997 season. The Cougars
were picked 10th last year and finished 10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the only guy in the history of the program to turn it
around twice,'' Cougars coach Mike Price quipped. ``I'm going for
three this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington was picked sixth last year in the preseason and
finished tied for second with Oregon. The media predicted Arizona
would win the conference last season, but the Wildcats finished
tied for sixth.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Arizona fell to eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listening to all these coaches, you'd think it's going to be a
10-way tie for first,'' Arizona coach Dick Tomey said. ``We've been
picked down before and won 10 games. I don't pay any attention to
where we are picked. It's just a best guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Oregon, the only conference team to win a bowl game in 1999,
welcomes back just 10 starters from last season's 9-3 squad.
Nonetheless, the Ducks were picked third, perhaps a sign of
newfound respect for the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are starting to realize the caliber of team we
are,'' Oregon defensive end Saul Patu said. ``But we really don't
pay attention to (polls).''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA was fourth in this year's poll, while Oregon State was
sixth, the school's highest position in the poll since the
conference expanded to 10 teams in 1978. Cal was ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The media last picked Washington to win the league in 1997, but
the Huskies ended up in fourth place. The Huskies' most recent
Pac-10 title came in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked ourselves into a position where they think we're
good,'' Neuheisel said. ``Now let's prove we're good.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ted Miller can be reached at 206-448-8017
</P>
<P>
   or tedmiller &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
