<HEADER>
A2461 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CONVENTION-ANALYSIS-K     08-04 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTION-ANALYSIS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CONVENTION WRAPS UP AS GOP COUNTS ITS SUCCESSES FOR
WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY and STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It had no suspense, a record-low TV audience and
nothing resembling a robust debate on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans couldn't be happier with their national
convention that ended Thursday. After all, conventions no longer
are about picking candidates as much as they are about catapulting
them to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a wildly successful convention,'' said John
Hancock, executive director of the Missouri Republican Party. ``We
got even more bounce than the campaign expected.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush leaves Philadelphia today with a double-digit
lead in the polls and a party brimming with confidence that he is
just three months away from being elected the 43rd president of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party is as unified as we've been since Ronald Reagan's
re-election in 1984,'' said Sen. Sam Brownback, a Kansas
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans achieved unity by virtually banning dissension in a
party that's been out of the White House since early 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers heard hardly a word about abortion and little about the
moral bankruptcy of the Clinton era until vice presidential nominee
Dick Cheney took the president to task Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And they saw no tributes to the House managers who worked so
diligently to impeach the intensely disliked Democratic Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-edged partisanship was out. A GOP with a smiling face was
in, allowing the party to move to the center in an all-out bid to
win in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't find anyone in the hall willing to utter an unkind
word,'' said University of Texas political scientist Bruce
Buchanan. ``I call that impressive discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans especially wanted to avoid the flame-throwing
rhetoric that Pat Buchanan voiced at the 1992 convention.
Buchanan's call for a cultural war drove legions of voters away
from the GOP and opened the door for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Bush himself requested a convention with a less strident tone.
In his acceptance speech Thursday night, he promoted his bipartisan
approach to governing that has seen him working hand in hand with
Democrats in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have enemies to fight,'' Bush said. ``And I have no
stake in the bitter arguments of the last few years. I want to
change the tone of Washington to one of civility and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some Democrats were impressed with the convention _ to a
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found it remarkable to watch how nicely the Republicans have
organized around the message they wanted to deliver,'' said Mike
McCurry, President Clinton's former press secretary who is now a
communications consultant.
</P>
<P>
   But McCurry said that eliminating any debate on the issues or
candidates doesn't necessarily generate voter enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was kind of an antiseptic quality to the convention,''
McCurry said. ``You need a little more depth.''
</P>
<P>
   But various polls show Bush has opened a lead of more than 10
points over Gore during convention week. A bipartisan poll by
Voter.com released Thursday gave him a 48 percent to 34 percent
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   In that poll, Bush surged 18 points ahead of Gore among
independent voters and six points ahead among women. A
preconvention poll by the same group had the two candidates
virtually tied among those two groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Republicans' week,'' conceded Jim Slattery, a
former Democratic congressman from Kansas. ``They are going to get
a nice bounce out of this convention. I don't think there's any
question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Slattery and others, however, chided Republicans for showcasing
speakers and entertainers from groups traditionally thought of as
Democrats, including African-Americans, Hispanics and gays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best Democratic convention Republicans have put on
for a long time,'' Slattery said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the unified front of the GOP stems from the choice of
Cheney, observers said. Cheney appeased conservatives who may have
thought of Bush as too moderate. His selection set a harmonious
tone for the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, the uptick comes after a convention,'' said Richard
L. Berkley, a former Kansas City mayor who was at a GOP convention
for the ninth time. ``This time I think it came before it
started.''
</P>
<P>
   The boost for Bush occurred despite an apparent lack of public
interest in the convention.
</P>
<P>
   A Nielsen Media Research Poll published in The New York Times
showed that only 8.8 percent of homes with televisions were tuned
into the convention Tuesday, down from a high of 31.5 in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to politics, people are tuning out and turning
off,'' said Robert Denton, a political communications professor at
Virginia Tech University.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of suspense about who will be nominated was considered
a key to the low ratings. But Republicans don't seem to mind, given
the alternative. Suspense implies division, and division translates
to lost elections.
</P>
<P>
   Look no further, Republicans argue, than the bitter 1976 primary
race between Reagan and President Gerald Ford or the equally heated
1980 Democratic bout between President Jimmy Carter and Ted
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question we would rather have people going home
feeling good about our presidential candidate than have the
infighting we've had at past conventions,'' said Catherine Hanaway,
executive director of the Bush campaign in Missouri and an
alternate delegate at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of rancor on the floor has been matched by a pattern of
scripted, kindly worded speeches from the speaker's podium. Not
until Cheney's speech Wednesday night where he lashed out at
Clinton and Gore did any major speaker go on the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is more like an incumbent president's convention,'' Denton
said. ``The unity, the tone, the not being attack-oriented. It's a
different kind of convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Gueary III, president of the Olathe branch of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People and a registered
Republican, said although he had watched every minute of the
convention, it had not kept him from leaning toward Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen anything inspiring,'' Gueary said. ``It's a lot
of fanfare but it didn't have any real meaning or purpose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
