<SLUG> BC-BBO-SULLIVAN-COL-OLYMPICS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW ABOUT A DREAM TEAM FOR BASEBALL?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. Sullivan 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember, you read it here first.
</P>
<P>
   Here is your United States Olympic Baseball Team, which will
compete in the Summer Olympics next month in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers: Rick Helling, Mike Mussina, Brad Radke, Dustin
Hermanson, Kris Benson, Todd Jones, Trevor Hoffman, John Wetteland.
</P>
<P>
   Catchers: Brad Ausmus, Jason Kendall.
</P>
<P>
   First basemen: Rafael Palmeiro, Jeff Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   Second basemen: Delino DeShields, Jeff Frye.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstops: Royce Clayton, Desi Relaford.
</P>
<P>
   Third basemen: Jeff Cirillo, Scott Rolen
</P>
<P>
   Outfielders: Rusty Greer, Johnny Damon, Rondell White, Richie
Sexson, Jermaine Dye, Greg Vaughn, Brady Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitters: Todd Helton, Dean Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty good, huh? Even with the loss of second baseman Craig
Biggio to injury, the Cubans don't have a chance. The gold medal is
in the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't tell Rangers manager Johnny Oates we're taking half
his team away for the final three weeks of the season. He'll go
ballistic.
</P>
<P>
   But he'll have to live with it. American pride is at stake, and
this is] the only way to ensure the gold medal will be brought back
to the United States. The plan is simple but ingenious (and totally
hypothetical), part of my ongoing effort to help Bud Selig run
baseball:
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 7, any major-league player on a team with a losing
record is free to call it a season and go play for the United
States in the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ```Hmmm, that would be pretty neat,'' Palmeiro admitted. ``I'd
consider it.''
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't? What major-league player wouldn't want the honor
of crushing the rest of the world in Sydney?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not at the top of my list of priorities,'' Greer said.
</P>
<P>
   What?
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes away from baseball,'' Greer said. ``No matter if
you're on a losing team or not, you still have a chance to be a
spoiler on teams ahead of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine. Greer is out. Gabe Kapler is in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like it,'' Kapler said. ``I'd like to represent my
country for two weeks, although my first obligation is to my
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   All right, check with Rangers general manager Doug Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Melvin said. ``They'd have to play Canada. Being
Canadian, I don't want the U.S. to have a stacked team.''
</P>
<P>
   All right, the Canadians get Larry Walker, Jeff Zimmerman and
Ryan Dempster.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a player wanted to go, I wouldn't stand in his way,''
Melvin said seriously. ``I think it would be great for someone like
\Rthe Orioles'\S Cal Ripken. I shouldn't speak for him, but they're
rebuilding anyway. If you're a player who has accomplished a lot,
it might be something to go for. Same with Tony Gwynn.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer is right about one thing. Taking these players away would
have a significant impact on the pennant race. The Rangers finish
the season with three games against the Oakland Athletics, and
playoff] contenders like Cleveland, Toronto and Seattle expect
Helling, Palmeiro, Clayton and Kapler to play that weekend.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Olympic team will consist mainly of
minor-leaguers. But this is still a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity,
as Melvin found out when three members of the Pan American Games
team _ manager Buddy Bell, pitching coach Marcel Lachemann and
pitcher John Patterson _ addressed baseball general managers at
their annual off-season meeting last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talked about what those games meant,'' Melvin said. ``How
after they lost the first game their pride kicked in. It was a
do-or-die situation. Professional baseball was the farthest thing
from their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave you a sense that we need to do our best to put the
best team out there.''
</P>
<P>
   It's settled. The plan is hereby adopted. Sept. 7 is the cutoff
date. The only one thing that we need between now and then is a
long losing streak by the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Hello, Ken Griffey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Eat your heart out, Fidel Castro.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
