<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SAFETY-DEVICE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVICE MIGHT HELP PREVENT SERIOUS HEAD AND NECK INJURIES IN AUTO
RACING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ NASCAR Winston Cup regular Brett Bodine plans to
compete in tomorrow's Brickyard 400 wearing a device he says might
have prevented the deaths of Adam Petty and Kenny Irwin Jr. in
separate crashes this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bodine wore stock-car racing's version of the HANS Device, an
evolving head-and-neck restraint system, for the first time during
the Pennsylvania 500 at Pocono Raceway last month, after trying it
on for size during Ford Motor Co.'s Brickyard test at the
Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a wonderful device,'' said Bodine, one of three
brothers racing in NASCAR. ``Ran it every lap at Pocono with no
negative about it. It does not restrict your side vision or your
mobility. It made me feel more secure in the car. I felt like I had
another piece of safety device that really was going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   HANS is the acronym for ``head and neck support.'' Developed in
the mid-1990s, it features a yoke that fits around the driver's
neck and over his shoulders, and straps that attach to the back of
the helmet. It is designed to keep a driver's head and neck from
violently snapping forward and backward during an impact.
</P>
<P>
   Indy Racing League regular Eddie Cheever Jr., who said he plans
to test the HANS later this month, said his understanding of the
device is that it spreads G-force loading under rapid deceleration.
Therefore, the shock of an impact is not concentrated on three or
four vertebrae in the neck.
</P>
<P>
   Petty, 19, was killed when he crashed while practicing his
NASCAR Busch Grand National car at New Hampshire International
Speedway on May 12. He suffered massive head injuries. Irwin, 30,
was killed when he crashed while practicing his Cup car on July 7
at NHIS, not far from where Petty suffered his fatal injuries in
Turn 3.
</P>
<P>
   Sticking throttles have been suspected in both incidents,
although NASCAR has not been able to prove that.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to those tragedies, NASCAR officials announced
Tuesday that beginning with tomorrow's race, Cup cars must be
equipped with a stop on the primary and secondary throttle shafts
and an on/off switch on the steering wheel to cut power to the
ignition.
</P>
<P>
   Bodine believes the HANS Device is the next logical safety step.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel it would have increased the chances of them \RPetty and
Irwin\S surviving those crashes. That's why I'm using the device,''
said Bodine, whose older brother, Geoffrey, survived a fiery,
parts-spewing crash in a NASCAR Craftsman Truck race at the Daytona
International Speedway in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend a lot of time, money and effort on making these race
cars go faster,'' said Bodine, driver of the No. 11 Ralphs
Supermarkets Ford Taurus. ``We should spend the same amount of time
and money and effort on making them safer.''
</P>
<P>
   The HANS Device has become the hot-ticket item in open-wheel
racing this summer. Michael Andretti and Christian Fittipaldi,
teammates at Newman-Haas Racing in the Championship Auto Racing
Teams series, wore the device during the Michigan 500 at the
Michigan Speedway last month. Formula One drivers will be required
to wear the device beginning in 2001, and CART officials are
considering making the HANS mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett, the reigning Winston Cup champion and Brickyard
400 winner, said he also is preparing to test a version of the
device.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the process of getting a new helmet done, and \RI want
to\S at least try it and see what adjustments we need to make,''
said Jarrett, driver of the No. 88 Quality Care Service/Ford Credit
Taurus. ``The problem that I have, maybe as a taller driver, is I
sit all the way back against the rollcage as it is. And I know to
make that device work, you have to bend the headrest part of the
seat back some more. With that, I'm going to be right against the
rollbar, and I don't know that we have room. But I'm looking for
anything that can make it safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nelson, Winston Cup Series director, said NASCAR is keenly
interested in Bodine's continued feedback.
</P>
<P>
   ``His comments were positive after the \RPocono\S race,'' Nelson
said in Gasoline Alley. ``But we still want to look at it and
discuss it with the whole garage before we make those kind of
decisions. We're looking at it. There's a lot of things that guys
can do \Rto enhance safety\S. The HANS Device is one of them.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
