<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WEALTH EFFECT' THEORY MAY NOT HOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As stock prices continue to sag and show no sign of recapturing
their upward dynamism of recent years, conventional wisdom holds
that a diminished ``wealth effect'' will undermine personal
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   The good news would be that a falloff in consumer activity would
probably lead the Federal Reserve to call a halt to its
money-tightening regimen of the past year. The bad news would be
that if consumers became too cautious, it could eventually lead to
recession, because personal consumption fuels two-thirds of U.S.
economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   This raises the question of whether what economists call the
wealth effect correlates as closely with personal consumption as is
generally believed. The wealth-effect theory assumes that as the
value of investments rises, so does investor propensity to spend.
Spending increases in tandem with the feeling of being wealthier.
This sense of being better off prevails even when the gains are
still in the form of paper profit because investors haven't
converted their newfound wealth to actual income.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher J. Neely of the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis
recently took a close look at the relationship between stock prices
and consumption and found traditional assumptions open to question.
Writing in the July issue of the bank's MonetaryTrends, Neely said
his research showed ``only a tenuous relationship between
consumption growth and asset prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Neely reviewed the period 1889-1999, comparing stock values to
consumption growth of services and nondurable goods, and failed to
find any ``strong pattern'' to support the wealth-effect theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although there are sound theoretical reasons to believe that
the rise in stock market wealth has fueled recent consumption
growth and that consumption is related to wealth in the long run,''
Neely observed, ``neither asset prices nor other variables have
proven especially useful in predicting future consumption growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Neely's findings bring to mind J.M. Keynes' observation that we
are often slaves to defunct economists.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Neely is concerned, the theoretical weakness revealed
by his study makes it difficult to say how much stock market gains
of recent years have fueled consumption, ``or to predict the likely
consequences of a sharp drop in stock prices.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes Neely's research interesting at this particular time
is the surprisingly strong economic growth recently indicated by
the second-quarter gross domestic product. The initial GDP estimate
was an annual growth pace of 5.2 percent, when most economists had
been forecasting a rate in the 3.5 percent neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   While business investment gave growth a strong boost, consumer
activity held up despite a stock market that has in many instances
provided the opposite of a wealth effect since March.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of ways to read recent events in the context
of Neely's findings. One is that a slumping market won't
necessarily threaten a recession, which is encouraging. Another is
that if Fed researchers in Washington are coming to the same
conclusion they are in St. Louis, a sluggish market won't be seen
as a reason to stop raising interest rates in the face of strong
economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2467 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-IBC-LAWSUIT-KAN &LR;      08-04 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBC-LAWSUIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERSTATE BAKERIES DOESN'T GET STAY OF PUNITIVE-DAMAGES AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Interstate Bakeries Corp. on Thursday failed to keep a jury
award of $120 million in punitive damages from being entered into
the court record. The award is the second largest in U.S. legal
history involving a private company accused of discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City, Mo., company said Thursday that it would
definitely appeal the damage award, which involves its San
Francisco bakery. A lawyer representing several of the black
plaintiffs said it was time for Interstate to acknowledge its
problems in dealing with black people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where arrogance gets you,'' said Angela Alioto, a San
Francisco lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate had said late Wednesday that it expected to receive a
stay of the award after talking to the judge. But in a conference
call to attorneys of both sides, the judge said Interstate's
attorneys had misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Dirkes, vice president of marketing at Interstate, said the
company had policies in place to deal with discrimination
complaints and took them seriously. But employees must bring any
problems to the company's attention, and that wasn't done by the
workers involved in the suit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a perfect world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco lawsuit isn't the only one the company has
faced. Interstate confirmed that it was involved in a
discrimination suit in New York and another in Florida. A suit in
Indiana was decided in the company's favor.
</P>
<P>
   The California case involved 21 black workers at Interstate's
Wonder Bread plant in San Francisco. The jury on Monday awarded $11
million in compensatory damages and on Wednesday awarded $120
million in punitive damages for discrimination against the workers.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate previously had said discriminatory practices alleged
in the case went back as far as 30 years, when other companies
owned the plant. Interstate bought the bakery in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   About $5 million of the compensatory damages was for
discrimination before mid-1997, and the judge has indicated he will
set that portion of the award aside. But the punitive award was
strictly for discriminatory practices since mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
   The total award _ about $126 million _ is the second largest for
a private company in a discrimination suit. Texaco settled a
discrimination case in 1996 for $176 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Griesemer, an analyst for A.G. Edwards in St. Louis, said
the award was large for a company of Interstate's size but not
enough to put it under. However, the award could trigger more suits
and more costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the big worry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate's stock closed Thursday at $18 a share, down 94
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Waukeen McCoy, a San Francisco lawyer representing some of the
plaintiffs in the California case, said there were several
inquiries from other Interstate employees around the country
wanting to join the suit. They were refused because they didn't
live in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a nationwide problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy said he had failed to get much response from civil rights
groups, including the NAACP in Oakland, regarding the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to the NAACP in Oakland and Kansas City and to its
national headquarters in Baltimore, as well as the Black Chamber of
Commerce of Greater Kansas City, seeking comment about the lawsuit
were not returned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Black workers who filed the California suit said they failed to
get their share of promotions and often worked in a hostile working
environment that included racial slurs.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Wright, who worked at the plant after it was bought by
Interstate, said he did get a foreman position, but it proved to be
short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   His job was on the loading dock, which turned out to be
understaffed, he said. He asked for another worker, but his request
was denied. Wright, a black man, said he had to skip lunch breaks
to relieve other workers to keep from falling behind. The extra
work gave him a shoulder injury that put him off the job.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement was a white man who was given the extra employee
that Wright was denied, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In another incident, he asked for a personal day off for Martin
Luther King Jr. Day. He was denied even though he made the request
two months in advance, and other white workers often took personal
days to go to baseball games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had different rules for the white guys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dirkes said that about 10 percent of the employees in the San
Francisco plant are black and that a proportionate amount are in
supervisory positions.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company offered diversity training at its plants.
The training had been given at the San Francisco plant, Dirkes
said, although he was unsure whether it was before or after the
lawsuit was filed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to equal opportunity and diversity, and
therefore we cannot and will not tolerate discrimination,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
