<HEADER>
A2470 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-herskowitz-HNS &LR;      08-04 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-herskowitz-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Give Rockets credit, as well as an arena
<TEXT>
<P>
   By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   After six suspenseful months of negotiations, the Rockets and
the Harris County-Houston Sports Authority have reached an
agreement on a new arena, proving that, yes, we can all get along
if the price is right, or close to it. If we can keep religion out
of politics, and politics out of sports, and sports out of both,
what a wonderful world this would be.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is up to you, the fan, the taxpayer, the thoughtful
citizen, the good American, to have the final say on whether the
Rockets will move into their $175 million court of last resort. The
lease also provides for a possible future major-league hockey team,
owner unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Checking the city's temperature, we find there is clearly wider
support for the arena than existed in 1999, when a referendum was
voted down by a sobering margin of 10 percent. At least, there is
less organized opposition, although the wild card in this deck is
the expected large turnout in November for a presidential election,
with a ballot led by the governor of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom _ no pun intended _ is suburban voters,
also known as Republicans, are less likely to vote for a sports
cathedral to be erected in downtown Houston. They will question the
cost, the effective use, the need, the long-term benefits and how
long the driving time is to get home.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, a lot of questions remain about the virtues of the
deal, and the critics do not consider ``it's none of your
business'' a responsive answer. This is not to single out
Republicans, but there is a reason the Rockets and their allies
have been romancing County Judge Bob Eckels, county tax boss Paul
Bettencourt and county Republican Party chairman Gary Polland.
Eckels was neutral during the last campaign; Paul and Gary _ may we
call you Paul and Gary? _ were prominent among the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   You hate to see the issue become a political football, partly
because no one wants to be accused of mixing a metaphor. But face
it, when was the last time you heard of anyone taking a Democrat to
lunch?
</P>
<P>
   The outcome might be decided by political loyalties or
obligations. By now, the arguments have been repeated enough that
there seems no need to restate them here.
</P>
<P>
   Is this agreement a better deal for the city than the last one?
From most accounts, it can't help but pass that test. Is it a
terrific deal for owner Leslie Alexander? But, of course. The
Rockets keep all the revenue from the luxury boxes and personal
seat licenses, and most of the revenue from concessions, signage,
advertising and naming rights. So do most teams.
</P>
<P>
   We can discard the threat of the Rockets moving to Louisville or
Las Vegas as a way of winning over the undecided voters. There is
always a chance the Rockets might get a deal they can't refuse from
an offshore island, but Louisville never had any interest in
building an arena with public money, and the NBA needs Las Vegas
like it needs another paternity suit.
</P>
<P>
   But there is what we consider a valid and even compelling reason
to provide the Rockets with a state-of-the-art facility. We did it
for the Astros and are building one for an NFL team that exists for
the moment in our imaginations. If Houston is going to play Sports
Stadium Bingo, how can we in good conscience deny equal footing for
the Rockets, who have weathered a lot of storms in 30 years and
gave us two NBA championships?
</P>
<P>
   Students of the process might find this a thin case to sway a
jury, but it happens to be the truest one. A new arena might
provide more momentum for the downtown renewal, and might attract
more concerts and ice shows and circuses, events better suited to
18,000 seats.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is all teams in all sports crave the new revenue
streams from luxury suites and VIP boxes and control of the master
lease. The vintage train that runs on an irregular schedule at
Enron Field is a gravy train, and the new football stadium is going
to be bigger, richer and smarter. The Rockets want theirs. We can't
spell it out any more clearly than this, and the only question left
isn't about economics or saving the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The question is: Do we give the Rockets the same advantages as
other members of the Planet Jock? I think so, and I am not one of
those protesters worried sick that we will run out of stadiums in a
few years. In the interest of full disclosure, I will remind those
who need reminding that I owned stock in the Rockets when they
moved from San Diego and played their first season in six
locations, including New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   That was a challenge, not a hardship, but the Rockets deserve
some credit for still being here.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
