r a BC-BUSH-SPEECH-SFCHRON(A     08-04 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SPEECH-SFCHRON(ANALYSIS) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SPEECH MAKES HIS CASE FOR CHANGE IN SPITE OF PROSPERITY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  PHILADELPHIA _ Bill Clinton campaigned for change in 1992 when
the economy was stagnant. Ronald Reagan called for change in 1980
when 52 Americans were being held hostage in Iran.
<P>
   Thursday night George W. Bush declared himself an agent of
change at a time when the economy is booming and the nation is at
peace.
</P>
<P>
   In an address that served as the nation's best introduction to
former President Bush's son, the Texas governor tried hard to keep
his boyish smirk in check as he offered his most detailed case yet
as to why eight years of Democratic control of the White House
should come to an end:
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of decency. It's a matter of vision. It's a matter
of responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Bush hardly mentioned his opponent, Vice President Al Gore, by
name. And he never specifically referred to President Clinton's
draft avoidance, his extra-marital affairs, or his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But he made it clear that his candidacy would offer a sharp
break from what many view as the excesses of a pair of spoiled baby
boomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hundred years from now, this must not be remembered as an
age rich in possession and poor in ideals,'' Bush said. ``Our
generation has a chance to reclaim some essential values. To show
we have grown up before we grow old.''
</P>
<P>
   As Republicans leave Philadelphia, ahead in the polls and
confident of victory, the shape of their upcoming campaign is
coming into focus.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to saddle Democrats with a failed economy or a foreign
policy crisis, they will try to present themselves as a refreshing
alternative to the political swamp of attack dog politics, negative
campaigning, and poll-driven policy decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not need to take your pulse before I know my own mind. I
do not reinvent myself at every turn. I am not running in borrowed
clothes,'' Bush declared.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Clinton and Gore at the hip, Bush suggested that the
pair squandered this ``unique moment of history'' because of their
self-centered obsession with advancing their political careers.
</P>
<P>
   `` For me, gaining this office is not the ambition of a
lifetime, but it  &UR; is  &LR; the opportunity of a lifetime,'' Bush said.
``And I will make the most of it. I believe great decisions are
made with care, made with conviction, not made with polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Clinton's impeachment and Gore's difficulties with
campaign-finance scandals went unmentioned, the issue of character
was implicit throughout Bush's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I put my hand on the Bible,'' he said, reviving the most
popular line from his campaign stump speech, ``I will swear to not
only uphold the laws of our land, I will swear to uphold the honor
and the dignity of the office to which I have been elected, so help
me God.''
</P>
<P>
   Fundamental issues divide the Republicans from the Democrats _
tax cuts, social security, gun control, abortion, to name a few.
Bush touched on all of them last night, but spent little time
trying to convince Americans that gun control is unconstitutional
or that abortion is murder.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican faithful packed in the convention center would
have loved nothing better. But Bush geared his remarks to moderate
swing voters, who may have been watching at home.
</P>
<P>
   His message, reinforced on each of the convention's four nights,
is that Republicans care about minorities, immigrants, the poor,
the disadvantaged. This is no longer your Daddy's Republican Party.
Delegates danced to the music of the Delfonics, Harold Melvin &AMP; the
Blue Notes, and thrust their fists in the air when Mick Jagger
yowled ``Start Me Up'' on the arena's PA system after Bush's
address concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Just a year and half after Republicans, led by Newt Gingrich,
Tom Delay, Dick Armey and other unabashed conservatives, impeached
President Clinton, Bush seemed to make certain that the party's
more strident wing was kept out of view.
</P>
<P>
   Bush talked about his good friend Bob Bullock, a powerful force
in Texas politics for decades, and a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked with Republicans and Democrats to get things done,''
Bush said before appealing to Longhorn pride in another jab at Gore
for his style of attack style politics. ``He worked by my side,
endorsed my re-election, and I know he is with me in spirit to
those who would malign our state for political gain. Don't mess
with Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives, who seem to trust Bush's convictions as well as
his political instincts, showed no signs of rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This convention is designed for a party whose base is very,
very happy,'' Armey said. ``We can afford the luxury of reaching
out to middle land _ where Ronald Reagan did so well.''
</P>
<P>
   If they didn't get the forceful policy speech they were looking
for, the red meat crowd adored his attacks on the Clinton-Gore
political style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their war room is up and running,'' Bush said as he concluded
his remarks. ``Their attacks will be relentless. But they will be
answered.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are facing something familiar,'' he asserted. ``But they
are facing something new.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
