<SLUG> BC-BBA-WISE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-WAVES PITCHER IMPRESSES ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ There's no mistaking Matt Wise in the Anaheim
Angels clubhouse. He's the guy with the biggest smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   For good reason. the 25-year-old right-handed pitcher took his
first step into a bright future, making his major-league debut for
the Angels Wednesday. It was a debut that Wise, a native of La
Verne, Calif., and graduate of Bonita High School, will long
remember.
</P>
<P>
   In two innings of relief for Anaheim starter Ken Hill, Wise
threw 31 pitches. He struck out one, gave up one hit and walked no
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really have time to think about what I was doing out
there,'' Wise said after the game. ``I just wanted to throw
strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wise was brought up to the Angels from their Triple-A club in
Edmonton, Alberta. There, he compiled a 9-6 record with a 3.69 ERA
and two complete games in 19 starts for the Trappers.
</P>
<P>
   For now he will fill the roster spot left vacant when right-
hander Al Levine was placed on the 15-day disabled list due to
inflammation of the right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Wise said he got the callup from the Angels just as he was
preparing to take mound Tuesday. By 6:30 a.m. he was on a plane
home and arrived at the stadium around noon for the 1 p.m. game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long day,'' Wise said. ``I'm so tired that all of
this hasn't really sunk in yet. I'm sure it will soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, Wednesday wasn't Wise's first time on the mound for
the Angels. He took several trips to the hill for the club in
spring training. Manager Mike Scioscia had nothing but praise for
his young pitcher, who attended Pepperdine and Cal State Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   His performance certainly made it apparent that he's recovered
well from reconstructive elbow surgery and is ready to contribute.
If anything, his time in the minor leagues has only sharpened his
skills, Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt was everything that we saw in the spring,'' Scioscia
said. ``He made some adjustments which look like he's ready for the
challenge of the major leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   One the big assets Wise brings to the game is mastery of a
repertoire of pitches, Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed real good location with his fastball,'' Scioscia
said. ``He's got a nice, tight breaking ball and he mixed some good
changeups in there too. So I think he's got a good combo.''
</P>
<P>
   While it's not going to break any speed records, Wise's fastball
is decent. He was clocked at 91, 93 and 90 on successive pitches
during Wednesday's game. All three were faster than Hill's best,
which crossed the plate at 89.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to throw hard, while mixing up his pitch selection
to confuse batters, will help Wise earn a more-permanent spot on
the team's roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a guy who can mix up his pitches, it's going to
be exciting to see how he contributes,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   How long his current stay with the Angels will last is anyone's
guess. Wise is happy to be able to spend some time with his wife,
Amy. High school sweethearts, the two were married six months ago
and Wise has been on the road ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be nice to spend a day or two at home,'' Wise said.
``That's one thing I'm really looking forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Scioscia, he said that no matter what happens to Wise
this season, for now he's and Angel _ and a good one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to keep an eye on him,'' Scioscia said. ``Not only
now while he's up here _ but in the future, 'cause this guy is
certainly one of our young pitchers who we're looking to have in
the mix.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
