<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2474 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-GOP-CONVENTION-SFCHRO     08-04 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONVENTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BUSH ISSUES CALL TO RID THE POLITICAL SLATE OF CLINTON AND GORE  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Portraying himself as a healer, Texas Gov. George
W. Bush issued a rousing call to clean the political slate Thursday
night, saying, ``We will seize this moment of American promise ...
we will use these good times for great goals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My fellow Americans, we can begin again,'' Bush told wildly
cheering delegates as he formally accepted the Republican party's
presidential nomination. ``This administration had their moment.
They have not led. We will.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 52-minute address that served as the defining moment of his
presidential bid, Bush argued his case as a Washington outsider
with character and conviction prepared to preside over a new era,
while dismissing the Clinton-Gore administration as a tired,
cynical vestige of old-style politics.
</P>
<P>
   Climaxing the four-day Republican National Convention, Bush's
tough talk fired up a GOP audience, starved for a winning
presidential candidate, and provoked a deafening ovation as
delegates in the First Union Center cheered, beat drums, blew
whistles and tossed their hats in the air.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, who had decried what he called the politics of
negativity from Vice President Al Gore _ and who had promised a
positive and upbeat campaign _ took off the gloves. He fired off a
battery of charges and insults at the current administration,
describing it as one of ``so much promise, to no great purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For eight years, the Clinton/Gore administration has coasted
through prosperity,'' he said to cheers. ``And the path of least
resistence is always downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   In a clear signal that the presidential campaign will be as much
about Clinton as Gore, Bush made the president a particular target
of his barbs. He had ``so many talents, so much charm, such great
skill,'' Bush said. ``But to what end?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of seizing the moment, the Clinton/Gore administration
has squandered it. We have seen a steady erosion of American power
and an unsteady exercise of American influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Without ever mentioning Gore's name, Bush belittled his
Democratic opponent as a narrow-minded thinker lacking political
vision, with ``the philosophy of the stop sign.''
</P>
<P>
   In a riff that brought the house down, Bush said, ``If my
opponent had been there at the moon launch, it would have been `a
risky rocket scheme.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And if he'd been there when the Internet was invented, well,''
he said, ``I understand he was actually there for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush then stapled Gore to Clinton, charging both with being
poll-watching politicians driven by ambition and lacking in
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not need to take your pulse before I know my own mind,''
Bush told the delegates. ``I do not reinvent myself at every turn.
I am not running on borrowed clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush acknowledged that he ``may lack the polish of Washington,''
but suggested that was not necessarily bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have enemies to fight. And I have no stake in the
bitter arguments of the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a chief executive who sets an agenda, sets big
goals, and rallies people to believe and achieve them,'' he said.
``Give me the opportunity to lead this nation and I will lead.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush also used the moment to address a central challenge of
his campaign _ why Americans should support a change of leadership
in strong economic times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times of plenty, like times of crisis, are tests of American
character,'' he said. ``Prosperity can be a tool in our hands ...
or it can be a drug in our system, dulling our sense of urgency, of
empathy, of duty,'' he said. ``Our opportunities are too great, our
lives too short, to waste this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech was very different from Bush's campaign stump speech,
which has changed little and served to outline his promise of
``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Thursday night's effort laid out a broad political
philosophy and vision.
</P>
<P>
   Bush underscored his themes of inclusion and the need to expand
the GOP's big tent to include non-traditional constituencies,
saying his party must reach Americans who feel left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are their country, too,'' he said. ``And each of us must
share in its promise or that promise is diminished for all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now the party of ideas and innovation. ... The party of
idealism and inclusion. ... The party of a simple and powerful
hope.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush also addressed bread-and-butter issues of his campaign,
portraying himself as an agent of change who will reach across
party lines to seek reforms in areas such as Social Security and
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time for Republicans and Democrats to end the
politics of fear and save Social Security, together,`` he said.
``Now is the time to make Head Start an early learning program,
teach all of our children to read, and renew the promise of
America's public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   He decried Americans schools that have relied on ``the soft
bigotry of low expectations,'' and argued that ``one size does not
fit all when it comes to education.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also called for tax relief, saying to cheers, ``the surplus
is not the government's money. The surplus is the people's money.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor pledged to provide the military with ``a means to
keep the peace ... and a commander-in-chief who respects our men
and women in uniform.'' He also made it clear that he would dump
the ``outmoded'' anti-ballistic missile treaty with Russia and
build an anti-missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who unlike Gore did not serve in Vietnam, said ``a
generation shaped by Vietnam must remember the lessons of Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also explored themes which, until recently, were
not often touched on by Republican leaders calling for fewer
government programs.
</P>
<P>
   He promised low-income Americans tax credits ``to buy the
private health insurance they need and deserve,'' and a ``next bold
step of welfare reform'' which would ``support the heroic work of
homeless shelters and hospices, foot pantries and pregnancy crisis
centers.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in one of the more poignant moments of his speech, Bush
told delegates that America is endangered by the growing division
between the rich and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one side are wealth and technology, education and ambition.
On the other side of the wall are poverty and prison, addiction and
despair,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fellow Americans, we must tear down that wall,'' Bush said,
pointedly echoing President Reagan's famous call about the Berlin
Wall.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also dealt directly with one of the potentially sensitive
issues of his campaign, abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will lead our nation toward a culture that values life _ the
life of the elderly and the sick, the life of the young, and the
life of the unborn,'' he said to one of the night's biggest bursts
of applause. ``Good people can disagree on this issue ... (but)
when Congress sends me a bill against partial birth abortion, I
will sign it into law.''
</P>
<P>
   The evening was punctuated by touching, and skillful, video
presentations aimed at introducing voters to the man behind the
nomination. The videos showed him at home, usually in warm,
humorous situations _ even including commercial outtakes _ touching
on his childhood, his courtship of his wife, Laura, his down-home
Texas roots and his closeness to family.
</P>
<P>
   Bush took the stage, thanking his father, former President Bush,
his mother, Barbara, and his wife and family.
</P>
<P>
   But he also had kind words for Sen. John McCain, whom he said
provided ``a touching tribute to America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
