<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SRI-LANKA-TAMILS (Chennai, India) _ Sri Lanka's ruling coalition
has proposed a new constitution that would give greater political
autonomy to the country's minority Tamil population in the hope
that _ if adopted _ it would help end the 17-year war waged by
separatist rebels for a Tamil homeland. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   BRITIAN-QUEEN-MOTHER (London) _ Queen Elizabeth, the Queen
Mother, turns 100 years old Friday, and the British have been
commemorating the event with what could be the last full-throated
hurrah for the crown. There have been full dress parades, Royal Air
Force flyovers, pageant-filled church services, ``God Bless You
Ma'am'' tabloid headlines and editorials crediting her with having
saved the monarchy from perils ranging from the abdication of her
brother-in-law to the bombing of Buckingham Palace by the Germans
to the dysfunctional family behavior of modern-day Windsors. By
Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KY-SCHOOL-RAMPAGE (West Paducah, Ky.) _ After their lives were
changed by a 14-year-old killer, the parents of three girls who
were gunned down in a school shooting here sued more than 50 people
they said shared responsibility for the deaths. They sued the
killer and his parents, teachers, school officials, other
teen-agers, neighbors, and the makers of violent videogames, Web
sites and movies. But, after a string of recent legal defeats in
which two judges have dismissed virtually all of the claims, there
will be just one defendant remaining: the killer himself, Michael
Carneal. He is the only one the courts have said can be held liable
for the deaths. The story of the lawsuits shows how difficult it is
to assign blame to the many people who, in retrospect, might have
been able to prevent rampage killings, and it shows how hard it is
to unravel what really happened in cases that are, by definition,
unfathomable. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SCHOOLS-RACE (Undated) _ The town of Nyack, N.Y., has
unofficially done what New York state and many other states will
soon require of all school districts: It has broken down academic
achievement by race. But its experience provides a cautionary tale.
The release of the numbers divided what had been seen as a diverse
and tolerant community in a way most people thought nothing ever
could. Some black parents decried how schools were segregating and
shortchanging their kids while white parents defended the schools,
pointing the finger at what they called neglect in black families.
Many affluent black parents decried the statistics themselves for
perpetuating painful stereotypes. In the tension, car windows were
smashed and confrontations erupted on the sidewalks. By Kate
Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BEACHES-POLLUTION (Los Angeles) _ The number of
pollution-related beach closures and advisories nationwide
increased by 50 percent between 1997 and 1999, with more than half
in California, according to a report released by the Natural
Resources Defense Council. The numbers are thought to reflect not
increased pollution but increased monitoring, particularly in
California. By Barbara Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EARLY-LIFE (Undated) _ Based on the chemical composition of
ancient rocks, scientists have developed a method to deduce the
amount of oxygen in the early atmosphere, thus giving insight into
the rise of the earliest forms of life. By Kenneth Chang.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GUARD _ The Army is proposing to change the way that it
deploys National Guard units in national emergencies or regional
conflicts. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SILICON-VALLEY (Beijing) _ Anyone searching for the soul
of China's Silicon Valley can find it here, up four flights of
concrete stairs, past walls with peeling paint and ledges strewn
with beer bottles, down a darkened hallway and inside what was once
the student activity room at Qinghua University Dormitory No. 20.
By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   KODAK-DIGITAL (Undated) _ The Kodak name is showing up in a lot
more places these days. Indeed, the unifying theme of the latest
products to carry the Kodak brand is that they have nothing to do
with capturing images, Kodak's traditional forte, and everything to
do with ``repurposing'' them _ industry parlance for the many
high-tech ways that people now view, swap, manipulate, store, print
and display images. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-DISCLOSE (Undated) _ Despite an outpouring of support
from individual investors and consumer groups, federal securities
regulators are still scrambling to revise a proposed rule against
selective disclosure of corporate information before it comes up
for a vote next week. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   ACCOUNTING-NORRIS-COLUMN (New York) _ Bull markets may not cause
companies to fiddle with their books, but they certainly increase
the rewards to be gained from creative accounting. Consider the
case of the Unify Corp., which this week put its two top officials
on leave and said that its revenue for the last fiscal year, and
perhaps the one before that, had been overstated. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ROCKPORT-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ An offbeat new campaign embraces
the philosophy of the comedian Jeff Foxworthy in declaring: ``No
shirt. No shoes. No problem!'' And what in the world are the
shirtless hunks and hunkettes peddling in the ads? Shoes, made by
the Rockport Co. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COLUMN (Philadelphia) _ Gail Collins offers a critique
of the GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ George W. Bush, writes Thomas L.
Friedman, is no longer vulnerable on foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column on Dawn
Ellerbe, who is a medal prospect in the first Olympic competition
for female hammer-throwers. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROSLER-RETROSPECTIVE (New York) _ If you happen to be on
basically OK terms with the world as it is, the alert, irritated,
combative work of the U.S. artist Martha Rosler may not be your cup
of tea. ``Martha Rosler: Positions in the Life World,'' is a
30-year-plus career retrospective divided between the New Museum of
Contemporary Art and the International Center of Photography. By
Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-SOUNDTRACKS (Undated) _ New movies come in on waves of
hype and anticipation, followed, if they're lucky, by swelling word
of mouth. When the waves recede, they leave behind something
tangible: soundtrack albums. If summer is a prime time for movie
releases, it's also a good time to look back over recent albums,
some of which are better than the movies themselves. By Jon
Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DANCING (New York) _ It is summer in New York, this year a
season that jumps from muggy heat to damp chill without warning.
There is relatively little dance in pleasantly climate-controlled
theaters. So what do those mad creatures called dancers do? Forget
about vacations or more trips to the office-temp center. Dancers
dance. So they are taking to the city's parks, rooftops, gardens
and empty buildings over the next four weeks in a surge of activity
that truly offers something for just about everyone. By Jennifer
Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE-RENAISSANCE (Undated) _ The presence of what might be
called the eternal modern can be felt in certain great examples of
African, Egyptian and early Greek art and different kinds of Asian
art. Right now this presence hovers like a beautiful mist over
``The Arts of Hon'ami Koetsu, Japanese Renaissance Master'' at the
Philadelphia Museum of Art, which pays homage to a late
16th-century artist who has become known as ``the Leonardo da Vinci
of Japanese art.'' By Roberta Smith.
</P>
