 INSTANT APPLAUSE METER ON THE WEB  &HT;     By VLAE KERSHNER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time George W. Bush finished taking his applause last
night, the political community already knew how his speech played
with Web watchers _ pretty well.
</P>
<P>
   The instantaneous feedback came from  &UR; www.speakout.com  &LR; in
cooperation with MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   The SpeakOut Web page displays a dial with a scale of 1 to 100,
initially set at a neutral level of 50. Users move the dial to the
right to register a higher number when they agree with the speaker
and move it to the left when they disagree.
</P>
<P>
   The scores are not a scientific sample of all voters, but they
are adjusted so that the gender and party affiliation of the users
match those of the voting public.
</P>
<P>
   Bush scored a 55. That's favorable, but not up with the
highest-ranked speech of the convention, John McCain's 62. Dick
Cheney's score was unavailable _ there was a network failure
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Bush got particularly high scores when he talked about restoring
character to the White House and fostering an era of
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The scores also went up when he talked about education and when
he said welfare reform should include support for homeless shelters
and food pantries.
</P>
<P>
   His lowest scores came when he attacked the Clinton-Gore
administration, mostly because Democrats didn't like it.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, there was no gender gap _ women may not have
voted for Bush's father in 1992, but they liked the son's speech
exactly as well as men did.
</P>
<P>
   I spent the first half of the speech with MSNBC, then logged on
to  &UR; www.voter.com,  &LR; which has, theoretically, a great format.
</P>
<P>
   Voter.com allows users to watch a speech, see how it is rated by
selected groups of voters and delegates, and participate in a chat,
all at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush vowed to support the rights of the unborn, that was
red meat to the delegates. But his ranking with voters went down,
although there was no way of telling how far, because the scale
wasn't lined up properly with the bars on the chart.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DISABILITY COVERAGE: &LR;  One good thing about the Web is that it
allows targeted coverage to specific groups. At this year's
conventions,  &UR; www.wemedia.com  &LR; is offering news for the disabled.
Among the articles: a story about Heather Whitestone McCallum, the
first hearing-impaired Miss America, who introduced the Laura Bush
video tribute last night; and interviews with both Hillary Rodham
Clinton and her opponent in the U.S. Senate race in New York, Rick
Lazio, both of whom have a strong interest in disability issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
