 FORMER PRIEST FINDS JAIL IS HELL  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ He is charged with being a serial child molester
and an embezzler supreme, but he is uncomfortable in jail and wants
you to help spring him.
<P>
   Brother, can you spare a house?
</P>
<P>
   Patrick O'Shea, the former Catholic monsignor, 16 years at two
parishes in San Francisco, is being held in isolation at the County
Jail on $5 million bail.
</P>
<P>
   He is charged with 224 counts of child molestation.
</P>
<P>
   It might be six more months before he goes to trial, and O'Shea
finds jail, you know, confining. Especially when compared to the
vacation house he bought with, according to a lawsuit, $250,000 in
church funds he ripped off over the years.
</P>
<P>
   That's not counting the $2.5 mil that he and some other priests
cost the church in a '96 settlement with 15 molestation victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assure you that no one knows what prison is like until one
experiences it,'' O'Shea says in an appeal letter to some old
friends.
</P>
<P>
   The former priest blames his high bail on the D.A.'s political
shenanigans. O'Shea asks that friends put up their house(s) as
collateral to help him make bail. He wouldn't ask ``unless I felt
it so important to my sanity that I get out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wonder how much cash ``friends'' could raise by pawning the
world's smallest violin?
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU'RE GOIN' to San Francisco, be sure to put some padlocks
on your flowers. (Apologies to Scott McKenzie.)
</P>
<P>
   In a series of daring predawn raids, thieves are digging up and
carting off flowers from Cayuga Park and other city parks.
Apparently, the flowers are then sold at the Flower Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Hydrangeas have a street value of $3 per stem.
</P>
<P>
   Cops and park officials are on the case. So if you stop to smell
the roses, you'd better not be carrying a shovel.
</P>
<P>
   STEVE YOUNG, Republican.
</P>
<P>
   That's a bitter pill for many Bay Area liberals who held out
hope for Young, who had never really announced before. He dressed
casual, lived cheap, showed a lot of outwardly liberal-leaning
signs.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe Steve really is a Democrat and is at the Republican
convention only because he's a compassionate liberal and figures
the GOP needs his prayers.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a bit sad down the road, though, when Steve runs for
president and can't carry 49er country.
</P>
<P>
   THE AVERAGE Los Angeles driver burns 390 gallons of gas per
year, according to one study. The average San Francisco driver goes
through 520 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our 49-square-mile patch of paradise is more fuel-intensive
than the sprawl that calls itself L.A.?'' asks Gar Smith. ``How
could this be? My only theory is that S.F. drivers spend more time
endlessly circling the blocks looking for parking spots.''
</P>
<P>
   NO PROBLEM, says the Hearst Corp., nobody will lose jobs over
the merger with The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fangs, new owners of the Ex, have said they intend to
service only San Francisco and maybe San Mateo County. So out in
the 'burbs and the countryside, hundreds of independent Examiner
dealers and carriers quietly sweat it out.
</P>
<P>
   WONDER BREAD builds mayoral war chests millions of ways.
</P>
<P>
   A San Francisco jury has called for a huge judgment against the
maker of Wonder Bread, on behalf of plaintiffs who charged
systematic racial discrimination in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney fees, when collected, will be huge. The attorney is
Angela Alioto, who has been hinting she plans to run for San
Francisco mayor next time around  &UR; if  &LR; she can raise enough of her
own money that she doesn't have to sell her soul to campaign
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   The Wonder Bread dough should vault Alioto into the race.
</P>
<P>
   She'll campaign as the Anti-Machine mayoral candidate, and her
star looks even brighter when you consider that she's winning huge
court judgments against corporate America, on behalf of the
underdog.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS CAN'T sing in booze joints, at least not in California.
</P>
<P>
   So several scheduled concerts of 14-year-old country music
phenom Kristen McNamara have been canceled, at places like
Sweetwater in Mill Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``No problem,'' Kristen told her people. ``Let's just raise some
money for charity.''
</P>
<P>
   So she's planning at least one benefit concert at the Palace of
Fine Arts, sometime in late September. Proceeds to the Little Jim
Club of California Pacific Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   They help babies. Now a babe helps them.
</P>
<P>
   HOOKERS and their advocates want San Francisco to decriminalize
prostitution, saying that would decrease violence against sex
workers.
</P>
<P>
   They claim that under decriminalization, cops would be more
sympathetic to hookers who are beaten and raped.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning seems faulty. If cops are ignoring real and
violent crimes, against hookers or anyone, the problem isn't the
legal status of the profession, it's the cops.
</P>
<P>
   And what's with this ``sex workers'' stuff? Is that kind of
sugar-coating appropriate here? It's like calling drug dealers
``pharmaceutical marketers.''
</P>
<P>
   If the hookers can't get help from the Board of Supervisors,
maybe they can call on OSHA.
</P>
<P>
   MAILBAG: ``What you gotta do is keep an eye out for a deal like
the Fangs got! I'll even go partners with you.'' (Signed, R.B.)
(Note: The Fang family bought the Examiner for $100 and will be
given as much as $66 million in subsidies.)
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, R.B., my tax attorneys say I can't afford to receive that
much free money. Besides, Willie doesn't fancy my horse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
