<HEADLINE>
MARINERS FACING CRUCIAL ROAD TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the things about being the two American League
teams farthest to the west and north is that Oakland and Seattle
frequently get paired together.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago at this time, the Mariners played the Rangers and
Angels while the A's played the Angels and Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing is happening this week, although the stakes are
getting higher.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle plays the AL East-leading New York Yankees on the road
for four consecutive games starting Friday, while the A's are
playing at the AL Central-leading Chicago White Sox three times.
</P>
<P>
   Then, starting Tuesday, the Mariners head to Chicago and the A's
head to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is in first place in the West. Oakland, riding a
five-game winning streak, is two games back. The A's would be the
wild-card entrant from the AL if the current standings hold.
</P>
<P>
   That makes this next week huge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a key part of the schedule,'' Mariners manager Lou
Piniella said. ``We'll be trading off teams. We're both going to
parks where it's going to be tough to win. It's going to be
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland manager Art Howe shares those sentiments. His team has
been able to make up one game in the standings on the Mariners
since the All-Star break. A's play just six games on this trip,
while the Mariners _ thanks to the makeup of a rained-out April
game in Chicago _ play eight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big trip,'' Howe said. ``We're playing two
first-place clubs. In a way, we'll see how we measure up. But
either way, I feel good about our team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to be playing this well at this point. That's
what's most important. We know we can play with anybody. We just
have to go out and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, do the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was the team's first day off after having played 21
games in 21 days after the All-Star break. It wasn't much of a day
off, given that storms in the New York area forced the Mariners'
charter to divert to Pittsburgh for four hours. It wasn't much of a
day of rest.
</P>
<P>
   And now the Mariners have four against the Yankees, four against
the White Sox and a total of 14 games in the next 13 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little tired, that's no secret,'' shortstop Alex
Rodriguez said Wednesday. ``The day off is important. But the games
just keep getting bigger for us. New York is always a tough place
to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are just 2-9 in Yankee Stadium over the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked playing there,'' said designated hitter
Edgar Martinez, who was born in New York, although he grew in
Puerto Rico. ``The fans are always into it; they know what's going
on. It's been a tough place for us to play, but it's a good-hitting
park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to play the Yankees there.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning would be more fun still.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
