<HEADLINE>
JOBS IN JEOPARDY FOR HALF OF PAC-10
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Paul Hackett of USC did an odd bit about his
neckware: ``I broke out my best new Jerry Garcia tie and I'm ready
for the start of a new era.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Toledo of UCLA tried a variation on an old coaches' comedy
theme: ``Our offensive linemen are all back. I don't know if that's
good or bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Price of Washington State recycled his own year-old joke:
``I'm the only coach in the history of the school to turn the
program around !ital!twice. I turned it around the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which goes to show that gallows humor takes many forms,
and sometimes it's actually humorous.
</P>
<P>
   The head coaches who appeared for Pacific-10 Football Media Day
at a Los Angeles airport hotel might as well have been handed
blindfolds and cigarettes along with the microphone Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely have so many Pac-10 coaches begun preseason practice with
their jobs on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's Tyrone Willingham is safe, meaning he could survive a
losing season, after coaching the Cardinal to the conference
championship in 1999. Oregon's Mike Bellotti should be all right,
having put up five consecutive winning records. Washington's Rick
Neuheisel and Oregon State's Dennis Erickson have the cushion of
big-time reputations, although each has a penchant for controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo might be a year away from the hard questions.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody else _ half the Pac _ is in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Price is in trouble with Washington State's new president and
athletic director if he can't improve on back-to-back 10th-place
finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Holmoe is in trouble if he drops a fourth straight losing
season on the Cal faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Tomey is in trouble at Arizona if he can't improve on
``probably the worst job of coaching I've done since I've been
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Snyder is in trouble at Arizona State if he can't bridge
the gap between what he calls ``the top teams and the . . .
not-the-top teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett is in trouble if USC doesn't improve _ by a lot _ on the
sixth-place finish that marked its worst in the Pac-10 since Larry
Smith sank to eighth in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   To ease his mind, or weigh on it, USC has been picked a close
second in the Pac-10 behind Washington in a media poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure? I didn't come back to USC to sit back in Manhattan
Beach and look at the sunset,'' said Hackett, whose season will
kick off early when USC faces Penn State on Aug. 27 in the Kickoff
Classic in East Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   At least this season he has company in other Pac-10 coaches. And
rightfully so after the conference's performance in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   __ The Pac-10 lost 18 nonconference games to equal the most
since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   __ The Pac-10 didn't have a team ranked higher than No. 19
(Oregon) in the final Associated Press poll for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   __ The Pac-10 didn't place a player in the top 10 of Heisman
Trophy voting for the first time since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   As strangely quiet as the offseason has been, without a Pac-10
coaching change for the first time since 1993, this season could be
a bloodbath.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to me the secret to withstanding the pressure is
adopting the proper attitude. You can be a defiant one like
Hackett, sticking your chin out at your critics. You can be an
optimist like Price, still smiling after a last-place finish, or a
pessimist like Willingham, on edge after a Rose Bowl trip.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you a good story,'' he said. ``My first year at
Weber State, the school was coming off a 3-8 season and had a new
president, and we opened against Long Beach State, back when they
had a football program. We took a bus all the way from Ogden, Utah,
to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played terrible. The new president wasn't pleased with the
performance and he mentioned that to some of the assistant coaches
during the game. Our coaches were doing their resume writing in the
back of the bus going home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We proceded to win our next 10 games. The athletic director
quit and they gave me an extended contract and made me athletic
director as well as coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's always darkest before the dawn.''
</P>
<P>
   A check of the record shows Weber State went 7-4 in 1981,
Price's first season as head coach. But if Price remembers going
10-1, well, that's the power of positive thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, here's Willingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``My principle is that my job is on the line every day,'' he
said. ``When is a coach's job !ital!not on the line?''
</P>
<P>
   Of the three, the Hackett attitude is the manliest, and the
Price approach sounds nicest. But Willingham's is the most
practical. If you're always paranoid, you're always prepared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 0155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
