<P>
   BORDER-RECRUITS (San Antonio) _ As the federal government aims
to complete Congress' five-year plan of hiring 5,000 new border
agents by October 2001, recruiters are hitting the airwaves,
theaters and shopping malls to bolster one of the nation's most
storied and controversial law enforcement agencies. By Dane
Schiller.
</P>
<P>
   TAX-HOLIDAY (San Antonio) _ Notebooks, pens, pencils, crayons,
erasers and lunch boxes remind shoppers that a new school year is
just around the corner. But school supplies won't be exempted from
state and local taxes during the annual three-day tax-free holiday,
which starts Friday and ends Sunday. By LUCY HOOD.
</P>
<P>
   DOTCOM-DEVELOPMENTS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Mayor Willie
Brown, responding to outcries over gentrification of working-class
San Francisco neighborhoods, is moving to bring dot-com
developments firmly under the city's stringent growth-control
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   PLANES-GROUNDED (San Francisco) _ Alaska Airlines has grounded
18 Boeing MD-80 airliners to further inspect the planes' jackscrews
_a part implicated in January's crash of San Francisco-bound Flight
261 that killed 88 people off the Southern California coast.
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH-THEFT (San Antonio) _ Three 18th-century statues stolen
from Mission San Juan in San Antonio could disappear into an
international black market of stolen art treasures. However, if
quick cash was the motive, church officials said the value of the
artifacts can't be measured in monetary terms. By MICHAEL PARKER.
</P>
