A2628 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LATHAM-COLUMN05-COX     08-04 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Here's how to make 'Survivor' a show that's really worth
watching
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I watched ``Survivor'' the other night and when it was over I
danced around the den waving my arms, yelling, ``We're gonna be
rich! I just won a million dollars!''
</P>
<P>
   That's when my wife coolly informed me that you don't win the
money for just surviving watching the TV show. You have to be on
the island.
</P>
<P>
   What? You call that difficult? Heck, that looks like some fun.
Lie around on the beach all day, play a couple of games, go
fishing, soak in some rays, build a sandcastle....
</P>
<P>
   But watching the show is another matter. There are no telling
how many of my brain cells took a dive while I was watching that
mindless drivel. I figure they just simply surrendered. When I
experimented with ``Three's Company'' and the ``Dukes of Hazzard''
back in my wild days I rendered some of my gray matter useless, but
it was nothing like an hour spent with ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet this show is popular beyond all belief. Popular and, yet, so
completely fake. These people might not be eating quite like they
want but otherwise, they are in no danger of anything but boredom
and sunburn.
</P>
<P>
   I say if you're going to do it, make it a real test. Let's
release a two or three dozen grizzly bears on that island, then
we'll see some fun, by golly. I'd settle for a pride of lions or
even 50 hungry wolves for that matter. Maybe a hundred or so cobras
would do the trick. Better yet, just stick them all on there. At
least that would justify the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   It would also justify the winning of $1 million. As it turns
out, teat honor or achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they ought to do something that proves those staying
are better at something that matters than those getting kicked off.
Have a fishing tournament, or make them build the best hut, or
manufacture anti-venom for all those darn cobras.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is a good reason ``Survivor'' isn't very tough.
All the people who are responsible for producing the show have to
live out there also. The contestants don't have to worrying about
contending with a few million killer bees or a sudden influx of
man-eating alligators because these Hollywood types aren't about to
get that ``real.''
</P>
<P>
   For a fact, though this is called ``reality'' television, I
didn't see much of anything that was real. Fortunately, they didn't
show the nut who decided to walk around nude on his birthday (where
did they get these losers?).
</P>
<P>
   If real is what you are looking for, but surviving is still your
game, try putting these folks, say, in a public housing project in
one of those big cities for three months. There's no need to find
some island in the South Pacific, just give them a rental car and
let them drive around Miami. For that matter, there are places in
East Texas where these people would have trouble surviving just
because of their northern accents.
</P>
<P>
   Want to try survival? Put them in high school two-a-days next
week. Oh, yeah. Now there's something that would be worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (Texas) News
Messenger. His email is platham(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
