r k BC-MINTER-COLUNMN0805-CO     08-04 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUNMN0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A double scoop of news
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In all the years I toiled in the newspaper business I
never won a Pulitzer Prize, or any of the other big honors awarded
for outstanding journalistic feats.
</P>
<P>
   I don't argue with that, but in all modesty I had a couple of
``scoops'' I think deserved honorable mention. For anyone who
doesn't know, a ``scoop'' is when a reporter digs up a significant
story before anyone else. For example, if Chelsea Clinton decided
to marry one of the Bush grandsons and I found out about it and was
the first to get the story into print, I'd have myself a scoop.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, most scoops, along with two-headed crocodiles and
such, show up in newspapers sold at grocery counters. I'm not sure
why a scoop is called a scoop. Perhaps it has to do with small
shovels little old ladies carry when they walk their poodles.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters get most of their scoops from tips passed on by
friendly sources. Both of mine came that way. About 40 years ago, I
was visiting with Tom Nugent, the head football coach at the
University of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tip you off to the best quarterback in America,'' Tom
said. ``He's a kid from Beaver Falls, Pa. We recruited him for
Maryland but he failed his entrance exams, much to our
disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Reid, a former UGA player and one of Nugent's assistants,
telephoned Johnny Griffith, the head coach at Georgia. Bernie told
Johnny that judging from UGA journalism graduates of his
acquaintance, the young man should be able to enroll in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith agreed. He asked UGA's president, O.C. Aderhold, for
permission. Dr. Aderhold said no. ``If he can't qualify at
Maryland, we'd look pretty bad admitting him at Georgia,'' was his
sensible academic answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``So he's just enrolled with Bear Bryant at Alabama,'' Nugent
said. ``You watch. He's going to be the best quarterback in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you be so sure?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Beaver Falls to sign him to a scholarship,'' Nugent
answered. ``I took him out to dinner. High school signees being
entertained by their future coach normally order milk, iced tea or
a large Coke to go with the steak. When the waitress asked this kid
what he would like to drink, he ordered a double bourbon.''
</P>
<P>
   When I wrote that story it was the first time, as far as I know,
that anyone outside of Beaver Falls, Pa., had heard of Joe Namath.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to speculate how the history of UGA and
Southern football might read if Dr. Aderhold had said yes.
</P>
<P>
   The tip that led to my other scoop was passed along by Dr.
George Patton, then practicing veterinary medicine in College Park,
Ga., later famous as a master gardener and a county commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   George told me about a fish dog. I had heard of bird dogs, sheep
dogs and rabbit dogs, but I had never heard of a fish dog. George
explained that Hokey Jackson, a former UGA baseball player then
coaching in South Georgia, had a dog that rode in front of a boat,
pointing bream, both beds and singles, just like bird dogs locate
quail in piney woods.
</P>
<P>
   Being acquainted with Hokey, I was wary. But after making
telephone calls to sources in his part of the state, I was pretty
well convinced that he really did have a fish dog.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote the story. The newspaper artist did a drawing of Hokey
casting from the back of a boat with the fish dog in the bow,
frozen on a classic point: tail high, left foot lifted off the
deck. As far as I know, that was the first nnted bream. She sent
pictures. Being as she was the wife of one of the doctors who
treated the ``Three Faces of Eve'' patient at University Hospital,
I figured I was off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   I don't question Dr. Patton's latest dog story. I had noticed
the absence of usual summer gifts from his garden. I attributed the
missing care packages to the drought, until his neighbor, Phyllis
Webb, passed on the real answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Patton's dog is eating his tomatoes and corn, even digging
up carrots and eating them,'' she confided. George confirmed that
Japanese beetles, deer and raccoons have receded into minor
problems now that his golden retriever with an appetite for fresh
vegetables is ravaging the crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake is especially fond of corn on the cob,'' he said. ``I'm
trying to train him to just eat the nubbins and leave the best ears
for us.'' Good luck, George. For the gardening classes, if it's not
one thing it's another.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
