<HEADER>
A2630 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0805-C     08-04 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lone Star politics 101
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Non-Texans need to understand the importance of
Jan Bullock's introduction of George W. Bush at Thursday night's
Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the people in Kansas and Arkansas felt the same way
about the 1996 convention coverage when Bob Dole and Bill Clinton
accepted their party's nominations. I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   It's apparent, however, that a lot of this year's national
coverage of the GOP convention in Philadelphia has failed to
understand Texas politics.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when Rep. Jim Kolbe of Arizona, the only openly
gay Republican member of the House, spoke about international
trade, the television networks kept showing clips of several
members of the Texas delegation bowing their heads in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   The meaning of this, according to the TV commentators, was that
Bush's message of inclusiveness was phony since his own delegates
were showing their aversion to Kolbe's sexual orientation, or at
least to his prominence on the program.
</P>
<P>
   I have no doubt that those delegates were demonstrating their
dislike of both Kolbe's sexual orientation and the fact that Bush
included him as one of the convention's presenters.
</P>
<P>
   TALKING HEADS DON'T KNOW TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   What non-Texans don't understand, which includes the television
producers and talking heads who kept showing this clip, is that
Bush and his mainstream Republican supporters have been engaged in
a prolonged battle with a well-organized group of doctrinaire
religious fundamentalists who have attempted to run state
government and the state GOP party according to their narrow
dictates.
</P>
<P>
   This Texas group is not unlike a group of Republicans in Kansas
that gained a majority on the Kansas Board of Education. The Kansas
group embarrassed the Republican governor and most Kansans by
removing evolution from the state's science standards.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his supporters have had similar battles in Texas with
religious-right Republicans attempting to impose their beliefs on
public education.
</P>
<P>
   More than just education, these Republicans have attempted to
gain control of the GOP's reins of power by organizing on the
precinct level and backing stealth candidates who play down their
religious agenda. Bush is the enemy to this branch of Lone Star
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush didn't even bother attending the Texas Republican
convention this year. He wants to stick with his message of
reaching out and inclusiveness. Fighting with a group of people who
want to make the party more exclusive would not be helpful.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt these ``Bush delegates'' didn't like Jan Bullock, the
widow of Texas Democratic Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, introducing Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, a life-long Republican, and Bullock, a life- long
Democrat, forged a partnership where they put aside their party
differences when they were conducting state business. Bullock's
power was such that he could have killed any legislation Bush
supported. Instead, the two men decided to do what was best for
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock even supported Bush for his second term as governor. He
said Bush was better for Texas than his Democratic opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush won 70 percent of the vote in his second run for governor.
He picked up votes from independents and Democrats. He also nearly
doubled Hispanic and African American votes compared to his first
race. He carried all 254 Texas counties except 14. All top
statewide elected offices were filled by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   When Democrats ruled Texas, that party's main- stream constantly
feuded with a group of liberal Democrats who kept trying to take
power. Now mainstream Texas Republicans feud with their group of
nettlesome insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
