<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ WACO, Texas _ Non-Texans need to
understand the importance of Jan Bullock's introduction of George
W. Bush at Thursday night's Republican National Convention. Perhaps
the people in Kansas and Arkansas felt the same way about the 1996
convention coverage when Bob Dole and Bill Clinton accepted their
party's nominations. I don't know. It's apparent, however, that a
lot of this year's national coverage of the GOP convention in
Philadelphia has failed to understand Texas politics. (Rowland
Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ ATLANTA _ In all the years
I toiled in the newspaper business I never won a Pulitzer Prize, or
any of the other big honors awarded for outstanding journalistic
feats. I don't argue with that, but in all modesty I had a couple
of ``scoops'' I think deserved honorable mention. For anyone who
doesn't know, a ``scoop'' is when a reporter digs up a significant
story before anyone else. For example, if Chelsea Clinton decided
to marry one of the Bush grandsons and I found out about it and was
the first to get the story into print, I'd have myself a scoop.(Jim
Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ There is a good reason ``Survivor'' isn't very
tough. All the people who are responsible for producing the show
have to live out there also. The contestants don't have to worrying
about contending with a few million killer bees or a sudden influx
of man-eating alligators because these Hollywood types aren't about
to get that ``real.'' (Latham, Marshall News-Messenger) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHULKEN-COLUMN _ The yellowed picture of a dark-haired girl
hardly shows the creases of the years it rode out bombs in a young
man's wallet. Nor does the snapshot of him on her nightstand convey
the weight of her wondering whether he would come home from that
place where the world had gone to war. He gave four years because
he was asked, and because it was his way to honor obligation. She
waited four years because he was handsome and kind and funny.
Theirs is the story of a generation. It is as familiar as the dust
mice that live under the refrigerator at home, and as remarkable as
buried treasure. And now it has become the marketing tool of a
political party with both eyes fixed on the White House.(Shulken,
The (Greenville, N.C.) Daily Reflector)
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ Mary McCarty's column will return Aug. 9.
(McCarty, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ I suppose it behooves those of us who have often
grumped against the right-wing cultural warriors who harry the
producers and sponsors of art and entertainment they dislike to
defend Dr. Laura Schlessinger from the gay- and human-rights
activists who are ganging up on her and undermining a proposed TV
show featuring her. Happily, speaking up for her does not require
actually speaking well of Schlessinger. (Tom Teepen is national
correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED WEDNESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ In Germany last week, two lawyers asked the
nation's Minister for the Family and the Elderly to classify the
Bible as dangerous to children, much as some in the United States
last month condemned the latest Harry Potter book as not only
violent but anti-Christian as well. Book police are everywhere. It
was only a matter of time until they got to the Bible.(Kleinberg,
Cox News Service.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ PHILADELPHIA _ While there will be no lack of
polls in the next three months, they really don't reveal too much.
That's due to a little secret of U.S. presidential politics: There
won't be a national election either. (Andy Glass is a columnist for
Cox News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
