<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-EXPERTS-ON-BEST-SITES-HARVARD-BUSINESS-REPORT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST WEB SITES FOCUS ON CUSTOMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For immediate release.)  
 &HT;    
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is for use by clients of
The New York Times Syndicate's HARVARD WEEKLY BUSINESS REPORT, a
new service composed of two articles per week from the Harvard
Management Update newsletter, Harvard Management Communication
Letter and Balanced Scorecard Report. These articles will guide
your readers to the ideas, trends, tools and solutions that are
changing the world of business.) 
 &HT;    
 (For information about purchasing this article as a
``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a CLIENT of the HARVARD WEEKLY
BUSINESS REPORT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 &HT;    
 FROM: THE HARVARD MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION LETTER  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Many companies are moving away from bare-bones marketing sites
and are throwing millions of dollars at their Web sites _ more
graphics, more video and sound, more everything.
</P>
<P>
   The result? Although the sites are usually impressive, often
they fail to do such simple things as differentiate between product
X and product Y or clearly explain whom to contact for customer
service.
</P>
<P>
   One business manifesto holds that all commerce is about
conversations _ conversations between companies and employees,
between employees and customers, and among customers. The World
Wide Web facilitates these conversations in a way that hasn't been
possible since the days of the village market.
</P>
<P>
   Web-site design experts say the best business sites focus on
creating such conversations with their customers. Here are some
other pointers on improving an organization's site:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1. DEFINE THE SITE'S VALUE. &LR;  ``Most companies don't bother to
sit down before they design their Web site and say, `Why will
customers come here? What do I want them to do? Why would they come
back?''' says Adam Hartung, senior e-business partner at consulting
firm CSC in Chicago. ``If that customer doesn't get value out of
that Web site, you are going to have a bad design no matter how
many graphic artists you hire.''
</P>
<P>
   Theo Fels, vice president and creative director of the Internet
services firm Circle.com, adds, ``You have to go through a
discovery process of really understanding what your audience wants
from you and what is the best way to deliver it. You don't want
them poking around your site, trying to discover something and
getting very frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2. FOCUS ON BEHAVIORAL _ NOT DEMOGRAPHIC _ SEGMENTATION. &LR;  On
the Internet, demographic segmentation is pretty worthless, Hartung
says. ``When somebody comes to your Web site, you have no way of
knowing who they are. But there's a behavior that brought them
there. If you appeal to that behavior, you'll capture them and
you'll do well.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, a site selling groceries could be visited by
someone in a hurry to get something for that evening's dinner, or
by someone with 60 items on his or her grocery list. These are
vastly different behaviors. Consider multiple interfaces, using a
pull-down menu or other selection method, to discover why each
person is visiting the site. An individual's selection takes her
promptly to the interface she needs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 3. DESIGN FOR EFFORTLESS NAVIGATION. &LR;  Content is king, but
users need to be able to find that content easily and in a way
that's visually pleasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't throw your customers into the role of researcher when
they're trying to find out information about you and your
products,'' says Roger Black, chief creative officer for
Circle.com. ``Try to have your brand and your voice at every level.
If you're trying to be a friendly, customer-oriented company, then
your Web site needs to be that way, too. You can't say you care
about customers and then have a Web site that looks like a tax
form.''
</P>
<P>
   Some ways to do this:
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep the navigation consistent. Every page on the site should
have the same navigation bars and icons, so users can always see
how to get around and how to get back.
</P>
<P>
   _ Remember the audience. Once users can easily find their way
through the site, they want to read copy that is relevant to them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make it legible. The type on most sites is set at level two of
the five HTML levels. Instead, try using level three or four. Or
try setting at least the first paragraph in larger type to give
readers an easier way into the content.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 4. CONSIDER THE SITE COMPLEMENTARY TO _ NOT INDEPENDENT OF _
THE EXISTING OFFLINE CHANNELS. &LR;  Most companies with a presence on
the Web have other, more established channels. Even so-called
pure-plays have at least an offline marketing presence. Therefore,
one must consider how the company's Web site interacts in a world
that includes other channels, Hartung says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your Web site has a relationship to your sales force. To your
distributors. To your bricks-and-mortar retailers,'' he says. ``A
good design takes into account who the other channel players are.''
</P>
<P>
   Visually, that means reassuring the customers that they're going
to have the same satisfactory experience they've had with the
company offline by carrying over the visual branding or identity to
make them more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   You can pay a lot of money to consultants to provide what's
called information architecture, but ``nothing that they give you
falls outside the realm of common sense,'' Black says. ``If you
have concerns about your site, just ask your wife or husband or
your boyfriend or girlfriend to look at it and see what they say.
And typically they'll say, `I'm confused.' So you know something is
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the
HARVARD WEEKLY BUSINESS REPORT and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
</TEXT>
