<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2641 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-CORPORATE-BACKSTABBER     08-04 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORPORATE-BACKSTABBERS-HARVARD-BUSINESS-REPORT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEWARE OF CORPORATE BACKSTABBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For immediate release.)  
 &HT;    
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is for use by clients of
The New York Times Syndicate's HARVARD WEEKLY BUSINESS REPORT, a
new service composed of two articles per week from the Harvard
Management Update newsletter, Harvard Management Communication
Letter and Balanced Scorecard Report. These articles will guide
your readers to the ideas, trends, tools and solutions that are
changing the world of business.) 
 &HT;    
 (For information about purchasing this article as a
``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a CLIENT of the HARVARD WEEKLY
BUSINESS REPORT _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 &HT;    
 FROM: THE HARVARD MANAGEMENT UPDATE NEWSLETTER  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   When the long knives come out in the workplace, the attacker
must be confronted. For many people, the backstabber is usually a
familiar face: a colleague or an employee who acts like a friend in
public but badmouths co-workers in private.
</P>
<P>
   A backstabber may see a co-worker as a competitor for favor or
promotion. In organizations undergoing big changes, backstabbing
may be one way people fight to hold onto their jobs or get needed
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Here, three experts in interpersonal communications and
executive coaching offer tips on how to keep from becoming a
victim:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THINK BEFORE SPEAKING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A company wants its employees to cooperate with each other _ not
open their hearts to others on the floor. Keep in mind that
anything said ``in confidence'' by the watercooler could be passed
on to others.
</P>
<P>
   Backstabbers look for information to use against people they see
as threats to their career aspirations or power base, notes Mildred
Saunders, president of Milsaun &AMP; Co., a N.Y.-based firm that
coaches executives. The schemer, she adds, will try to get his or
her ``target'' to share personal secrets or professional opinions
that could undermine that person's position.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WATCH FOR SIGNS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to be paranoid. But if a colleague's smile seems a
little forced, or if he or she acts excessively chummy, be careful.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in the study of animal behavior have found that similar
behavior in chimpanzees reflects a highly agitated state. The
animal is preparing to defend its territory and is making a hostile
gesture to establish its dominance, says Andrew DuBrin, author of
``Winning Office Politics'' (Prentice Hall, 1990). So, too, a
too-big smile in humans often hides aggressive thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Another clue: People who have backstabbed before are likely to
do it again, so learn from past victims' experience.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KNOW THAT BACKSTABBERS LINE THE CORPORATE LADDER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gary Namie, author of ``The Bully at Work: What You Can Do
to Stop the Hurt and Reclaim Your Dignity on the Job''
(Sourcebooks, 2000) and leader, with his wife Ruth, of the Campaign
Against Workplace Bullying, has studied backstabbers, which he
refers to as ``two-headed snakes.'' He points out that supervisors
backstab just as frequently as colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kiss up the ladder and attack down below,'' he says.
``They tell you that you're wonderful while telling their boss that
you are incompetent.''
</P>
<P>
   Even customers can be backstabbers, playing Dr. Jekyll with,
say, a salesperson, and Mr. Hyde with his boss when discussing the
employee's efforts on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders believes it's best to keep such people as far away as
possible while still maintaining a professional demeanor.
Backstabbers use emotional proximity as a means to hurt others.
</P>
<P>
   However, it's wise to stay alert to alliances that potential
backstabbers may be forming. Savvy employees don't completely
distance themselves from their colleagues, but rather keep their
ears open for rumors that even distant backstabbers may start.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, when stories circulate about someone in an
organization, the subject is often the only person who hasn't heard
them. One way to stop a schemer's actions is to know what's being
said, which means being part of the grapevine. Not only will this
increase the likelihood of hearing the stories, it may even
discourage some potential backstabbers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONFRONTING THE GUILTY PARTY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; STEP 1: ENLIST SUPPORTERS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the only way to stop the backstabbing is to confront
the perpetrator. Preparing in advance for a confrontation is
essential. Namie advises that those who are uncomfortable
confronting a person alone should check to see if others have had
similar problems with that individual.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STEP 2: PLAN THE APPROACH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to get the backstabber to admit the truth. Start by
saying:
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) ``If you have a problem with something I've done, we
should talk about it and try to resolve it.''
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) ``We need to work together. Here's what we can do to
ensure no repetition of this situation ...''
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) ``There's a way you and I can improve our work
relationship. Are you interested in hearing about it?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STEP 3: DOING IT PUBLICLY VS. PRIVATELY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DuBrin advises handling the confrontation privately, or even
bringing in a third party if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Namie disagrees: Better to do it in public, he says, and bring
the backstabber's actions into the light. ``Snakes are obsessed
with appearances,'' he says. Confront them in public. If the victim
remains emotionally in control, the culprit will feel embarrassed
enough to stop spreading lies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STEP 4: KEEP THE BOSS INFORMED &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A person who has learned that a colleague has badmouthed him to
the boss should request a private meeting with that supervisor. The
victim should never make it a personal issue between the
backstabber and him. Rather, he should organize his defense and
present it calmly, rationally and with the evidence in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Namie isn't optimistic about the support one can expect from
management. If the company's executives see backstabbers as sources
of valuable information or value them for their performance, he
says, they may ignore dirty politicking. That's why Namie believes
it's up to the individual to take action.
</P>
<P>
   And what if the backstabber is the boss? Namie suggests that the
employee demand clarification regarding the specific procedures or
results that his boss is after, and put on record the performance
standards by which he will be evaluated. Clarity usually puts an
end to the confusion _ and also to the backstabbing.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
