<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT ALL FLUFFY FILLING AT CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BILL THOMPSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somebody asked me the other day why I didn't go to the
Republican National Convention in Philadelphia. How in the world,
this aficionado of politics wanted to know, could I pass up an
opportunity to spend four days and nights rubbing elbows with
thousands of political fanatics wearing funny hats and throngs of
media news hounds tripping over each other in search of a story?
</P>
<P>
   Is that a question that requires an answer?
</P>
<P>
   All kidding aside, these quadrennial pep rallies can be fun if
not fascinating _ or vice versa _ but in one respect they sort of
remind me of Miss America pageants: When you've seen one, you've
seen 'em all.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Miss America competition has something going for it
that the political conventions do not: In Atlantic City, you have
to wait until the end to find out who wins.
</P>
<P>
   The media constantly grumbled this week about how boring the
convention was, how scripted it was, how utterly fake and
meaningless it was. Having watched the festivities in the comfort
of my Texas living room, I'm probably in no position to argue with
those who were on the scene; if I'd been there, maybe I'd be
whining about the oversupply of staging and the undersupply of
substance just like the other opinionizers.
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of seeming like a sap, however, I must admit that I
found the whole deal fairly entertaining and even enlightening.
</P>
<P>
   For example: I attended the Republican convention in San Diego
four years ago, and I vaguely remember hearing Colin Powell speak
there, but I had no idea until I watched him on television this
week what an amazingly dynamic speaker he is.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, I didn't even know that actress Bo Derek was a Republican
until the TV cameras zoomed in on her while panning the VIP
section. If I'd been there in person, the convention security army
wouldn't have let me anywhere near the VIP seats.
</P>
<P>
   And let's not forget the best reason of all to watch the
convention on television instead of in the convention hall: remote
control.
</P>
<P>
   Any time I felt myself about to lapse into unconsciousness
during a speech or one of those weird musical interludes, I was
just a click away from a refreshing change of pace. When you're in
the hall, the speakers won't shut up no matter how many times you
click your clicker.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the downside. Some of the speeches can leave a totally
different impression on an at-home listener than they leave on the
in-person audience.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates on the convention floor went wild when vice
presidential nominee Dick Cheney spoke Wednesday night _ and the
on-site media analysts couldn't stop talking about what a rousing
attack Cheney had launched against the Democrats. From where I was
sitting, though, Cheney's speech was about as exciting as Lee
Greenwood's 10 billionth rendering of ``God Bless the USA.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. It was a fine speech, and the would-be veep
made some excellent points. But Cheney is so reasonable, and his
speaking style is so low-key, that he couldn't have come off as a
hatchet man if he'd actually been wielding a hatchet.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe that's me, as comic-turned-football-commentator Dennis
Miller likes to say.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the delegates were so hungry for some fightin' words
after three days of sweetness and light that they looked at Cheney
and saw a fire-breathing attack dog, while I, on the other hand,
saw a painstakingly civil and distinguished statesman making a
straightforward case for the Republicans' 2000 ticket.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe the media and the Democrats were so hungry to blast a
GOP convention that had been unwaveringly positive and upbeat that
they listened to Cheney and heard a savage, partisan attack, while
I heard George W. Bush's running mate offering up some common-sense
criticism of the officeholders whom Bush and Cheney hope to
replace.
</P>
<P>
   I know a savage, partisan attack when I hear one, and I don't
think Cheney's speech qualified. If it's savage, partisan attacks
you crave, you'll have to wait for the Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
