<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2655 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     08-04 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THERE ARE NO SHEKELS WITHOUT THE SHACKLES'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By J.R. LABBE 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Use the word ``religion'' in connection with anything
governmental, and a gaggle of ACLU lawyers will be on you like a
cat on a cricket, railing about the need for separation of church
and state.
</P>
<P>
   Let a popular Republican governor running for president use the
term ``faith-based,'' however, for the kinds of organizations that
should receive money to help America's struggling and, voila!,
everyone thinks this is a peachy idea for addressing some of the
social ills plaguing the nation. So peachy, in fact, that a
slightly less popular (according to people who answer polls)
Democratic vice president has co-opted the concept as part of his
presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faith-based agency'' may be a catch phrase for the new
millennium when it comes to who should provide services to
Americans in need, but it also serves as code to disguise where
those public dollars are going _ to organizations aligned with
religious institutions and specific religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Folks, the line between church and faith-based is so thin as to
be imperceptible in all too many cases.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the Jobs Partnership of Washington County.
Sounds like your typical bureaucratic agency working to help people
find jobs. Except that this Texas job training program uses
evangelical Christianity to help people get off welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Which in and of itself isn't a problem _ as long as program
organizers don't use public dollars to do it. In a lawsuit filed by
two civil rights groups, the Jobs Partnership is accused of using
state money to buy Bibles and to tell people that they can find
jobs through a relationship with Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled in Bowen vs. Kendrick that
public dollars can fund a religiously affiliated agency but not a
pervasively religious agency. The Jobs Partnership may have crossed
that line when it used biblical references to teach subjects such
as relations, authority, attitude, integrity, money and others.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of church-affiliated social services taking public
dollars should bother not just strict constitutional
constructionists and civil rights lawyers, but also church folk _
because no public dollar was ever expended that didn't come
attached to a bureaucrat with a rule book. As Melissa Rogers,
general counsel for the Baptist Joint Committee on Public Affairs,
said during a recent conference of the First Amendment Institute:
``There are no shekels without the shackles.''
</P>
<P>
   On its face, the notion of ``charitable choice'' _ allowing
religious organizations to qualify as nongovernmental providers of
services _ looks like a reasonable idea. If the government is
supposed to be neutral when it comes to handing out the
dough-re-me, why shouldn't a church-affiliated service provider be
given the same opportunity as an independent agency?
</P>
<P>
   ``When one witnesses the good work that houses of worship are
doing, it is absolutely natural to want to extend a helping hand.
But churches and other pervasively sectarian ministries should not
administer tax money in an effort to help the needy _ it is the
wrong way to do right,'' Rogers wrote to argue against Sen. John
Ashcroft's Charitable Choice Expansion Act.
</P>
<P>
   She warned that ``houses of worship that provide government
benefits and services may come to be viewed as arms of the
government. People need to know that their church is not Big
Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   When ``faith-based'' organizations take on the societal
significance of another bureaucratic agency, we're all in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of church-based programs' receiving government money
argue that churches and parochial schools should be treated like
everything else when it comes to being able to compete for
government contracts _ even if there is some red tape attached.
</P>
<P>
   But religion, as Rogers says, isn't like everything else.
Churches, throughout this nation's history, have fought hard to
make sure that they aren't considered the same in order to protect
citizens' rights to worship as they please.
</P>
<P>
   ``So at times there are special limitations on religion _ a
church cannot receive government grants as its secular counterparts
can _ and at times religion is granted special accommodation _ a
church may prefer people of the same religion in hiring as its
secular counterparts cannot,'' Rogers said. ``This is not
discrimination against religion. It is giving religion the
breathing room it requires.''
</P>
<P>
   Bureaucrats don't need to be fiddling with church-state
relations in order to address the social problems facing America.
</P>
<P>
   People of faith do the right thing because it's the right thing
to do, not because there is a government contract in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
