<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN CELEBRATES 100TH BIRTHDAY OF QUEEN MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Surrounded by three generations of the royal family,
Queen Elizabeth, the Queen Mother, celebrated her 100th birthday
Friday, waving to cheering well-wishers from the Buckingham Palace
balcony where she helped lead national rejoicing at the end of
World War II and on other notable occasions.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 40,000 people thronged the Mall as she rode by in a
horse-drawn open-top carriage garlanded with flowers in her
stable's gold-and-blue colors. Her grandson, Charles, the prince of
Wales, sat by her side as the coach entered the palace grounds to
the sound of a 41-gun salute and the strains of the national anthem
``God Save the Queen.''
</P>
<P>
   As the band of The Coldstream Guards struck up ``Happy Birthday
to You,'' she emerged from the darkness of a curtained doorway onto
the sunny balcony with her daughters, Queen Elizabeth II, 74, and
Princess Margaret, 69, and 25 other immediate family members
including her two great-grandsons, Princes William, 18, and Harry,
15.
</P>
<P>
   The Queen Mother's day began with the arrival of a royal postman
at her Clarence House residence, just off the Mall, bearing a
ceremonial card that the queen daily sends to her subjects who are
turning 100. One of 12 such cards delivered Friday, hers was the
only one to carry a personal greeting and to be signed not with the
formal ``Elizabeth R'' but with ``Lilibet,'' the queen's family
name since childhood.
</P>
<P>
   The festivities Friday capped weeks of commemorations that have
included full dress parades, Royal Air Force flyovers,
pageant-filled church services and ``God Bless You Ma'am'' tabloid
headlines in what could be the last full-throated hurrah for the
monarchy. Editorials have credited her with having saved the
monarchy from perils ranging from the abdication of her
brother-in-law Edward VIII in 1936 to the bombing of Buckingham
Palace by the Germans to the dysfunctional family behavior of
modern-day Windsors.
</P>
<P>
   Her first duty as queen was taming the stammering rages of her
husband, the newly crowned King George VI, by holding his wrist and
counting down his heart beats, and it set the tone for her job ever
since _ steadying the pulse of the crisis-prone British royal
family.
</P>
<P>
   George VI died of lung cancer in 1952 at the age of 56, and
Elizabeth, then 51, had to adjust to becoming the mother of a
monarch rather than the wife of one. A steely traditionalist, she
forcefully moved to end the love affair between Princess Margaret
and Group Capt. Peter Townsend, a palace equerry who was in the
process of divorce. More recently she sided with Prince Charles in
his marital dispute with Princess Diana. Diana retaliated by
telling a biographer that the Queen Mother was ``the chief leper in
the leper colony.''
</P>
<P>
   She is generally regarded as the most popular royal, though, and
it is difficult to imagine the image makers who have been hard at
work combating the declining popularity of the other members of the
family spinning any better presentation of her than the one she
herself created unaided over 75 years in the public eye.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There is no more endearing sight to tradition-minded Britons
than her tilted head, upcurled hat brim, ready smile and girlish
waves. The Queen Mother is seen as a favorite grandmother,
surrounded by her pet corgis, open and approachable, with a love of
the blustery British outdoors, an eye for the daily racing form and
a famous fancy for gin and mischievous dinner party chatter.
</P>
<P>
   While she never gave interviews or otherwise let the outside
world into her life, she became a figure whom the public embraced,
particularly during the wartime blitz, when she visited London's
East End to observe the damage for herself and try to lift the
spirits of besieged Londoners. Today the Queen Mother remains a
living link to a legendary time in British history.
</P>
<P>
   Her instinct in trying to associate the royal family with the
common British family laid the foundation for the effort to make
the monarchy less remote and more personable. She was the first
royal to stroll up to crowd barriers and greet the public in what
has now become the common practice of a ``walkabout.''
</P>
<P>
   As at so many occasions involving British royalty, many of the
most enthusiastic celebrators were Americans. One of them, Connie
Missinger, 47, a librarian from St. Louis, Mo., said: ``I came here
especially for the birthday. I came here last year and had such a
wonderful time that I thought I would love to come again. She is a
very special person and has seen everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
