a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      08-04 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO TRUE SUBSTITUTE FOR LIFE'S SWEETER PLEASURES 
 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Demi Moore's favorite snack, it is reported, is a glass of
water. Soon much of America may be saying their favorite snack,
too, is a glass of water, because much of America is under the
mistaken impression that the less you eat the more you'll look like
a movie star.
</P>
<P>
   That's what it has come to, I guess. The great American love
affair with food has collided with the great American guilt about
eating and decided that water is a snack.
</P>
<P>
   Water's fine. We need at least eight glasses a day. But it's no
snack. A snack is a treat, a gustatory gift to yourself, a reason
to lick your lips and close your eyes and smile.
</P>
<P>
   Ice cream is a snack, one of the original comfort foods, the
thing you wanted when you had your tonsils out, broke up with your
lover, had a root canal, but never found on fad diets.
</P>
<P>
   I spotted a woman eating ice cream the other day in the driver's
seat of her car. She was parked in the grocery store lot with the
car idling and probably the air conditioner going and she was
spooning ice cream out of a carton.
</P>
<P>
   I commiserated. I'm not good at waiting either and know about
driving while fishing through bags of groceries _ usually for a
Good and Plenty fix _ but this woman had planned ahead enough to
bring a spoon with her.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she was indulging on the sly. Even if she wasn't, she was
probably humming to herself as she ate, it being almost impossible
to consume ice cream and feel miserable.
</P>
<P>
   I like those towns in places like Mexico and Spain where on hot
nights people of all ages dress up to stroll around the square and
eat ice cream cones, twirling the creamy cold on their tongues,
looking like little kids in grown-up clothes.
</P>
<P>
   When you think about it, the exercise probably balances off some
of the calories, making ice cream practically a health food.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be as American as apple pie, but now like pie, ice
cream comes in non-fat, non-sweet basically inedible
what's-the-point variations. You appreciate seeing someone pleasure
themselves with the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   My pal Miriam recently turned 80 in relative good health and
delightful spirits. What water is to Demi, ice cream is to Miriam.
It's her favorite snack. Pralines and cream, first; vanilla,
second.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam said she expects to one day read in her newspaper that
ice cream has been found to have surprising restorative and healing
powers _ good for the brain or maybe simply a stress reducer _ and
should be consumed a little bit each day, like a glass of red wine.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam's been around long enough to see such things as butter,
bacon, red meat and eggs go in and out of fashion and chuckles over
new reports that chocolate is good for the heart. She believes her
favorite snack is also due for a blessing by some health guru.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there are signs that her body runs well on ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Right before her birthday, she took a bone density test and
passed with flying colors. No signs of osteoporosis said her amazed
doctor. Equally amazed are her younger friends who are hoping that
gulping calcium pills and Vitamin D at middle age will keep their
bones from crumbling like egg shells. After being so wary about
dairy, now we're starting to think more kindly about those half
gallons of temptation Miriam keeps in her freezer.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea of the status of Demi's bones, but I believe
anyone who spends their life snacking only on water will at age 80
be about as tall as Miriam's knee.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam also is a happy person, seldom blue, and I think that
might have something to do with how she relishes the sweet parts of
life, ice cream and otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
