<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN REPUBLICANS LOOK TO VICTORY IN NOVEMBER  

</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers)  
 By CARL HULSE  
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Republicans emerged from their big tent here
energized about their prospects across the South, firmly convinced
that Texas Gov. George W. Bush has a strong grip on the region.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does Bush's conservative philosophy play directly to
the sympathies of a dominant bloc of Southern voters, but he has
special advantages: brother Jeb is the governor of Florida, W.
himself is a neighbor over in Texas and his energy background plays
well along the Gulf oil and gas belt.
</P>
<P>
   Dixie delegates were downright giddy about bringing home the
bacon in November, giving Gore about as much chance as a homecoming
opponent at a Southeast Conference football game.
</P>
<P>
   Haley Barbour, the Mississippian who used to head the Republican
National Committee, agreed that the trend line is moving up on the
GOP ticket. He said the party is in its best position since the
re-election campaign of President Reagan in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   But he offered a word of caution to the faithful lest they get
too cocky and drop their guard. ``Don't kid yourself,'' Barbour
told a group of Alabamans during convention week, ``this is going
to be a close election.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveying the South, Barbour predicted that North Carolina,
Tennessee, Kentucky and Arkansas will be competitive, though he
noted Vice President Gore has taken positions on tobacco and coal
that saddle him with baggage in those states. Barbour also believes
Florida will be a fight.
</P>
<P>
   But his chief warning to the GOP shock troops that came together
in Philly was to brace for steady assaults on Bush, running mate
Dick Cheney and their records.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get ready for a tough campaign,'' he said. ``They
will attack Bush every day, every way, on every subject.''
</P>
<P>
   POWELL POWER
</P>
<P>
   Southern Republicans revere Gen. Colin Powell, considering him a
certified military hero and irrefutable evidence that there is room
in the GOP for African Americans. But Powell's convention speech
and remarks elsewhere illustrated some policy positions that put
him directly at odds with Southern conservative orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   Powell reaffirmed his support for affirmative action programs
for minorities both in his formal address and in several news
interviews that followed, saying he thought it was wrong for the
party to try to make a political issue out of preferences.
</P>
<P>
   In a CNN interview, he contrasted affirmative action with
federal sugar price supports, asking why it was fine for sugar
growers to get government help but was somehow unconstitutional for
minority students to get a leg up.
</P>
<P>
   The retired military leader also took on those who would try to
win Southern elections using tactics aimed at dividing blacks and
whites on civil rights issues, calling that approach the ``old,
dead, Southern strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   FAIRCLOTH RETURNS
</P>
<P>
   Former North Carolina Sen. Lauch Faircloth has kept a low
profile since his election loss to Democrat John Edwards in 1998,
returning to his personal business and agricultural interests.
</P>
<P>
   But the dedicated Republican has been very active in the Bush
presidential campaign, chairing the North Carolina effort and
making the rounds at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   As he strolled down Market Street to yet another event,
Faircloth was asked if he would return to the nation's capital
should there be another President Bush occupying the White House.
``We'll have to see,'' said Faircloth, who would qualify for a top
administration appointment. Agriculture secretary, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he could also seek his old Senate seat if Edwards is
tapped by Vice President Al Gore as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   A NO VOTE ON THE ROLL CALL
</P>
<P>
   Republicans adopted a new version of the trademark convention
roll call this year, spreading the state tally out over four nights
rather than devoting a couple of hours at the climax of the
convention. The rationale was that the primaries made the outcome
preordained.
</P>
<P>
   But quite a few delegates said they preferred the old system and
that the new approach robbed the proceedings of a bit of convention
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Pryor, the Alabama attorney general, said he still vividly
recalls staying up to watch the count during the close 1976 fight
between Ronald Reagan and Gerald Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm a political junkie, but I like watching one big
night,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
