<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-RECRUITS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BORDER RECRUITERS LOOKING TO FILL 1,600 PATROL JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By DANE SCHILLER   
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ As the federal government aims to complete
Congress' five-year goal of hiring 5,000 new agents by October
2001, U.S. Border Patrol recruiters are hitting the airwaves,
theaters and shopping malls to bolster one of the nation's most
storied and controversial law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience the thrill of intense action, suspense and danger
as you maneuver through deserts, canyons, gulf waters and the
sky,'' a San Antonio radio spot blares. ``Your mission is to
protect the boundaries of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol is pitching the excitement of roaming the
2,000-mile U.S.-Mexico border and drawing a federal paycheck as
leading reasons to choose ``a career with borders, but no
boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest in a patrol job fair swept the spectrum of
20-somethings this week as potential recruits turned out in
military-issue fatigues, hospital scrubs, sneakers and sandals.
</P>
<P>
   Rocio Romero, 24, who works in a bank, said she was drawn by
``the challenge of being a female in a man's world.''
</P>
<P>
   Her boyfriend, Joseph Medina, 21, who works in a medical office,
said he was inspired by the stability of a federal job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to branch out,'' Medina said after filling out an
application at the Omni Hotel. ``We are willing to relocate.''
</P>
<P>
   They are not alone.
</P>
<P>
   The patrol expects to hire 1,600 recruits this year, about 500
more than the approximately 1,100 recruits hired last year, said
Nicole Chulick, a Border Patrol spokeswoman in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going continue the hiring blitz,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With about 8,600 agents _ the most ever _ the patrol is short of
the federal hiring goal and struggling to fill the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The agency needs to hire at least 2,000 agents a year to meet
the goal and replace agents who quit, retire or transfer to other
law enforcement agencies, Chulick said.
</P>
<P>
   To hire, train and deploy 2,000 new agents, the patrol will have
to pull in at least 70,000 applications nationwide, said Luis
Gonzalez, recruiting coordinator for the patrol's Laredo Sector,
which includes San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Selzer, a spokesman for Proyecto Libertad, a Rio Grande
Valley-based immigration rights group, said Congress is asking the
patrol to grow too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are that desperate for recruits, to what extent are
they really going to look into who they are hiring,'' Selzer said.
``We demand the Border Patrol do thorough background and
psychological checks.''
</P>
<P>
   Recruits face a four-hour written exam, a criminal background
check and an interview. Candidates must be U.S. citizens, hold a
valid driver's license and be younger than 37 years old.
</P>
<P>
   A misdemeanor conviction for domestic violence or any felony
automatically disqualifies a recruit.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Silvestre Reyes, D-El Paso, said the hiring goal is
not unreasonable and should be expanded to bring in 1,000 agents
per year for the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very well thought-out and measured number of agents to
hire,'' said Reyes, who was a Border Patrol agent for 26 years
before being elected to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   A recruiting video Wednesday featured punchy music and agents
repelling from a helicopter, riding horses and shooting targets in
the desert.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
