<HEADLINE>
AS CONVENTION ENDS, BUSH BEGINS A WHISTLE-STOP CAMPAIGN TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated by 9 p.m. EDT with a story
by Frank Bruni.) 
 By JULIAN E. BARNES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The morning after accepting the Republican
presidential nomination and pledging to use the nation's prosperity
to solve difficult problems and fix politics, Gov. George W. Bush
promised to bring a new civility to the country.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and the delegates from the Republican National Convention
packed their bags and left Philadelphia Friday morning. Hundreds of
Republicans gathered at the airport to see off their nominee as he
left for Pittsburgh, where he was to begin a whistle-stop train
tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We leave this city of brotherly love energized and united and
focused on victory,'' Bush said at the rally. ``Our job is to
restore confidence to America, to lift this nation's spirit, to
call upon the best of our citizenry.''
</P>
<P>
   The train trip, which the Republicans are calling the ``Change
the Tone Tour,'' will take Bush through Pennsylvania, Ohio,
Michigan and Illinois. Karen P. Hughes, the campaign spokeswoman,
said Bush hoped to use the tour to emphasize the call for civility
he made during his acceptance speech and to highlight examples of
his bipartisanship in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign by train is set to end on Sunday, when he will
return home to Austin, Texas. But he is likely to travel to
California next week, just days before the Democratic National
Convention in Los Angeles. Vice President Al Gore, the presumed
Democratic candidate, has a strong lead in California, but Hughes
said that the Bush campaign was eager to show that it would not
concede the state.
</P>
<P>
   At a prayer breakfast Friday morning, Bush suggested that he
could unite Americans to help improve the lives of those who have
been left behind or left out in this time of economic strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job as leaders, Republicans, Democrats and the
non-affiliates is to rally that compassion of America,'' Bush said.
``Our mission, regardless of political party, is to work together
to make sure no child is left behind as we go into the 21st
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the size of the television audience Thursday night was
smaller than for past conventions, Bush's speech was still seen by
millions, and, for many of them, it represented their introduction
to the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In his address on Thursday, Bush said the Clinton-Gore
administration had squandered the opportunity to use the strong
economic health of the country to expand Medicare, reform Social
Security and strengthen the military.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not offer many policy changes that differed radically
from the moderate agenda of the current administration. But the
convention was peppered with tough criticisms of Gore and Clinton
to suggest that Bush could offer a different style of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current president embodied the potential of a
generation,'' Bush said Thursday night. ``So many talents. So much
charm. Such great skill. But in the end, to what end? So much
promise, to no great purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush accused Gore of playing up the fears of Americans, blocking
reforms but not advancing solutions. He said that rather than
transforming himself or polling before staking a position, he would
lead based on his principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have not led, we will,'' Bush said repeatedly in his
remarks Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A disciplined campaigner, Bush hopes to control the debate with
his opponent by focusing on only a handful of issues, which he
outlined Thursday night.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bush also signaled this week that he wants to try to change how
Republicans talk about their agenda and portray their party. Like
previous Republican candidates, Bush has promised tax cuts, but he
did it cloaked in words traditionally associated with the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those in the greatest need should receive the greatest help,''
Bush said. ``So we will lower the bottom rate from 15 percent to 10
percent and double the child tax credit.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush also promised something to the wealthiest Americans. He
said no one should pay more than 33 percent of their income to the
government, a proposal that would give the wealthiest taxpayers at
least a 6 percent cut.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day convention here generally avoided discussing
divisive issues like abortion. Still, the biggest reaction from the
crowd on Thursday came when Bush mentioned that he would press to
outlaw the procedure opponents call ``partial-birth'' abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Those comments made a minority of the delegates in the audience
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry he mentioned the life of the unborn,'' said Dee
Beaubien, 58, a Republican from Barrington, Ill., who supports
abortion rights. ``I know it was politically the right thing to do.
But I am sorry about that part of the speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Republican Party rank and file at the convention
reacted warmly to the speech Thursday, arguing that it showed
Bush's leadership and charisma.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exactly what I was looking for,'' said Ray Hoffman, 56,
a delegate from Sioux City, Iowa. ``It was a message people need to
hear, it is a message we want to hear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
