<HEADLINE>
PATRIOT UNIT MAY NOT NEED ANY DEFENDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Veteran safety Lawyer Milloy was a happy
camper Monday night. For one, he had had a chance to tour the Pro
Football Hall of Fame, shake hands and talk with Ronnie Lott, the
mold for all modern safeties, and then go out on the field and play
for a most cohesive defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to be predictable on defense,'' said Milloy,
the Patriots' strong safety. ``Other teams ought to know we're
going to be attacking them week to week. As long as we stay
healthy, I think we can be one of the best defenses in the
league.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one exhibition game has been played and while it is often
difficult to predict how good a pro football team will be based on
its exhibition play, it is much easier to predict which teams will
be bad.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots clearly showed cohesion in their win over the
49ers, and that cohesion and discipline will be closely watched in
Friday night's second game against the Detroit Lions in the Pontiac
Silverdome. Is it the real deal or not?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important, though, Patriot after Patriot has spoken
in the last few days about how well the team has been prepared.
Clearly, Bill Belichick has passed the initial hurdle of a new
coach, winning the confidence of his veteran players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, from being in camp, the extensive approach that he
has taken, his demands and his defensive philosophy, what we did in
that game (against the 49ers) was really elementary compared to
what we've been doing in camp,'' said Milloy. ``To go out and do
things that were elementary and still dominate means a lot to us
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran linebacker Chris Slade also felt the same confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Belichick is a more detail-oriented guy, very specific in what
he wants,'' said Slade. ``And the guys have been able to respond to
that so far.''
</P>
<P>
   As Slade sees it, the faith of the veterans in their coaches
leads to two-way reinforcement. If the veterans believe in what the
coaches have laid out, the veterans will then show the younger
players _ who have not been exposed yet to the vast differences in
coaching in the NFL _ how to go about their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The veteran guys have shown some quality leaderswhip and the
rookie guys have stepped up so far,'' said Slade. ``It's good to
get off on the right foot like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Football fans can debate whether instilling faith in the players
is more important than X's and O's and making the right personnel
decisions. And of the many decisions to be made on defense, perhaps
few will be more important than who starts at free safety. Last
year's starter, Chris Carter, was relegated to third string Monday
and Tebucky Jones was given a chance to win the job.
</P>
<P>
   The free safety position is a interesting mix of physical
aggressiveness, ability to cover, and mental sharpness. Jones seems
to have the first two qualities, an aggressive player who
frequently was flagged for being over-aggressive the last two years
during Pete Carroll's quest to make him a cornerback. And being
forced the last two years to cover wide receivers _ often in
man-to-man defenses _ has sharpened Jones's coverage skills.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the third quality, being able to recognize offensive
formations and make the right calls, that remains to be seen.
Another factor in whether Jones stays at safety is whether
Belichick is confident either Kato Serwanga or Antonio Langham can
play the opposite corner from Ty Law.
</P>
<P>
   So far, anyway, Jones seems comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see (the play) in front of me,'' said Jones. ``The only
difference is you've got to know more. Being the safety, you've got
to make the calls. Being a corner, you don't have to make any
calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the 49ers, ``both of us were making the calls,'' said
Jones of him and his partner at strong safety, Lawyer Milloy. Jones
thought his calling of defenses ``went pretty good. Everything was
on key.''
</P>
<P>
   On offense, the veterans are now playing for their fourth
offensive coordinator and fourth offense. And even if Belichick and
offensive coordinator Charlie Weis were with the team four years
ago when Bill Parcells was the coach, the Patriots' offense of 2000
is much different from the offense that coordinator Ray Perkins ran
under Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one's a lot more wide open,'' said Brisby. ``There's a
lot more of guys getting down the field; some of the things are
similar but it's more spread out.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, at least, there seems to be the same faith by the
offense in their coaches and schemes, a faith that waned under
Ernie Zampese. The Patriot veteran offensive players also seem to
believe thay are entering the regular-season wars with a weapon or
two.
</P>
<P>
   `The coaches really put a big burden on us during the camps,''
explained Brisby of the cohesion the Patriots displayed Monday.
``They threw the whole offense at us in camps and offensively now,
I think we're ready to open up.''
</P>
<P>
   No football team shows much of its offense or defense during
exhibition games, particularly the first one or two, ``and what you
saw the other night is just a little bit of what we're going to
do,'' said Brisby. ``We showed very little of what we're going to
do. It was fairly basic and we kept a lot of guys in for (pass)
protection and things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, the offense still performed with cohesion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different situation (with a new coaching staff),''
explained Brisby. ``Guys are a lot more attentive now than we were
back when, what with different coaches and all. Guys are more on
the upbeat. (Coaches) are hollering at us to pay attention to
what's going on, even if we're not in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro football players often reach their potential out of fear or
respect or their coaches, or fear of the consequences if mistakes
are made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a little bit of both,'' said Brisby. ``I think
it's more the preparation than anything. Guys were prepared. We
went into the game looking for an opportunity to play. We just
wanted to go out there and show people what we can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
