<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2710 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-LOBSTER-BOATS-ART-BOS     08-04 1607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOBSTER-BOATS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 THE FASHIONABLE ARE HOOKED ON HARDY LOBSTER BOATS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SAM ALLIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHWEST HARBOR, Maine _ Like a good barn, a Down East lobster
boat looks better the longer you eyeball it.
</P>
<P>
   The thing does not take your breath away like a Friendship sloop
or a Concordia yawl. It simply is part of the seascape with the
fish and the gulls. That's the point.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, discriminating folk have bought lobster boats as
pleasure craft for their seaworthiness and spare lines. They
appreciate the marriage of form with function and prize the economy
of design.
</P>
<P>
   There is a rich vein of reverse snobbery at work here. By and
large, this has been a sailing crowd who race with skill and cruise
with intimacy off the coast they adore. Their disdain for
``stinkpots'' runs deep. Eventually, though, they ease off sail for
the comfort of motor. But it had better look good.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not banana-shaped, futuristic-looking things,'' Bruce
Cunningham, owner of Padebco Custom Boats in Round Pond, says about
lobster boats. ``They're a real boat that looks like a real boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Due to the vagaries of vogue and the torrents of new money, the
secret of the lobster boat is out among the greater public. The
``lobster yacht'' market is booming in boatyards up and down the
Maine coast that sell to clients from the Pacific Northwest to the
Great Lakes and down to Florida. Their boats pop up in Italy and
the Galapagos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market has just exploded with the fiberglass hulls,'' says
Lee Wilbur, a veteran builder in Southwest Harbor. ``The demand for
Maine lobster yachts seems to increase every year.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their traditional owners, the boats have
attracted freshly minted millionaires who don't know much except
that they should have one _ often subtly sumptuous affairs that
sell for half a million dollars or more. Ranging from about 20 to
more than 40 feet, they are superb for island-hopping, martinis at
sunset, or fishing offshore in a rolling sea.
</P>
<P>
   Purists bemoan the use of fiberglass in hulls and amenities such
as air conditioning and microwave ovens, but builders just beam and
scour the area for skilled workers to meet the demand. A
prospective buyer can wait a year or longer.
</P>
<P>
   Just what accounts for this hot market?
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes a Land Rover special?'' answers Donnie Ellis, a
second-generation builder in Southwest Harbor. ``You use it for
years in deserts and jungles. You beat the hell out of it and can't
kill it. Same thing with these boats. Commercial fishermen have to
go out in them or they starve.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that the Down East hull puts a lot of boat under
the waterline. This does wonders for stability. Glenn Holland, a
builder out of Belfast, estimates that the waterline length of his
38-footer, Spare Parts, is about 37 feet. This is a far cry from
the Ray Hunt-designed deep-V hulls in most power boats, which leave
less of the boat in the water for speed.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a summer lobster boat racing circuit in Maine.
These are torrid affairs, drag races on water where boats top 50
knots for a flat-out run of about a mile. Yachts, these are not.
We're talking working boats stripped for speed, some of which pack
engines upwards of 1,000 horsepower that drink racing fuel and make
so much noise that crew members don headphones to keep their
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise you'd be deaf as a flounder,'' observes Holland,
whose 32-foot Red Baron has been the scourge of the unlimited
gasoline class this year.
</P>
<P>
   The pursuit of speed extends beyond the racing circuit and
permeates the entire lobster yacht market. The engines are bigger
than ever, producing top speeds close to 30 knots. Where 200
horsepower was once the norm, today lobster yachts routinely top
400 and can cruise at more than 20 knots.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Lynch, who is on his fourth Wilbur boat, has an
800-horsepower engine on his 38-footer. ``I'll admit to 900,''
Holland says.
</P>
<P>
   Constellations of lobster yacht builders dot the Maine coast.
You've got the Beal clan all over Beals Island and Jonesport. One
of the biggest hubs is Southwest Harbor, where Chester Clement
began building lobster boats in the 1930s, followed by the
memorable team of Raymond Bunker and Ralph Ellis, and then Ralph
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ellis's son, Donnie, continues the family tradition,
albeit in fiberglass, down the road from Wilbur. They are joined by
a handful of other builders in the area. Stanley is still building
in wood. At 71, he is the dean of the wooden boat builders in the
area and has been honored by the National Endowment for the Arts
for his skills.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tight breed. Donnie Ellis's mother was a Beal. His father
designed a hull for Wilbur, and his brother was in business with
Wilbur for a while. So if a prospective client chooses Wilbur over
him, Ellis can live with it. ``It's still part of the family,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Such largesse does not extend to Hinckley Co., the giant
boatyard a quarter-mile from the Ellis yard. Hinckley has
revolutionized _ some say adulterated _ the lobster yacht market
with its wildly popular Picnic Boat (a Hinckley trademark name that
Wilbur says he and others used informally for years).
</P>
<P>
   The Picnic is a 36-foot confection of Kevlar, fiberglass, and
carbon _ usually powered by a 420-horsepower jet engine _ that
maneuvers like a quarterhorse. It has a mere 18-inch draft. The jet
allows it to skim over lobster pots that are snagged in the
propellers of traditional lobster boats.
</P>
<P>
   A bowthruster, a small propeller located in the bow to ease the
embarrassment of docking for the neophyte, is standard. (They are
increasingly popular in other lobster yachts as well.) Like the
boats of Ellis and Wilbur, they are studies in teak, mahogany, and
cherry.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Bennett, Hinckley's director of sales and marketing,
likens the lobster yacht craze to the mushrooming sport utility
vehicle market: ``SUVs are trucks with creature comforts.'' Lobster
yachts, in turn, are commercial boats with stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   Lobster yacht chic, he says, is a result of evaporating leisure
time in the United States. ``Someone promised us more free time and
paper-free offices. It didn't happen,'' he says. ``With less time,
people want to get out on the water faster. This is simpler than
sailing.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionalists concede the Picnic is easy on the eye, but they
maintain its light weight _ 11,000 pounds _ and relatively narrow
beam provide for an unamusing experience when the wind blows hard.
And they howl at the gall of Hinckley to call it a lobster yacht in
the first place. Its bloodlines, they say, lie elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a lobster boat model,'' Stanley says. Adds Wilbur:
``It is absolutely different. It has more relevance to the old Gar
Wood, Chris-Craft-type bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   And it attracts a different kind of buyer, often a first-time
owner with little water experience.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Hinckley, whose high-performance sailboats are
recognized throughout the world, could care less. The company makes
about 40 Picnic Boats a year at $400,000 a pop, and people get in
line to buy one. It has sold 178 since the model first appeared in
1994. A new 44-foot model, the Talaria, boasts double jet engines,
a top speed of 32 knots, and myriad amenities for about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hinckley defends the performance of its Picnic in heavy weather
by arguing that width alone does not determine stability. ``People
say you need a wide hull to be stable,'' Bennett says. ``But if you
have a low center of gravity, you get the same effect.'' Bennett
adds that the Picnic engine is mounted very low, creating
stability.
</P>
<P>
   At its core, the complaint against Hinckley's lobster yachts is
less about seaworthiness than the damage done to the ethos of
custom boat building in Maine, the soul of small yards. ``They've
practically got them on the shelf,'' Stanley says.
</P>
<P>
   But the range of lobster boats being built these days is
striking. Indeed, it is an aesthetic stretch from Stanley's spare
wooden confections to the fuller fiberglass boats of Ellis and
Wilbur and on to the glitz and technology of Hinckley. There has
been enough business for all concerned, but Ellis, for one, worries
about a recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a false economy,'' he says. ``I lost $750,000 with the
drop in the Nasdaq last spring. I had two guys who wrote out checks
and then had to call up and ask for them back.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Hinckley assembly line in high gear, Stanley remains a
magnificent dinosaur across the harbor. He disdains what he
considers the bloated look of the newer lobster yachts and despises
fiberglass. ``The pleasure boats are out of balance. There's too
much stuff in them,'' he says. ``That's why they've made them so
wide. But they don't handle well.''
</P>
<P>
   And he minces no words about fiberglass: ``I don't like the
smell of it. I don't like the itch of it. And you build the same
damned thing over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley doesn't even like the term ``lobster yacht.'' ``It's
either a yacht or a boat,'' he snaps.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, lobster boats continue to seduce with their long,
lean looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enthralled by them,'' says Tom Ewens, a philosophy
professor at the Rhode Island School of Design who fell in love
with a 36-foot Harold Gower boat and bought it two years ago. It
needed a lot of work and has eaten a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not perfectly rational decisions,'' he concedes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
