<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-EYES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAMMY FAYE, BEHIND THE MAKEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
EYES OF TAMMY FAYE 
Documentary directed by: Randy Barbato &AMP; Fenton Bailey 
Narrated by: RuPaul Charles 
Running time: 79 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (some sexual content) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At one point toward the end of ``The Eyes of Tammy Faye,'' the
title-roleist shoos away a Los Angeles makeup man engaged in giving
her a new look and says, ``I get so sick of this Hollywood crap! I
like real!'' Then, a moment later, she adds, with a little
self-deprecating laugh, ``That's why I wear all these wigs.''
There'll always be room in America for a rogue who has the good
sense to laugh publicly at his or her own roguishness. If Randy
Barbato and Fenton Bailey began their documentary by regarding
Tammy Faye Bakker Messner as the campy essence of ambulatory
American kitsch, they quickly were won over by her survivor's
toughness. ``The Eyes of Tammy Faye'' is a lively and affectionate
cross between an infomercial and a genuflection.
</P>
<P>
   Of course there are those mascara-laden eyes, with their huge
cowcatcher lashes that became a trademark when Tammy Faye sang and
banged the tambourine while her televangelist husband, Jim Bakker,
exhorted the faithful to keep the money flowing. No small part of
this film involves payback for Tammy Faye, who may or may not have
known about the shady side of her husband's PTL televangelism
empire, which at one time included a theme park and resort and was
eating up a million a week. Eventually, it all came crashing down.
Bakker was sent to prison for fraud following his bankruptcy,
divorce, and tabloid-fueled scandal tied to a $265,000 hush money
payment to Jessica Hahn. Tammy Faye entered the Betty Ford clinic
for prescription drug addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a dozen years later, she's seen repairing her relationship
with her grown daughter and son, recalling teary-eyed how Bakker's
big-bucks fever left her and the children in the dirt, and making
it clear that she has weathered adversity before and will weather
it again. First of eight children born into modest circumstances in
Minnesota, she married Bakker when she was 17. They clicked on Pat
Robertson's TV channel, only to be ousted by the presumably jealous
Robertson. Undeterred, the Bakkers founded the Trinity Broadcasting
Network, only to be bumped from it, too, by greedy partners. Third
time lucky. They founded the PTL Network and it took off. Old video
clips indicate that Tammy Faye played no small role in its success.
While Bakker provided the slickness and drive, Tammy Faye softened
the huckstering with her singing and open emotionalism. Between
them, they made Elmer Gantry look like Tiny Tim.
</P>
<P>
   After Bakker's downfall, the PTL was ripe for the picking, and,
according to Tammy Faye, Jerry Falwell came along, shut it down and
got its board of directors to bounce the Bakkers. Falwell was
careful to declare that he was, in effect, putting a successful
commercial rival out of business from only the most Christian of
motives. Tammy Faye, who married PTL board member Roe Messner,
himself shortly thereafter jailed for financial misdeeds, learned
from Falwell. When she cites his misdeeds to a congregeation in
Oklahoma, she ends her litany by piously concluding that it would
do no good to hate him.
</P>
<P>
   One comes away from the film convinced that serving as Jesus'
self-appointed middleman on TV is a lucrative but cutthroat
business and that Tammy Faye is a lot hardier than she first seemed
when the Bakkers' troubles first came to light in the '80s. Jim
Bakker, interviewed after his release from prison, still seems a
snake-oil salesman. Tammy Faye, who firmly believes that you don't
have to look dowdy to be a Christian, is much more ingratiating
because she convinces people she's connecting with them on an
empathetic emotional level. She's persuasive in her
self-salesmanship and image rehabbing because she obviously isn't
putting on an act, but has internalized her litany of suffering and
forbearance and tells her story with real conviction. You can't not
admire her tenacity and spirit, even as you note her convenient
myopia on several issues. Tammy Faye clearly believes in Tammy
Faye, even when nobody else does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
