<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OLD MEN AND THE SKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
SPACE COWBOYS 
Directed by: Clint Eastwood 
Screenplay by: Ken Kaufman &AMP; Howard Klausner 
Starring: Eastwood, Tommy Lee Jones, Donald Sutherland, James
Garner, Marcia Gay Harden, William Devane, Loren Dean, Courtney B.
Vance, James Cromwell 
Running time: 123 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (some language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When obsolete technology needs fixing, who ya gonna call? The
over-the-hill gang, that's who. That's the launching pad for
``Space Cowboys,'' Clint Eastwood's new movie about geezer heroics
in space. How they refrained from calling it ``The Ripe Stuff''
we'll never know. One reason it works as well as it does is that
while many stars try to deny advancing age, Eastwood, ever the
pragmatist, uses it. When he's reluctantly called back to NASA to
fix a crippled Russian space station whose guidance system is so
old that only he can remember it, James Cromwell's summoning
bureaucrat can't resist needling him. ``How many years has it been
since you retired? Five?'' ``Four,'' Eastwood's retired astronaut
replies, underplaying what clearly is his annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Space Cowboys'' isn't the John Glenn story in quadruplicate,
even after Eastwood gathers his former and in some cases
cantankerous old team consisting of Tommy Lee Jones's hot-rodding
test pilot, whose throttle-jockeying got them all grounded; Donald
Sutherland's ladies' man of a systems designer, whose
aviator-rimmed glasses can't conceal the thickness of their lenses;
and James Garner's navigator turned preacher, the only one of the
four remotely content with his newfound lot in life. The film
begins with a black and white flashback to 1958, to the tune of
``Fly Me to the Moon.'' Scarcely have they left Earth's atmosphere,
however, than they're ingloriously replaced by jump-suited,
space-helmeted chimps.
</P>
<P>
   One of the film's jokes is that the ex-astronauts' old feuds are
livelier than they now are. These involve Eastwood's with Jones and
everybody's with Cromwell _ the paper-shuffler they all feel knifed
them in the back. The film takes rather too long setting the stage
for the long-postponed space shot they regard as unfinished
business. It lingers too lovingly on the comedy of decrepitude as
they huff and puff their way into shape and slog through their
training courses. En route, there's a romance between Jones's
ornery widower and Marcia Gay Harden's scientist. She's on the
old-timers' side, as opposed to Cromwell, who'd like to see them
flunk out so he can use a pair of young hotshots he feels he can
control once Eastwood's loose-cannon veteran has told them what to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Matters become more pulse-quickening when the film turns away
from character sketching and becomes much more conventional and
generic, namely in space. There it quickly becomes apparent that
the repairs prove much more fraught with complication than anyone
supposed, except perhaps Rade Serebija's taciturn Russian general,
there as an observer with a piece of bad news he had hoped he
wouldn't have to reveal. ``Space Cowboys'' has a meandering first
half with savory moments, and a much less original, but more
suspenseful second half. As usual, Eastwood's economy of gesture
both behind and in front of the camera is a pleasure in itself.
``Space Cowboys'' does achieve liftoff, even if just barely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
