<HEADLINE>
SHOWTIME CAN REALLY KILL AN EVENING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Tonight' refers to Sun., Aug. 6) 
Our rating: 1 1/2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``One Kill'' is one of those legal dramas where little slivers
of information trickle out in a dramatically convenient but
logically baffling manner _ even though the facts seem to easily
exonerate the accused, she's so stupid she withholds them until
they blow up in her defense attorney's face.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Heche plays a Marine captain accused of murdering a
superior (Sam Shepard). Her defense attorney (Eric Stolz) can only
watch with befuddlement as he slowly discovers that she got some
ammunition the day of the murder _ and, oh, yeah, that she had had
an affair with the victim (he woos her, music swelling, with a box
of Kentucky Fried Chicken). Oh, and that he was violently unhinged.
Forgot to mention that part.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, ``One Kill'' _ ``based,'' God knows how loosely, on
a ``true story'' _ wants to be a sort of paranoid persecution
fantasy about how much tougher it is for women than for men in the
Marine Corps. True, particularly when they murder well-liked,
good-old-boy colonels and refuse, for reasons of some ill-defined
principle, to mount a defense for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The cast in general _ but Stolz in particular _ walk through
their parts as if on an afternoon stroll. This lack of commitment
and tension suggests the title refers to what you've done to your
evening should you watch this snoozer. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``One Kill.'' &QL; 
What: Docudrama about a female military officer's legal ordeal
after killing an attacker in self-defense. &QL; 
The stars: Anne Heche, Eric Stolz, Sam Shepard. &QL; 
Where: Showtime. &QL; 
When: 8 tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
