<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLEN GETS THE CALL TO MAKE THE CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the day, networks used two, maybe three cameras to cover
NFL games. Nowadays, networks use as many as 10 to cover
regular-season games and about 30 for playoff and Super Bowl
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Every angle has been covered, with one exception: the officials.
</P>
<P>
   That has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Yessiree. Blame it on the Internet. Blame it on network
executives' burning desire to give viewers value-added coverage and
a you-were-there feeling. Whatever it is, game officials now are
being equipped with cameras, and, to be honest, it's not bad.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the referee cam's shaky debut on ABC's ``Monday Night
Football.'' Rest assured that those transmission bugs will be
worked out. The potential for these cameras is enormous. The images
shot from the camera afixed to the referee's cap captured the speed
of the game unlike anything seen before on TV.
</P>
<P>
   The referee cam soon will be right up there with the yellow
on-screen stripe ESPN has been using to help viewers keep tabs on
how much yardage is needed for a first down.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN will use the referee cam this exhibition season as well.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports will take it a step further in a couple of weeks.
Color analyst Matt Millen will work as a game official during the
third quarter of the Patriots-Tampa Bay exhibition Aug. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Millen has been in training for the last two months, including a
stint at the NFL's annual Officials Clinic in Dallas and several
days at the training camps of the Oakland Raiders, San Francisco
49ers, Philadelphia Eagles, and Washington Redskins. ``I didn't
know what to expect from Matt when he first arrived,'' said Jerry
Seeman, the league's senior director of officiating. ``But he
really worked hard and may have developed another career for
himself if he ever decides to leave the booth.''
</P>
<P>
   For Millen, the training was amazing. ``The hand signals,
convening with the other officials _ it's an aspect of the game I
thought I fully understood. Nope. I now have a completely different
perspective on football,'' he said. ``I wish I knew what I know now
when I was a young player, because I would have been able to get
away with a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Fox analyst John Madden wonders whether Millen will have
a flashback to his playing days once he steps on the field. ``Matt
was such a competitive player,'' said Madden, ``I hope he remembers
that he's not allowed to tackle anyone out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Millen does still have aggressive tendencies, even seeing the
game from a different angle. ``These guys (linemen and running
backs) are doing stuff today that I used to take guys out for,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. Millen has been amazingly restrained, even
acknowledging, ``Last week I was run over by 49ers receiver Terrell
Owens.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Terry Glenn can do the same Aug. 20 _ and the camera can
capture it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
