<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-INTENT-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ULTIMATE HOW-TO MANUAL
</HEADLINE>
  Teaching the reader to kill 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Tonight' refers to Sun., Aug. 6) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can words kill and, if so, can those behind the words be found
liable for their actions? We've seen two sleazy jabberfests in the
past few years provoke _ no matter how peripherally _ murders.
``The Jenny Jones Show'' was ordered to pay a huge settlement to
the family of a victim it set up to unwittingly humiliate a guest;
just last week, one of ``Jerry Springer's'' usual family squabbles
turned lethal when two guests murdered another mere hours after a
taping.
</P>
<P>
   There also exist a couple of spurious lawsuits against
filmmakers, namely those behind ``Natural Born Killers'' and ``The
Basketball Diaries,'' suggesting that some already unhinged viewers
saw these movies and elected to ape them in real life, with real
death.
</P>
<P>
   But those cases were just examples of amoral hosts or
exploitative movies ratcheting up the tension bubbling inside human
pressure cookers, not specifically suggesting that problems can
really be resolved with a humble little homicide or two. In the
'90s, a seedy little publisher called Paladin Enterprises published
a how-to manual on murder, which demonstrated, step by step, not
only the most efficient way to kill someone but also listed every
safeguard to prevent authorities from tying prospective assassins
to their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hit Man: A Technical Manual for Independent Contractors,'' in
fact, did show the way for one two-bit punk, who iced a family at
the behest of its estranged father. While a violent movie could be
said, on the vaguest level imaginable, to inspire some idiot to
take up arms, it also shows the bad guys getting caught, which, in
the eyes of most, would take the glamour out of committing such
acts. Paladin incited violence by insisting !ital!you could get
away with murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deliberate Intent'' _ the first film from cable's FX _ is a
surprisingly thought-provoking drama by TV standards, exploring a
highly controversial and compelling issue that pushes at the
boundaries of the First Amendment. Timothy Hutton stars as Rod
Smolla, a top First Amendment attorney who, after reading ``Hit
Man'' and hearing the particulars of the murders, decides to argue
seemingly against the very thing he has built his career and
reputation eloquently protecting.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Rifkin co-stars as Howard Siegel, the unctuously
self-righteous attorney who drags Smolla into his ethical dilemma.
``NYPD Blue's'' James McDaniel walks on the other side of the law
with his performance as L.T. Horn, the man who contracts the hit on
his family.
</P>
<P>
   Briskly and efficiently, with crisply delivered dialogue,
``Deliberate Intent'' bounces around chronologically and covers a
lot of ground _ the police investigation that led to the arrest of
Horn and his hired gun (Clark Johnson), the passages in the book
that led the killer to his prey, the First Amendment arguments that
initially suggested to the court that even speech as repugnant as
``Hit Man'' was nonetheless protected, and the appellate process.
It's grim and riveting stuff.
</P>
<P>
   And, ironically, given that more people will see this tonight
than had ever probably even heard of Paladin Press and ``Hit Man,''
with its paragraph-by-paragraph re-creation of key passages from
the book, ``Deliberate Intent'' is potentially more dangerous than
the publishing slimeballs ever were. Of course, should it actually
inspire someone to commit murder, I'm sure the filmmakers will
stand behind their First Amendment rights. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``Deliberate Intent.'' &QL; 
What: Docudrama about a lawsuit against a publishing house that
released a how-to manual on murder. &QL; 
The stars: Timothy Hutton, Ron Rifkin, James McDaniel, Clark
Johnson, Penny Johnson. &QL; 
Where: FX. &QL; 
When: 8 tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
