<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2723 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-04 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERATION PAP: OLD ARGUMENT SIMPLY DOESN'T WASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As of today, I can't listen to them anymore. They live in a
world in which pendulums swing from their clocks, yet their time
remains still. They think you are using foul language when you say
anything positive about modern pro sports. To them, every day is
1950. Or 1960. Or some bygone, ``magical'' sports era when (take
your pick):
</P>
<P>
   Pro athletes (itals)played for the love of the game;(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Leagues weren't (itals)ruined by free agents and
expansion;(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Men were real men. There was none of this New Age, sensitive
male mumbo-jumbo. Thus, real men were so tough that they were
(itals)unafraid to play with broken bones!(unitals) (Notice that
women are rarely mentioned in these Good Ol' Days rants.)
</P>
<P>
   You can count on hearing from these grumpy folks at this time
each summer. It's inevitable. Baseball and football usually have
their Hall of Fame induction ceremonies a couple of weekends apart.
Understandably, this is a time for celebration, nostalgia, and
contributing to oral tradition by spinning old stories. But the
problems arise when former athletes and current fans get Hall of
Fame Hangover, which leads to a foolish cliched bashing of all
things 2000.
</P>
<P>
   So now we hear from NFL Hall of Famer Deacon Jones that he
couldn't play today, even for a billion dollars. He would be fined,
he said, because he couldn't play by the soft rules. Nor could he
deal with players dancing in the end zone. We hear from NFL Hall of
Famer Chuck Bednarik that players are ``pussyfoots'' because so
many of them are specialists, unlike rugged two-way star Bednarik.
</P>
<P>
   Blah.
</P>
<P>
   Blah.
</P>
<P>
   Blah.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, fellas. Ever hear of evolution?
</P>
<P>
   Jones and Bednarik aren't the only ones guilty of promoting one
sports era while attacking, rather than debating, the merits of
another. It happens in all sports. Maybe you have a friend who does
the same thing. You rave about airborne Vince Carter, rising from
the court as if he were a plane leaving the tarmac. Your friend
replies that the NBA is weak and that Carter would have never
dunked on Wilt. You salute the physical New Jersey Devils; your
friend replies they are overrated and wouldn't have won anything if
they had to deal with the Big Bad Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, listening to these harangues is harmless. You nod your
head to the monologue and then move on. But here's why I can't
listen for the rest of the year: distraction. That is, I might be
distracted from watching and enjoying one of the most significant
and poetic sports years ever. If the Grumpy Ones weren't so
occupied with their zoot suits, Edsels, and 8-track tape players,
they would know that I'm talking about 2000.
</P>
<P>
   This is the year when two tennis-playing sisters from Compton,
Calif., met in the Wimbledon semifinals. One of the sisters, Venus
Williams, won the tournament. No one would have guessed that was
possible 10 years ago, when the late comedian Robin Harris cracked,
``Don't you know that Compton-to-Hell is a local call?''
</P>
<P>
   This is the year of Pedro Martinez, who may wind up with a
season we've never seen before in major league history. You might
be aware that Bob Gibson had a 1.12 ERA for the St. Louis Cardinals
in 1968. Gibson's gems included eight runs allowed in his first 110
innings; 13 shutouts; and a remarkable, three-runs-in-101-innings
stretch. As amazing as these numbers are, they came during a time
when the National League ERA was 2.99. Only four league players hit
30 or more home runs the entire season. Sandy Koufax may have been
even more dominant, but he retired two years earlier at the age of
30. In 1966, his last season, Koufax was 27-9 with a 1.73 ERA and
won his third Cy Young.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez pitches in a softball-like American League, in which
the average ERA hovers around 5. In this circus atmosphere, he
allows 1.42 runs per game. Twenty-three men have scored on him all
season. Toronto's Shannon Stewart and Tony Batista, the only
players to cross the plate on him twice, should receive ``I Scored
On Pedro'' bumper stickers. In two months _ May and July _ Martinez
gave up a total of four runs. In other words, twice he pitched for
a month and still allowed one fewer run than the average pitcher
gives up in a game.
</P>
<P>
   Will you see that again? Sure. It just may take another 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   This is the year of Pete Sampras and Tiger Woods, winning more
often and more convincingly than anyone in history. In 1966, fans
were surprised when 26-year-old Jack Nicklaus won $5,000 at the
British Open. In 2000, the 24-year-old Woods played the Open course
at St. Andrews as if he designed it. He took home more than
$700,000.
</P>
<P>
   No golfer has played with such power and accuracy. No golfer has
made so much money so quickly. No golfer has been able to change
the way the sport is perceived.
</P>
<P>
   Will you see that again? Of course. It just may take 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine being 16 years old now. One of the Grumpies might tell
you about watching players such as Johnny Unitas and Deacon Jones.
You could say that you saw John Elway and Jerry Rice. You could say
that you saw Michael Jordan pass his championship baton to the
likes of Tim Duncan and Shaquille O'Neal. You could say that you
saw a great athlete named Lance Armstrong overcome testicular
cancer to win the Tour de France. In your youth, you saw, for the
first time, professional basketball players on national television
_ women pro basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   Be prepared. Some 2000 haters will continue to tell you that pro
sports are not what they used to be. They will continue to talk
about this era obscenely. But an obscenity will occur only if you
listen rather than watch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
