<HEADLINE>
AFTER 2 STRONG YEARS, CHIP EQUIPMENT MAKERS' STOCK FALTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is the party over?
</P>
<P>
   Companies that make expensive equipment used by semiconductor
chip manufacturers have enjoyed a roaring business for the last two
years, but suddenly investors are selling stocks as if the
notoriously cyclical industry might be heading south.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is hardly conclusive and many analysts believe
demand for chips used in everything from personal computers to
cellular telephones will remain strong for at least another year.
Continued demand for chips means the same thing for companies that
sell the equipment needed to make them.
</P>
<P>
   But the industry's boom and bust cycles that can last two or
three years each are accompanied with similarly severe stock
swings, so no one wants to be the last to realize fortunes are
taking a turn for the worse. Huge advances in semiconductor
equipment stocks over the last few years only add to the jitters of
the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have made a lot of money in these stocks,''
said analyst Neil Wagner, who covers semiconductors and equipment
makers at MFS Investment Management. ``You have people trying to
lock in gains at any sign of weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   This is bad news for practically everyone holding shares of a
herd of local companies serving some slice of the semiconductor
market because the stocks typically all rise or fall with the
tides.
</P>
<P>
   Among Bay State companies, Teradyne Inc. of Boston, fell about
10 percent Thursday. LTX Corp. of Westwood sank more than 20
percent and Varian Semiconductor Equipment Associates Inc. of
Gloucester slipped 13 percent. Cognex Corp. of Natick fell about 10
percent and MKS Instruments Inc. of Andover lost about 18 percent.
Only PRI Automation Inc. of Billerica escaped with a modest decline
on the day, though its stock was steeply lower through much of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   The news of the day: One leading equipment maker, Kulicke &AMP;
Soffa Industries Inc., said delayed orders could hurt profits
throughout the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
   No one catches cold alone in this crowd. So right away, analyst
Min Pang of SG Cowen Securities Corp. cut his rating on Teradyne
from a ``strong buy'' to a ``buy'' Thursday, noting the two
companies had similar market exposures, particularly among Asian
subcontractors.
</P>
<P>
   As sudden as the stock selling was Thursday, threads of doubt
and potentially negative news have been collected for several
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, analyst Jonathan Joseph of Salomon Smith Barney said
chip shipments would slow and prices would decline, forecasting
tapered demand within six to nine months.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of semiconductor equipment have reported slowing
growth in demand for two straight months. A leading trade
organization said its book-to-bill ratio had slipped from 1.36 to
1.26 between April and June.
</P>
<P>
   The ratio measures the rate of new customer orders compared with
the amount of equipment being shipped, so any figure above 1.0
suggests a growing market. In this case, the market was growing but
not at as fast a pace as it had been previously.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Teradyne reported its second-quarter orders actually
declined compared to the previous three months, after two straight
quarters of growth exceeding 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, leading cellular phone makers Nokia Corp.,
Ericsson AB and Motorola Inc. have issued varying shades of
pessimism about business in the near term.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular phone demand is closely watched by the semiconductor
world because its growth has been so spectacular. But those devices
still only account for about 8 percent of semicondcutor sales while
personal computers still account for about one-third of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The cycles of the semiconductor business are so severe, in part,
because it costs so much to build manufacturing facilities. Big
fabrication plants might cost $1.5 billion, so suppliers build when
demand is pent up and pump as many chips as possible through the
facility to make it pay off.
</P>
<P>
   So supply and demand is tracked in detail, but getting a handle
on the market as it turns is no easy task.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like we've probably reached the midpoint where supply
is catching up with demand, at least for awhile,'' said Lauriann
Kloppenburg, director of equity research at Loomis Sayles &AMP; Co. in
Boston. ``In this business people are always on the edge of their
chairs. Fear plays as a large factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts can argue about how much business might slow or
semiconductor equipment stocks could slide, but there is no
arguement about the industry's spectacular success over the last
three years.
</P>
<P>
   The value of Teradyne shares has been halved since their spring
peak, but are still up 590 percent between Sept. 30, 1998 and the
end of last month. Those share had been up about 1,100 percent as
of April.
</P>
<P>
   LTX shares are up 1,000 percent and PRI Automation has advanced
265 percent since the same point in the fall of 1998, though their
appreciation was twice as high as of April.
</P>
<P>
   So what do you do now? Don't expect a definitive answer from any
anlayst.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry should be healthy for at least the next year and
perhaps longer than that,'' said Wagner at MFS. ``The question is
the stock, whether that's enough to satisfy investors or not.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre (929-2918) and Charles Stein (929-2922) can also be
reached by e-mail at boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
