<HEADLINE>
LITTLE FEAT BOUNCES BACK WITH NEW ENERGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a little help from friends Phil Lesh, Jimmy Buffett, Phish,
and String Cheese Incident, the pioneering Little Feat has a new
lease on life, proving that the jam-band community takes care of
its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a band that was headed downhill fast, we've turned things
around,'' says Little Feat pianist Bill Payne. ``I didn't think
we'd get out of the tailspin, but we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Feat has a snappy new CD, ``Chinese Work Songs.'' The
title is meant as a playful swipe at the many styles the group has
covered through more than two decades together, first as a vehicle
for the legendary Lowell George (author of ``Dixie Chicken'' and
``Willin','' among other rock classics), and, throughout, as a
thinking man's party band.
</P>
<P>
   The new album contains a cover of Phish's ``Sample in a Jar,''
meant as a tribute to that Vermont-based band. ``We've influenced
Phish and String Cheese Incident, but the influences go both
ways,'' says Payne. ``So what better way to demonstrate that by
cutting some songs by people we admire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't yet played with Phish, but we did sit in with
String Cheese Incident,'' he adds. ``It was at the Gorge in
Washington State. We played `Pocky Way,' the old Neville Brothers
song. And we agreed to hook up with String Cheese at the festival
in Boulder, Colo., that they do every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Feat has also loosened up considerably since Payne and
Feat singer/guitarist Paul Barrere were tapped by former Grateful
Dead bassist Phil Lesh to be in his revolving jam band, Phil Lesh &AMP;
Friends, earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``By opening the door to the Grateful Dead audience and their
allegiances, we've been able to let people know we're still
around,'' says Payne. ``I loved working with Phil. He's a very
smart man, among other talents, and has such a knowledge of how to
put things together. The impact he's had on Paul and me over the
last six months is hard to calculate. It opened our eyes in many
ways. When we went back to Little Feat, it helped us shake up our
shows and run different songs into each other. We were getting to
where our shows were too predictable, so it was a godsend to work
with Phil and have his influence rub off.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Buffett, he suggested that Little Feat should be on his
Internet station at radiomargaritaville.com. They agreed and now
have ``The Little Feat Radio Hour'' (hosted by David Moss) running
three times on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The revitalized Little Feat is performing a bunch of tunes from
``Chinese Work Songs,'' an album that includes original tracks
spanning rock, funk, and Tex-Mex styles, along with covers of The
Band's ``Rag Mama Rag,'' Bob Dylan's ``It Takes a Lot to Laugh, It
Takes a Train To Cry,'' and the aforementioned Phish tune.
</P>
<P>
   The album was recorded in Barrere's house, with all the band
members in the same room no more than 10 feet from one another.
``On previous albums, we'd only have two or three in the room, and
the rest would be overdubs,'' says Payne, commenting on the
intimacy at the heart of the new CD.
</P>
<P>
   They also came to another conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that, as Little Feat, we really have a platform
after all these years,'' says Payne, who has also played with Bob
Seger, Bonnie Raitt, James Taylor, and many others. ``And that
platform allows us to play in any manner. It gives us the freedom
to stand tall or fall flat _ and I like that. We get into trouble
sometimes on the business side of things because of that freedom,
but it's what Little Feat is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AC/DC on the way: ``I'm going back out there to try to scream
again,'' AC/DC singer Brian Johnson says of the band's new tour.
It's a season overloaded with classic rock, but AC/DC is at the top
of any enthusiast's wish list.
</P>
<P>
   The band has been revived by a new album, ``Stiff Upper Lip,''
and by being featured in a recent VH1 ``Behind the Music'' episode,
though Johnson says the group hated the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like it. It was terribly done _ bloody awful,'' says
Johnson, who felt the show was sensationalized. As examples, he
cited how the producers spent a half-hour on the overdose death of
former AC/DC singer Bon Scott and dwelled on a serial killer who
was a fan and on a tragic accident at an AC/DC concert in Salt Lake
City when three fans were crushed in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, bad things have happened, but it's 99.9 percent
good things in this band _ and they weren't shown,'' says Johnson.
``It was an embarrassingly amateurish production. We have
complained about it to VH1 and they're redoing the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Much closer to Johnson's heart is a discussion of the group's
new album, which reuinited the band with George Young, who produced
their famed ``Powerage'' and ``Let There Be Rock'' discs. ``George
is great. He's like a cool uncle. He gets nothing but the highest
respect from me,'' says Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   As for the recording, Johnson adds, ``I did the whole album in
the control room with an old Shure microphone. I just belted it out
and it worked. But it was in a small room. I was knocking all the
furniture around when I was singing. I was like a pregnant hippo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 1334EDT &QL; 
