<HEADLINE>
BELLS, WHISTLES AND PREHISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
DAWN OF MAN 
A four-part miniseries 
Executive producers: Phillip Martin and Alexandra Middendorf 
Narrated by: Richard Dreyfuss  
On: TLC 
Time: Sunday and Monday, 9-11 p.m. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The labors of paleontologists, anthropologists, and other
scientists exploring the origins of man are not the stuff of breezy
television entertainment. Digging for artifacts in the field or
subjecting old bones to lab analysis are painstakingly incremental
tasks. Although this often tedious work has resulted in stunning
revelations about our prehistoric ancestors _ about their ability
to kill other animals or to speak, for examples _ how do you
dramatize the scientific busywork?
</P>
<P>
   The ``Dawn of Man'' series on TLC, debuting Sunday night at 9
and concluding Monday, does it with jazzy cinematography and
rapid-fire editing. Thus you might see an archeologically important
skull filmed from several angles with a variety of colored filters.
Add to this an eerie, reverberating musical score and brief,
shadowy reenactments of bits of prehistoric behavior, and I think
you're supposed to have a kind of nonfiction ``X-Files''
experience.
</P>
<P>
   While the four-part miniseries demands tolerance for this
obviously contrived style, close attention pays some dividends. The
series _ coproduced by the BBC and TLC _ offers an overview of the
emergence and spread of what were to become, over 5 million years,
modern human beings. Clear, if theatrical, narration voiced by
Richard Dreyfuss and often solid interviews tell fascinating
stories about man's evolution and how dedicated scientists pieced
them together.
</P>
<P>
   For only one example, take the segment in Sunday's second hour,
``Body Human,'' involving shards of flint associated with Altamura
Man, so-called because a complete skeleton was discovered in
Altamura, Italy, in 1993. Elsewhere, scientists unearthed flint
fragments that they then almost miraculously reassembled into the
large stone from which the slivers were chipped, only to discover a
central missing piece. A cast of the shape of the missing piece
revealed what a contemporary of Altamura Man, approximately a
half-million years old but almost as brainy as we are today, had
fashioned _ an efficient hand ax. Fossil evidence strongly suggests
it was used to butcher and clean extinct rhinos, elephants, and
horses.
</P>
<P>
   Ancient humans moving slowly north into Europe from Africa had
changed from scavengers into hunters apparently capable of
reflective thought, teamwork, and, one scientist hypothesizes,
family love.
</P>
<P>
   To judge from the first two hours of the miniseries, accounts of
discoveries like this abound in ``Dawn of Man.'' Individually, they
are well chronicled, despite the distracting atmospherics. But
important connections between them are often missing or murky,
making the larger evolutionary narrative difficult if not sometimes
impossible to follow. Most problematic is the uncritical approach
to the work of the articulate and generally passionate scientists
involved. Rarely is the viewer told the difference between what is
established fact, hypothesis, serious speculation, or just fanciful
conjecture _ so, in the end, it's not entirely clear how much we
really know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0092 </DOCNO>
