u e BC-MOVIE-SAVING-BOS &LR;      08-04 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SAVING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARMING CHARACTERS SAVE `GRACE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
SAVING GRACE 
Directed by: Nigel Cole 
Screenplay by: Craig Ferguson 
Starring: Brenda Blethyn, Craig Ferguson, Martin Clunes, Tcheky
Karyo, Jamie Forman, Bill Bailey, Valeria Edmond, Tristan Sturrock 
Running time: 94 minutes 
Rated: R (drug content and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Saving Grace'' is what a friend of mine calls a village
comedy, one in which an entire village quaintly conspires. It's the
latest in a long, droll line of comedies from ``Tight Little
Island'' to ``Local Hero'' to ``Waking Ned Devine.'' It can't quite
go the distance. It runs out of ideas, eccentricity and local color
before collapsing in a forced ending. But it's funny and charming
most of the time, thanks to Brenda Blethyn as a widow who turns out
to be more worldly and less cocooned than everyone thinks. The
point is that everyone feels involved, even if only in the most
loosely communal way, because everyone in the small Cornish seaside
village likes upbeat, matronly Grace Trevethan, whose ne'er-do-well
husband not only has left her widowed, but heavily in debt.
</P>
<P>
   So their natural reaction is to turn the other way when she
stumbles into a get-rich-quick plan that would save her homey
cottage from creditors by utilizing her gardening skills in
hitherto unforeseen ways. When she sorrowfully informs her Scottish
gardener, Matthew (Craig Ferguson, who also co-wrote the film),
that reduced circumstances will force her to lay him off, he
responds with a proposal. Until now content to raise a few
marijuana plants on the sly in a secluded piece of woodland, he
suggests that they escalate the project in Grace's greenhouse.
Thanks to Grace's green thumb, the plants all but start spilling
out of what becomes their marijuana plantation.
</P>
<P>
   Belthyn's Grace, looking both gentle and sleek, never falls into
the trap of stereotypical twittering as the kindly housewife who
never once thinks of herself as a victim as she becomes ever more
adept at dodging the man from the bank in London, calling about the
mortgage payments. Ferguson, a skilled farceur, similarly mutes the
Scotsman's growing anxiety and certainty that he's getting in over
his head, which of course makes him that much funnier. Valerie
Edmond, as his girlfriend whose pregnancy motivates him to amass a
pile of money, is a gust of fresh air as she introduces skepticism
to the mix. She's convinced that Grace will wind up in jail and
that it'll be Matthew's fault despite the fact that the whole place
is rooting for Grace and trying not to blab too much to outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   What keeps the film going is Grace's way of matter-of-factly
revealing surprising depths of resiliency. These involve
confronting her late husband's mistress in London and later facing
a French drug dealer, to whom the veteran Tcheky Karyo imparts a
few surprising facets. ``Saving Grace'' _ who, by the way, seems
quite capable of saving herself _ edges into genre cliche in its
portrayals of the villagers _ a pair of old woman shopkeepers who
get titteringly high when the weed slips into the food chain, a
vicar addicted to Hammer horror movies on the late show, and a
bumbling local cop whose ability to turn a blind eye to victimless
crimes by the locals who are his friends approaches the breaking
point. ``Saving Grace'' goes down easily, if implausibly, enough.
But it's more agreeable than it is original.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0093 </DOCNO>
