<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HOLLOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOLLOW MAN' OFFERS LITTLE SUBSTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
HOLLOW MAN 
Directed by: Paul Verhoeven 
Screenplay by: Andrew W. Marlowe 
Starring: Elisabeth Shue, Kevin Bacon, Josh Brolin, Kim Dickens,
Greg Grunberg, Joey Slotnick, Mary Randle, William Devane 
Running time: 114 minutes 
Rated: R 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Hollow Man'' is an invisible man movie that should have been
an inaudible man movie. Every time the characters open their
mouths, they hammer it deeper into the ground. Taken from dull to
ludicrous by a script with a death grip on the obvious, ``Hollow
Man'' is the kind of film in which one character says, ``He'll be
OK,'' about a guy who's gushing blood and obviously has only
seconds to live. That's followed by Elisabeth Shue glancing at her
wounded lover and saying, as she reaches for a handy roll of duct
tape, ``He didn't hit any organs _ I'll find something to close the
wound.'' These are people who are supposed to be scientists,
including Kevin Bacon, who day after day climbed into a skin-tight
latex costume to play the genius who grows aggressive and
power-crazed once he realizes he doesn't have to look at himself in
the mirror the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the film runs amok much more problematically than
the scientist does. Like so many sci-fi movies, it's reactionary to
its core. Its message is don't do research, you'll discover
something that will offend the gods. In other words, don't mess
with nature, or else. But science is precisely about messing with
nature. Without science, we'd still be living in caves, without
appendectomies, penicillin or the World Wrestling Federation. It
can at least be said that ``Hollow Man'' begins with some neat
special effects, in which an ape turns invisible by degrees, first
shedding its skin, then its muscle and sinew, then its blood
vessels, and finally its skeleton. When the invisibility is
reversed, the primate reappears in reverse order.
</P>
<P>
   But when Bacon's megalomanical scientist tries it on himself, he
gets stuck in invisibility. His irritability and aggressiveness
escalate, steered into sadistic misogyny, a Verhoeven trademark
ever since Arnold Schwarzenegger's character in ``Total Recall''
emptied a gun into his wife's midriff and said, ``Consider this a
divorce.'' In the film, Bacon's scientist had been thrown over by
Shue's researcher, so part of his power-tripping is of the
psychosexual variety, first exercised when he sneaks up, invisible,
on a couple of other women and turns them into unwilling sexual
playthings. Suffice to say that the longer the scientist is stuck
in the invisibility mode, the worse his crimes become, and that he
never bothers with stuff like world domination. For him, rape will
do.
</P>
<P>
   The film begins to crumble the moment we see the invisibility
serum, which has the bad luck to be the exact bright red color of
Eddie Murphy's truth serum in ``Nutty Professor II.'' It's as if
Hollywood science, a dicey proposition at the best of times, has
succumbed to a lazy serum-of-the-month mentality. Not that this is
the best of times for science at the movies. These days, scientists
just punch up what they want on computer screens. Slick but
mundane, not as campy or juicy as, say, Bela Lugosi peering into a
bubbling beaker in ``Bride of the Monster'' or Colin Clive waiting
for a bolt of lightning to jump-start his tableful of sewn-together
body parts in ``Frankenstein.'' Or, for that matter, Claude Rains
surpassing the new film in every way in the antiquated but still
effective 1933 original ``Invisible Man.'' If not for cable and
video, ``Hollow Man'' would become an invisible film. Sherman Klump
is going to have to carry the ball for science singlehandedly this
summer at the movies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2740 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV0     08-04 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV06-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BE CAREFUL ADDING LAYERS TO FLOOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August   06, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. The 12-inch-square vinyl tiles on my kitchen floor are 40
years old. Ten or 15 years go, a man put down thin plywood, then
sheet vinyl. Now I'd like to put down another layer of sheet vinyl.
Can I put down thin plywood on top of the old sheet vinyl and put
on new?
</P>
<P>
   D.M.D., Hyde Park, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, it is possible, but adding the plywood and new sheet
vinyl will add half inch to the floor, and this might become a
problem at doorways, where the raised floor may interfere with
doors opening and closing. Or, the raised floor may be higher than
the floors of adjacent rooms, most noticeable at doorways, where
someone could trip over the lip.
</P>
<P>
   These problems can be solved. Door bottoms can be trimmed so
they will clear the raised floor. Thresholds can be applied to the
openings to ease the differences of each floor.
</P>
<P>
   If there are no other problems, anticipated or real, then you
can add another layer of plywood and new sheet vinyl.
</P>
<P>
   Taking off the top sheet vinyl can be risky, if it contains
asbestos. The backing of sheet vinyl installed 15 to 20 years ago
may contain asbestos, and if so, it must be removed professionally.
To determine this, break off a small chip, seal it in a plastic
bag, and take it to an asbestos abatement company. They are in the
Yellow Pages under Asbestos Abatement. If the sheet vinyl does
contain asbestos, you can cover it with more plywood or have it
removed professionally. If it doesn't, you can do anything with it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My bathroom has a clawfoot tub under a sloped ceiling, so I
can't install a wrap-around shower curtain around it. My friends
seem to be exuberant bathers, and a lot of water spilled on the
floor, which leaked, and ruined the kitchen ceiling below. Can I
make the floor waterproof? It has sheet vinyl on it, in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   V.G., Somerville, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Instead of waterproofing the floor, how about
exuberant-proofing your friends? I assume you have tried every
which way to put in a wrap-around curtain. Could you move the tub
under a higher ceiling to accommodate the curtain?
</P>
<P>
   OK, try this: Lift the round metal or plastic bells that wrap
around water pipes and drains coming up through the floor. Caulk
around the pipes and put the bells back. If necessary, caulk all
edges of the room.
</P>
<P>
   Then give your exuberant friends a big mop so they can mop up
all that water.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am not overun by silverfish, but I do see one on the floor
occasionally. How can I get rid of them and keep rid of them?
</P>
<P>
   A.C., Bedford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. One critter occasionally? Certainly not an infestation. Sweep
it up and throw it away. If you get a lot more, you could sprinkle
boric acid along baseboards and in the cellar and attic where you
think they might be proliferating. If you can see the boric acid,
you have used too much. That means that very little is needed to be
effective. Remember too that it is toxic and must be kept away from
humans, babies, kids, and pets. Sweeping and throwing away is still
your best bet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house needs to be painted, but it has asbestos-cement
shingles. The paint is not peeling but has streaks. Can I cover the
shingles with new siding?
</P>
<P>
   J.K., Rockland, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You cannot put anything on top of the shingles, because
anything new must be nailed or screwed on, and this would damage
the asbestos and release fibers. Your choice is to paint;
professional removal is very expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The streaks are probably mold. Remove it with a bleach solution
and rinse with a hose. You can't sand the finish or pressure-wash
it, but you can wash it with a strong detergent solution, then hose
off. Apply two thin coats of a latex house paint or two thin coats
of a solid color latex stain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am applying shingles to the walls of a shed. I am doubling
the first course, to create a flared drip edge. How far should I
drop the first course below the sheathing? I am weaving the
shingles at corners. Should I caulk them where they meet?
</P>
<P>
   JAN HUBBELL, Franklin, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Drop the shingles 1/2 to 3/4 inch. If the sheathing boards
are flush with the concrete or other part of the foundation, butt
the undercourse shingles flush with the sheathing. Overlap the
starter course by 1/2 to 3/4 inch.
</P>
<P>
   Weaving shingles means alternating the overlap of each course
where the shingles meet at a corner. Do not caulk that joint; the
shingles will move and open up, which is normal, and will look
worse if they are caulked.
</P>
<P>
   To solve this, you can put in corner boards, two boards nailed
together to form an ``L'' shape; this ``L'' is applied to the
corner. Shingles will butt up against the boards instead of being
weaved.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail
hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
