<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONDOLEEZA-CABINET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ACHIEVER IS `FIRST AMONG EQUALS' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PEGGY FIKAC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ She's the ``first among equals'' on Texas Gov.
George W. Bush's presidential campaign team of foreign policy
advisers, this 45-year-old woman striding briskly through the halls
at the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   She was director of Soviet and East European Affairs for the
National Security Council when Bush's father was president, and
served as his special assistant for national security affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at age 38, she became the youngest, first black and first
female provost at Stanford University in California, where she had
begun teaching political science 12 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   She left the provost's post last year, is on a leave of absence
from the university, and has become a close adviser to Bush,
leading to speculation that she may get a Cabinet post if he wins.
</P>
<P>
   Condoleezza Rice, who Tuesday helped sketch Bush's foreign
policy thinking in a featured convention speech, turns aside the
speculation with, ``Oh, we're not going to start staffing the
presidency until he wins the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Pausing in the convention bustle for an interview, she answers
another question in a way that seems at odds with her high-powered
resume.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how a super-achiever interacts with a man who _ though now
possibly destined for the White House _ acknowledges he only found
his path in life when he turned 40, she said: ``As a matter of
fact, I think I found my path later, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to be a concert pianist. And I had no intention of
doing anything with politics or foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``later'' for her still was sooner than for most people.
</P>
<P>
   According to her biography, Rice entered the University of
Denver at age 15.
</P>
<P>
   She switched her major from piano performance to political
science when she realized she wouldn't be a great pianist,
according to ``Contemporary Black Biography.''
</P>
<P>
   She graduated with a bachelor's degree in political science when
she was 19. She received a master's degree from the University of
Notre Dame and a doctorate from the University of Denver's Graduate
School of International Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a very driven person, I don't think,'' she said this
week. ``I like doing well, but I really like to keep balance in my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice said she and the governor probably share that sense of
balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The importance of family. The importance of church. The
importance of ... sports,'' she said. ``And I don't think of myself
as somebody who's been single-minded throughout my life. It just
isn't who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   One of her most intense policy sessions with Bush occurred while
they were hiking on Bush's ranch ``and hiking `Balkan Hill' _ we've
now named it, because we were having an intense discussion about
Balkan history,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   They made it to the top of the hill ``and never stopped
talking,'' demonstrating that the two fitness enthusiasts are in
good shape.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is an avid runner. She also runs, but restricts the
activity because of ``not-so-great knees,'' a lingering reminder of
a time when she figure-skated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't run with him. There's no way,'' Rice said. ``I
could lift with him, though. I lift weights.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice, who lives in Palo Alto, Calif., works out with the
Stanford football strength coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he (Bush) likes that as much as he likes anything
about me ... that I'm physically fit and able to walk Balkan Hill
with him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Ray Sullivan said the governor and Rice
got to know each other in 1995 when she visited Austin.
</P>
<P>
   They became friends in 1998 when both were in Kennebunkport,
Maine, where the Bush family has a home, and began to talk about
foreign affairs and military issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could call her the first among equals when it comes to
Bush's foreign policy experts,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's speech was a one-two punch for Bush's presidential
campaign, encompassing foreign affairs and the high-profile
campaign post held by an African-American woman.
</P>
<P>
   Rice helped give a national audience some insight into the
foreign-policy thinking of a man who, early in his campaign,
slipped at times on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   In one spur-of-the-moment television interview, for example,
Bush couldn't remember the names of leaders of several world hot
spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows a great deal about foreign policy,'' she said. ``My
job has really been to bring together people around him who can
give him good policy options as he develops an agenda for foreign
policy, to have him think about how he wants to communicate that
agenda to the American people and to deal with some of those
tougher challenges that he would have to cope with if he became
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice said Bush ``has long cared about and studied and been
interested in Mexico and Latin America, and that's an area of the
world that has often been neglected in American foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   As a woman and African-American, Rice also is part of a
high-profile group that Republicans hope will show their desire for
including different faces in their party.
</P>
<P>
   Rice was a Democrat until 1980, when she voted for Ronald Reagan
because she didn't like the course of American foreign policy under
Jimmy Carter, for whom she also had voted.
</P>
<P>
   She said she hoped her speech Tuesday would contribute to the
message of inclusion pushed by Bush, with its focus not only on
Republican principles of operating in the world but on ``who we are
as a people, and why it's important for the American president to
understand what it is that motivates and inspires the American
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have sought to paint Bush and the Republican Party as
unfriendly to women and minorities, calling the message of
inclusion only a veneer.
</P>
<P>
   Among many issues, Democrats cite the Republican platform's
opposition to allowing women to choose abortion and the small
percentage of minority delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an illusion of inclusion,'' Democratic National
Committee spokesman Rick Hess said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rice also said that the GOP can understand and respond to
the idea that there are experiences and concerns related to gender
or race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in emphasizing education, has put the focus on an issue
that has been ``the North Star for African-Americans since the end
of slavery,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be the first to admit that sometimes the party has had a
tone that hasn't always been very welcoming,'' she said, ``but I
think that Gov. Bush is trying to send a message of inclusion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
