<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GODS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM PAGANS TO PAUL, HUMANITYS' SEARCH FOR GOD DEFTLY TOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN CLEGG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
A WORLD FULL OF GODS:  THE STRANGE TRIUMPH OF CHRISTIANITY 
Keith Hopkins, The Free Press, 416 pp., $26.00 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Ancient religions did much of their business with stories,''
historian Keith Hopkins writes. ``Poets, priests, and temple
attendants used stories to help confirm faith among the faithful,
to explain the origin and future of the world, and to describe the
complex relationship between Gods and humans . . .''
</P>
<P>
   But modern religions need narrative, too. The New Testament has
its Gospels, which tell and retell the events of Jesus's life.
Judaism has a rich history of midrash, or stories, that interpret
biblical passages. Pagans, modern or ancient, have their thundering
tales of gods and goddesses. Hopkins, a professor of ancient
history at King's College in Cambridge, England, spins legends and
stories of his own in ``A World Full of Gods,'' an exploration of
the roots of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   Like Karen Armstrong in ``A History of God,'' Hopkins tries to
comprehend the religious impulse by reviewing history and context.
And, like Armstrong, he doesn't hesitate to examine the interplay
of the human spirit with the divine. He gives full brief to the
strange, the bawdy, and the just plain wrong. History may be
written by the victors, but it's the losers who add the footnotes,
and the spice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gloss it as you will,'' Hopkins writes, ``the worship of a
crucified criminal as the Son of God, the divine exaltation of a
humble human, the crucifixion of God, and the ethical message of
achieving individual salvation through faith, virtue, and
repentance constituted a radical break with pagan polytheism,
animal sacrifice, and temple worship.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins reminds us that Jesus was a messianic Jew intent on
overturning more than just a few moneychangers' tables in the
Temple in Jerusalem. Executed during a time of political ferment in
the Roman Empire, Jesus left a corps of fervent believers who went
on to found a church.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Armstrong or Elaine Pagels, however, Hopkins flirts with
danger stylistically. Some chapters are serious, scholarly
monographs. Others are written as fiction. Time travelers (equipped
with learn-as-you-go computer chips) experience pagan rites in
Pompeii and traffic in magic in Egypt. A fictional dinner party
runs aground when a religious discussion erupts between Christians,
pagans, and Simon the Jew, who refuses to partake of the wild boar.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should just look around,'' Epiphanius the pagan says.
``The great mass of the world is suffering from want, cold, hunger.
Meanwhile the Christians, racked with fever and disease, dream of
posthumous immortality. Who is this God who can help you in the
next world but not in this? We don't need your God, thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Interspersed throughout are letters from colleagues, reacting to
drafts that Hopkins has sent to them for comment. (One such
grouping is titled, ``Interlude: Objections). Reacting to the
dinner party piece, a scholar at the Jewish Theological Seminary in
New York writes, ``Somehow your piece seems more of an idealized
twentieth-century Cambridge college high table than genuine
second-century Antioch or Caesarea. Rather funny, really _ you try
to write a genuine atmospheric piece about antiquity, and quite
unconsciously, instead, you reproduce your own social world.'' He
goes on to pick apart the historic setting and the overall method
but makes a substantial contribution to the debate by sharing his
own take on God, demons, and angels.
</P>
<P>
   Like Edmund Morris in ``Dutch,'' Hopkins has a penchant for the
literary jump-cut, the fictive pause. But it works better here. The
theology is packed into pages of notes at the end of the book,
adding gravity without bogging down the narrative power of the main
text. Readers are more likely to remember the vivid dialogue in his
mini-screenplay, ``How the Dead Sea Scrolls Were Found and Lost,''
than slog through the source text, Justin's ``Dialogue with
Trypho.''
</P>
<P>
   As a host of apostles, rabbis, and pagan mythologizers realized,
it all comes down to the story. Hopkins, in the end, tells it well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
