<HEADER>
A2745 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-ALICE-BOS &LR;      08-04 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ALICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BINOCHE'S SPIRIT LIFTS `ALICE AND MARTIN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
ALICE AND MARTIN 
Directed by: Andre Techine 
Screenplay by: Techine, Gilles Taurand 
Starring: Juliette Binoche, Alexis Loret, Mathieu Amalric, Carmen
Maura, Jean-Pierre Lorit, Marthe Villalonga 
Running time: 124 minutes 
Rated: R (a scene of sexuality and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's no wonder that France's finest actors keep returning to
work with Andre Techine. The most underrated of French filmmakers,
he constantly specifies world after provincial world of gnarled
emotional complexity, rendered in striking images that amplify the
often careening lives of his protagonists. Catherine Deneuve and
Daniel Auteuil twice have teamed up with Techine, in ``My Favorite
Season'' and ``Thieves,'' Deneuve had one of her best roles in
Techine's ``Scene of the Crime'' and Juliette Binoche now follows
her breakthrough film, Techine's ``Rendez-Vous,'' with the even
more richly compelling ``Alice and Martin.''
</P>
<P>
   It rides several strong emotional arcs, yet it never plays like
anything preordained, as a Hollywood star vehicle (of which it
occasionally reminds us) would. It's messy and permeated by a
provisional air, although its passions are relentless. Techine also
trusts us to put the pieces together, refrains from spelling
everything out in exposition and dialogue. Rather, the film moves
in quantum leaps. They always proceed logically from what preceded
them. It takes us a while to figure out what's what, yet the effort
is more than repaid, especially in Binoche's performance as Alice.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with a boy being brought to live in the grim
iron-gated house of a provincial industrialist, its squat stony
heaviness in vivid contrast to the hurtling nature of the scenes
played out there. One quick flash-forward later, we see the boy
named Martin, now a young man (Alexis Loret), flee the house. He
tries to lie low in the country, but when he's caught stealing eggs
in a henhouse, police are called, intervention from home ensues,
and he's soon on his way to Paris to live with his bohemian
brother, Benjamin (Mathieu Amalric), and the latter's musician
roommate, Alice, who at first resents Martin's presence, which she
regards as intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   Alice and Benjamin, who is gay, share everything except sex. To
their surprise, Martin the sensitive bumpkin, is spotted at a cafe
by an agent, who whisks him into a modeling career. Almost
offhandedly, and always with a light touch, Techine uses the
contrast between the slick, driven commercialism of the modeling
world and the maverick artist sensibility of Alice and Benjamin to
serve as a precursor of the tension that never quite departs when
Alice and Martin become lovers. It simply is rechanneled. The depth
of Alice's commitment becomes apparent when she learns she's
pregnant and fragile Martin freaks out.
</P>
<P>
   Binoche and Techine take their time unveiling Alice's quiet
strength. But there's no overlooking it once she makes up her mind
to go to Martin's home town in the southern region of Cahors and
put things to rights, against entrenched opposition. Martin's stern
father is dead, his widow (Marthe Villabella) is a born
stonewaller, another forceful local woman (Carmen Maura) plays a
part in Martin's story, and his brothers aren't quite what Alice
expected. Binoche convinces utterly as a force of nature who's
making it up as she goes along, possessed by a sense of mission,
but not premeditation. Without ever overdoing, Techine photographs
her as a force of nature, too, whether against a rocky seashore or
a deceptively mellow background of trees in autumn. I'd be
surprised if the year gave us another film in which a woman stands
by her man with such softly unstoppable resolve. Lucky Martin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
