<HEADLINE>
INSURERS TRY TO BOOST REPUTATIONS AS MONEY MANAGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; At most mutual fund companies, this would be crisis time.
</P>
<P>
   The top marketing executive quit in April. The chief executive
jumped ship in May. Both veterans left their slow-moving Boston
investment shop, State Street Research &AMP; Management, for Internet
start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   A sign of the times? That's what the firm's parent, MetLife
Inc., says as it hunts for new top talent for the group. But it's
also an indication of the struggle insurers face as they try to
boost their lagging stature as money managers _ especially insurers
that have just become publicly traded.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle is both cultural and financial, as people who have
worked for insurance companies attest. With a few notable
exceptions, insurers have a poor record of inspiring top-notch fund
performance and attracting assets to their fund groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insurance company assets are managed in a completely different
way than retail mutual funds,'' said John Benvenuto, a consultant
with Financial Research Corp. in Boston. ``You have to literally
build a large firewall and let them operate completely
independently.''
</P>
<P>
   Most insurance companies have only been in the fund business
since the 1980s or later. They entered the field to help attract
customers and to offer one-stop shopping for customers' financial
needs. But many have learned that's easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
   At Boston's John Hancock Financial Services Inc., which sold
shares to the public for the first time in January, fund assets are
dwindling at a time when more successful fund groups are exploding.
</P>
<P>
   Assets in Hancock's fund group have dropped 6.7 percent in the
past 12 months, to $31.9 billion, as investors have withdrawn
millions of dollars in investments. Hancock's pretax earnings on
the fund unit fell 25 percent from a year ago, to $16.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   In another Hancock investment unit, Independence Investment
Associates, institutional investors have pulled $1.2 billion from
the firm, mainly to shift to lower-cost index funds, Hancock said
in its earnings report.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock declined to discuss its investment groups. But the
company installed a new chief executive for the funds at the end of
last year _ annuity expert Maureen Ford, formerly of Mass Mutual
Life Insurance Co. _ and recently changed its commission structure
to improve fund sales.
</P>
<P>
   MetLife, which went public in April, is grappling with the same
issue: how to grow an investment business under a conservative
insurance culture.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, MetLife said it earned only $11 million on
its investment businesses, down from $14 million a year earlier.
Those earnings will decline once the company's sale of its 48
percent stake in another Boston investment firm, Nvest LP, is
complete. MetLife said it couldn't pass up the $2.2 billion deal,
but the move sparked questions about the insurer's commitment to
the sector.
</P>
<P>
   State Street Research's interim chief, Jeff Hodgman, a longtime
executive of the parent, assures: ``Having a first-rate investment
capability is not only desirable. It's critical to the growth of
the insurance business.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the words of a company suddenly trying to impress Wall
Street. State Street Research's assets have been stagnant at about
$54 billion for the past 12 months. And for years, State Street has
been all but homeless at MetLife, reporting to the insurer's
general counsel, instead of to someone with responsibility for a
business line.
</P>
<P>
   Hodgman said that reporting line may change, but he promised
nothing: ``It's unusual, but that's the way we do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry is watching with some interest to see who will
replace Ralph Verni as CEO, as a gauge of MetLife's seriousness
about growing the business. The top candidate is said to be an
executive from T. Rowe Price, the successful Baltimore fund group.
</P>
<P>
   Putting a strong investment person in charge would help State
Street Research, analysts said. Two standouts among fund groups
that are owned by insurance companies, Boston-based Putnam
Investments and MFS Funds, are run by strong leaders who didn't
grow up in the insurance world.
</P>
<P>
   MFS's earnings have surged over the past three years and are now
the biggest slice of the profits of its parent, Toronto's Sun Life
Financial Services. Sun Life also recently switched from a mutual
company owned by its policyholders to a publicly traded concern.
Putnam's revenues grew at a rate of 19 percent in the second
quarter, nearly double the overall 10 percent rate for its parent,
March &AMP; McLennan Cos. Putnam's operating income jumped 17 percent,
to $256 million.
</P>
<P>
   No amount of good management can replace the power of strong
investment performance in attracting assets, analysts said. Both
Hancock and State Street Research have struggled with spotty
performance in recent years, while MFS in particular has batted out
huge returns on the kinds of aggressive stock funds that investors
favor these days.
</P>
<P>
   Fund executives complain that only a handful of companies have
been enjoying investors' attention in recent years. Outside of
Fidelity Investments, Janus, Vanguard, and a few others, it's been
tough going, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lehman Brothers analyst Eric Berg said, MetLife appears
committed to State Street Research: ``I believe it's an area
they're working on _ believing that performance issues can be
turned around there.''
</P>
<P>
   If the newly public insurance companies can't make a go of asset
management, Wall Street will surely demand that they spend their
resources elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Hodgman isn't giving in yet. He says the goal for State Street
Research is ``clearly to make it larger, stronger, more profitable
and certainly more involved in the future of MetLife products.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
