   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Aug. 5:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-QUEEN-MOTHER (London) _ Surrounded by three generations
of the royal family, Queen Elizabeth, the Queen Mother, celebrated
her 100th birthday on Friday waving to cheering well-wishers from
the Buckingham Palace balcony where she had helped lead national
rejoicing at the end of World War II and on other notable
occasions. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-EVOCATIVE-SIGNS (Mexico City) _ The map of the world's
largest metropolis is a kind of literary masterpiece. The street
guide reads as if a writer from the school of magical realism had
cut his work into confetti and sprinkled it over the city. People
live on streets named Heart and named Soul. They live on Forest of
Light, Mirror of Water, Forest of Miracles, Garden of Memories,
Tree of Fire, Forest of Secrets, Sea of Dreams. Surreal street
names can reflect hard realities: Work is long. Love and Happiness
are short. Good Luck crosses Hope, then hits a dead end.
Intersections become works of imagination: the Volga River flows
into the Nile, Beethoven meets Bach, the Himalayas cross the Alps.
And Comprehension ends in Silence. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-U.N. (Shanghai) _ Taiwan is again pushing to join the
United Nations, arguing that the world body could be a good forum
in which Taiwan and China could settle their differences. By Craig
S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-REACT (Datelines to come) _ Voices from around the country
as citizens react to the Republican National Convention. With
pieces by Jane Gross, Dirk Johnson, James Sterngold and Tina Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-BUSH-ECONOMY (Washington) _ Gov. George W. Bush's acceptance
speech at the Republican National Convention Thursday night
emphasized several touchstones of his economic plan _ that this is
an age of prosperity and that those in greatest need should receive
the greatest help. But much of the Bush program was not mentioned _
like tax help for the rich. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAMPAIGN (Dateline to kum) _ George W. Bush day
developments. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CAMPAIGN (Wrightsville Beach, N.C.) _ Al Gore day
developments. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT1,2.
</P>
<P>
   NAACP-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ The NAACP starts a $7 million
get-out-the-vote effort. By Raymond Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SINATRA-STATUE (New York) _ A proposed statue of Frank
Sinatra in Times Square has touched off one of those
only-in-New-York neighborhood battles.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PHILIPPINES-CHARITY (New York) _ A tale of philanthropy: a
publishing executive has gained notoriety and popularity in the
Philippines by contributing vast sums of money _ in the millions,
perhaps _ to build hospitals and civic facilities. The problem,
Manhattan prosecutors say, is that she embezzled the money from her
company. By Katherine E. Finkelstein.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Job growth slowed in July, in the
clearest sign yet that the red-hot economy is cooling down.
American businesses added just 138,000 jobs in the month, down from
242,000 in June. The number of government jobs tumbled, as the
Census Bureau disbanded the legions of temporary workers it hired
to conduct the 2000 census, resulting in an overall loss of 108,000
jobs. The decline in overall payrolls was the first since January
1996 and the biggest in nearly a decade. But factories added the
most jobs in almost two years, and employment surged at restaurants
and financial firms, and the unemployment rate held steady at 4
percent. Average hourly wages grew 0.4 percent, slightly more than
expected but the same pace as in June. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   UNILEVER-DIVIDE (London) _ Unilever, the global consumer goods
giant that has been on a buying spree in the United States,
announced Friday that it would realign the company into two
divisions, one focused on food brands like Lipton Tea and Ragu and
the other on consumer products like Dove soap and Elizabeth Arden
products. Unilever also announces a 7 percent rise in
second-quarter profits, higher than expected. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   ORPHANED-BRANDS (Cincinnati, Ohio) _ Is now a good time to try
to make a business out of someone else's jilted labels? Behemoths
like Procter &AMP; Gamble and Unilever are becoming more aggressive in
dropping brands that are no longer among the market leaders. The
business of reviving so-called ghost or orphaned brands has its
risks, of course. For the two former P&AMP;G employees who have
acquired Procter &AMP; Gamble's Oxydol laundry detergent, the challenge
is how much life they can squeeze out of the 73-year-old brand.
``The question is, is Oxydol such an ancient brand that it is
valueless and not worth it to revive it?'' says a branding
consultant, noting the market's fierce competition. By Kruti
Tirvedi.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT4.
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON-LABOR (Undated) _ Looking at the labor dispute between
Verizon Communications, formerly Bell Atlantic, and the
Communications Workers of America and the IBEW ahead of a strike
deadline of 12:01 a.m. EDT Sunday. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   AETNA-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Aetna says it will track costs more
closely while relaxing some managed-care restrictions. The company
posts a 17 percent increase in operating earnings, better than
analysts' lowered forecasts. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
