<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2768 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-SCHULKEN-COLUMN05-COX     08-04 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHULKEN-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Old photos convey much more than mere props for a GOP skit
 &HT;    By Mary C. Schulken
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ The yellowed picture of a dark-haired girl
hardly shows the creases of the years it rode out bombs in a young
man's wallet.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does the snapshot of him on her nightstand convey the weight
of her wondering whether he would come home from that place where
the world had gone to war.
</P>
<P>
   He gave four years because he was asked, and because it was his
way to honor obligation. She waited four years because he was
handsome and kind and funny. Theirs is the story of a generation.
It is as familiar as the dust mice that live under the
refrigerator, and as remarkable as buried treasure.
</P>
<P>
   And now it has become a marketing device for a political party
with eyes fixed on the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The party of George W. Bush, baby boomer, has put him forth as
its best to hold the highest office in the land. He has never
fought a war. He served in the National Guard. He has a father who
fought a war, the big war, they call it. And a father who later
held, with dignity if not overwhelming effectiveness, the office
his son seeks.
</P>
<P>
   This week in Philadelphia, on the occasion of George W.'s
nomination, the Grand Old Party for one night devoted its
convention to the veterans of the nation's wars. There were teary
tributes to the greatest generation, and to past Republican
presidents, including Bush, that pointed to their years in uniform,
and what that meant. There was '40s song and dance by costumed
young performers far too carefree to know about war.
</P>
<P>
   And when it was through, the lives of men and women in ragged
wartime snapshots were draped around a candidate who seeks the
presidency with the name of his father, and little else.
</P>
<P>
   The girl in the yellowed picture is my mother. She spent her
life prodding knowledge into the minds of children who sometimes
didn't have shoes. They give her bear hugs now in the grocery
store.
</P>
<P>
   She is 81, and lives alone in the house she shared with the
young man who carried her to war in his back pocket. At night,
before she turns out the lights, she looks at him in his
dress-downs in that photograph on her nightstand, just as she did
those long years they were apart.
</P>
<P>
   The life they lived was true and good and honest. But the times
were filled with unforgiving choices. My parents asked no thanks
for their convictions beyond the chance to live quietly.
</P>
<P>
   That contribution is deserving of a memorial that shares
Lincoln's view of reflection in the most powerful city on earth.
</P>
<P>
   It is deserving of policies that honor the sacrifices of war,
and the infirmities that come at the end of good lives.
</P>
<P>
   But their life was not a silly song and dance in a red, white
and blue spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Nor swaddling clothes for a candidate without a blanket of his
own.
</P>
<P>
   Mary C. Schulken is editorial page editor for The Daily
Reflector. E-mail her at mschulken(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
