<SLUG> BC-TAX-HOLIDAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SHOPPERS GEAR UP FOR TAX-FREE SPREE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By LUCY HOOD   
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express News   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Notebooks, pens, pencils, crayons, erasers and
lunch boxes remind shoppers that a new school year is just around
the corner.
</P>
<P>
   But school supplies aren't on the list of items exempt from
state and local taxes during the annual three-day tax-free holiday,
which began Friday morning and ends at midnight Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators says they hope to add school supplies _ as well as
backpacks and sewing materials _ to next year's list of tax-exempt
items and to extend the three-day event to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the notion of a sales tax holiday makes good public
policy in Texas, because we have such a regressive form of
taxation,'' said Texas Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, who sponsored
a bill in the 1999 session that created the tax-free holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ```I think the consumers appreciate a tax decrease any way they
can get it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sales tax reprieve applies to clothing and shoes with a
price tag less than $100. Consumers in San Antonio will save 7.75
percent in state and local taxes if they purchase any of the more
than 100 items on the list this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The list includes the expected _ pants, shirts, tennis shoes,
socks _ and the unexpected _ adult diapers, boat shoes, hunting
vests and chef uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   State Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander says she wants to add
backpacks to the list, as well as fabric, thread, needles and other
sewing materials. She also wants to extend the tax-free period, but
she has not yet determined how long the holiday should be, said
Nick Voinis, a spokesman for the Comptroller's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comptroller is running some numbers to see how that would
affect the overall budget and revenue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers statewide saved more than $32 million last year, and
they're expected to save about $37 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   The extra money that back-to-school shoppers pocketed last year
represented a $25 million loss in state revenue and $7 million loss
in local revenue. One city, Sunset Valley outside Austin, opted out
of the sales tax holiday. At least two others, San Marcos and
Beaumont, considered the possibility, but decided against it.
</P>
<P>
   Voinis said the loss in revenue wouldn't be a problem, despite
cost-overruns in the state budget amounting to $610 million. A $1.4
billion surplus in revenue covers that and the amount relinquished
this year because of the tax-free holiday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis also wants to exempt school supplies from the taxes and
extend the three-day tax reprieve to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize there are fiscal implications,'' he said, but ``by
expanding it, it would make it a lot easier on merchants and
families.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes Rylander and Ellis advocated require the approval of
the Legislature, which will convene in January. If approved, they
would take effect next summer.
</P>
<P>
   This year's tax-free holiday is identical to last year's, with
one exception: Customers can put clothes and shoes away on layaway
this weekend and still get them tax-free when they buy them later.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is one of four states with a tax-free holiday. The others
are Iowa, Florida and South Carolina. New York offered two weeks of
tax-free shopping in 1997, but the state eliminated the sales tax
on clothing beginning March 1, 2000, making the sales tax holiday
unnecessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
