<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-THEFT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STOLEN STATUES STUN SAN ANTONIO CHURCH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MICHAEL PARKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Three 18th-century statues stolen from San
Antonio's Mission San Juan could disappear into an international
black market of stolen art treasures.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials said the value of the artifacts can't be
measured in monetary terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an atrocity and a sacrilege, not only against the
church but against the priceless heritage of the whole community
and the nation,'' said Monsignor Larry Stuebben, vicar general of
the Archdiocese of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Someone pried open the doors to the mission church Monday night
or Tuesday morning and stole the carved and painted wooden statues
of St. Joseph, St. Francis of Assisi and St. John of Capistrano,
police reported.
</P>
<P>
   The thief or thieves removed the statues from the church's altar
and carted them off on a two-wheeled dolly, which left tracks to a
secluded parking lot on the north side of the church, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The lot has a gate adjacent to the priest's residence, but it
was unlocked and the priest was not in at the time, a police report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police had no suspects and said the statues' worth could not be
determined because of their ``religious, cultural and historical
value.''
</P>
<P>
   The statues are 3 to 4 feet high. Archdiocesan business manager
David Castilleja said they were carved in Spain during the 18th
century but donated as gifts to the mission recently.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Alexander, a San Antonio art and antiques appraiser, said a
huge market exists for stolen religious artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just here, it's around the world,'' Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the statutes could be easily shipped off to auction.
</P>
<P>
   Stuebben said church officials are ``making an urgent appeal for
whoever took these items to return them for the sake of the church,
the community and the nation. They're irreplaceable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 1432EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
