<P>
   COXNET INSIDE NASCAR 0804: POLISHING INDY'S MYSTIQUE _ The
inscription on the Hall of Fame Museum at Indianapolis Motor
Speedway that calls IMS the ``Racing Capital of the World'' is now
accurate. Until last year, the declaration was debatable. This
year's Brickyard 400 is Saturday, but IMS officials have Sept. 24
circled on their calendars. That's when the fabled track moves to a
higher level _ an international level _ by hosting a Formula One
race, the United States Grand Prix, for the first time. (Lance,
Dayton Daily News). Art includes a 2-column color photo of the
pagoda at IMS and a 1-column photo of track president Tony George.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR Q&AMP;A _ Brett Bodine, driver of the No. 11 Ford, is one of
the few remaining owner-drivers on NASCAR's Winston Cup Series.
Bodine recently talked with members of the media about the
challenges he faces. (Minter, Atlanta journal-Constitution) Art
includes a 2-column color photo of Brett Bodine in his car.
</P>
<P>
   WALLACE IN CONTENTION _ Rusty Wallace won at Pocono Raceway two
weeks ago and raced into contention for the Winston Cup
championship. (Carvell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes
a 6-pica color photo of Rusty Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   MAKING HEADLINES _ Matt Kenseth holds a 21-point lead over Dale
Earnhardt Jr. in the NASCAR Winston Cup Series Rookie of the Year
standings. Most figured ``Little E'' would be a shoo-in for the
award, but Kenseth's steady driving has gained the low-key rookie
plenty of respect from other drivers, Others. (Carvell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 6-pica color photo of Matt
Kenseth, a 6-pica color mug of Johnny Benson, an 18-pica color
photo of Jeremy Mayfield and a 18-pica color photo of Jeff Gordon.
