 ATTN: Style and Leisure Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, August 6, and thereafter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TALISMAN-CHIC (Undated) ) There is a vastly expanding tribe of
New Yorkers who, trusting nothing to chance, attempt to ward off
evil or beguile the gods by draping themselves in exotic beads and
talismans. Beetles and Buddhas, scarabs, pentagrams and pale pink
quartz _ any of these may function as a symbol of sincere religious
belief. But in the age of Spirituality Lite, they are also likely
to attest to the wearer's inner grooviness, just as her Jimmy Choo
mules speak of her up-to-date chic. By Ruth La Ferla.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ROCK-FAN-FAMILIES (Undated) _ The rock concert, once a raucous
and often drug-filled rite of initiation into American adolescence,
is slowly becoming a family affair. Parents of teenagers and
younger children _ ones who, in their day, treasured concerts as
escapes from the parental clutches _ now want to share the
experience with their own offspring. It is increasingly easier to
do this as the musical tastes of the generations meld _ the 40-plus
group of Americans now buy more rock albums than those 15 to 24 _
and as concerts have been tamed by commercial sponsors to be as
clean as Broadway musicals. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-ELIZABETH GILBERT (New York) _ On the town with
Elizabeth Gilbert, creator of ``Coyote Ugly.'' The heavily hyped
new Disney movie is based on a 1997 GQ article by Ms. Gilbert about
her experiences tending bar at the real Coyote Ugly in New York's
East Village. By Simon Houpt.
</P>
<P>
   DOTCOM-BLUES (Undated) _ ``Our multimillion-dollar dot-com
folded'', writes Timothy Jack Ward, ``and all I got was this lousy
T-shirt ... Everyone at Posh&AMP;Sticks got one, the day our enigmatic
_ let's face it, odd _ name was announced last January. Now it is a
bittersweet souvenir from the rush for the elusive e-commerce
mother lode. Don't get me wrong: I loved the name and was proud to
wear it on my chest. We gave this our best shot, but we are
toast.''
</P>
<P>
   MARGARET-CHO (New York) _ TV comic and former sitcom star
Margaret Cho is back as the one-woman star of her own movie. By
Linda Lee.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ I once disdained cannas, but that was
before I met Cleopatra. And before encountering Aaron, I was among
the many who looked down on caladiums. Maybe we've all loosened up
a bit, or perhaps summer bulbs have improved their image. For
whatever reason, summer bulbs are way cool again. By Tovah Martin.
</P>
</TEXT>
