<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2838 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ROCK-CLIMBING05-COX     08-04 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-CLIMBING05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Here's a step-by-step guide to tell you how to get started
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Climb on!
</P>
<P>
   In rock climbing circles, that's the standard ready-to-go signal
at the start of an ascent. But it also could be the rallying cry of
the small but die-hard corps for whom climbing has become a
religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a metaphor for life,'' claims Jerry Dodgen, a 69-year-old
retired Atlanta stockbroker who runs the Challenge Rock Climbing
School with his wife, Kathryn. ``Climbing teaches people about
trust, accomplishment and overcoming fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Indoor and outdoor climbing is still widely regarded as a fringe
sport _ the New York-based fitness research company American Sports
Data, Inc. reports that about 7 million Americans climbed at least
once in 1999, up slightly from the previous year. Many, says
spokesman Harvey Lauer, consider it a once-in-a-lifetime challenge,
``like bungee jumping.''
</P>
<P>
   But as more and more people seek out extreme activities,
climbing's popularity may surge. Thom Gillott, 44, corporate
marketing director for the indoor climbing gym Atlanta Rocks, says
the sport's appeal is broadening.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I began climbing six years ago, the demographic was male,
30 and older, at least 50K a year,'' he says. ``Now, we're getting
many more women and families.'' Gillott's own daughter is in on the
act _ 8-year-old Angelica recently won a gold medal in her age
group at the Georgia Games.
</P>
<P>
   Women, in fact, may make better climbers than men, says Thornton
Elmore, 23, climbing specialist at the northeast Atlanta location
of the adventure sports chain REI. ``They're more agile, and they
don't try to muscle themselves up the rock like many men do.''
</P>
<P>
   But where to start? Unlike, say, jogging, rock climbing takes a
good deal of preparation and the initial supervision of more
experienced climbers. ``You never want to go alone when you're a
beginner,'' cautions Elmore. Below, we've provided a list of what
you need to get a leg up on this complex, fulfilling pastime.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO BUY
</P>
<P>
   Beginners get more than sound advice by accompanying advanced
climbers, climbing specialist Thornton Elmore says. Expert rock
crawlers usually come well-equipped with ropes, clips, rings
(called carabiners) and temporary anchors (cams), so novices need
only spring for these essentials:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  HARNESS
</P>
<P>
   Supports climber. Connects to ropes and rock anchors to prevent
falls.
</P>
<P>
   The REI Trilogy ($55), with padded, adjustable leg loops and
four gear loops, is a good starter. For people with back problems,
Elmore recommends the Black Diamond Dyno ($49.95), which allows you
to shift weight from the back to the legs.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SHOES
</P>
<P>
   Sturdy, flat-soled climbing shoes, called board-lasted shoes,
are best for beginners.
</P>
<P>
   Elmore suggests the Five Ten Spire ($99): ``It's not very
flexible, so it's good for feet that aren't yet strong enough to
hold on to the rocks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  CHALK BAG
</P>
<P>
   Absorbs sweat from the hands.
</P>
<P>
   Available in either finger or whole-hand sizes, each around $19.
Chalk, in palm-size solid chunks or in powder form, is about $4.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROPE
</P>
<P>
   Intermediate climbers will want to invest in a rope that's
bi-colored, to aid in balancing lengths, and dynamic, or slightly
elastic, to cushion falls.
</P>
<P>
   Ropes range from $99 to $195.
</P>
<P>
   Where to learn
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Challenge Rock Climbing School. Conducts all classes
outdoors, at Rocktown on Pigeon Mountain in northwest Georgia and
other locations. One-day beginner classes teach the proper use of
equipment, knot-tying and basic climbing skills. $80, optional shoe
rental $10. 1085 Capital Club Circle, Buckhead, 404-237-4021,
www.thechallengerock.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Atlanta Rocks. Daily two-hour ``Introduction to Gym Climbing''
class for ages 12 and older, $35, includes daily membership rate
and equipment. Supervised novice climbs Wednesdays, Saturdays and
Sundays; $22. Club memberships range from $75 for one month to $480
for a year. Daily rates to climb $10.50-$12.50. Shoes, harness and
chalk bag available for rent. 1019-A Collier Road, Atlanta,
404-351-3009. 4411-A Bankers Circle, Doraville, 770-242-7625.
www.atlantarocks.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wall Crawler Rock Club. Two-hour beginner class (by
appointment), $45, includes rental gear and daily climbing rate.
Memberships range from $60 for one month to $385 for a year. Daily
rate to climb $12, $10 for students. 1522 DeKalb Ave. N.E. No. 2,
Atlanta, 404-371-8997.
</P>
<P>
   Where to shop
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  REI. 1800 NE Expressway, Atlanta, 404-633-6508. 1165 Perimeter
Center West, Dunwoody, 770-901-9200.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mountain Ventures. 3040 N. Decatur Road, Scottdale,
404-299-5254.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Call of the Wild. 425 Market Place, Roswell, 770-992-5400.
Also offers intensive climbing classes, from $85 to $175, and
private guiding, $225 and up.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Galyan's. 3535 Peachtree Road, Buckhead, 404-267-0200. 691
Ernest Barrett Parkway, Kennesaw, 770-281-0200. 3333 Buford Drive,
Mall of Georgia, Buford, 678-482-1200.Where to climb
</P>
<P>
   You've got your gear, you've been to school and now you're ready
to hit the rocks. Here are two Georgia locations to try.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rocktown and Lost Wall. Two areas on Pigeon Mountain near
Lafayette in northwest Georgia. Rocktown is a 150-acre ``city'' of
sandstone formations, featuring a variety of climbs as well as
hiking trails and caves. Lost Wall offers harder climbs in a
picturesque setting, complete with waterfall. 706-295-6041.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Zipper and Long Island. Two areas in the Chattahoochee
River National Recreation Area in Atlanta. The Zipper is a large,
split boulder used by experienced climbers to practice technique.
Long Island is a small cliff near Powers Ferry Landing, good for
short workouts. 770-399-8070.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
