<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2839 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-SANFRAN-NEWSIDE06-COX     08-04 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANFRAN-NEWSIDE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Once-seedy district San Francisco's South of Market morphing
into Bay area's newest center of culture
 &HT;    Eds: Emabargoed for Sunday, August 6.
 &HT;    By Tom Sabulis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When it comes to recharging downtown, this city
apparently feels there's no such thing as too much art, too much
culture, too much cool.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're already swimming in it.
</P>
<P>
   When 146,000 tourists show up on an average day _ more than the
population of Savannah _ it seems only smart to keep the museums
and high-tech hot spots coming online. After all, not everyone's
lining up for the cable cars, Fisherman's Wharf, Alcatraz and the
other traditional attractions.
</P>
<P>
   That's where South of Market comes in. This edgy enclave south
of the main artery (Market Street) is the city's new cultural
crossroads, a thriving blend of museums, restaurants, clubs and
dot-com businesses. SOMA has extended downtown's cosmopolitan
appeal through a once-seedy warehouse district south, in the
direction of Pacific Bell Park, the new waterfront home of
baseball's Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Although occupying the flat part of town, topographically
speaking, SOMA's future appears to be all upside. Its colonization
of cultural capital has sparked a land rush of dot-com companies
and their college-educated employees who have spawned a wave of
condo conversions and construction, driving up the already
intergalactic cost of housing (and drawing ire for uprooting some
of the have-not locals).
</P>
<P>
   Two destinations with different missions, the San Francisco
Museum of Modern Art and Metreon, a Sony-sponsored entertainment
complex, have led the way. Each has attracted a comfortable mix of
residents and visitors, the cafe crowd and technology-infatuated
families. A steady stream of conventioneers from the Moscone Center
adds to the daytime pedestrian crush. (The neighborhood thins out
considerably at night.)
</P>
<P>
   Although SOMA is spread over roughly an 11-block area, the heart
of its activity is the stretch between Third and Fifth streets.
Here you'll find the museum of modern art _ ``SFMoMA'' to the SOMA
set _ the city's most popular museum.
</P>
<P>
   Just down Third Street from the museum is the icily cool,
cyberchic W Hotel, fronted by the fashionable XYZ restaurant, a
favorite hangout for the digerati from nearby Media Gulch.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel is a floppy-disk toss from the placid gathering place
of Yerba Buena Gardens and Center for the Arts, a visual, media and
performing arts nexus with a waterfall tribute to the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   That's adjacent to the high-tech, family-embracing Metreon,
touting the world's only Microsoft and PlayStation stores along
with 15 movie screens, an Imax theater, a Discovery Channel store,
a digital-era arcade for teens and an interactive Maurice
Sendak-inspired rumpus room for kids.
</P>
<P>
   And that's within eyesight of the under-construction Jewish
museum. Near the planned Mexican museum. Close to the proposed
African-American museum. The reborn Ansel Adams Center for
Photography that opens this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a profound transformation,'' says Chris Culwell,
spokesman for the Yerba Buena center, referring to the last seven
years, when SOMA began its turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, this area was a dive, skid row,'' Culwell
says. ``You still hear some criticism that the development has
pushed lower-income people out of the neighborhood. But I think San
Franciscans view what's going on in SOMA as a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, SOMA's development has cost the area some of its
funkier character, which drew from its heavy population of bikers,
gays and nightclubbers. But the area's success is hard to dismiss,
even for old-timers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fringe element is the biggest thing I miss,'' says Dennis
Juarez, house manager for Slim's, an eclectic live-music club
nearby co-owned by musician Boz Scaggs. ``You don't see as much
black leather around here anymore. But the influx of new people in
the neighborhood is one reason we're doing so well.''
</P>
<P>
   Many feel the emphasis on culture is the key that made SOMA
work. ``It makes the city look more like an arts center,'' says
Culwell. ``People realize San Francisco should be more than a place
to shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can shed your share of disposable income in SOMA,
too. It's also just a five-block walk to the upscale shopping
district of Union Square.
</P>
<P>
   If you're feeling athletically inclined, all of SOMA's hot spots
exist within walking distance of the city's most acclaimed new
landmark, Pacific Bell Park. Here, right field meets the bay, and
the national pastime becomes subservient to a spectacular panorama
that, in the context of SOMA's story, offers nothing less than
another artistic experience.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sabulis writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2840 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-SANFRAN-TOUR06-COX     08-04 2225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANFRAN-TOUR06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cultural adventure is a San Francisco treat
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, August 6.
 &HT;    By Tom Sabulis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   San Francisco _ No cable car goes to SOMA (South of Market
street), a trendy new cultural development. That automatically cuts
down on the touristy feel of this one-time working-class
neighborhood, a place where you can blend in with artistically
inclined visitors and techies who live and work in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of SOMA is dense enough not to require car or cab, but
it has plenty of breathing room, with sidewalk cafes and Yerba
Buena Gardens offering ample space to spread out.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you'll want wheels if you're headed to some of SOMA's
more remote high points, such as Pacific Bell Park, home of
baseball's Giants. They're walkable from the museum district on a
nice day, but too far unless you have time to stroll or, at night,
a taste for unwelcome adventure.
</P>
<P>
   The following guide spotlights some of SOMA's best offerings.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Museum
</P>
<P>
   of Modern Art
</P>
<P>
   It says something about this city's sense of cultural adventure
that its most popular museum is dedicated to 20th-century art:
SFMoMA has 40,000 members, about the same as Atlanta's High Museum
of Art. Its annual budget is in the neighborhood of $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   SFMoMA's dramatic building, opened in 1995, is headquarters for
an institution founded 65 years ago as the second oldest museum in
the country dedicated to modern art, after New York's Museum of
Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by an impressive acquisition spree in the past two
years that has netted more than $130 million worth of art (Robert
Rauschenberg, Jasper Johns, Ellsworth Kelly), the permanent
collection includes key works by Belgian surrealist Rene Magritte,
Piet Mondrian and Marcel Duchamp.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, an exhibit of 70 Magritte works and a retrospective
of photographer Walker Evans are the marquee shows _ through Sept.
5 and 12, respectively. You can sample the permanent collection in
``Matisse and Beyond,'' featuring, among others, Jackson Pollock's
``Guardians of the Secret,'' Joseph Stella's ``Bridge, 1936'' and
Picasso's ``Women of Algiers.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum is a good place to start your tour of SOMA's Yerba
Buena Gardens area _ and an easy one to find. Its geometric
burnt-sienna facade is centered by a skylight that caps a
five-story cylindrical turret of contrasting black-and-white
granite. Inside you can head upstairs to the galleries and read up
on exhibits at one of many computer stations. Or you can
people-watch in the adjacent Caffe Museo. Or you can shop in the
3,500-square-foot, Nordic ice birch-appointed museum store.
</P>
<P>
   151 Third St. 415-357-4000, www.sfmoma.org
</P>
<P>
   Metreon
</P>
<P>
   You get the feeling that when Atlanta leaders were talking about
a downtown entertainment center, this high-tech amusement park and
digital-era shopping mall is what they had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   A Sony Entertainment Center, Metreon, 1 year old in June, is a
four-story phantasmagoria where your options move at main-frame
speed. You're never quite sure when you've switched from retail
world to entertainment city, mostly because the shopping is such a
hands-on experience.
</P>
<P>
   The stores are so busily interactive, they seem just as happy
showcasing an item as selling it. You can send a digital postcard
for free from the Microsoft store (the world's only one, Sony
claims). Check out software in the PlayStation store. Listen to any
CD in the Sony Style store.
</P>
<P>
   Tykes can push buttons and operate all kinds of characters in
the Maurice Sendak-inspired attraction ``Where the Wild Things
Are.'' Older kids will want to try HyperBowl, Metreon's most
popular attraction, a virtual keggling game where you roll a real
bowling ball that shows up on a video-screen lane. You then
maneuver its speed and direction over various landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   Metreon's greatest appeal?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's big, it has a lot of technology and it's fun,'' says
Kevin Lee, 13, of suburban Burlingame, while on a HyperBowl break.
</P>
<P>
   For a city as cosmopolitan as San Francisco, the mallish $115
million Metreon brings a suburban feel to the inner city. Intowners
apparently approve, though. The 15-scring geared to tourists and
conventions,'' says Louisa Lin, 28, a resident who works in
advertising. ``But I like the way they did it. It's nice to have
theaters and shops nearby. After work, we'll stop in sometimes to
get something to eat or see a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty like her, too; 60 percent of Metreon's audience
is local.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that some of Metreon's crowd drifts over to SFMoMA can
only help the museum. Last year's attendance tallies: SFMoMa,
736,136; Metreon, 6.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   If Atlanta leaders are interested in those numbers, call Sony;
the only other Metreons are in Berlin and Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth and Mission streets. 415-369-6000, www.metreon.com
</P>
<P>
   W Hotel
</P>
<P>
   There are bigger hotels in SOMA (such as the Argent). Hotels
with more outlandish architecture (the Marriott has been called
``the Jukebox''). There are more intimate boutique hideaways (the
Palomar). Yet none fits its SOMA address, the corner of culture and
technology, like the W San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   This 31-story, 423-room hotel next to SFMoMA caters to the wired
business traveler, with each room's dual-line telephones and
high-speed Ethernet laptop access. But it's not merely functional:
The design has a New Age noir feel. The halls are lit with tiny
blue lights, large mirrors play with your depth perception. It
doesn't skimp on luxe amenities, either: Bathrooms are stocked with
Aveda products, each exercise machine in its 24-hour workout
facility is equipped with a Sony TV.
</P>
<P>
   If the W doesn't fit your lodging budget _ doubles average $325
per night _ it's still a destination. The XYZ restaurant is noted
for the French-accented California cuisine of chef Jeffrey Amber,
recently named by the San Francisco Chronicle one of the city's
five young chefs to watch (a signature dish: Pumpkin Seed-Crusted
Monkfish). You can have a luncheon feast for two for under $100,
including tip.
</P>
<P>
   The XYZ Bar was featured in a recent Harper's Bazaar magazine
story titled ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?'' that
nominated the watering hole, with its Ultrasuede seating and
glowing, egg-shaped fertility lamps, as happy hunting ground for
would-be golddiggers. A segment on NBC's ``Today'' show about
Silicon Valley singles was also taped here.
</P>
<P>
   In the lounge-happy Living Room just off the lobby, a young
crowd drapes all over the furniture and each other _ drinking,
reading, playing chess or, as on a recent night, engaging in
spirited laptop necking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever those people were plugging in to, they tapped into my
whole vibe about the hotel,'' says Jaime Wolf, 38, an entertainment
lawyer from Manhattan and recent W guest. ``It's totally relaxed.
Even though I didn't introduce myself to anyone, it felt very
comfortable and friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf found the XYZ Bar ``a little more swanky and stylish than I
was expecting from San Francisco. But I feel like to some extent
this (scene) is part of the dot-comization of San Francisco, where
you find this growing class of itinerant young people with dough.''
</P>
<P>
   181 Third St. 415-777-5300. www.whotels.com
</P>
<P>
   Yerba Buena
</P>
<P>
   Center for the Arts
</P>
<P>
   ``You think this could play in Atlanta?'' asks Chris Culwell,
the center's public relations manager.
</P>
<P>
   We're watching a video in which performance artist Patty Chang
slices through her brassiere with a huge knife, eventually
revealing a halved cantaloupe, which she scoops out with a spoon
and eats, all while relating a family anecdote. With a plate
balanced on her head.
</P>
<P>
   Yerba Buena is a visual and performing arts complex specializing
in small, experimental and, in the case of a recent surfing
exhibit, wavy shows illuminating San Francisco's diverse culture
while commenting on its history and contemporary society. (The
surfing show featured a couple of dozen mechanized life-size hula
girls dancing while brandishing automatic weapons.)
</P>
<P>
   The arts center doesn't attract the crowds that Metreon and even
SFMoMA do, drawing 20,000 annually. But its outdoor esplanade,
highlighted by a waterfall tribute to the Rev. Martin Luther King
Jr., is a green refuge for thousands of workers, tourists and
conventioneers every day. An ideal spot to lunch, read, watch the
human parade go by.
</P>
<P>
   701 Mission St. 415-978-2787, www.YerbaBuenaArts.org
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell Park
</P>
<P>
   You get the feeling the San Francisco Giants have thought of
everything with their new stadium, once you learn they've found a
way for you to watch the ballgame in person without a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Several screened archways in right field are vantage points
especially customized for ticketless pedestrians, who can watch the
game for free, while practically standing on the warning track.
Giants employees supervise and rotate crowds every three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Fans with tickets get a lot more. The comfortable spectating
confines of a new retro design. A stunning view of San Francisco
Bay, which abuts the right field wall at Willie McCovey Cove, where
batted ball occasionally meets waiting boaters. A diversity of
pricey California-accented concessions (tacos, garlic fries, sushi,
microbrews); a cheeseburger and fries cost $9.50, not including
beverage.
</P>
<P>
   Like Coca-Cola Skyfield at Turner Field, PacBell has a
playground area above left field for kids. Instead of Turner's base
path, though, PacBell has a miniature version of the entire stadium
where kids can hit and circle the bases, while watching themselves
on a digital scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   You also get something with every game that you rarely got at
Candlestick Park (later 3Com Park), the Giants' former home: a full
house. ``The park has galvanized this town,'' says Ronn Owens,
morning host for KGO-AM.
</P>
<P>
   Although the stadium is technically sold out for the season, the
team puts several hundred bleacher seats on sale for every game.
(The Braves visit Aug. 18-20.)
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there's that free standing room. And boat seating
appears unlimited.
</P>
<P>
   24 Willie Mays Plaza. 415-972-2000. www.sfgiants.com
</P>
<P>
   Hamburger Mary's
</P>
<P>
   Ask co-owner Rose Christensen the recipe for her popular
restaurant's 28-year success, and the answer comes fast and sunny
side up. ``Big portions. Heavy food. Fair price. Mediocre
service.''
</P>
<P>
   You get a laugh with that, too.
</P>
<P>
   If you're seeking to sample genuine South of Market character,
this roadhouse-style joint with its cluttered garage-sale decor and
colorful clientele is a natural starting point. It's even better if
you're looking to chase a hangover with one of the 11 hamburgers
and eight Bloody Marys on the menu. (We should note that this is
the original Hamburger Mary's restaurant; it's independent from the
small West Coast chain that an early owner has built.)
</P>
<P>
   If you're beyond breakfast or brunch, Hamburger Mary's can be
used as a launch pad or nightcap niche for late-nighters who
migrate to area nightclubs like DNA Lounge and Slim's. (Breakfast
is served all the time; the bar is open until 2 a.m. You can get
the peanut butter shake anytime.)
</P>
<P>
   For an Atlanta point of reference, it's a bit like Manuel's but,
true to SOMA's early gay-district origins, heavy on the kitsch.
Cream for your coffee sits in miniature baby bottles, nipples
intact. The centerpiece of the main room is a giant plastic heart
hanging from the ceiling wrapped in barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   Christensen takes SOMA's gentrification in stride, although the
restaurant's area has not yet seen the drastic changes that have
taken place in the museum district. With parking at a premium and
homeless people flagging taxis for you, it's still definitely for
residents of the urban core and heartier outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   1582 Folsom St. 415-626-5767
</P>
<P>
   Slim's
</P>
<P>
   Presenting everything from head-banging metal to introspective
folk, this nightclub co-owned by musician and Bay area resident Boz
Scaggs has been a sturdy live-music survivor on the city's south
side since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Its eclectic schedule is somewhat akin to that of Variety
Playhouse in Little Five Points; recent headliners have been John
Mayall, Bruce Cockburn and Peter Case. The exposed-brick interior
changes formations depending on what the act's clientele requires _
tables and chairs or ad hoc mosh pit.
</P>
<P>
   The beer list is extensive, the menu limited. The club is long
on the working-class environment that used to dominate SOMA. If the
music bill suits your taste and you're in the mood for decidedly
ungentrified surroundings, Slim's, a short walk from Hamburger
Mary's, is worth the cover charge.
</P>
<P>
   333 11th St. 415-255-0333. www.slims-sf.com
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Tom Sabulis covered arts and entertainment in the
San Francisco Bay area for two years, back when SOMA was a sea of
parking lots and vacancy signs.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Fly nonstop to San Francisco for $353 round
trip on Delta and United airlines, with a 14-day advance purchase
and a Saturday night stay. Seven other airlines offer connecting
service.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: San Francisco Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau,
415-391-2000, www.sfvisitor.org
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sabulis writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
