r l BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX     08-04 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAC USER READY TO TAKE PC PLUNGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Many years ago, I bought a Macintosh computer
and have continued to buy Macintoshes through the years. I want to
buy a PC. Where can I have my files from Microsoft Word 98
converted to be used on my PC? If this is impossible, I may have to
buy another Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seen the Light
</P>
<P>
   DEAR SEEN: Stop! Put down that checkbook nice and slowly, ma'am.
That's it. Now back away from the MasterCard. Good, good. OK, cuff
her, boys. Another senseless Macintosh purchase avoided.
</P>
<P>
   You Apple-heads put your pitchforks and torches away. Whether
you like it or not, most of the world's personal computing is done
on the PC platform, and there are people just as fervent about PCs
as you are about your Macs. I've used both, and guess what? They
both crash, they both have their eccentricities and they both
occasionally make me want to drive my fist through the monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of a computing platform should be based on which
software someone intends to use, not on goofy case colors or
Compuserve rebates. For example, there are graphics and digital
video programs that either work better on a Mac or simply don't
exist for the PC. If that's the stuff you use, the decision is a
no-brainer. If you lean toward office suite software _ word
processing, databases, spreadsheets _ you're probably better off
with a PC. At least the hardware is usually cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   When software publishers saw Apple's market share sliding a few
years back, they made sure there would be PC versions of their
stuff around just in case Steve Jobs decided it was time to have
the big garage sale. Today, programs like Quark Xpress, InDesign,
Photoshop and Microsoft Office can read and write files from either
platform.
</P>
<P>
   Word is a good example. If you create a document on the Mac in
Word, it can be opened by Word on a PC. But don't think you have to
pay somebody a ton of money to do this, unless you'd like to hire
me for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Put a PC-formatted disk in the Mac and save your Word document
to it. If you give it a .Doc extension as you save it, you'll make
it a little easier on the PC end. Take the floppy to the PC, call
up the file, then do a Save As (from the File menu) to save it
somewhere on the PC, making sure the ``Save as type'' box on the
Save As dialog box is set to ``Word document,'' which it usually
is.
</P>
<P>
   Now go buy your PC. Sorry, Steve. Bill Gates wins another one.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Sometimes when I turn on my computer, the
hourglass icon appears on my screen as if I have clicked on an icon
to start a program or action. Can you tell me what this might be?
</P>
<P>
   _ Tempus Fugit
</P>
<P>
   DEAR TEMPUS: No need to worry. That's just Microsoft's
Eavesdropper 2000, a little-known feature of Windows that sends a
complete inventory of your hardware, copies of all your personal
documents, your browser history file and your bank balance and
credit card numbers back to World Domination Headquarters in
Redmond, Wash., every time you boot.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that hourglass just means that all the little
behind-the-scenes programs are continuing to load. Sometimes they
add icons to the System Tray as they load, sometimes not. To get an
idea of what's running, hit Control-Alt-Delete to get a list. The
only things that absolutely have to be there are Explorer and
Systray. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay was kidding about Eavesdropper 2000. Except
for the credit card numbers, of course. Write him at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: (817)
390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial
systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
