<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2875 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKW-COACHING-WOMEN-AR     08-04 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-COACHING-WOMEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA COACH FINDS JOY IN WOMEN'S LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAN HOFFMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Back then, he coached the greats, from Bob Lanier to
Shaquille O'Neal. He traveled on the Orlando Magic's private jet,
stocked with lobster, steak and Shaq's very own seven-foot bed.
</P>
<P>
   Now? His greats have names like Teresa Witherspoon, Vickie
Johnson. Luxury? Even the coach has flown coach.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, guy talk.
</P>
<P>
   Now?
</P>
<P>
   ``The women cry at everything,'' says Richie Adubato, 62, the
coach for the New York Liberty, who, with four games until
playoffs, are the top team in the Eastern Conference of the Women's
National Basketball Association. ``They cry if we lose. They cry if
we win.''
</P>
<P>
   He's throwing up his hands as he strides off the court after
practice at Madison Square Garden. ``Tari Phillips!'' he says, on a
tear about his sojourn in this strange new country. ``It takes her
an hour to put on her makeup _ and that's if she can find it!''
</P>
<P>
   What's a coach who spent nearly 40 years around sweaty guys to
do?
</P>
<P>
   It happens that Adubato is thrilled to be here. After 19 years
as an up-and-down coach in the National Basketball Association, he
has been as rejuvenated by this gutsy team of women _ many started
this season green, injured or overweight _ as they have been by
him. Referring to last summer, his first with the Liberty and with
coaching women, he adds, sitting in his office, ``I tell you, I
never had so many hugs and kisses in one season.''
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever chanted with the sweet, exuberant Liberty crowds
of 14,000 at the Garden or seen a game on TV _ Lifetime carries the
big one Friday night against the Orlando Miracle, former team of
Tari Phillips, the Liberty's center _ you know Adubato. He's the
ginger-headed man (New Jersey Italian dad, New Jersey Irish mom) in
a natty suit, running along the sidelines, frantically signalling
the girls (his term), working the refs, hard:
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw look, she's an actor! Did you see that? Right there! That's
an Academy Award. That was a nasty, hard foul. Wow. Now that _ that
is a new trick. I've never seen that before. Look, she did it
again!''
</P>
<P>
   Although one year he was fined 27 times _ What? Just for
defending his team? _ Adubato has calmed down. Being hired and
fired a lot, divorced and remarried, having a granddaughter, can
have that effect on a person. He was an assistant in Detroit,
Dallas, Cleveland, New York and Orlando; head coach at Detroit,
Dallas and Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when Blaze _ Carol Blazejowski, the Hall of Fame
guard and Liberty general manager _ had a meeting with Adubato in a
New Jersey diner, Adubato was just consulting for the Celtics' Rick
Pitino. He was courtsick for a team of his own.
</P>
<P>
   She was skeptical about hiring someone who was older, a guy and
who had never coached women. (He wondered: ``Do I have to say
woman-to-woman defense or can I still say man-to-man?'')
</P>
<P>
   She didn't know Adubato, son of a Cincinnati Reds' scout,
elected basketball over baseball, on the theory that even if your
team is short and can't shoot, there are a thousand other ways to
win. That he loved basketball so much that for 18 years, while a
junior high classroom teacher in inner-city Paterson, N.J., he
coached at local Catholic schools and colleges (when, fans, he
befriended coaches like Dick Vitale and Hubie Brown).
</P>
<P>
   Nor that his worst moment was not being fired after his first
two years coaching in the NBA, but having to walk back into that
eighth-grade classroom as a teacher again.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of her concerns, Blazejowski liked him. What's not to
like? He's funny, kind, pumped-up, demanding, a natural teacher, a
storyteller, not a screamer and a basketballholic.
</P>
<P>
   As his wife, Carol, says, he may not be able to remember bread
AND milk, but he can recite plays from 40 years ago. He relaxes
watching eight NBA games a night, taking notes. Orlando, you better
believe that at practice, he was teaching your moves: he watched
four tapes and had a scout's reports.
</P>
<P>
   He is also astute:
</P>
<P>
   In a tight game with Orlando, Crystal Robinson, his prize
shooter, fouled a player on a three-point shot with 20 seconds
left. She looked devastated. During timeout, he soothed her. You
didn't foul. Bad call. You can shut them down. Buoyed, she did the
job and then some.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's coming to dinner?'' he will shout into the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Adubato is still on a learning curve with this woman thing.
If the women are more coachable, more eager, more grateful, more
team-spirited and harder-working than the men, they are also ``more
emotional.'' He'll often ask a co-captain to deliver his stern
message. As for personal stuff?
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys could talk to me about marriage and divorce,'' he
says. ``None of the women are even married; they don't have those
kinds of problems.'' They turn to the co-captains or Patty Coyle,
an assistant coach, with personal issues. ``They come to me about
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   He never won an NBA championship. In the WNBA, the Liberty has
to clinch the conference title, win the playoffs, face down mighty
Los Angeles or Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? His team surprised everyone this season. He always
fantasized about a Manhattan ticker tape parade. ``But I never
dreamed,'' he says in wonderment, ``it might be for women.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 1600EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2882 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-BANK-AMERICA-HNS &LR;      08-04 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-AMERICA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BANK OF AMERICA WILL HEADQUARTER CALIFORNIA OPERATIONS IN LOS
ANGELES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Continuing a management reshuffling and
de-emphasis of San Francisco in the wake of its merger with
NationsBank, Bank of America has announced it would reunite its
northern and southern California divisions into a single unit, with
a Los Angeles-based executive heading the state operation.
</P>
<P>
   That executive will report directly to Charlotte, N.C., where
the bank is now headquartered.
</P>
<P>
   The former Bank of America was based in San Francisco from its
founding in 1904 to its acquisition by Charlotte-based NationsBank
in 1998. NationsBank then assumed the old Bank of America name, but
virtually every other local vestige of the former bank has
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Liam E. McGee, a 10-year veteran of the bank, has been serving
as the financial institution's president of operations in southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   As the new head of the statewide division, McGee, 45, will
report to Gene Taylor, who was recently promoted to nationwide
president of consumer banking. Taylor, based in San Francisco, will
move to Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Connie Beck, the president of Bank of America's northern
California operation, has been reassigned to head the bank's
Western division of its increasingly important private banking
service, which caters to wealthy individuals. Beck will remain in
San Francisco and will be Bank of America's top-ranking executive
in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Beck replaces Kathleen Brown, the former president of private
banking for the Western region. Brown is leaving the company to
pursue ``other personal and career interests,'' according to a
release.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is a former state treasurer and a former California
gubernatorial candidate. She is the sister of Oakland Mayor Jerry
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   McGee will oversee 40,000 employees and the management of more
than $185 billion in loans and deposits. Statewide, Bank of America
has 960 branches and about 5,000 automated teller machines, and
contributed $1 billion - or about a third - of the entire company's
profits last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America's shares rose $1.88 to $49.06, or 4 percent, in
trading on the New York Stock Exchange Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While the changes are expected to have little impact on
customers' business with the bank, it may raise hackles from those
who believe the bank's power base has been drained away from The
City.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, McGee referred to the new California operation
as ``one rather substantial regional bank.`` He said the statewide
operation would not have an appreciable impact either on customer
service or on internal banking operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived in San Francisco, I'll spend a considerable amount
of time in San Francisco and I don't think that's an issue,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest moves are yet another indication of how much the bank
has changed since 1998. Prior to its merger with NationsBank, Bank
of America managed each line of business _ consumer, commercial,
small business and so forth _ on a statewide basis. After the
merger, the new North Carolina owner consolidated management of all
business lines into essentially regional banks, covering Northern
and Southern California. Now those functions will be consolidated
yet again, covering all lines of business for the entire state.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Wells Fargo _ the state's second-largest bank _
splits its California business into five regional banks _ Northern,
Southern, Central, Bay Area and greater Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Bank of America said it would cut about 10,000 jobs,
representing about 7 percent of its total U.S. work force. The bank
has not yet provided details of the expected cuts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
