s f BC-WORLDBIZ-POLAND-$ADV0     08-04 1391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDBIZ-POLAND-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLES MAKE A FEAST OF COLD WAR LEFTOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 6) 
 By PETER S. GREEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEGNICA, Poland _ The eye-watering fumes of fresh paint waft
into the office in a former airport hangar, where Zofia
Kargul-Smalewska, president of Gielda C.D., a small exhibitions
company, is organizing the annual auto show this summer in this
small city in western Poland. She expects 10,000 people to show up
for the three-day event, kicking the tires of new and used cars and
watching drag races and motorcycle demonstrations on a former
Soviet air force base that was decommissioned after the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   There is no comparable building in Legnica, said
Kargul-Smalewska, who has helped turn the base into a makeshift
industrial park. ``The Russians have been good for my business,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kargul-Smalewska is among thousands of Poles who, with
government aid, have worked to beat Soviet swords into shares of
post-Communist prosperity, an opportunity they have grabbed with
both hands. The Russians left behind scores of military
installations around the country, and at many of them factories,
apartments and even resorts are rising or are being planned _
although some of these plans do not yet amount to much. Most of the
investors so far are Poles, including several former redevelopment
officials; no one has tracked the totals.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, the 108,000 inhabitants of Legnica (pronounced
leg-NEE-tsa) had a very different view of the Russians, and there
was not much fresh paint to be smelled in the cavernous hangar. The
occupying Soviet Army's Northern Group of Forces used the town,
which was once German, and its garrison buildings from the 1930s as
their Polish headquarters. The occupying forces were despised by
the locals.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviets invested billions of rubles building roads, an
airport, barracks, bunkers and fuel dumps for their army. War never
arrived, but when the Russians pulled out of Poland, Hungary and
what had been Czechoslovakia in mid-1993, they took with them every
sewage pump, electrical wire, door frame and window pane.
</P>
<P>
   What they left behind across the region resembled battlefields.
But it was also a unique opportunity. Kargul-Smalewska, in fact,
was one of the economic development officials in charge of finding
a new use for the abandoned airport before she decided to form her
own company and use the base for trade fairs and other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Getting started was a struggle, she said. First, the Polish army
had to remove the mines seeded around the airfield. Then experts
had to clean up the fuel spills and industrial wastes. Because the
Soviets even took the maps of the water and electric lines, it was
simpler to put in new ones. ``It looked like a typhoon had been
through here,'' she said. ``Only the sewer lines were still good.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, crop dusters and private planes occasionally use the
runway. The hangars alongside the tarmac house a supermarket, a
hardware and building supply store and a string of apparently
successful small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Ryszard Kliszewski moved his small workshop, which
makes burglar-proof steel doors, from the city center to a former
Russian electric transformer station near the airstrip. The
Russians left only a roof and four walls. He invested about
$10,000, he said, and business is up 30 percent. He has increased
his work force from four to six men.
</P>
<P>
   ``You add a door here, a window there and you have a building,''
he said. ``It's a good location. All the big companies are around
you and because of the exhibitions next door, lots of people see
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Some abandoned airfields find less exalted uses. In Kluczewo in
northwest Poland, Franciscus Nouwen, a Dutch farmer and one of the
few foreign investors, raises potatoes along the abandoned runway,
storing his crop in the bunkers that hid Soviet warplanes from
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   In Legnica itself, the Soviets occupied an entire district of
the city _ called Tarninow _ that before World War II was home to
the mercantile upper crust. Gates and armed patrols kept most Poles
out of the quarter, which had its own shops and services for the
Soviets. Nearly everything the Soviets occupied was left damaged or
destroyed, but much has been rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any choice,'' said Stanislaw Kasprowiak, who
runs the Legnica city office charged with reviving the formerly
Soviet areas that were handed back to the Polish authorities. ``We
had to reconstruct these bases. Otherwise our city would be half
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The fall of Communism in 1989 and the ensuing economic shock
therapy brought Poland hyperinflation and 20 percent unemployment,
from which it is still recovering. Legnica had almost no cash to
put into redevelopment, but investors were attracted by ads in
local newspapers and, later, a Web site (www.celarf.gov.pl) and
speeches that public officials gave around the region. ``The goal
was for people with money to come here and take over the
properties, and basically it worked in Legnica,'' Kasprowiak said.
More than 92 percent of the property once occupied by the Russians
in the town has found new owners.
</P>
<P>
   Bogdan Wyznikiewicz, an economist who is deputy director of the
Gdansk Institute for Market Economics, said Poles have been able to
capitalize quickly on the Russian withdrawal. ``This
entrepreneurship is something in the national character,''
Wyznikiewicz said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors and economists say that spirit is an important factor
in Poland's booming economy, which is expected to grow 5 percent
this year. The country is also bursting with start-up companies and
high-technology ventures.
</P>
<P>
   While entrepreneurs are making the most of the old bases, it was
only through government-run programs that the bases were sold.
Western governments provided no money and just a few training
programs for Polish officials trying to build capitalism on these
Communist ashes. But national and local officials provided tax
breaks, advice and inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the city of Legnica finished rebuilding two of the
Soviets' rickety prefabricated concrete apartment blocks as a
demonstration of the gold that could be found amidst the Soviet
dross. The refurbished buildings were so attractive that the
apartments were rented within weeks, and now developers are
rebuilding the remainder of the apartments for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the buyers and investors were from the area. The city
offered easy terms, and Kasprowiak said most borrowers were making
their mortgage payments on time. He estimated that while the city
has taken in only about $7.5 million from selling 497 buildings, 10
to 15 times as much was privately invested in rebuilding the old
installations, and 600 to 700 new jobs were created, increasing tax
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the Polish government has used the changes as an
opportunity to encourage people to settle in certain areas. In
Borne Sulinowo, a northern village that once housed Soviet
intelligence officers, some 5,000 migrants were recruited; most of
them were from Warsaw and the Silesian coal basin and fed up with
high prices and polluted air.
</P>
<P>
   A local entrepreneur was lured in to build a furniture factory
that now employs more than 400 people. New government jobs for
doctors, teachers and public administrators helped to draw in
others. So did the prices. ``We were selling apartments for an
eighth or a tenth the price of places in Warsaw,'' said Maria
Czerwinska, who heads the Polish government agency overseeing the
sale of the bases.
</P>
<P>
   But not all the reconstruction stories have turned out so well.
Warsaw city officials had high hopes for one abandoned airfield
near the city center after the singer Michael Jackson signed a
letter of intent in 1997 to build a $500 million theme park there.
On a visit to Poland, he told local journalists that he had fallen
in love with the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson's project has yet to materialize, and the Warsaw
mayor canceled a scheduled news conference in March as negotiations
stalled. Jackson said in a statement then that he remains
interested.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the sale of former military property winds down,
other opportunities remain. ``There's an airport on the Baltic
Coast,'' Czerwinska said. ``A beautiful space for a golf course or
a luxury hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
