r d BC-MUSSELS-HNS &LR;      08-04 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSSELS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MUSSELS: THE MIDDLE-CLASS OF THE MOLLUST FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUTH FANTASIA   
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mussels seem to be the middle-class of the mollusk family. They
aren't as revered as oysters and aren't as common as clams. But
they're there, by the thousands, filling bouillabaisse bowls and
adding color to paellas. But mussels are good for more than just
adding body to mixed seafood dishes. Mussels are also tasty on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   There are two kinds of mussels available in Capital Region
grocery stores and seafood markets: The smaller, black, Prince
Edward Island mussel and the large, green-lipped New Zealand
variety.
</P>
<P>
   Black mussels have a delicate briny flavor and go well with
light ingredients such as white wine and chopped shallots. Most of
the black mussels you'll find in stores are farm-raised, which
means they'll be relatively free of sand and silt. They're also not
as flavorful as the wild mussels you can pluck from rocky beaches
in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the small black mussels, green-lipped mussels have a
pronounced flavor that can be paired with stronger ingredients such
as curry powder, chorizo or ham. The meat varies from tan to a rich
salmon color but this is no indication of taste or quality.
</P>
<P>
   When buying live mussels, whether black or green, look for
shellfish that are tightly closed. If the mussels are open, tap the
shell with your finger. The mussel should close within 30 seconds.
If it doesn't, the mussel has died and should be discarded.
</P>
<P>
   Store fresh mussels in a bowl in the refrigerator covered with a
damp dish towel, writes James Petersen in ``Fish &AMP; Shellfish''
(1996). They are best eaten the same day they are purchased but can
be stored for a day or two. However, be sure to check them again
before cooking to ensure they are still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Clean mussels by scrubbing with a stiff brush and remove the
beards just before cooking. How many to serve? If using as an
appetizer, allow 1/2 to 3/4 pound per person, according to the New
York Seafood Council. For a main course, 1 1/2 pounds per person is
sufficient.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2898 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-04 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    AHEAD: BUSH'S THREE LONGEST MONTHS
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now for the hard part.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has had a phenomenal post-primary season. He's
dominated media coverage both on image, not difficult given his
personality, and, more amazingly given the wispiness of some of his
proposals, on substance. Al Gore, meanwhile, has flounced from one
incarnation to another (nice Al, nasty Al, populist Al) seeking the
right tone for his campaign. Gore has yet to come anywhere close to
finding a silver bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bush has concluded a Republican National Convention almost
devoid of the usual right-wing diatribes and ham-fisted attacks on
Democrats. Bush delivered a hope-filled acceptance speech and seems
to be at least 10 percentage points ahead of Gore in national polls
of likely voters. Maybe Bush has even picked up a touch of the
``inevitability'' factor that melted away in the heat of John
McCain's assault last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has to wish the election were this Tuesday instead of Nov.
7. It's not, as he and his campaign are painfully aware, but they
still like their chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in a powerful position in a very tough, close race,''
Bush strategist Karl Rove told reporters in Philadelphia last week.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will attempt to get back in the hunt with the announcement
Tuesday of his vice-presidential running mate as a curtain-raiser
for the Democratic convention that begins Aug. 14 in Los Angeles.
But it's difficult to see how almost any of the main prospects,
each a classic center-left Democrat, would dramatically alter the
basic political equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing that Gore could do to jolt the race,'' Rove
contended.
</P>
<P>
   What Gore can do at his convention is seek to bring more
Democrats home. Polls show Bush already has the solid backing of
most Republicans (in the 90 percent range), but Gore lags on
support from traditional Democrats (in the 70s-low 80s).
</P>
<P>
   Republicans believe that if Gore plays his convention correctly,
he could pick up those wavering Democrats and see a good bounce in
national polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is far from over,'' Rove said. ``This race is
going to be by Labor Day in single digits one way or the other.
There are going to be points after the Democratic convention where,
in all likelihood, we're going to be behind.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not telling you I think Rove really believes that. I'm
telling you he said it.
</P>
<P>
   After the conventions, the race hinges on swing voters and swing
states.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is looking most closely, Rove said (and he's the one who
really does the looking), at &QL; 
(1) suburbanites classed as ``weak Republicans'' or independents, &QL; 
(2) Roman Catholics, a big bloc in the usually closely contested
Great Lake states, and (3) Hispanics, who can be the margin of
victory in California, Florida and some smaller states.
</P>
<P>
   Looking across the Electoral College map, Rove found ``an
embarrassment of opportunities.'' Most alluring is the West Coast,
where Republican presidential candidates have not fared well &QL; 
of late.
</P>
<P>
   It's generally accepted that Gore cannot win without taking
California, and Rove believes Bush remains competitive in the
Golden State, despite the GOP's crash-and-burn showing in state
races two years ago and constant attention from President Clinton
and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be getting our brains beat in California, and, in
fact, we're not,'' Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   In a bit of bravura, Rove did the map without even mentioning
the usual battlegrounds of New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Ohio, Michigan
and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an election that has yet to shape up to a few, simple
states,'' Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest test for Bush between now and November is almost
certainly the debates. Along with the national party conventions,
that's the only time the nation is anywhere close to being focused
on politics.
</P>
<P>
   These contests are a legitimate worry for Republicans. There's a
reason anti-wonk Bush is not known as a fabulous debater, and his
campaign remains hard at work to lower already basement-level
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our debate strategy can be summed up in one word: survive,''
said Rove, a grin starting to form. ``We hope to survive Governor
Bush's necessary appearance in debates against the world's most
pre-eminent debater _ a man who is more proficient at hand-to-hand
debate combat than any. ...'' You get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
