   THE WRONG MAN: MY NAME IS NOT ROBERT
</P>
<P>
   WRONG-MAN-JAILED-CENTERPIECE _ At 11:56 a.m. on Oct. 5, 1993,
Kerry Sanders was arrested in Los Angeles and booked as Robert
Sanders. The booking sheet included Kerry's physical
characteristics _ his height and weight, his right thumb print, the
scar on his left arm _ and Robert's birthplace and fugitive warrant
number. Within 24 hours, Kerry Sanders' extradition was approved.
Within two weeks, he was in the New York State correctional system.
But he was the wrong man. A look at how sloppy police work, a
hands-off justice system and an asleep-at-the-wheel prison turned
one man named Sanders into another. By Benjamin Weiser.
</P>
<P>
   (EDITORS: At the author's request, this article can only be
reprinted in its entirety. Due to the 7,300-word length of this
story, newspapers may want to publish it in parts over several
days.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Prison photos of Kerry Sanders and Robert Sanders are
available on Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at
212-499-3355.)
</P>
<P>
   (Benjamin Weiser is a court reporter for The New York Times.)
</P>
<P>
   THE RELUCTANT IMPERIALIST: BERNARD KOUCHNER IN KOSOVO
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N.-CHIEF-CENTERPIECE _ Bernard Kouchner, who 30 years
ago helped found Doctors Without Borders, pioneered the idea of
grand humanitarian intervention. But in Kosovo, where his theories
are being put to the test as the U.N. special representative, the
noble gesture may not be enough. By Michael Ignatieff. 2,900 words.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: For inquiries about photographs, please contact
Phyllis Collazo at 212-556-1243.)
</P>
