<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2903 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-04 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    PARTY STILL TOO ANGLO FOR GOP'S GOOD
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The small, distinctive building in a historic
section of this historic city began its life 250-plus years ago as
the colonial capitol, or state house, of Pennsylvania. Most of us
now recognize it as Independence Hall, the place where the United
States was born.
</P>
<P>
   The act of giving birth still ranks as the most difficult
political decision ever made in this country. Benjamin Franklin's
warning to his fellow Declaration of Independence signers was,
after all, quite literal:
</P>
<P>
   ``We must all hang together, or assuredly we shall all hang
separately.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in this city, in a sports arena _ a place far less
dignified _ other political decisions were made and/or carried out
last week during the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest immediate stakeholder in how those decisions and the
overall convention message were received by the American public was
George W. Bush, the GOP's presidential nominee. But the Republican
Party itself also was on trial.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions were far too numerous to list here. They ranged
from the inconsequential _ such as the choice of tie for Bush to
wear during his acceptance speech _ to the delicately balanced
selection of other convention speakers and the oh-so-delicately
balanced selection of topics to be discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Should Colin Powell be allowed to make a pitch for affirmative
action? He did. Should an openly homosexual man be invited to
address a Republican National Convention for the first time ever?
He was, but he was allowed to discuss only trade, not gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   And on and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   The convention was well-scripted and under the airtight control
of the Bush campaign. It presented televised podium images of a
demographic mix designed to further Bush's message of inclusion and
tolerance, his professed goal of expanding the GOP's tent to all
Americans without breaking down into a ``quota'' system that,
Republicans contend, has cost the Democratic Party a sense of
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   It is a theme that Bush will continue to try to hammer home
during the fall campaign, balancing a message that he hopes is
conservative enough to keep his party's right wing solidly behind
him and compassionate enough to attract the independent and
moderate Democratic voters he also will need to capture the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party has been on a roll in Texas in recent
years, and it controls both houses of the U.S. Congress and most
governorships. But the party's efforts to put its best face forward
at its convention also displayed its biggest weakness for the
not-too-distant future.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the abundance of black and Hispanic speakers, the
convention audience was overwhelmingly Anglo, a characteristic
rapidly becoming out-of-step with America's changing population
mix.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how Bush fares in this election, his party may be
turning out its lights _ for good _ within the next generation or
two if it does not become more aggressive _ and more successful _
in recruiting blacks and Hispanics. The reason is simple
arithmetic. Those two groups, combined, will make up a majority of
the country's population before too many more presidential
campaigns have run their course, and they remain overwhelmingly
Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been wooing minorities with some success, both as
governor of Texas and in his national campaign. He backs up his
calls for inclusion and his claim to be a ``different kind of
Republican'' with calls for such critical advances as improved
health care and improved educational opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seems sincere, and his presidential race, if successful,
could pump new life into the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   But, Democrats argue that Bush hasn't done nearly enough to
advance educational and social issues. And, they contend, the
governor's ``compassionate'' side is still overshadowed by his
conservatism _ a desire to cut taxes for corporate America and
avoid confrontations over social issues with his party's right
wing.
</P>
<P>
   The debate is valid, and how it plays out will affect Bush's
future after November.
</P>
<P>
   It also will help determine how much longer his party remains on
the active political landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Robison is chief of the Chronicle's Austin Bureau.
(clay.robisonchron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
