 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Saturday, Aug. 5. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
warnken(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-QUEEN-MOTHER (London) _ Surrounded by three generations
of the royal family, Queen Elizabeth, the Queen Mother, celebrated
her 100th birthday Friday waving to cheering well-wishers from the
Buckingham Palace balcony where she had helped lead national
rejoicing at the end of World War II and on other notable
occasions. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-EVOCATIVE-SIGNS (Mexico City) _ The map of the world's
largest metropolis is a kind of literary masterpiece. The street
guide reads as if a writer from the school of magical realism had
translated the encyclopedia, cut his work into confetti and
sprinkled it over the city. This is a place where people live on
Heart and on Soul. They live on Forest of Light, Mirror of Water,
Forest of Miracles, Garden of Memories, Tree of Fire, Forest of
Secrets, Sea of Dreams. Surreal street names can reflect hard
realities: Work is long. Love and Happiness are short. Good Luck
crosses Hope, then hits a dead end. Intersections become works of
imagination: the Volga River flows into the Nile, Beethoven meets
Bach, the Himalayas cross the Alps. And Comprehension ends in
Silence. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SINATRA-STATUE (New York) _ The Rev. Francis Patrick Duffy
got a spot on Times Square in 1936 for his heroics on the
battlefield and the streets of Hell's Kitchen. George M. Cohan
followed in 1959 as a tribute to one of show business's greatest
song and dance men. Mayor Rudy Giuliani says there is room for one
more, Frank Sinatra, whose last big hit, in 1980, was ``New York,
New York.'' But the hushed refrain playing around Times Square is
not so gushing or welcoming. No one really wants to say so, at
least not loudly enough to irk Giuliani or offend the Sinatra
family, but the plan to erect a statue of Ol' Blue Eyes on a
traffic island at 44th Street and Broadway has acquired some
powerful enemies. The local community board, along with some Times
Square developers, isn't crazy about the idea. And theater moguls
say the square's theatrical tradition would be shortchanged by
showcasing a singer and film actor who started in Hoboken, made a
quick splash at the Paramount Theater and then followed fame and
fortune west of the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-REACT (Undated) _ Vocies from around the country as ordinary
people react to the Republican convention in Philadelphia. By Jane
Gross, Dirk Johnson, James Sterngold and Tina Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CAMPAIGN (Chicago) Al Gore bounded back onto the campaign
trail Friday and, in the unconditional embrace of 3,400 union
firefighters, mocked the Republican National Convention as a
special-interests-sponsored sham. ``This is Day One of the fight
for working families,'' he declared. (Summary from wires) By James
Dao.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ American companies added fewer new jobs
in July than economists had expected, further lessening the chances
that the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates when it meets
later this month. In the latest sign that economic growth is
slowing, the nation's unemployment rate remained unchanged at 4
percent as private sector payrolls grew by 138,000, about half the
number that most analysts had predicted. The employment numbers
offered the first picture of the economy's performance in July, and
economists predicted that the Federal Reserve's policy-making
committee will decide on Aug. 22 that it does not need to raise
interest rates in order to cool the economy. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON-LABOR (Undated) _ Verizon Communications moved to avoid
a strike by more than 86,000 telephone workers by submitting a
proposal on Friday addressing concerns over issues including wages,
benefits and job security. Still, the company avoided the unions'
central concern of unionizing the wireless work force, increasing
the possibility of a walkout. Unless the company and unions agree
on several issues by 12:01 a.m. Sunday or agree to extend
discussions _ 72,000 members of the Communications Workers of
America and 14,700 members of International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers will walk out on Verizon Communications, the
company formed by Bell Atlantic's acquisition of the GTE Corp. By
Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ANARCHY-REVIVED (Undated) _ Since Karl Marx bested the anarchist
leader Michael Bakunin in a struggle to shape world revolution a
century and a half ago, anarchism has undergone a half-dozen
resurrections, and almost as many deaths. It was crushed with the
Paris Commune in 1871, suppressed in the United States after an
anarchist shot President McKinley in 1901, destroyed by Franco in
the Spanish Civil War of the late 1930s and it withered away with
1960s student radicalism. Ideologically opposed to power and
ambivalent about organization, anarchists perpetually live on the
fringe of great movements _ and on the verge of defeat. Yet the
very qualities that consign anarchism to obscurity also endow it
with many lives, if only as a prefix: anarcho-collectivism,
anarcho-syndicalism, anarcho-mutualism, anarcho-individualism,
anarcho-ecologism. And at the turn of this century, it is
undergoing a fresh resurgence. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT5.
</P>
<P>
   IRONY-RECONSIDERED (Undated) _ So is irony a bad thing or a good
thing? It depends, in part, on what you mean by irony, which has
become a critical term of nearly infinite elasticity. By Charles
McGrath.
</P>
