<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2910 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS &LR;      08-04 1363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH'S SPEECH: PROMISES, PROMISES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HELEN THOMAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers +
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The speech by Texas Gov. George W. Bush accepting
the Republican presidential nomination can be summed up as
``promises, promises.''
</P>
<P>
   It was long on general themes but short on specifics. We await
with great interest the details. He is going to have to do some
explaining to translate his high flown rhetoric into actual deeds.
His words evoke memories of the famous dare by former Attorney
General John Mitchell: ``Watch what we do, not what we say,''
referring to his days in the Nixon administration.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the worshipful assemblage that the nation should seize
this time of peace and prosperity to confront threats to our
national security and threats to our health and retirement
security. ``And we will extend the promise of prosperity to every
forgotten corner of this country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will have his work cut out for him when he tries to make
good on those pledges, especially when he says ``big government is
not the answer,'' a line stolen from both Presidents Ronald Reagan
and Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He also swiped the slogan that ``no child will be left behind,''
an adage originated by the Children's Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Bush may find that people do not hate the government as much as
his ``compassionate conservatives'' do because they are taught that
the government is ``we the people.'' And much as they try,
religious charities cannot possibly take care of the millions of
the poor, the sick and the maimed.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Bush's well-rehearsed address to the foot-stomping
delegates made him sound like a Democrat _ and in fact he
confiscated a few pages out of President Clinton's book.
</P>
<P>
   But all's fair in love and war. After all, Clinton hijacked the
GOP agenda's calling for a balanced budget, welfare reform and
reducing the national debt. But Clinton amazed his critics by
accomplishing those goals, with the help of the Republican-led
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   There's irony in the fact that Bush hopes to ride the crest of
the Clinton-Gore prosperity but, at the same time, he's being very
careful to avoid giving them credit for the good times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prosperity can be a tool in our hands,'' Bush said and recited
his goals to use the government surpluses. But he seems to have
conveniently forgotten that his father lost his reelection bid in
1992 because the economy back then was in a slump. Clinton's
in-house campaign slogan that year was a reminder to the candidate
and his staff: `It's the economy, stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the disconnects between Bush and reality.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it was almost embarrassing when Bush praised the
heroes of World War II, considering the fact that he and his
running mate Richard Cheney resorted to loopholes to dodge the
draft in the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and let's not forget the video picturing John F. Kennedy,
the Democratic icon, and civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr.
That snippet overlooked the fact that Cheney voted against making
King's birthday a national holiday when he was a House member.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the spectacle of Bush promising to expand the
goals of Head Start, a highly successful government-funded
education program, which Cheney also voted against when he was a
six-term congressman from Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure many in the audience grinned as I did when Bush, who
attended Andover, Yale and Harvard, spoke of his ``lack of polish
of Washington''in seeking to depict himself as an outsider. Give me
a break.
</P>
<P>
   So Bush has a lot of blanks to fill in _ unless American voters
let him off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Westerners are known for calling a spade a spade. So why do
George W. Bush and Dick Cheney, proud sons of Texas and Wyoming,
resort to code words when talking about their opponents?
</P>
<P>
   Their barbs against Clinton come wrapped in such gauzy veils as
the need to restore ``respect, dignity and honor'' to the West Wing
of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Potential first lady Laura Bush also slipped into code when she
said moms, dads and grandparents are telling her husband: ``I want
my son and daughter to respect the president of the United
States.'' She later denied she was attacking the president.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying such mysterious lingo is the fact that the
Republicans are afraid get too blunt when talking about Clinton's
affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky. They fear
voter backlash against any heavy-handed negative attacks. The last
such Republican effort ended in an embarrassing defeat for the GOP
when the Senate failed to convict Clinton of his impeachment
offenses _ and the voters removed some Republican House members in
the middle of the flap.
</P>
<P>
   Bush started the current round of code talk when he went to
Arkansas, Clinton's home state, and introduced Cheney as a man who
knows ``what the definition of `is,' is,'' an obvious reference to
Clinton's much lampooned hair-splitting answers to the Kenneth
Starr grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd at the Arkansas rally understood the code and roared
appreciatively. It was more than Clinton could stand. He slammed
back at Bush, calling him in effect a ``Daddy's boy'' who was
riding his father's coattails.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush responded by threatening to tell the world what
he really thought of his successor ``as a human being and a
person.''
</P>
<P>
   In attacking Clinton, Bush had departed from the Republican
script, which called for him to avoid the ``politics of personal
destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole exchange suggests that the younger Bush has been
harboring resentment against Clinton for defeating his father in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bush says he takes after his mother Barbara Bush in
her feistiness, and therein lies the problem.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign strategists want only a ``positive reflection'' of
the candidate _ they want him to control his combative nature and
desire to retaliate.
</P>
<P>
   Like the party pros, former President Jerry Ford was
disapproving of the negative approach and called it
``counterproductive.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Pollster John Zogby says Hillary Rodham Clinton is doing
``terrible'' in her bid for a Senate seat from New York. She's
eight points behind Rep. Rich Lazio a Republican from Long Island,
according to a recent Zogby poll. It's Zogby's contention that the
first lady ``should have waited'' until her husband was out of
office, and then perhaps run for Senate from her native Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The pollster said that Clinton ``is doing everything right'' but
she is ``not connecting'' with the women in New York. It seems that
New Yorkers are hung up on the fact that she was not born in New
York, a ``carpetbagger'' label she has been unable to shake off. It
is an angle that Lazio is playing up to the hilt. Not that the
first lady is totally bereft of political fodder. Lazio was close
to former Speaker Newt Gingrich and voted for the convervative
manifesto ``Contract for America.''
</P>
<P>
   Some New York women are still mad at Hillary because she didn't
leave her husband in the aftermath of the Lewinsky affair. Their
chagrin is matched by Cheney's ultra conservative wife Lynne who
said the first lady was ``hypocritical'' for holding her husband's
hand in public.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the same Lynne Cheney who flaunts ``family values'' but
who seems incapable of understanding women who believe in
forgiveness? I guess not.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, President Clinton says he wishes he could help his
wife more and feels that her Republican opponents are using their
enduring antagonism against him to tar her with the same brush.
Zogby claims the late Robert Kennedy was victorious in his Senate
race in New York because of his brother's assassination, winning
him a sympathy factor. He also says that the ``worst thing to
happen'' to Mrs. Clinton was when the more vulnerable New York
Mayor Rudy Giuliani dropped out for health and marital reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Senate race is already the most interesting
election contest this year. Bush vs. Gore doesn't even come close.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QR;
</P>
<P>
   (Helen Thomas can be contacted at 202-298-6920 or via e-mail:
helent &LR; hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
