<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2913 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-CLEANWATER0     08-04 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CLEANWATER0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY
 &HT;    Three little words for Mr. Sam's lake
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Legendary Texas politician Sam Rayburn said the
three most important words in the English language were: ``Wait a
minute.''
</P>
<P>
   In considering recent state action regarding water quality at
the important reservoir named for ``Mr. Sam,'' citizens might well
demand the thoughtful pause he advocated.
</P>
<P>
   The state's three environmental commissioners last week voted
unanimously to lower water-quality standards for the Sam Rayburn
Reservoir in the Piney Woods of East Texas. The vast impoundment is
a popular bass fishery and water sports site.
</P>
<P>
   Angler groups and environmentalists were abashed and said, in
effect, ``Wait a minute.'' They asked federal regulators to
overrule the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission and set
a higher standard for the lake. They noted that the woodland
reservoir is a ``world class'' fishery that generates an estimated
$38 million in recreation revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments for the downgrade came mainly from owners of the
60-year-old Donohue Industries paper mill on the shore near Lufkin.
The mill empties industrial wastewater into a tributary of the
Angelina River, which feeds the reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   The owners, Abitibi Consolidated Inc., of Montreal, contend that
tighter pollution standards could force them to close the paper
mill, a major East Texas employer.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental commissioners last week adopted new
water-quality standards for streams, lakes and bays as part of the
state's duties under the federal Clean Water Act. New protections
for aquatic habitat, coastal seagrasses and wetlands were hailed by
anglers and environmental groups as advancing protection of Texas
waters. Commissioners said the statewide plan would improve overall
water quality.
</P>
<P>
   But downgrades of standards for some waterways, in particular
Sam Rayburn Reservoir, were called a threat that federal regulators
should examine critically. The Texas Parks and Wildlife Department
opposed the change.
</P>
<P>
   Downgrades were also approved for part of the Nueces River near
Corpus Christi, the Pease River in West Texas and various East
Texas streams.
</P>
<P>
   The big reservoir was completed in the mid-1960s and named for
Rayburn shortly after his death. It honors a plainspoken East Texan
who served as speaker of the Texas House and the U.S. House,
serving almost five decades in Congress. He is recalled for his
political skills, simple tastes, fierce rectitude and refusal to
use positions of public trust to amass wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Rayburn would understand the political realities that bear on
many modern environmental decisions. He might less readily
recognize his home state's rapidly growing population, flourishing
industries and daunting challenges for cleaning up air and water.
</P>
<P>
   The water supply grows increasingly precious each year, and a
scarcity of clean water for drinking and recreation threatens many
communities. The environmental commission's decision to downgrade
water quality standards for this important reservoir in the heart
of the Angelina National Forest deserves, at the very least, closer
public scrutiny. Practical compromises between needs of industry
and public need may be possible. Federal regulators should not
accept the state decision without saying, as Mr. Sam might have
said, ``Wait a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
