<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2914 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-DEATHROW080     08-04 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DEATHROW0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY
 &HT;    A view from inside death row
 &HT;    By Prat Thakkar
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIVINGSTON, Texas _ The East Texas heat is so intense that time
itself seems to stand still.
</P>
<P>
   The winding, two-lane road to death row curves past farms ringed
by low wooden fences. In the pastures, cows compete for shade and
graze on parched grass. Those pastoral scenes soon surrender to
high steel fences topped by coils of razor wire, their jagged edges
glistening in the blazing sun. The steel guards the Terrell Unit,
home to Texas' death row.
</P>
<P>
   As in other states, death row here is part of an elaborate
machine created to extract the ultimate penalty. The theory is
biblical: An eye for an eye. But matters of human life and death _
even here _ are rarely that simple. As the country re-examines the
death penalty and Texas undergoes renewed scrutiny because its
governor would be president, questions about capital punishment
demand answers that are as elusive as they are difficult.COMMUNITY
LIFE
</P>
<P>
   The chain-link fences and boxy, nondescript buildings that make
up the Terrell Unit are like a Hollywood version of a prison.
Nothing on the outside calls attention to the prison's dubious
distinction of housing more than 450 men sentenced to die in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Not much on the inside does, either. The foyer gleams from the
constant attention given it by trusties whose job is to polish,
vacuum and buff. The benign facade crumbles as you approach death
row.
</P>
<P>
   On death row, innocuous tasks mark the slow passing of the hours
and days. It's a place where questions are plentiful and easy
answers are scarce. The questions echo off the constant chatter of
hundreds of men engaged in conversation around the clock each day.
</P>
<P>
   Several electronically controlled gates lead to death row. The
hallways inside lead to the six identical death row ``pods''
labeled from A to F. Each pod has 84 cells divided into six
sections, again labeled from A to F. Along the far wall are
two-tiered rows of cells with heavy white metal doors. Each door
has a rectangular slot for the food tray. The slot is opened by
officers at mealtimes _ breakfast begins at 3:30 a.m., lunch at 10
a.m., dinner at 3:30 p.m. So populated is death row that feeding
the inmates takes two to two and one-half hours for each meal.
</P>
<P>
   The doors also have two narrow rectangular panels, about 2.5
inches wide and 12 inches long, of thick black metal grill _ the
only view inmates have into the pod.
</P>
<P>
   Inside a cell that is about 6 feet by 9 feet is a steel bunk
against the back wall with a mattress and pillow. Two metal shelves
jut from the wall, used as a table or as supports. A metal toilet
with a small metal sink sits in one corner and above it, built into
the wall, is a tubelight and an electrical outlet. The only other
source of light is a thin strip of window above the bed.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD BEHAVIOR PAYS
</P>
<P>
   Inmates who have the money and behave themselves are allowed to
buy items such as hot plates, fans or radios from the prison
commissary.
</P>
<P>
   Each pod also has 12 showers, six indoor and four outdoor
recreation areas. The indoor rec areas are mostly rectangular
spaces encircled floor to ceiling by black steel bars. Inside are a
few metal stools and a chinning bar. The outside rec areas have a
basketball, a hoop and a chinning bar. Sunlight filters in through
the mesh ceiling. Recreation time _ like visiting time _ is a
privilege, varying according to prisoners' behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Among the men receiving visitors that day is Danny Dean Thomas,
44, on death row since 1982. He was 27 when he became a dead man.
Thomas was convicted for shooting a woman named Sylvia Hamson in
July 1981. He and an accomplice killed Hamson, tied bricks to her
body and dumped her in the San Jacinto River.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas, someone still comes to visit you?'' asks Larry
Fitzgerald, manager of public information for the Texas Department
of Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' shoulders droop over his lanky frame. A slow,
anticipatory smile breaks across his lined face as he looks at the
door that leads out of the building. ``Yeah, every week, Larry,''
he replies, eyes glistening.
</P>
<P>
   In the regimented world of prison, visits are prized, their
frequencies varied as a way of encouraging good behavior. Visits
mark one of the rare opportunities for death row inmates to leave
the death row building.
</P>
<P>
   A DEAD MAN'S REQUEST
</P>
<P>
   Back on death row, the catcalls from neighboring sections drown
out the voices of my guides.
</P>
<P>
   Once the novelty wears off, the screaming dies down and the
chatter picks up. But the seven men along the bottom tier of Pod A,
section F stare at me silently. The cells in the top tier are
empty. This section houses inmates whose appeals are exhausted and
who have scheduled execution dates.
</P>
<P>
   A short, sprightly man named Cruz calls out to Fitzgerald. Cruz
asks if he can shoot a video explaining how he ended up on death
row as a warning to young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll look into it and get back to you,'' Fitzgerald says.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz breaks into a broad, mischievous smile. ``I'll still be
here,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Cruz laughs, scampers back to his cot and sits down to write.
Bright photographs paper the wall by his cot. He looks no older
than 22. He's 33, and has been on death row since 1989. EXECUTIONS
SET
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, David Oliver Cruz is a ``model inmate.''
Personable, cheerful, well-behaved. He is also a rapist and a
murderer. His victim was 24-year-old Kelly Elizabeth Donovan. His
co-defendant got a 65-year sentence for murder in exchange for
testifying against Cruz. A few cells down is Brian Keith Roberson,
36, who has been on death row since 1987. He was convicted for the
stabbing death of his 79-year-old neighbor, Jamie Louis Boots. He
also killed Lillian Wallace Boots before burglarizing the home.
</P>
<P>
   Roberson and the men in neighboring cells spot me and walk up to
the cell doors, leaning their arms and faces against the black
grill panels. They all stare at me silently. Tiny beads of sweat
collect on Roberson's face. His neighbors move back to their cots.
Roberson continues staring, a curious mixture of hope and
desperation frozen in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Both Cruz and Roberson are scheduled to die Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The stagnant hot air inside death row offers no answers to the
questions that lurk behind my inquiries about the routine of life
on death row _ how did men such as Cruz and Roberson go so wrong?
Was there a more fitting punishment for the lives they ruined so
carelessly? Death row offered no clear answers, no clear sense of
revenge or justice.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
