<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2916 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-TRIBES-RIGHTS-NEWHOUS     08-04 2186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIBES-RIGHTS-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBAL STATUS STILL ELUSIVE CONCEPT FOR AMERICANS
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Friday, AUGUST 4, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADVISORY: With 1933 photo of Indians contesting treaty
violations in court (NNS1) and a graphic available on the Newhouse
BBS showing decline in tribal lands from 1775-1992 
 By COURTENAY THOMPSON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- In 1783, George Washington wrote that American
settlers moving west would uproot American Indians and ``certainly
cause the savage as the wolf to retire.''
</P>
<P>
   But while he compared Indians to ``wild beasts of the forest,''
Washington and his new government dealt with tribes as independent
nations with recognized claims to the lands desired by American
settlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indian affairs was the most important foreign affairs issue
facing the Colonies,'' says Robert J. Miller, assistant professor
at Northwestern School of Law of Lewis &AMP; Clark College and a member
of the Eastern Shawnee Tribe of Oklahoma. ``The people who were on
their borders were Indian tribes. The biggest risk was that.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal scholars say the nation's founders inherited the policies
of the British and French, who made treaties with tribes in the
18th century for peace, land and later as allies in the
Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   And these policies, they say, became enshrined in the U.S.
Constitution, as well as in two centuries of Supreme Court
decisions upholding the sovereignty and treaties of tribes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for many Americans today, the concept of tribal sovereignty
remains elusive and ill-understood, tribal leaders and scholars
say. And that ignorance, they say, leads to such proposals as the
recent Washington state Republican Party platform that included
language seeking ``to terminate all such non-republican forms of
government on Indian reservations.''
</P>
<P>
   Northwest tribes took that as a direct attack on their
sovereignty, and Republican leaders in Washington state and in
Congress have scrambled to distance themselves from the
controversial position.
</P>
<P>
   But tribal leaders and scholars say more needs to be done to
educate the public about the history of tribal sovereignty --
especially at a time when tribes, bolstered by gambling revenue and
favorable federal policies, are increasingly asserting their unique
rights to govern themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the greatest untold stories, and one of the most
disappointing deficiencies of our educational system,'' says W. Ron
Allen, chairman of the Jamestown S'Klallam tribe in Washington
state and vice president of the National Congress of American
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said no other nation has such a relationship with its
aboriginal tribes, a relationship in which they are
semi-independent tribal nations, with their own laws, territory and
cultures. They exist within the United States with unique rights to
hunt, fish, even go whaling, rights that are not necessarily shared
by the rest of the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always talk about a historical foundation that has to be
seen in the birth of this country,'' says Alan Parker, director of
the Northwest Indian Applied Research Institute at Evergreen State
College and a Chippewa Cree from Rocky Boy, Mont. ``The British
government, when it first sent settlers to this country,
established a precedent of negotiating treaties. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason for those treaties was easy to understand. They
were suing for peaceful relations, and in some cases suing for an
exchange of land. They were dependent on having peaceful relations
or the little colonies wouldn't have survived.''
</P>
<P>
   That was particularly true as the new, weak federal government
struggled to control the states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The states were entering their own treaties with tribes,
pushing tribes around, stealing land, starting wars,'' Miller says.
``I think everyone agreed the federal government had to be in
charge of Indian affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   The result, he says, was included high in Article 1, Section 8,
of the U.S. Constitution: that Congress shall have the power to
``regulate commerce with foreign nations, and among the several
states, and with the Indian tribes.''
</P>
<P>
   As the federal government grew more powerful during the early
19th century, treaties became increasingly favorable to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1830s, the federal government adopted a removal policy to
push Eastern tribes west of the Mississippi or force them to
assimilate. Tens of thousands of Indians died in forced
relocations, according to the U.S. Bureau of Indian Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But tribes were already becoming more legally sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   The Cherokee Nation fought the state of Georgia, taking the case
to the U.S. Supreme Court, which for the first time defined tribes'
status as that of domestic, dependent nations.
</P>
<P>
   The court also described the federal government's trust
responsibility to tribes: the legal obligation to look out for
their interests.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1800s, as the discovery of gold in California and the
Homestead Act of 1850 sped white settlement westward, the federal
government hurried to reach treaties with tribes in the West.
</P>
<P>
   In a flurry of federal treating-making in the Northwest in 1855,
tribal leaders agreed to give up millions of acres of aboriginal
lands in exchange for reservations and specific rights, especially
to fish, hunt and gather the roots and berries on which they
depended.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very intelligent, creative people with a high degree
of civilization, albeit different from European,'' Parker says of
the tribal negotiators. ``I believe they knew what was going on and
tried to protect themselves as best they could.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the 19th century waned, federal policy shifted toward
trying to assimilate Indians through a series of policies that
devastated tribal cultures: children were sent away to boarding
schools, traditional languages and religions were banned, and
reservations were whittled down through subsequent treaties and the
1887 Dawes Act, which broke up many reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, faced with evidence of appalling tribal
poverty, the federal policy pendulum swung back toward
strengthening tribes through the Indian Reorganization Act of 1934.
</P>
<P>
   But after World War II, federal policy once again encouraged
assimilation. In the 1950s, Congress moved to terminate its
relationship with more than 100 tribes.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, the Kennedy administration ended the termination
policy. Against the backdrop of civil rights, the federal
government, under the leadership of President Nixon, once again
moved to strengthen tribal governments.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said tribes were also tapping into the modern legal
system in the 1970s and 1980s, making great strides toward having
their rights recognized and respected.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   In the Northwest, for example, tribes fought an emotional and
contentious battle for their treaty rights to fish on the Columbia
River, rights upheld in the 1970s by the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Indians never assumed their treaties were affected by the
passage of time,'' Parker says.
</P>
<P>
   Tribes increasingly asserted their rights, following the lead of
visionary tribal leaders such as Joe DeLaCruz, the recently
deceased leader of the Quinault Indian Nation in Washington, Parker
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His vision was we needed to assert those rights if we are
going to protect ourselves,'' he said. ``A lot of the conflicts
over zoning, over gaming, over fishing, they are conflicts because
tribes had these rights but they never attempted to assert or
exercise them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had a generation of leaders who saw this is what they
should do.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Terminated tribes sought, and won, re-recognition from Congress.
Tribes moved into gambling, sparking an economic and political
renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Rapida, associate professor of public administration at
Portland State University in Oregon, said the concept of
sovereignty, outside its legal definitions, is difficult to explain
in part because it is so all-encompassing.
</P>
<P>
   Rapida, a member of the Shoalwater Bay Tribe in southwest
Washington, said that for Native American people, sovereignty is
the ``right to be who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   For many tribes, it is a sacred, spiritual concept, intimately
tied to the land -- it's their right to worship, to abide by their
own laws derived from their creator, to eat their traditional,
sacred foods such as salmon and berries.
</P>
<P>
   By agreeing to give up land in treaties, Rapida said, tribal
leaders made sure they kept the right to govern themselves, take
care of their land and decide as a community what is important.
</P>
<P>
   ---------
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR
</P>
<P>
   1532: Franciscus de Victoria, a Spanish Dominican priest,
delivers lectures arguing aboriginal inhabitants of the Americas
possess natural legal rights as free and rational people.
</P>
<P>
   1700s: England makes formal treaties with various tribes.
</P>
<P>
   1763: King George III issues a royal proclamation banning
colonists from settling west of the crest of the Appalachians,
calling it ``Indian Territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 17, 1778: The Continental Congress enters into its first
treaty with a tribe, the Delawares, suggesting under some
conditions ``to form a state whereof the Delaware Nation shall be
the head, and have a representation in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   1787: The Constitutional Convention vests Congress with
exclusive authority to make treaties with tribes and to regulate
commerce with ``foreign nations, and among the several states, and
with the Indian tribes.''
</P>
<P>
   1831: In Cherokee Nation vs. Georgia, U.S. Chief Justice John
Marshall calls tribes ``domestic, dependent nations'' with a
relationship to the United States resembling that of a ward to a
guardian.
</P>
<P>
   1832: In a second case involving the Cherokee Nation, Marshall
says the Cherokee Nation is ``a distinct community, occupying its
own territory ... in which the laws of Georgia can have no force.''
</P>
<P>
   1830s: Removal begins with federal policy to relocate Indians
from their homelands, making way for white settlement westward.
</P>
<P>
   1850s: Reservations take hold after the California gold rush of
1849 and as whites begin to flood west on the Oregon Trail.
</P>
<P>
   1855: Treaties are reached with many Northwest tribes, including
the Yakama, Nez Perce, Warm Springs, Quinault and Makah. Tribes
cede lands while retaining specific rights to fish, hunt and gather
foods, among other things. The United States promises to do such
things as build schools and blacksmith shops, and provide plows and
other tools as well as medical care.
</P>
<P>
   1871: Congress passes a law ending the treaty-making era.
</P>
<P>
   1887: Congress passes the Dawes Act, or General Allotment Act,
opening up tribal lands for settlement by non-Indians. In the next
few decades, many reservations are split into individual
allotments, intended to make private property owners and farmers of
Indians; many allotments leave Indian hands. The result is a
patchwork of land ownership on some reservations that persists
today. Of the 140 million acres of tribal land in 1887, only 50
million remained by 1934.
</P>
<P>
   1924: Congress makes all American Indians U.S. citizens
</P>
<P>
   1928: The federal Merriam Report calls the allotment policy
devastating to the health and welfare of tribal people.
</P>
<P>
   1934: Congress passes the Indian Reorganization Act, ending
allotment and encouraging tribes to create constitutional forms of
government and corporations for economic development.
</P>
<P>
   1953: Congress passes the Termination Act, part of a policy to
terminate the federal relationship with tribes. Congress terminates
109 tribes. Public Law 280 allows some state civil and criminal
jurisdiction on reservations.
</P>
<P>
   1961: The Kennedy administration refuses to terminate more
tribes. A decade later, the Nixon administration advocates tribal
self-determination and a lessening of the federal role.
</P>
<P>
   1975: The Indian Self-Determination Act passes Congress,
increasing the power of tribes to administer their own programs.
This begins the era of restoration, when some terminated tribes are
once again recognized by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   1988: Congress passes the Indian Gaming Regulatory Act, creating
a regulatory framework for gambling on tribal lands. The aim is to
create economic development in Indian country and address poverty
and unemployment. It is seen by some as an erosion of tribal
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   1994: Congress passes the Self-Governance Act, extending tribal
authority to run all federal programs for the tribes' benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Robert Miller, Lewis &AMP; Clark Law School; U.S. Bureau of
Indian Affairs; ``Cases and Materials on Federal Indian Law,''
Fourth Edition, by David H. Getches, Charles F. Wilkinson and
Robert A. Williams Jr.
</P>
<P>
   -----------
</P>
<P>
   (Courtenay Thompson is a staff writer with The Oregonian of
Portland, Ore.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
