<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2917 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-BUSH-ACCOMPLISH-NEWHO     08-04 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ACCOMPLISH-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS SAY GOP CONVENTION'S MANAGEMENT, MESSAGE WILL LIKELY BOOST
BUSH BID
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Friday, AUGUST 4, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By JOHN J. FARMER  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush's ``iron fist'' management of the Republican
convention and its message robbed it of spontaneity and suspense
but probably boosted his bid for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   That's the view of a cross-section of political scientists and
politicians, including some Democrats. Only an adverse public
reaction over the next few days to Bush's acceptance speech
Thursday night, they said, could dampen the post-convention lift
he's likely to get in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They accomplished everything they wanted -- a safe vice
presidential candidate, no problems with the far right, and they
stayed on Bush's message,'' said Harold Hodes, a Trenton, N.J.,
Democratic political consultant and adviser to Vice President Al
Gore's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The message -- one that all week soft-pedaled partisanship,
promised Thursday night to spread prosperity and in general
preached a ``compassionate conservatism'' -- drew favorable comment
from those interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either through good intuition or focus groups, they've
properly judged the temper of the times,'' said Stephen Hess, a
senior fellow at the Brookings Institution in Washington, D.C.
``It's a feel-good time. Civility, shaving down the sharp edges (of
politics) is probably what Main Street wants today.''
</P>
<P>
   John C. Green, director of the Ray Bliss Institute of Applied
Politics at Akron University in Ohio, concurred. ``Overall, they've
probably helped themselves a good bit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Green cited as especially wise Bush's decision to avoid focusing
on the Clinton impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newt Gingrich and the impeachment managers are very
controversial. They've given the party a bad image and people are
offended by their strident tone,'' Green said. ``By staying away
from them, George Bush is saying, `I'm different from the
congressional wing of the party.'''
</P>
<P>
   Washington political consultant Lyn Nofziger, a staunch
conservative and former political operative in the Reagan White
House, is not sympathetic to Bush's ``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   He found Colin Powell's defense of affirmative action ``a
discordant note,'' for example. And he would have liked at least
one plank in the Bush platform used to bash Bill Clinton over
impeachment and Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But he conceded that Bush's decision to side-step impeachment in
favor of an ``above the (Washington) battle'' stance may be smart.
``You journalists have made the public think they're tired of
impeachment,'' Nofziger cracked.
</P>
<P>
   And he had high praise for the Bush team's tight control over
the convention -- better even than the 1984 ``Morning in America''
convention that preceded Reagan's landslide re-election, Nofziger
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even higher praise came from an unexpected quarter -- Russ
Hemenway, head of the National Committee for an Effective Congress,
which provides money and campaign help for liberal Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Noting Bush's surge in the polls in the weeks leading to the
convention and this week, Hemenway said, ``This is the most
brilliantly managed three weeks I've ever seen in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, he said, ``cut a deal with the Christian Coalition, told
them to shut up, and they did. It's extraordinary. Everyone's on
message. The convention speakers were good, especially Colin
Powell. Dick Cheney was the worst. He doesn't help, but he doesn't
hurt either. Vice presidents almost never do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemenway said he is particularly impressed with Bush's success
in ``defining himself as a moderate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's believable,'' he said, ''`and it resonates. It's
what people want. If they can keep this up for 90 more days,
they're probably in.''
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Cheney as Bush's running mate -- and his
acceptance speech -- drew mixed reviews. But several felt that
Cheney's solid record as a social conservative -- his appeal to the
party's right-wing base -- freed Bush Thursday night to appeal to a
wider audience, to moderates and even disgruntled or disappointed
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what Bush did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Cheney) let Bush go broader,'' said Merle Black, professor
of politics at Emory University in Atlanta. ``He let him say that
this is a different type of Republican Party, more diverse. He let
him really go after moderates.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if they get them, they'll win,'' Black added.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, most felt Cheney would not hurt Bush (``He's a
serious adult,'' Black said) but would not help much, either in the
Electoral College or as a party-rallying stump speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's no stem-winder,'' said Brookings' Hess, ``but I found a
certain charm in his acceptance speech -- until I fell asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   A problem for Bush -- ``a heck of a problem,'' Akron
University's Green called it -- is the robust economy of the
Clinton-Gore years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rightly or wrongly, Democrats get a lot of the credit,'' Green
said. Bush's strategy, evident in his acceptance speech, is ``to
change the subject to reform of the economy -- reform of education
and Social Security -- and to values,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   While most applauded Bush's promise of a more civil tone in
political debate, several questioned how long he can hold to that
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Nofziger, the GOP conservative, predicted flatly that it won't
last: ``He can't stay above the battle. He has to answer charges
and say why Gore should be defeated.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Ditto Democrat Hemenway. But what worries Hemenway most is a
campaign in which Bush is seen as running a high-road campaign
while Gore hurls thunderbolts daily. It's Gore's stock-in-trade,
Hemenway said, what he does best, as he has demonstrated in two
national campaigns and in demolishing his Democratic rival this
year, Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Gore's closest advisers, particularly media expert Bob
Shrum, specialize in rough stuff, Hemenway said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Bush handlers) will say, `There they go, slinging
mud again.' These guys worry me,'' Hemenway said of the Bush team,
especially Karl Rove, the boss of Bush's campaign brain trust.
``He's terrific,'' Hemenway said of Rove and his handling of the
Bush campaign and the convention.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, the key to Bush's ``bounce'' from this
convention lies with voter reaction to Thursday night's acceptance
address.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's viewed as a flop,'' said Merle Black, ``then nothing
else that went on in Philadelphia will matter much.''
</P>
<P>
   ---------
</P>
<P>
   (John J. Farmer is a staff writer with The Star-Ledger of
Newark, N.J.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
