<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2918 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-UGANDA-NOVELIST-2TAKE     08-04 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGANDA-NOVELIST-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAGIC OF WRITING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Netherlands, Germany, Finland, Uganda)   By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Growing up in Uganda, Moses Isegawa was an insatiable
reader, savoring books by writers as diverse as Philip Roth, V.S.
Naipaul, Timothy Mo and Gabriel Garcia Marquez. From the age of 14,
he dreamed about becoming a novelist himself. ``I thought it must
be magical to be a writer,'' he said recently. ``To tell a story
and somebody deep in a village in Uganda reads it and can identify
with the place and the characters _ I never lost that idea of the
magic and the excitement of literature.''
</P>
<P>
   It took many years, but at 37 Isegawa is a novelist, with an
increasing international reputation. His first novel, ``Abyssinian
Chronicles,'' was recently published by Alfred A. Knopf, having
already been published in the Netherlands (where the author now
lives) and in Finland and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The book is both a coming of age novel with a cast of evocative
African characters and an account of the political turbulence
during the regime of Idi Amin, the former Ugandan dictator.
</P>
<P>
   During his first visit to New York, Isegawa said the book was 90
percent fiction and 10 percent memoir. But throughout it resonates
with the knowledge of a first-hand experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skeleton'' of the novel, he said, came from his life _ his
move from the country to the city of Kampala, his years studying in
a Roman Catholic seminary and his eventual departure for the
Netherlands. He fleshed out the book by cross-pollinating
characters, ``working up'' incidents and imagining dramatic events.
At the heart is an Isegawa-like protagonist named Mugezi.
</P>
<P>
   From the first sentence of the novel, it is clear that this
fictional world is not so distant from magic realism: Mugezi's
father is consumed by a ``colossal crocodile.'' Then the book moves
into a flashback. Isegawa's father and mother live in Uganda, and
they have not yet read their son's book. They may be surprised by
the unflattering portraits of Mugezi's parents, especially the
mother, who is emotionally and physical abusive of her son. If his
parents are upset, Isegawa said, so be it: ``I think Philip Roth
said, if a family gets a writer in its midst, there's going to be
trouble _ and it's going to be on my address, on my doorstep.''
</P>
<P>
   Mugezi has his own strong streak of malice, often pitting his
parents against each other. This is not a portrait of a hero as a
young man. Instead, in the author's words, Mugezi is closer to a
villain. ``I tried to get away from the love-me kind of book,'' he
said. ``I wanted to treat everybody the same way. I was not going
to be soft on myself and then go out and start punching people
below the belt. I wanted to write a challenging book, challenging
to myself and to other people.''
</P>
<P>
   He stressed the fictive elements in his protagonist. ``If I had
written a book about myself,'' he said, ``it would have been the
most boring book ever written.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the aggressive Mugezi, Isegawa seems soft-spoken
and genteel. Mugezi may be a case of wish fulfillment: ``He became
my cowboy, my outer ego, who is not afraid to get in trouble: to
hit and also get hit.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the family story, the portrait of Idi Amin is
drawn directly from life. When Amin leads a coup d'etat in 1971 to
overthrow the corrupt Obote administration, Mugezi _ in common with
other Ugandans _ greets him as a savior. At first, Isegawa said,
``He did everything people wanted him to,'' and announced political
and social reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only afterwards that reports started coming in that
people had been kidnapped and killed.'' In one of several harrowing
scenes in the book, soldiers rape one of Mugezi's aunts. In the
end, Amin also ``destroyed the physical structure of the economy''
and the culture, as publishers left the country and books
disappeared from bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   At the time Isegawa knew little about the regime. Politics was a
taboo subject at home. In his family, it was his grandfather, a
lawyer, who was the most communicative, and it was from him that he
gathered family stories.
</P>
<P>
   While at the seminary Isegawa began writing short stories. He
sent some to a pen pal friend in the Netherlands who passed them on
to a Dutch missionary magazine, which published them, and then
asked Isegawa to write a monthly column.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by this encouragement, at 26 he decided to leave
Uganda. ``It was like stealing away,'' he said. He told only a few
people, and simply got on a plane and flew to the Netherlands. An
aunt and a cousin saw him off at the airport: ``They didn't even
know that I was going to be a writer. They thought I was going to
do what other young people do'' _ leave the country to make money
and send it back home.
</P>
<P>
   He had something entirely different in mind. ``I had burned all
my bridges,'' he said. ``I think writers need a shock. In Amsterdam
I had to begin at zero level. I had to learn the language, and find
my own feet. When people would ask what are you doing, I would say
I was a bookkeeper.'' That was one of his occupations. In secret he
became a book writer.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years his book grew larger and more personal, and by 30
he was more confident about his talent. When he finished the novel,
he made four copies and sent them at random to four Dutch
publishers. Two immediately returned the manuscript, but the third
publisher accepted it and commissioned a Dutch translation of the
English. The author was jubilant, and the subsequent rejection of
the fourth copy did not discourage him.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, eight months before the book was published, he was
interviewed on Dutch radio, and that set off a series of other
interviews. By the time the book came out, he was already a
celebrity in the Netherlands. Favorable reviews sparked sales.
Acting as intermediary, his Dutch editor helped find publishers in
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the curious title, Isegawa said he wanted to find a
word that would encapsulate the desperate situation in Uganda, and
hit upon ``abyss,'' then expanded it to Abyssinia. As the father
says in the book, ``Uganda was a land of false bottoms where under
every abyss there was another one waiting to ensnare people.'' For
him, it was Uganda not Ethiopia that was really Abyssinia.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Isegawa could call himself a writer, a feeling that was
underscored during his visit to the United States. In New York he
shared an evening's reading with the critic Stanley Crouch, who
told him he had been at a birthday party for Saul Bellow and had
recommended that Bellow, Roth and William Kennedy read ``Abyssinian
Chronicles.''
</P>
<P>
   When Isegawa heard that, he said, ``Wow! Incredible stuff. I
can't imagine those writers taking the time to read my book. I
would be honored to be in their company, but, for me, I'm still the
wannabe. I have one book. I'm just saying this is the way I want to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   In the book the name Mugezi is defined as meaning brilliant in
Ugandan. Asked what Moses means, he said, ``taken out,'' which
seems relevant: He was taken out of Uganda. But as Mugezi says, ``I
carried the village with me, and it would remain so the rest of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still part of it,'' Isegawa said about Uganda. ``When you
leave, you leave with all the images. I planted that tiny village
in the book and now it has grown to this big thing in the world.
You leave a situation but you can't leave it psychologically.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer the British edition will go on sale in Uganda. His
parents will have a chance to read it, and the author will return
home, for the first time. In some small outlying village other
young men may read the book and be inspired by the magic of
Isegawa's story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
