<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2920 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-STL-NITEOUT-ELIZABETH     08-04 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STL-NITEOUT-ELIZABETH-GILBERT-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT OUT WITH ELIZABETH GILBERT AND THE COYOTE REGULARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 6)  
 By SIMON HOUPT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was definitely a mistake to have only one pint of
Jack Daniel's before seeing that,'' Elizabeth Gilbert said to her
friend Jana. This was a few minutes after the end credits rolled at
the Monday night Ziegfeld premiere of ``Coyote Ugly.'' The heavily
hyped new Disney movie is based on a 1997 GQ article by Gilbert
about her experiences tending bar at the real Coyote Ugly in the
East Village. She was out of sorts after watching the film, which
transformed the gritty, tiny, blue-collar dive into an outsize,
airbrushed party palace. Usually armed with a quick and cynical
wit, Gilbert could only mutter, ``It's so weird,'' as she wandered
toward the exit.
</P>
<P>
   But feeling weird is normal for a writer at a movie premiere,
fluttering through the big night in an odd twilight between being a
star and a nobody. Gilbert went to join her friends, the Coyote
regulars Beertruck, Big Daddy and Redneck Lou, who were waiting at
the exit with her husband, Mike. The movie's cast was being ferried
the three blocks to Roseland by stretch limos for the after-party.
Gilbert's posse walked. Disney booked their car only for the first
half of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Flashbulbs were popping at the Roseland entrance. ``Hey, Liz, is
it like this on your book tour, too?'' Jana asked in mock
amazement. Gilbert had just come back from two weeks spent in small
Maine bookstores, reading from her new novel ``Stern Men.'' ``Oh,
yes,'' she replied, going along with the joke, though the
flashbulbs stopped at her arrival when none of the paparazzi
recognized her.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the ballroom had been transformed into a theme version
of the celebrated drinking hole. ``Wow, faux ugly!'' Gilbert
exclaimed, taking in the battered license plates, neon beer signs
and bras hanging from the fixtures, all of which serve as decor at
the real Coyote Ugly. Sexy young things stripped down to black bras
and leather pants strutted atop the bar. Every so often they
breathed fire or sprayed water into the crowd, dancing to David
Bowie, ZZ Top and Kid Rock. ``It's like a ride!'' Gilbert
exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   She and Jana headed straight for a makeshift tattoo parlor, an
attraction the real bar doesn't offer. Though the only tattoo
available was a decal of the movie's logo, they nonetheless took
turns applying it to each other's biceps. Hugh Jackman (``X-Men''),
'N Sync and LeAnn Rimes were there with the movie's cast. Gilbert
went to say hello to Piper Perabo, the lead actress, but was
waylaid when the bartenders uncorked a thunderstorm of bottled
water onto the heads of the crowd. Most scurried away, but Gilbert
stood her ground, removing her leather jacket to shield herself
from the downpour. After a couple of minutes she'd had enough and
gathered her friends to make a run to the real Coyote Ugly.
</P>
<P>
   ``First Avenue between Ninth and Tenth, please,'' she instructed
the cabdriver. ``Boy, if I had a nickel for every time I've said
that.'' At 12:30 a.m., Gilbert made a grander entrance at the dark,
steamy, sweaty, genuine Coyote Ugly, where she was greeted with
hoots and hollers. She hit the jukebox and punched in the kind of
music they didn't play up at Roseland: the country stalwarts George
Jones, Merle Haggard, Dwight Yoakam. When Hank Williams Jr.'s
``Family Tradition,'' came on, Chris, the only male bartender, took
her hand and struck up an impressive two-step.
</P>
<P>
   By 2:30, Gilbert's feet were getting tired. Claiming she no
longer had the same stamina as when she worked at the bar seven
years ago, she and Mike headed for the door, despite pleas from
Beertruck and Big Daddy. ``We're leaving,'' Gilbert said firmly.
``It's Monday night and I'm 31 and I need an Advil. It's time for a
cab.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
