<HEADER>
A2926 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-IMMIGRANTS-UNION-N     08-04 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-IMMIGRANTS-UNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPUTE WITH HANDBAG MAKER TAKEN TO STORE 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nieves Pena watched in admiration a year and a half
ago as her mother voted to unionize the garment district factory in
which she worked, one that made handbags for Kate Spade.
</P>
<P>
   But when Pena tried to help start a union in June at her own
factory, KC Accessories, which also happened to make Kate Spade
bags, she ran into a wall, she said. The owner, Kulwant Chouhan,
pulled her aside and told her not to talk about a union, she said.
Then, on June 30, he dismissed all 50 or so workers, most of them
Latino immigrants, she said. Later, she said, he rehired about 20
who were not union sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can do anything he wants,'' said Pena, who came from the
Dominican Republic in 1998. ``There's a reason why we want to join
a union.''
</P>
<P>
   The Union of Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees has
filed a complaint with the National Labor Relations Board, accusing
KC Accessories, at 22 W. 32nd St., of anti-union practices.
Chouhan's lawyer has denied the allegations, and an investigation
is pending. But Thursday, Pena joined two dozen protesters outside
a Kate Spade boutique in SoHo to denounce her former employer and
to ask Kate Spade to put pressure on Chouhan.
</P>
<P>
   The action against KC Accessories is the latest in a series of
complaints against high-end designers and the contractors who do
much of their manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Spade has taken the stance that it has no control over the
labor practices of its contractors. ``They're not our employees;
it's not our business,'' said Elyce Cox, a partner at Kate Spade,
which had more than $60 million in revenue last year.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Post, a lawyer who represents both KC Accessories and
Kate Spade, denied the allegations against Chouhan. ``KC
Accessories complies with all applicable labor laws and
regulations,'' he said. ``We believe that KC Accessories will be
vindicated by the National Labor Relations Board after the board
has had the opportunity to review all of the circumstances and not
just one side of the story, as it has now.''
</P>
<P>
   The workers said that in June, Chouhan began meeting with
workers one by one to discourage them from forming a union. This
came after some workers had already approached UNITE about
unionizing the shop, and had begun to collect signatures from their
colleagues, Pena said. Then on June 30, hours after UNITE
representatives went to the shop to ask Chouhan to recognize the
union, Chouhan dismissed his employees, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pena said she worked 40 to 50 hours a week and earned $6.50 an
hour, but was never paid extra for working overtime or holidays.
She said she also did not receive health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Also on June 30, UNITE filed a petition with the National Labor
Relations Board for the factory workers to hold a vote on whether
to form a union. The election is scheduled for Tuesday, but union
officials are asking the government to cancel the vote because they
say that in mid-July, Chouhan rehired only those workers who are
anti-union.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, garment workers and union officials marched outside
the Kate Spade store while a well-dressed man stood inside the
display window and thumbed his nose at them. Minutes later, he
stormed outside and grabbed a stack of pamphlets from one woman and
ran back into the store. Then he rushed back outside, slammed his
elbow into the face of a photographer and walked quickly down the
street, witnesses said. Police officers said the man was a Kate
Spade employee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
