<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-REAL-LIFE-TV-NYT &LR;      08-04 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-TV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE BRUTAL TRUTH IS JUST POLITICS IN AN EXOTIC SETTING 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching Greg, the Ivy League graduate, earnestly pretend a
coconut is his cell phone in the middle of the jungle, or Richard,
the scheming corporate consultant, strip naked in honor of his
birthday; watching Mega, the black nationalist, sarcastically tell
one-legged Eddie that he supports ``cripple rights,'' or Karen, the
troubled housewife, confess her affair with her stepfather's nephew
_ watching these ``real life'' moments from the television shows
``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother'' (or the latter's 24-hour-a-day
live Web site), I felt an all too familiar twinge.
</P>
<P>
   Plato described it as the contradictory feelings of repulsion
and fascination that arise when a dead body is viewed by the
living. Corpses must have caused an ancient form of rubbernecking.
Now television does it. I watch in gruesome embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor,'' of course, stranded 11 people on a South Seas
island, where they have to manage to survive the elements and one
another; ``Big Brother'' stranded 10 people in a bourgeois house,
where they have to survive one another and a very tiny
refrigerator. Once they enter these worlds, they abandon all hope
of privacy; cameramen invisibly stalk the islanders; cameras
noisily swerve throughout the house. And lest everything become too
dull, much effort is expended to ensure discomfort and conflict.
There are limited rations, unpleasant sleeping conditions, contests
to teasingly create group loyalty and others to shatter it.
Presumably the veneer of ordinary public manners will gradually
fall away, revealing the private self in all its unsettling
nakedness.
</P>
<P>
   The concept behind these shows is not unfamiliar. Take a group
of types _ figures who, in their occupations or views, are
recognizably representative personalities _ and throw them together
in an isolating setting. Eugene O'Neill tossed his social emblems
together in a bar for ``The Iceman Cometh.'' Katherine Anne Porter
put them to sea for ``Ship of Fools.'' ``Gilligan's Island'' turned
the gathering into slight farce, Sartre's ``No Exit'' into
pretentious nightmare. All are meant to be microcosms of a society
in which various public roles collide, revealing hypocrisy or
crudity or sterility or venality. Names become irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   The types are part of these shows as well. On the island: the
single mother of two, the clueless doctor, the leather-skinned Navy
Seal; in the house: the middle-aged dad, the exotic dancer, the
eccentric virgin, the quiet beauty queen. And much of the drama is
how, once pulled away from the society that defines those roles,
figures like these manage to fend for themselves, supposedly
becoming more ``real'' in their isolation, unveiling private
truths.
</P>
<P>
   But what bizarre truths they are! The real is actually the world
being left behind; the artificial is the world being created. Soap
operas take ``fake'' people and put them in ``real'' situations;
these shows take real people and put them in fake situations.
Despite the trappings of primitivism _ the gongs, torches and
rituals _ the participants in ``Survivor'' are at summer camp, a
``Lord of the Flies'' summer camp to be sure, but one complete with
relay races and obstacle courses. The house of ``Big Brother'' is
unlike any ever designed; the main lights never turn off; the hot
water is rationed; there are weekly activities including
mask-making, domino mazes and jump-rope contests. While creating
supposedly Darwinian struggles, these settings actually infantilize
their inhabitants: like children, if they are good, they get to
play; if uncooperative, their elementary school friends cast them
off into oblivion. And the hosts of these shows are two of the most
smarmy and coy on television, adults who don't really know how to
talk to children. Big Brother isn't frightening; he's creepily
chummy.
</P>
<P>
   The climax of each show is the banishment of one of its
citizens. But what qualities are being bred for success?
``Survivor'' boasts that many of its participants have wilderness
skills; ``Big Brother'' has its share of more domestically oriented
talents. But it isn't the most skillful who survive. Naked
aggression is condemned, not rewarded. Mega, the first to be voted
off ``Big Brother,'' seemed to relish creating conflict and
demonstrating his superiority. Sense and maturity, as demonstrated
by Gretchen on ``Survivor'' may have made her a threat and
accelerated her banishment. I would wager that Rich, the most
scheming of the Survivors, is doomed not to be one. Aggression must
be hidden behind comradely socializing. ``I love her to death,''
says one islander after voting off a friend. ``This is no
reflection on the type of person she is.'' Residents of the house
often say they are voting off their house mates for their own good,
because it would be better for them to head home.
</P>
<P>
   So it isn't the brutal truth that is shown; it is more like
office politics with an exotic setting and bizarre comrades,
complete with alliances and betrayals, friendships and rivalries
and aggression cloaked by phony good feeling. ``Survivor'' even has
a consulting psychologist, Dr. Gene Ondrusek, who provides the
show's moral on CBS's Web site: ``Research overwhelmingly confirms
that success in the workaday jungle depends more on your
interpersonal skills and ability to get along with people than your
technical competence.'' These shows don't break with their social
surroundings; they incorporate them.
</P>
<P>
   In such a confusing universe, which at once resembles ordinary
life while having nothing whatsoever to do with it, the moments of
real emotion become all the more disturbing; it is as if someone's
mask fell in the midst of a drama. Infantilism and adulthood,
fakery and feeling, public and private swirl together in some eerie
melange. The sensation recalls the queasiness caused by seeing
tapes of President Clinton testifying about his sexual activities,
or of Bill Gates squirmily claiming a poor memory in his testimony
in the Microsoft antitrust trial. These public figures failed to
contain their private selves; in the television shows, private
figures eagerly court the public glance.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that at the heart of these shows is a cultural
confusion about just what the private and public realms are.
Culture is, to a great extent, about the relationship between the
public and the private. But here, all coherence is gone. Public
authority is fake ritual and the voice of Big Brother. Private
feeling is pop psychology and confession. It's all very depressing.
But riveting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
