<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2932 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-MARGARET-CHO-SURVIVOR     08-04 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARGARET-CHO-SURVIVOR-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONING UP ON BACK-STABBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(Eds., spelling Chin-a, in 6th graf, is CQ.) 
(For release Sunday, August 6) 
 By LINDA LEE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Margaret Cho was a virgin. That was why her friends
gathered Wednesday night in her suite at the Paramount Hotel to
initiate her into the world of those who can spell Gervase _ a
universe that does not include contestants on the television series
``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   She needed help, because she was going to appear the next
morning on ``The Early Show'' on CBS to analyze the latest
``Survivor'' episode. She knew nothing about it, not where the
island was (``It's near China?'' she asked), nor any of the players
or rules.
</P>
<P>
   Suite 1526 was fully stocked with viewing aids: Triscuits, Bagel
Chips, salsa, Tostitos, peeled baby carrots, Evian, but no booze.
</P>
<P>
   Cho speaks honestly in her new one-woman film, ``I'm the One
That I Want,'' based on her stage show, about battling her weight
and her overindulgence in alcohol and other mind-altering
substances. In the film, she also explores being a ``fag hag''
(``Thank god for gay men, because if it weren't for gay men, I
wouldn't talk to men at all''), and addresses the question of her
own sexual orientation. (``Am I straight? Am I gay?'' she recalls
wondering in the film. ``Then I realized, I'm just slutty.'')
</P>
<P>
   Friends began arriving and showering her with gifts. Christopher
Schelling, her literary agent (is there a stand-up comic who isn't
writing a book?), offered a bag from Three Dog Bakery for her dog,
home in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Chin-a Panaccione, who shares a Korean ancestry with Cho but has
an Italian father (``So my mother would make kim chee and
lasagna,'' Panaccione said), offered Cho some DVD's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality is so much better,'' Panaccione, who works in
film, said. ``Porn looks really good on DVD. The camera angles are
particularly good. Or `Lost in Space,''' she added.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Matrix,' too!'' Evan Greenberg, a New York University
student, interjected.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation turned to ``Survivor.'' One thing her friends
agreed on: the naked gay guy had to go.
</P>
<P>
   Schelling said flatly, ``Every gay man I know just hates him.''
</P>
<P>
   Guests began free-associating. ``Did you know there's a
`Survivor' cow in front of `The Early Show' near FAO Schwarz?''
Jessie Cohen, an office temp, asked.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Schulman, a publicist on Cho's movie, tried to get the
star back on track. `` `Survivor' is not about surviving,'' he
offered. ``It's about back-stabbing.''
</P>
<P>
   Schelling, who was seated next to Cho on a white Philippe Starck
tall-back bench, which looked about right for King Cole, tried to
fill her in on tactics. (The series will conclude on Aug. 23, with
the voting of the winner of the $1 million purse.) ``At first, it
was the people who were unpopular who got kicked off the island,''
he said. ``But now, they try to figure who is going to win, and
then they vote them off.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk turned to the contests the castaways compete in to win a
phone call home or temporary immunity from being voted off the
island. ``The challenges are like, how long you can hold your
breath under water, things that guys can win,'' Karen Taussig,
Cho's manager, said.
</P>
<P>
   Panaccione then gave away a big secret. ``If you go to the Web
site, and get under the HTML, there's a little red `x' next to
every name but one,'' she said. ``That's the one who gets the
prize.''
</P>
<P>
   Her Deep Throat on this? Entertainment Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard the winner is Gervase,'' Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The program began. Like golf announcers, the assembled guests
whispered asides to Cho as each castaway came on screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard used to be a corporate trainer.'' (Also ``the naked
gay guy.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy _ the old guy _ was a Navy Seal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean is a doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gervase has two kids, but he's not married.'' (Almost true.
Gervase has four children, but he's not married.)
</P>
<P>
   After 15 minutes, Cho made her first observation: ``The thing
about human nature is to distrust people who excel. It's why we
worship mediocrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Heads nodded. So true.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there were commercials to deride. The reaction to a teaser
for ``Autumn in New York,'' a romance with Richard Gere and Winona
Ryder, was unanimous. Eueueuew. One guest, Zekio Dawson, noted that
Ryder was on the cover of Jane magazine. ``There was the cover
line, `Is Your Look Dated?''' he said. ``I wouldn't want to be on a
cover with that on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to ``Survivor,'' a cultural phenomenon that seems to
positively require group viewing. There was universal consternation
when Sue, the truck driver, burst into tears over what she would or
wouldn't do to Kelly, the white-water guide. ``What happened just
now?'' Cho said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could we get a replay on that one?'' someone else asked.
</P>
<P>
   Then Rudy, the Navy Seal, began expounding on Gervase's habit of
fathering children out of wedlock. ``There's abortion,'' Rudy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' Cho announced, ``that's Roe vs. Wade-Rudy.''
</P>
<P>
   More time passed. Gervase shared his prize, a slice of pizza. No
one made fun. Suddenly, Dawson had a revelation: ``You know what?
They all have tattoos.'' He enumerated the tattoos he had seen,
what they were and where they were located.
</P>
<P>
   Back to ``Survivor.'' Sean, the doctor, was on. ``Look at that
six-pack!'' Schulman said, admiring his abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at strangers in bathing suits has to be one of the
primary attractions of the series, especially for those who do not
yet have their fall catalogs from Victoria's Secret. Cho leaped up
and grabbed a bottle of Evian. Soon, the episode was over and _
consternation! _ it was Gervase who was voted off the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the HTML was wrong,'' Panaccione said weakly.
</P>
<P>
   All assembled tried to sum the experience up for Cho, who was
less than 12 hours away from needing a sound bite.
</P>
<P>
   Schelling said, ``This is `Citizen Kane,' and that other show,
`Big Brother,' is . . .''
</P>
<P>
   `` `Melrose Place?''' Cohen offered.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Big Brother' is `No Exit,''' Schelling finished.
</P>
<P>
   Cho wondered, ``Wouldn't you be sick of the people there after
all that time?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'd vote myself off the island,'' Schulman said.
</P>
<P>
   Cho practiced answers to the obvious questions: Who will win?
Would you eat bugs for $1 million? What personal item would you
bring? ``I'd bring an armoire,'' she said. ``Can't leave home
without that.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the series was ``pretty addictive and dramatic,'' at
least judging by the one episode. ``But I don't know if I'd watch
it again,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, when Bryant Gumbel primed his three experts on
the panel to discuss CBS' blockbuster show, Cho jumped right in:
``I hate Rich,'' she said. Welcome Cho. You're now a member of the
tribe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 1719EDT &QL; 
