<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2935 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-TALISMAN-CHIC-$ADV06-     08-04 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALISMAN-CHIC-$ADV06-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALES OF MONEY, GREED AND NAIVETE IN THE GOLD RUSH OF 1999 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 6)  
 By TIMOTHY JACK WARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Our multimillion-dollar dot-com folded, and all I got
was this lousy T-shirt. Everyone at Posh&AMP;Sticks got one, the day
our enigmatic _ let's face it, odd _ name was announced last
January. Now it is a bittersweet souvenir from the rush for the
elusive e-commerce mother lode. Don't get me wrong: I loved the
name and was proud to wear it on my chest. We gave this our best
shot, but we are toast.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of Posh&AMP;Sticks, a home-furnishings Internet business
financed by a group that included Ronald and Leonard Lauder, was
not as splashily public as the recent comeuppance of more deeply
financed sites like Boo.com, which sold clothes until it declared
bankruptcy, or iVillage, whose stock has pancaked. Our experience
is not unique, but it is emblematic of the Great Web Wipeout of
'00, when the capital for e-commerce suddenly dried up and the
dot-com magic carpet ride ended ingloriously.
</P>
<P>
   One day before the scheduled debut in mid-June of our high-style
home furnishings site, we were told that our board had decided to
pull the plug after spending between $14 million and $30 million
(the accepted figures around the office). Since then, the business
has wound down in a painful series of mass layoffs and liquidation
sales. On Monday, we last stragglers packed and moved out of our
offices on far West 26th Street, in what had once seemed the
hippest dot-com building in town.
</P>
<P>
   Plug-pulling doesn't quite capture it. It was more like cutting
the strings that tethered a magnificent kite, moments before its
maiden flight. It seemed like a weird way to toss in the towel. But
perhaps no weirder than the notion of selling furniture, lighting
and accessories, sight unseen, via the Internet, which is what our
business proposed.
</P>
<P>
   Just nine months earlier, I had been startled from my normal
life by a headhunter who read a free &UR; - &LR; lance article I wrote for
The New York Times about buying furnishings on the Web. To research
it I'd spent two months surfing the Web, and that was all it took
to make me a kind of world expert in a brand-new sector of
e-tailing then being promoted as the next great bonanza, a
multibillion-dollar market. By January, I was creative director of
the company, overseeing a creative team that was putting together
the visual design of our Web site, along with the company's logo
and even its gift wrap.
</P>
<P>
   When I arrived in November, our competition, sites like
GoodHome.com, HomePortfolio.com and Furniture.com, were already
well out of the gate. But the group of Israeli software developers
who founded the company along with the Lauder brothers, who run the
Estee Lauder Cos &UR; . &LR; , promised that we would eclipse the competition
with superior technology, which they were building. Our Web site
would be chock-full of bells and whistles like streaming video
interviews with famous designers and 3-D tools that would let
customers take their sofas for a virtual spin before purchase.
</P>
<P>
   But our competitors already do this, some of us whispered. Our
proprietary technology is superior, the software developers, who
all seemed to have ties going back to their service as Israeli
military officers, assured us.
</P>
<P>
   We studied our competitors' sites like entomologists. No detail
was left unpinned, untweezed and unitemized. We recruited a staff
of dozens to create images and text for our site that would rival
the glossy shelter magazines we had formerly worked for. We sent
columnists to Milan, Italy, and Tokyo, photographers to shoots in
lovely estates in Bedford, N.Y., and sleek lofts in Manhattan. We
set up our own state-of-the-art digital photo studio in our offices
in the Starrett-Lehigh Building.
</P>
<P>
   Starrett-Lehigh is a 19-story fill-the-block warehouse, stark
and vast with 15-foot-tall lofts. Around every floor are multipane
glass window walls. (Look closely, and you'll see them as a
backdrop in many fashion magazines and catalogs.) The photographers
who enjoyed this once-cheap-to-rent outpost (hence the ubiquitous
J. Crew backdrop) were mostly chased out by the building
management. The new tenants were style-oriented dot-comers like
Screaming Media, ibeauty and Martha Stewart Omnimedia, who made it
the place to be in Silicon Alley.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The awesome views jazzed my many late nights. I was surrounded
by the glittering Hudson river-scape from the George Washington
Bridge to the Statue of Liberty. One night I realized I could pick
out most of my resume in the skyline: the statuesque Hachette
Filipacchi offices at Broadway and West 50th Street, the New York
Times Building tucked behind the Disney development on 42nd Street,
and the headquarters of Ian Schrager Hotels, aglow like a
lighthouse in Hell's Kitchen every night till exactly 11.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Our warrens of wobbly Ikea desks were almost always gritty to
the touch from drywall dust that wafted in each night from a
renovation project down the hall. Starrett-Lehigh folklore: the
Marthas (as anyone associated with Martha Stewart was known)
planned to drive golf carts through their vast offices. Martha
herself would drive her Range Rover door to door from her new farm
in Katonah and into the building by way of the truck-size freight
elevators.
</P>
<P>
   I found that I could save time, and have fun, by riding my desk
chair like a skateboard to get around in our 7,000-square-foot
space. The young women down at ibeauty rode those shiny chrome
scooters to the bathrooms, which are a block away down the hall.
</P>
<P>
   The two halting elevators functioned like a vertical Main
Street. As you stopped at a floor, you'd find the citizens to-ing
and fro-ing, as if from central casting: hopped-up and pierced-out
programmers, teams of 27-year-old venture capitalists dolled up in
Prada, everyday-is-casual chief executives, impossibly tall and
dour teen-age girls on their first go-sees, lost Urbanfetch
messengers packing Haagen-Dazs pints (the Breakfast of Champions
after start-up all-nighters).
</P>
<P>
   Where did all that adrenalin in Starrett-Lehigh come from? It
was all about the options. We were all thinking options, the stock
option plans you just cannot get out of your mind, no matter how
hard you try. The hard-knock lesson: options mean nothing if you
crash and burn.
</P>
<P>
   What to call yourself is a big deal for dot-coms. You want
something earthshaking, nothing off the rack. In four months our
name changed three times, from C2Buy to IBELLI to Posh&AMP;Sticks. This
decision was overseen by first the entire staff, then by a blue
ribbon panel that included branding experts and board members. The
time, talent and invention devoted to the name could have launched
a thousand ships. Or maybe one Web site.
</P>
<P>
   One night we had a book party in our photo studio for Marco
Pasanella's ``Living in Style Without Losing Your Mind.'' The
author rode his vintage Vespa in and parked it at the middle of the
room. A Tuscan chef roasted a suckling pig, which was displayed
with Old Testament flair, and Glenfiddich provided a steady stream
of old Scotch. It was a wonderful feast, all lighted with votive
candles that seemed to mirror the glittering Hudson below.
</P>
<P>
   There was trouble on the wind. The Nasdaq had recently gone into
its swoon. The date for our Web coming-out had been pushed back.
That night, colleagues mused about feeling like the roast pig. I
kept my game face. When I saw old friends from the shelter
magazines at the party, I invited them to my desk for a sneak
preview of our site on my monitor, to mostly rave reviews.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the ill omens were growing. Our visionary founding chief
executive had been sacked without warning in December, a month
after I was hired. Thereafter our investor-technologists would
surface in New York, jet-lagged after overnight flights from
Israel; they would attend meetings and pick brains, but clearly
they were the ones making the major decisions, not the replacement
chief executive, Vivian Behrens, who had been recruited after 20
successful years with Estee Lauder.
</P>
<P>
   The ad budgets were cut to zero. We'll get the word out with PR,
the technologists said. The site will not work on an Apple, we were
told, as if in an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   I remember the day the long-awaited proprietary 3-D software the
technology developers had promised arrived. It looked to us like
off-the-shelf software and was packed in a box marked California
Closets, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Umpteen variations on our business plan were written. Teams of
managers would return from investor pitch meetings empty-handed,
only to grind out another draft of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Today, no one will say how much money has been flushed down the
e-toilet. We do know that scores of thousands of dollars are owed
to free-lancers. Part of the pain of failure is the knowledge that
my enthusiasm for the gold rush brought many of our creative people
to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever went wrong wasn't unique to Posh&AMP;Sticks. The whole
home-furnishings sector of the Web has been in free fall, as
entrepreneurs face the cold reality of returned merchandise, the
difficulty of ordering and warehousing inventory and the reluctance
of manufacturers to undercut their longstanding retailers. Today
less than 1 percent of all furniture sales are made on the Web, and
whatever growth is possible will come much more slowly than first
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   We should have listened to our hearts, or common sense, the
instincts that tell you that building a brand from the ground up is
a tough sell when your only medium is a slow-mo, glitched-out home
computer.
</P>
<P>
   In the final days, colleagues straggled into the office dressed
either in shorts and flip-flops or in their interview best. It was
a decent gesture from management that we were allowed a staging
area for our job searches. Our Web master has joined the Marthas.
Dale, a store designer, is with Calvin Klein. Anita, our talented
style director, has returned to Elle Decor. When a member of my
team lands safely at a next job, I give a little cheer and a silent
thank you.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A pioneer ancestor of mine, Solomon Hockett, was part of a great
wagon train adventure west on the Oregon Trail. His family's wagon
was loaded improbably _ but perhaps no more so than a Web site
stocked with sofas _ with fruit tree seedlings from the Midwest,
which in time provided the orchards for an entire region.
</P>
<P>
   His exploits made for a great 1950s children's book, ``Tree
Wagon,'' which my children have enjoyed growing up with, and we
take a special delight in eating an Oregon apple or pear from the
market.
</P>
<P>
   When I'm old, I'll be able to tell the story of being a pioneer,
too, of the Great Gold Rush of 1999. I'll edit out the unsavory
parts about money, greed and naivete. But I'll remember the
elevators, the Hudson view and this silly T-shirt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
