<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2937 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0805-COX     08-04 1880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Toot-toot, change the tone
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The morning, after accepting his party's presidential nomination
and pledging to bring a new civility to the country, George W. Bush
and Dick Cheney, with hundreds of Republicans gathered at the
airport to see them off, went to Pittsburgh and began an air and
rail tour of key battleground states. Bush's ``Change the Tone
Tour,'' will take him through Pennsylvania, Ohio, Michigan and
Illinois. Bush said he needled his rival Al Gore in his acceptance
speech, but he denied it was unduly critical of the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   DID SOMEBODY SAY BIG OIL?
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore ended a vacation week in the shadow of rival George W.
Bush and bounded back onto the campaign trail today. In the
unconditional embrace of 3,400 union firefighters in Chicago, Gore
mocked the Republican convention as a special-interests-sponsored
sham. ``This is Day One of the fight for working families,'' he
declared. Gore derided the confetti and fireworks of the GOP
convention, saying they couldn't mask Bush's allegiance to special
interests: ``Behind the flashing video wall is an agenda of rising
gas prices and smog-filled skies that is of Big Oil, by Big Oil,
and for Big Oil.''
</P>
<P>
   BETTER WITH BETTER HALF
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush won't be doing much solo flying before the Nov. 7
election. The campaign decided to have George W. and his wife
travel together this fall, rather than separately to cover more
territory. Laura Bush has never been a particularly public person,
and although she dutifully traveled alone during the primaries, she
preferred to be on her husband's plane. In addition _ and perhaps
more importantly _ the governor seems to function better when she's
with him. Said Mark McKinnon, the campaign's media adviser, ``He's
just happier when she's there. ... We think he's better when she's
there.''
</P>
<P>
   FORD _ LIKE A ROCK
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say Gerald Ford is almost back to normal just three days
after a stroke. They said today he's walking and catching up on the
news. But they still don't know what's causing his tongue to swell.
His doctors say it could be trauma, an infection or a tumor. They
also say Ford will recover fully without needing rehabilitation
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   A FORD IN HIS FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Harold Ford Jr. (D-Tenn.) will be among three keynote
speakers at the Democratic convention the week after next. Ford,
30, the youngest member of Congress said that Al Gore asked him to
speak during prime time on Aug. 15, the second day of the gathering
in Los Angeles. Ford, a two-term congressman from Memphis, was a
member of a Democratic ``truth squad'' in Philadelphia this week.
His father, Harold Ford Sr., previously held the seat for 11 terms
and was Tennessee's first black congressman.
</P>
<P>
   BUT IKE ALWAYS SAID `NUCULER'
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has been known to stumble over words on occasion,
but having that happen during his big speech would not do. So the
script he read from a TelePromtTer screen took special care to help
him through one tricky word: nuclear. The script spelled it:
nuke-lee-er. It appeared to be the only word spelled phonetically
in the rolling script. During the New Hampshire primary campaign,
Bush spoke about the need for ``tackuler'' nuclear weapons instead
of tactical ones.
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTION OVER, JAIL TIME NOT
</P>
<P>
   A Philadelphia judge set a $1 million bail today for a protest
leader who police said instigated property damage during
sometimes-violent demonstrations surrounding the convention. John
Sellers, 33, a leader of the Berkeley, Calif.-based Ruckus Society,
was charged with numerous misdemeanors, including conspiracy,
obstruction of justice and disorderly conduct. Police singled out
as many as six leaders of activist groups, many of them
instrumental in disruptions at last fall's World Trade Organization
meetings in Seattle, and said 371 people have been arrested since
last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   THAT'S THE WAY THE CONVENTION BOUNCES
</P>
<P>
   It's crunch time for the Democrats. George W. Bush's lead over
Al Gore grew to 19 points today in a bipartisan Battleground Poll
of likely voters, 50-31 percent, taken Wednesday and Thursday. He
led by 11 points, 47-36 percent, among registered voters in an NBC
poll taken Thursday night. Bush often fares better in polls of
likely voters because of intensity of support and the voting habits
of Republicans. The Battleground Poll had a 3 percentage point
error margin; the NBC poll an error margin of 4.5 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   INSTANT ANALYSIS TRUE TO FORM
</P>
<P>
   The jury of pundits is still out on the long-term impact of
George W. Bush's acceptance speech, but it was well-received by 500
voters participating in the SpeakOut.com/MSNBC Internet instant
poll, says Democratic polling expert Peter Hart. Republicans
strongly supported the speech, giving Bush a good overall score of
79. Rarely did opinions drop below 75. With Independents, the marks
were mixed. Bush's overall score was 51, reflecting the average of
highs and lows with the group of voters who ultimately will decide
this election. The average score from Democrats was only 37.
</P>
<P>
   PROF SWATS GADFLY IN TENNESSEE
</P>
<P>
   By fewer than 900 votes, Jeff Clark, a Middle Tennessee State
business professor, squeezed a victory from maverick candidate John
Jay Hooker in the Senate Democratic primary. Only about 190,000
people voted in the race, which many thought would fall to the
political gadfly Hooker because of his name recognition: He has
lost elections in the state since the 1960s. Clark faces incumbent
Republican Bill Frist in November.
</P>
<P>
   NEW BUSH TAKES ROOT
</P>
<P>
   George P. Bush brought tears to the eyes of his father and
grandfather as he gave his first nationally televised campaign
speech at the GOP convention. The 24-year-old nephew of George W.
Bush (the son of Florida Gov. Jeb Bush and his Mexican-born mother,
Columba) spoke in English and Spanish about his mixed heritage,
telling the cheering crowd that if his uncle is elected president
he will look out for ``those of us whose faces look different.''
</P>
<P>
   ALWAYS A WAY TO BUY INFLUENCE
</P>
<P>
   When General Motors became the first corporation to voluntarily
stop writing large checks to political parties in 1997, the
automaker's executives sent a powerful message that they were
disgusted by the political culture of cash and influence. Since
then, GM has stuck to its pledge to forswear soft money. But all
this week, GM demonstrated that it has found other ways to curry
favor. GM provided 400 Cadillacs, sport utility vehicles and
minivans for use by convention organizers, part of a package of
``in-kind contributions'' that the host committee here estimated
was worth $1 million. And GM sponsored two lunch receptions at
different downtown locales.
</P>
<P>
   A GRAND OLD PARTY, LITERALLY
</P>
<P>
   After five days of lavish fund-raisers and corporate-sponsored
entertainment during the Republican convention, some participants
expressed concern that the grand scale of the partying may have
hurt the GOP's image. Sen. Chuck Hagel of Nebraska, a reform-minded
lawmaker who introduced Sen. John McCain of Arizona at the podium
on Tuesday, decried what he called ``these gluttonous parties, this
incredible show that we put on that almost forces everyone to
gobble as much shrimp and lobster as you can possibly inhale.''
</P>
<P>
   PART OF THE PARTY NOW
</P>
<P>
   The harsh message to homosexuals at the 1992 GOP convention was
find another party. Unwelcomed, unwanted, and enraged over Pat
Buchanan's vitriolic speech in Houston, a gay Republican
organization refused to endorse President Bush for re-election.
Now, however, the Log Cabin Republicans say Bush's son, George W.,
has lived up to his commitments: no prime-time gay-bashing from the
podium in Philadephia, modified anti-gay language in the party
platform, and a speaking slot at the convention to an openly
homosexual congressman, Rep. Jim Kolbe of Arizona .
</P>
<P>
   INCLUDE HER OUT, TOO
</P>
<P>
   During the roll call of states, New York Gov. George Pataki got
one of the lustiest cheers of the night when he worked in a dig
while casting his state's votes. He said that when Dick Cheney told
the crowd a night earlier that it was time for them to go, ``He
meant not just Bill Clinton and Al Gore, but Bill Clinton and Al
Gore and Hillary Rodham Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   DON'T PULL THAT STUFF IN MY TOWN
</P>
<P>
   Across the country in Los Angeles, the mayor of the city about
to host the Democratic confab broke into an angry tirade when a
reporter asked him about charges from community activists that his
convention plans ignored those living in poor neighborhoods near
the Staples Center convention site. ``For them to suggest that we
care more about people in Brentwood or Bel Air is a damn, damn
lie,'' Richard Riordan, a Republican, shouted, referring to two of
the city's more exclusive districts.
</P>
<P>
   RON JR. MOSTLY TUNES OUT
</P>
<P>
   The Republican convention tribute to his father wasn't exactly
required viewing for Ron Reagan Jr. ``I was driving to the market
and flipped on NPR and heard my father's voice coming out of the
radio,'' said Reagan, a Seattle resident who was in Philadelphia
briefly to moderate a panel discussion. He knew the tribute was
coming up, but didn't watch it on TV. ``It hasn't been the most
exciting convention,'' he said. ``I can be forgiven for going to
the market. The frozen food section is more exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   OUT OF SITE, OUT OF MIND?
</P>
<P>
   The GOP convention was wired to the hilt, but a new study
suggests that candidates for Congress still live in an offline
world. The survey, by the University of Pennsylvania's
Netelection.org project, found that 46 percent of congressional
candidates don't have a presence on the Internet. Senate candidates
fared better than their House counterparts, with 80 percent
maintaining campaign sites. House candidates logged in at 51
percent.
</P>
<P>
   AND ALL WE GOT WAS THIS LOUSY T-SHIRT
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian Institution dispatched two political junk
collectors to the Republican convention of political junkies. The
mission of Harry Rubenstein and Larry Bird, curators at the
Smithsonian's National Museum of American History in Washington,
was to procure memorabilia to add to the 90,000 objects already in
the museum's political history collection. Funny hat, catchy
button, screaming poster? You bet. Harry and Larry snagged them.
They left for home loaded with stuff.
</P>
<P>
   EVEN A KID KNOWS IT'S THE ECONOMY, STUPID
</P>
<P>
   Neil Bush, another son of the former president, recalled during
the convention how, four years ago, when his son Pierce was 10, he
asked him to list the greatest presidents.'' Pierce named George
Washington, Abraham Lincoln and Ronald Reagan. When Neil Bush
reminded the boy that he had left his own grandfather off the list,
the youngster looked up at him and said, ``Dad, what about the
economy?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
