<HEADER>
A2941 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MOMS-IN-TOUCH0805-COX     08-04 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOMS-IN-TOUCH0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moms believe in the power of prayer
 &HT;    By Khalid Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Just because school prayer has been deep-sixed by
the United States Supreme Court doesn't mean that parents can't
offer up a supplication or two.
</P>
<P>
   Moms in Touch International (MITI) is a group of mothers who
believe that prayer makes a difference. Individual chapters
consisting of of two or more moms meet once a week to pray for
their children and the schools they attend. Members believe that
prayer is a way to surround children with a spiritual presence even
while they're at school.
</P>
<P>
   LaVonna Beerf, Miami Valley coordinator for MITI, says the
campaign began in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``This organization started in 1985 when a mother with a burden
to pray for her two teen-age sons entering school sought out other
moms,'' Beerf said. ``Clearly the Bible tells us there is power in
numbers in our prayers, so through that burden Moms in Touch was
born. The movement is booming around the country and
internationally as well.''
</P>
<P>
   At their weekly, one-hour sessions, the mothers engage in
conversational prayer _ also called praying in one accord _
focusing their thoughts on their children, teachers, the school and
its administrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first joined, my four friends and I agreed to attended
on the condition that we wouldn't be asked to pray out loud,''
Beerf recalled. ``But when we went, the Lord just moved on all of
us. It was never a problem from day one.''
</P>
<P>
   MITI is nondenominational. Meetings are held one hour a week at
members' homes. It's not a social hour so no refreshments are
served and groups are encouraged to start and finish on time.
Beerf's group prays for Beavercreek High School but there are MITI
chapters involving mothers of students at Alter, Fairmont, Dayton
Christian High School and Centerville High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an unsafe pickup procedure at Beavercreek High
School. The doors were open, kids came out and just ran through the
parking lot and jumped in any car,'' Beerf said. ``We prayed about
that and the next year there was a brand-new parking lot with new
procedures and ID tags. You would be amazed at some of the things
God has done through this format.''
</P>
<P>
   MITI is neither evangelical nor political. Networking is done
mostly through word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was having a conversation with a friend about the challenges
kids encounter in the high schools today and the kind of support
they need,'' said Oakwood mother Susan Johnston. ``She suggested I
start a Moms in Touch group.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston had never heard of the organization so she did some
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``I received the booklet that is given to each new member and I
read the background material. That's how I first became interested
in getting the program started in this community.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston was quick to note that although her kids don't attend
Dayton public schools, that school system is never far from their
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We include the Dayton Public Schools in our prayers every
week,'' she said. ``One of our goals is to see groups evolve in
those schools that can fulfill the same goals that we have in our
community. We can see the need there is enormous and we are
interested in doing everything we can without being intrusive. To
increase the growth of groups in that area, we will come and talk
about what we do and help groups get started.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
