<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2943 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-ROCK-FAN-FAMILIES-$AD     08-04 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-FAN-FAMILIES-$ADV06-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES THAT ROCK TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 6)  
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a glowing mid-July evening on the floor of Giants Stadium in
New Jersey, Derek Pedersen, 11, was settling in to enjoy his first
rock concert. Waiting for the show to start, he leaned shyly on the
shoulder of his mother, Leslie Pedersen, 43. But later, as the Dave
Matthews Band took the stage and built to a crescendo of rhythmic
guitar and violin, he climbed aboard his 21-year-old sister's
shoulders, threw his arms into the air and swayed rhapsodically
with the rest of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   A few rows back, Emily and Glenn Blair, an obstetrician and
podiatrist, from Easton, Conn., were enjoying a similar musical
communion with their daughters, Madeline, 8, and Hillary, 15.
Although dressed as country club stalwarts _ he with linen shorts
and loafers, she with pearls _ they are rock concert regulars. This
was the third Dave Matthews concert the family had attended.
Enjoying the jazzy, soulful improvisations that have made the band
a favorite among today's college undergraduates is a bonding
activity, the Blairs say. ``On the way home in the car, we discuss
our favorite guitar riffs,'' Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   The rock concert, once a raucous and often drug-filled rite of
initiation into American adolescence, is slowly becoming a family
affair. Parents of teen-agers and younger children _ ones who, in
their day, treasured concerts as escapes from the parental clutches
_ now want to share the experience with their own offspring. It is
increasingly easier to do this as the musical tastes of the
generations meld _ the 40-plus group of Americans now buy more rock
albums than those 15 to 24 _ and as concerts have been tamed by
commercial sponsors to be as clean as Broadway musicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely see that there are two generations that come to
see our shows,'' said Paul Tollett, of Golden Voice, a leading West
Coast concert promoter of acts like Rage Against the Machine and
the Red Hot Chili Peppers. ``Parents nowadays understand music that
their kids like, whereas parents 20 years ago would not have gotten
the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Sting, the singer-songwriter, who has been on and off the
touring circuit since 1976, says he has watched his audience grow
older with him, and expand to the next generation. ``I look out and
I see the baby boomers who have been with us since the '70s, and
now they have their kids,'' he said. ``It is very
multigenerational.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own home, he added, he has watched his six children, ages
2 to 24, discover music of previous decades on their own. His
9-year-old daughter, Coco Sumner, who is a budding guitarist, likes
to pick out tunes from Jimi Hendrix's ``Voodoo Child'' album. ``The
idea that music should separate the generations is a new one,''
Sting said. ``Historically, it used to bring everyone together.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all bands have a sound that is so convivial or
that makes for family togetherness. Not a lot of moms and dads will
groove this summer to Eminem or the latest edition of Ozzfest, with
its hard-rock headbangers. The acts that the baby boomers grew up
with are the ones that are pulling in the largest mixed crowds.
This year, five of the top 10 largest grossing concert tours were
long-in-the-tooth acts like Bruce Springstein, Tina Turner and
Crosby, Stills &AMP; Nash, according to Pollstar, a concert industry
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Kids sometimes attend such outings basically at the behest of
parents, who hope to pass on their own musical tastes. But in just
as many cases. children have been exposed to these favorites on car
trips or home stereos and have acquired a love of the artists all
their own.
</P>
<P>
   At a Santana concert at Jones Beach last week, two generations
of the Ramirez family gathered in the parking lot drinking beers
and blasting ``Supernatural,'' the artist's 1999 smash hit album,
from their van's stereo. Pepe Ramirez, 49, who recalls seeing
Carlos Santana at the Filmore East in 1969, said he and his
brothers played the music at all kinds of family gatherings,
beginning when the children were young.
</P>
<P>
   To prove the point, his niece Laura Benito, 23, hummed hit tunes
off the Abraxas album from 1970. ``This is the first time we've all
been to a concert together,'' said her brother, Antonio Benito Jr.,
``but we grew up listening to this music &UR; , &LR;  and I knew it was going
to be inevitable that this would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The concert industry does not keep records of fans' ages: It is
a business dominated by independent-minded impresarios, who judge
an act's popularity by the gut. Many performers, promoters and
recording executives say they have personally observed that
concerts become more multigenerational every year.
</P>
<P>
   This is not just classic rock nostalgia fueling the graying of
the scene. Although boomers do have a soft spot for the artists of
their youth, many keep current with music through VH-1 and radio,
and they are responsible, in part, for the success of younger
performers like Shania Twain, Macy Gray and Faith Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest-growing category of customers for rock albums is
those 45 and older, according to the Recording Industry Association
of America. This middle-aged group bought 24.7 percent of all CDs
last year, more than double the 11.1 percent they purchased in
1990. Meanwhile, young people from 15 to 24, widely perceived as
the big pop industry drivers, bought a significantly smaller share
of recordings than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Walsh, the vice president of marketing for the recording
association, attributed the shift partly to the Internet, which
allows busy working parents to shop from their desks. The fact that
a larger percentage of the general population is over 40 today than
a decade ago also affects the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who recall how their love of Janis Joplin or Jimi
Hendrix defiantly marked their differences from their own parents
now want to share music with their children, hoping it will bridge
the generation gap. At a Dixie Chicks concert last month at Radio
City Music Hall, none of the three members of the Perrucci family
there could remember whether it was Mary Perrucci, 46, or her
daughter Christine, 18, who first brought home ``Wide Open
Spaces,'' the band's platinum-selling 1998 album. But both parents
and daughter listen to the music at home, and Mary Perrucci said it
brings them closer. ``It gives us something fun to do together,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that parents see concerts as venues for family fun,
sometimes even for very young children, also, of course, speaks
much about the transformation of concerts themselves. ``Concerts
don't have the same rebellious nature,'' said Gary Bongiovanni, the
editor of Pollstar, who has been following the industry for many
years. ``It is a more conservative atmosphere these days. It's not
just that there are less drugs _ I mean, no one smokes
cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bongiovanni also said that open concert seating, which was
common two decades ago and added to the anarchic nature of events,
has been replaced almost entirely with reserved seating. ``Before,
it was much more social,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Steen, director of marketing in the Northeast for
Delsner/Slater, the nation's largest concert promoter, says rock
concerts have become so commercialized that some now resemble Las
Vegas floor shows. ``The production of the shows, the lighting, the
sound, the amount of extras and dancers is greater than 10 years
ago,'' he said. ``There is more emphasis on preshow activity. There
is also a different level of expectations, especially from the
upper-scale demo. They want VIP areas and fancy boxes and corporate
suites.''
</P>
<P>
   Most rock concerts may no longer be bacchanalias, but they are
not Disneyland _ not yet. There can be drugs in the audience, or
explicit sexuality from the stage, but parents seem to take these
in stride. At the Dave Matthews Band concert at the Meadowlands, a
marijuana haze perfumed the air almost as soon as the sun went
down. Pedersen said 11-year-old Derek did not really notice.
``Besides, my feeling is that kids are going to be exposed to it
anyway,'' she said. ``I am really strict, and I'd rather be around
to explain what is happening if they have questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the lewd antics and graphic lyrics that bothered
previous generations of parents slide more easily off this
generation's back. At the Dixie Chicks concert, Clare Ryan, 33, and
her husband, Kevin, 34, brought their three sons _ John, 5, Liam,
6{, and Danny, 9 _ each of whom had a Norman Rockwell crew cut and
a clean-scrubbed face. Ryan said the kids loved the music but had
questions about a song called ``Goodbye Earl,'' about an abused
wife who plots to kill her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked why Earl has to die,'' Ryan said. ``And I explained
that if you grow up and hit your wife, you might deserve to get
killed. And they accept that.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most mysterious part of the intergenerational
phenomenon is why teen-agers seem to accept their parents' company
at rock shows so easily. Many used the word ``cool'' to explain
their feelings about their parents' presence at the kind of event
once framed as a pageant of youth rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   One possible explanation: With the average price of concert
tickets skyrocketing _ up 30 percent in the last year, to $43.63,
according to Pollstar _ bringing Mom and Dad means there is always
someone ready with a Visa card.
</P>
<P>
   There are other conveniences, as well. Zoe Reid, 18, and two
teen-age friends didn't seem to mind that Zoe's father, Gerald
Reid, 51, was sitting next to them at the Dave Mathews concert and
passing the time with a hand-held computer. ``What do you think
about Gerald being here?'' Zoe asked her friends. ``He's cool,''
one replied. ``And besides, now we have a ride home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-IRONY-RECONSIDERED-2T     08-04 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRONY-RECONSIDERED-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO KIDDING: DOES IRONY ILLUMINATE OR CORRUPT? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Ideas) 
 By CHARLES McGRATH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One person who was glad when ``Seinfeld'' ended was Jedediah
Purdy. He is also, no doubt, eagerly awaiting Bart Simpson's
retirement. Purdy is the home-schooled West Virginia wunderkind who
last year, at the age of 25, published ``For Common Things,'' an
earnest, impassioned homily that urged us to rediscover civic
virtue, both in government and in our private lives, and that
blamed for our current malaise nothing less than irony itself.
</P>
<P>
   Irony, he wrote, is a corrosive, world-weary habit of mind, ``a
quiet refusal to believe in the depth of relationships, the
sincerity of motivation, or the truth of speech _ especially
earnest speech.'' He singled out Jerry Seinfeld, ``irony
incarnate,'' as a symbol of all that is wrong with our culture, but
he could have just as easily chosen Bart or, for that matter, Dave
Eggers.
</P>
<P>
   Eggers, of course, is the public-schooled Illinois wunderkind
who this year, at the age of 29, published ``A Heartbreaking Work
of Staggering Genius,'' a memoir about the death of his mother and
father, eight years before, and about how he became, in effect, the
single parent of his 8-year-old brother.
</P>
<P>
   From its title to its cheeky acknowledgments (``The author
wishes first and foremost to acknowledge his friends at NASA and
the United States Marine Corps''), to its own reader's guide to the
book's themes and metaphors, to the very last page, which is a
parody of Molly Bloom's soliloquy, ``AHWSG'' is suffused with
jokeyness and self-awareness _ with a refusal to take its own
enterprise seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this is also a deeply affecting work, one that makes a
powerful, if unconventional, case for that most Purdyian of values,
family togetherness; and it succeeds not in spite of its antics _
all the authorial winking and nudging _ but to a large degree
because of them. The ultimate irony, you could say, is that Eggers'
wise-guy approach allows him to invest his book with insight and
genuine feeling.
</P>
<P>
   So is irony a bad thing or a good thing? It depends, in part, on
what you mean by ``irony,'' which has become a critical term of
nearly infinite elasticity. We use it all the time (especially in
the adverbial form) to refer to strange or untoward coincidence, as
in ``Ironically, just hours after rescuing the cat from a tree,
Jedediah ran over it by mistake in the pickup.''
</P>
<P>
   Or we use it, as counseled by The New York Times Manual of Style
and Usage, among other authorities, chiefly to indicate sarcasm, as
in: ``Dave looked down at the mangled, lifeless feline. `Nice cat,'
he said ironically.'' (As the Times manual wisely points out, if
the sarcasm is effective, the adverb is often unnecessary.)
</P>
<P>
   Etymologically, ``irony'' comes from the Greek word for
``dissembling,'' and the ancient Greeks used it in reference to
that abiding preoccupation of theirs, the gap between appearance
and reality, or between truth and belief. What interested them most
was dramatic irony, which is what occurs when the reader or the
audience knows something that a character doesn't (Oedipus was the
favorite example); far from being funny, this was for the Greeks
the stuff of tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction between audience and character was also
essential for the critic Northrop Frye, who in his magisterial
``Anatomy of Criticism'' (1957) included irony in his taxonomy of
essential narrative modes: Irony for Frye is what happens when the
character is in some way inferior to the reader, who then looks
down on the work, so to speak, and sees the poor character
embroiled in scenes of bondage, frustration or absurdity. (The
great ironic author in this sense is Kafka.)
</P>
<P>
   Frye comes closer to our everyday understanding of the term in
his discussion of the ironic persona, which is essentially a kind
of literary straight man; the ironist pretends to be ignorant of
everything, Frye says, even of his own irony. The classic example
here is the Swift of ``A Modest Proposal,'' who says one thing and
depends on his audience to conclude the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Irony in this sense is a rhetorical strategy for suggesting
things you don't want to come right out and say directly, and it's
a strategy of particular use in oppressive or censorious
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Irony is what keeps Hamlet going, for example _ he's the Dave
Eggers of medieval Denmark. And irony was for a time the preferred
(and often necessary) method of Eastern European writers like
Vaclav Havel and Milan Kundera. This is the kind of irony that was
in the mind of the Hollywood movie mogul who said, ``Irony is what
goes over the heads of the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   But irony in Purdy's sense is something different _ less a way
of conveying hidden meaning than of undermining meaning altogether.
Irony for him is an attitude _ a bad attitude.
</P>
<P>
   And Purdy is right in suggesting that this particular kind of
attitude has its roots in television and in the political
disillusionment of the 1960s. (Though he doesn't say so, a telling
early example of the Purdy-Eggers split manifested itself during
the 1969 trial of the Chicago Eight. The Jedediahs _ Tom Hayden and
Rennie Davis _ wanted a serious debate on the nature of civil
disobedience; the Daves _ Abbie Hoffman and Jerry Rubin _ wanted to
make fun of the entire proceeding.)
</P>
<P>
   Irony in this latter-day incarnation consists largely of
indicating that you are in fact being ironic. It's a way of putting
invisible quotation marks around speech or action, the way Willis,
the terminally ironic protagonist of David Gates' novel ``Preston
Falls,'' does. (Whenever he mentions his office ``colleagues,'' for
example, he's careful to precede the word with a meaningful
half-beat of hesitation.)
</P>
<P>
   This kind of irony also relies heavily on repetition and
allusion. The first time Chevy Chase fell down, on the original
``Saturday Night Live,'' it was slapstick; every week thereafter it
was ironic.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same is true of Dave Letterman's various shticks; as
Purdy suggests, the joke is at the expense of some hypothetical
audience _ rubes and squares, or maybe people just awakened from a
coma _ that could possibly take late-night television seriously or
expect anything new from it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What troubles Purdy about this kind of irony is that in its
extreme forms it can lead to alienation and indifference; it can
become a substitute for action, and even for thought, and amounts
to a passive acceptance of things as they are. In the view of some
of his critics, though, what's troubling about Purdy's prescription
is that the society he envisions is apparently one that makes very
little room for humor _ for laughing at those things that cannot be
changed.
</P>
<P>
   And earnestness, in its extreme form, requires that language
itself be purified, scrubbed of all its puns and double-entendres
and hackneyed associations _ until, for example, you could use the
phrase ``a heartbreaking work of staggering genius'' with a
straight face.
</P>
<P>
   In Frye's view, irony is a late and somewhat degenerate form.
(It comes after, and is inferior to, myth, romance and both high
and low realism.) But Frye's scheme is also a circular one, in
which irony sometimes comes around to myth again. Clowns, he says,
are just sacrificial gods in another guise. And perhaps this is
where we are headed: to an irony of cosmic, mythic proportion.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, we now have Jedediahs and Daves all around us _
in art, in business, even in politics: Anselm Kiefer and Jeff
Koons; Bill Gates and Paul Allen; Al Gore and George W. Bush. One
set of these prophets is telling us to please get serious; the
other to lighten up, dude. They would never admit it, but they
probably need each other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
