<HEADER>
A2947 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-THEATER-ISABEL-LADN &LR;      08-04 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-ISABEL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEXPECTEDLY, UNCONDITIONAL LOVE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Underneath the carnivalistic send-up of the fertility industry
that dominates Lisa Loomer's play ``Expecting Isabel'' is a sweet
and very knowing story about a husband and wife who simply want to
have a child.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute. I think I may have that backward. Take 2.
</P>
<P>
   Behind a husband and wife's desperate quest to become parents,
Lisa Loomer's play ``Expecting Isabel'' is a keen satire on the
fertility industry and the extreme lengths to which some people
will go to add the words ``mommy'' and ``daddy'' to their resumes.
</P>
<P>
   Nope, that doesn't sound right either.
</P>
<P>
   Satire? Drama? Burlesque? ``Isabel'' doesn't categorize easily.
It often feels like a couple of different plays with conflicting
agendas. Douglas Wager's production at the Mark Taper Forum is very
entertaining yet very puzzling. Are we expected to laugh until it
hurts or ache until we laugh? Both, I suspect. Such is this play.
And such _ Loomer contends _ is parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   That's Nick and Miranda Saracini's quest despite a lot of doubt
from both parties. They're a New York couple in their late 30s _
him a sculptor, her a greeting card writer _ middle class and very
much in love. Their Candide-esque parenting quest leads them
through the labyrinth of infertility treatment, support groups,
therapy and adoption efforts. What should be easy isn't, causing
Miranda's already fragile sense of self to crack. The action takes
place under a blue-gray cut-out New York skyline dotted with
fluorescence and a couple of product placement billboards and
designed by John Arnone.
</P>
<P>
   That Loomer can identify her targets and hit bull's-eyes as
skillfully as she makes us understand her characters is no mean
feat. But in this play, the task is unquestionably a balancing act
since characters are either satiric or real, rarely both. So often,
there seems to be no connection between Nick and Miranda and the
barrage of doctors, counselors, therapists and family members they
encounter. If our heroes are relatively normal people dumped into
extraordinary circumstances, everyone else is from Planet Oddball.
Or Planet Spoof.
</P>
<P>
   Take actor Fred Applegate, one of the six ensemble members who
collectively play something like 30 parts. Taking on Nick's stoic
father, New York's best fertility doctor, a gypsy cab driver and a
participant in a couple of support groups, Applegate is one of
these actors who can make you laugh just by walking on stage but
eventually we're laughing for no real reason. OK, what goofy
character is he this time? Ah, right, the quirky marriage
counselor. Got it.
</P>
<P>
   So it's a little unsettling when a character we've come to
accept as borderline wacky gets to deliver a rational speech, as
Applegate's fertility doc does: ``I view infertility as a human
disorder, just like any other. Why shouldn't we do whatever we can
to correct it?'' Less abrupt is a wonderful turn by Eileen Galindo
as a dignified Puerto Rican woman considering giving up her unborn
child for adoption. It's one of the few instances in this
production where an actor is allowed to play her role almost
completely straight, and Galindo nails it.
</P>
<P>
   So does Julie White, who brings a hint of Lucille Ball to
Miranda. The character starts the play with a monologue that verges
on stand-up patter, fires off most of the play's funny lines, wades
through farce and ultimately has to steer her way around a
breakdown. It's a tricky role, but White doesn't miss a turn, and
she never loses the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Also charismatic in a less well-written role, is Anthony
Crivello's Nick. Nick's a nice guy, an optimist who happens to come
from a loopy _ and somewhat cliched Italian family. He's the
grounded yin to Miranda's hormonal yang, and we're expected to like
him as well. Like White, Crivello's very good with the funny stuff.
</P>
<P>
   And the funny stuff is plentiful, even if director Wager doesn't
always know when to pull back. The temptation is understandable. By
taking on the parenting obsession and setting the action in New
York, Loomer aims for all the easy targets, and, yes, even at a few
that are less obvious. She's working with a great topic, one with
built-in recognition. After all, the play ends with the words ``Oh
my God'' _ a line that any parent _ current or hopeful _ will
recognize.  &QL; 
--- &QL; 
What: ``Expecting Isabel.'' &QL; 
Where: Mark Taper Forum, 135 N. Grand Ave., Los Angeles. &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Tuesday through Saturday, 2:30 p.m. Saturday and
Sunday, 7:30 p.m. Sunday; through Aug. 27. &QL; 
Tickets: $29-$42. Call (213) 628-2772. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
