<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2953 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CBOT-TRADE-$ADV06-ART     08-04 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CBOT-TRADE-$ADV06-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS ABOUT THE FUTURE IN THE CHICAGO BOARD OF TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 6)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients and a graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ When the Chicago Board of Trade opened for trading at
9:30 a.m., Earle Combs IV, known as Chip, was doing what he loves
to do _ jostling for position in the soybean pit with his arms
raised high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sell 200 at a half! Sell 200 at a half!'' he shouted into a
crowd of burly traders, as he tried to sell 200 soybean meal
contracts at $156.50. ``Sell 200 at a half!''
</P>
<P>
   Casting a glance to the left, he spotted a buyer in the crowd, a
man in his 40s wearing a trading jacket decorated with roulette
wheels. Their eyes met, and a nod from Combs completed the sale.
</P>
<P>
   The trade was made virtually the same way that Combs' father,
grandfather and great-grandfather would have been done it _ by two
men winking and nodding across a frenzied trading pit, then
recording the sale on index-sized trading cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it's been done here for more than 150 years,''
said Combs, 41.
</P>
<P>
   These days, however, more efficient and accurate computerized
trading is threatening to wipe out Chicago's 19th-century trading
pits, just as it did in London last year. Some experts say, the
demise of the ``open outcry'' method of trading _ the shouting and
flashing of hand signals into a trading pit _ might doom the
exchange itself.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a century and a half of dominating the sale of
commodities, beginning with corn and soybeans, and expanding to
include products like futures on Treasury bond prices, the Chicago
Board of Trade, the nation's oldest derivatives exchange, can no
longer lay claim to also being the world's largest. That honor
belongs to Eurex, a fast-growing fully electronic market in Germany
that was created only two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Board of Trade remains a force in the United States
futures market, industry experts say the exchange's reluctance to
adopt computer technology and its stubborn defense of face-to-face
pit trading may be its undoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless they adapt in the next 18 months, it's over,'' said
Richard L. Sandor, who helped introduce financial futures at the
board in the 1970s. ``This is the endgame; this is not the opening
or middle game. They have to get going.''
</P>
<P>
   New rivals are moving quickly to introduce their own electronic
trading systems. Merrill Lynch and Goldman Sachs are part of a
group of Wall Street firms that are planning to go head-to-head
with the Board of Trade by creating computerized systems that they
say will sharply reduce trading costs. Independently, Cantor
Fitzgerald, the huge bond-dealing firm, also wants to grab a share
of the electronic futures market.
</P>
<P>
   The rivals' chief target is financial futures, a
multibillion-dollar marketplace where investors buy and sell
futures to hedge against a shift in the value of stocks, bonds and
currencies. Industry experts say screen-based trading is more
efficient and can reduce or eliminate the need for a trading floor.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Chicago Board of Trade, which opened a new
60,000-square-foot trading floor three years ago, is facing its
biggest challenge. And because control of the exchange rests
largely with a group of agricultural traders who favor the
auction-like style of open-outcry trading, exchange leaders have
had to confront some difficult choices.
</P>
<P>
   If the exchange adopts a fully electronic trading system _ and
it is inching in that direction, offering experimental computer
trading and starting a joint venture with Eurex _ members fear that
it could doom the open-outcry system, eliminating the jobs of
thousands of people who have staked their careers on face-to-face
buying and selling.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Board of Trade insists on continuing to do most of
its business through pit trading, the exchange could be outflanked
by a fledgling electronic rival in the United States futures
market.
</P>
<P>
   Something similar happened in Europe in 1998, after the Eurex
electronic trading system in Germany went head-to-head with LIFFE,
the London financial futures exchange, which operated with a giant
trading floor. The results: business dried up for LIFFE, which just
a few years ago was Europe's biggest futures exchange, and it was
forced to abandon its trading pits in favor of computer trading.
</P>
<P>
   In France, Matif, the derivatives exchange that is a unit of the
Paris bourse, tried to offer both electronic and open-outcry
trading in April 1998. Two months later, most trading migrated to
computers and the trading floor was shuttered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Floor trading is dead,'' says Benn Steil, a senior fellow at
the Council on Foreign Relations. ``It's not going to be pretty,
but it's going to happen in a short, sharp shock. That's what
happened in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways echoing Matif's approach, the Board of Trade would
also like to offer both types of trading. The Board plans to split
itself in two: one company offering traditional floor trading and a
competing one devoted to electronic trading. The exact framework of
such a split is unclear, however, and will require a vote of the
membership.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange has also vowed to make its operations more
efficient, by moving orders into the pits via computers, rather
than by using legions of clerks and ``runners'' who have long
crowded the exchange floor.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, the floor operates essentially as it did a
century ago. Clerks and runners take orders by phone, dash to
deliver them to traders in the 1,200-square-foot octagonal pits,
return with messages to the brokerage stations. The floor is
littered with paper: orders, erroneous trade tickets, lunch orders.
</P>
<P>
   It is as inefficient as it is colorful. There are more clerks
than traders; many sit around reading papers and gossiping during
trading lulls.
</P>
<P>
   When a trader sells, he might catch an eye, a nod, a tap from
someone agreeing to buy. They record each other's badge acronym and
the size of the trade. But there are frequent mistakes. Every
morning, traders gather in a lobby just off the floor to check
``out trades'' _ transactions that did not match up the previous
day.
</P>
<P>
   The financial trading floor, where futures on interest rates are
traded, is more automated. But no derivatives exchange in the
United States is as paper-heavy as the Chicago Board of Trade, and
none have been as late to the game with technology.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of electronic trading say it ends the need for a
trading floor and all that it requires: clerks, runners, security
officers booths and so on. An electronic system, they note, simply
posts and matches all prices and automatically clears and
distributes the information.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the board's delay in implementing technology is the
membership's longstanding reluctance to change the floor, or to
alter an environment and a trading style that has worked for
generations.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Giving up the old way will not be easy for traders, many of whom
are the second, third or even fourth generation of their family in
the pits. Chip Combs' family, for example, is in its third century
of working at the Board of Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Combs' great-grandfather, Earle M. Combs, bought a membership in
1898, when the Board of Trade was largely a marketplace for farmers
to sell their corn and soybeans. His grandfather, the second Earle,
worked through the Great Depression. And his father, Earle III, was
a soybean trader for 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other people here, Chip Combs and his father say they
never intended to work the floor. It just sort of happened. Earle
Combs III, now 70 and retired, says he first tried to be a
photographer. But when his father's partner died in 1952, he came
to the floor and immediately fell in love with the business.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived, Morse code was used to relay trades, grain
prices were still listed on a chalk board and the exchange was
largely a gentlemen's club, a place where members would enjoy a
cigar on the edge of a pit after completing a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Combs and his younger brother Rick followed their father to
the floor. Rick didn't stay long, though. He left to become a
salesman after a man for whom he was working committed suicide
during a nasty market downturn. Chip, after briefly considering
working as a banker, was eventually bitten by the trading bug and
had a more auspicious start.
</P>
<P>
   He was, after all, Earle IV, the nicknamed ``chip'' off the old
block. And while he says he felt no pressure to come to the Board,
he grew up surrounded by the lore of the industry. As a boy, he saw
images of the Board everywhere. At home, his father kept a large
piece of marble that once rested inside the foyer of the old Board
of Trade building, which was demolished in the 1920s. Later,
vacations were spent at a log cabin in Wisconsin that his father
had built in the shape of a trading pit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on, I'd come down with a big trading jacket with sleeves
down to the floor and my father would put trading cards in my
pocket,'' he recalled. ``Standing by the pit, he seemed to know
everyone in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   When Chip Combs started trading in the pits, colleagues joked
that he would be a natural. It was all in the genes, they said. He
recalled someone saying: ``Oh, you're Earle Combs' son. All you
have to do is stand next to him in the pit. If he goes this way,
you go that way.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last 16 years, he has made a good living on the floor.
He commutes each day from Barrington, Ill., about 40 miles
northwest of Chicago, where he lives with his wife, Karla, and four
children. He gets to the office at 7 each day. Between 9:30 a.m.
and 1:15 p.m., he trades in the soybean meal pit, speculating on
futures in the way that a day trader speculates in the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   His edge, he says, is being able to read the market by knowing
the pit: the faces, gestures, positions and idiosyncrasies of
people on the trading floor.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, he commuted by train with his father, and they
swapped trading stories. But now that his father is retired, he
comes in alone, sometimes pondering whether there will still be a
trading floor when his children come of age.
</P>
<P>
   On the wall in his office is a portrait of Chip with his father
and his 7-year-old son Marty, actually Earle Martin Combs V, now
14. Marty and his brother Matthew have both made the ritual trip to
the floor in long-sleeved trading jackets. Their father and
grandfather have already offered lessons in how to fill out a
trading ticket.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Chip is concerned about the edge he would lose if
the floor closed; if it did, he would probably have to move to the
computer. He loves the energy of the floor, the emotion and the
culture. He loves being part of a daily drama in which billions of
dollars are funneled through a group of frenzied traders. He loves
the rush of making a great trade.
</P>
<P>
   The pit is filled with personality and families. Most of the
agricultural pits are populated by second- and third-generation
traders.
</P>
<P>
   The genealogy of the trading pits even includes David A.
Brennan, 42, the chairman of the Board of Trade _ and the man
charged with moving the exchange forward in these perilous times.
From time to time, Brennan still works the agriculture pits with
his 77-year-old father and three brothers. His grandfather was on
the floor at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   The corn pit may have more families than any other. There are
the Murrays, the McBrides and Andrew Flakus, a 23-year-old clerk
who aspires to trade alongside his father and two brothers. There
is John Pietrzak, a 44-year-old man with frayed vocal cords who
followed his father and his grandfather into the pits, after
working as an accountant. There is Ted Dangles. When he retired as
a clerk at another exchange at 76, his son Angelo, a trader in the
agriculture pits, got him a job as a runner; today, at 89, he still
scampers across the trading floor.
</P>
<P>
   The floor, however, is no longer confined to men. Mary Guth, who
has worked at the exchange for 25 years, followed her father and
her brothers there, as did her two sisters. After graduating from
journalism school, Kelly A. King joined her father, Richard King,
known as Whitey, in the corn pit, where they now trade side by
side.
</P>
<P>
   Many traders cannot explain exactly what attracted them. They
mention the adrenaline and the camaraderie _ the sense of community
and family _ and even the danger. Visitors can sense the energy
while watching the scene, hearing the voices in the crowd, the
sounds of friendship that pass beneath the din of trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just remember coming down here as a boy and liking it,''
said Terry Cullerton, a third-generation trader. ``I guess I
thought it was thrilling; this was exciting. It got your blood
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there are no official figures, people on the floor say
traders' annual earnings often run well into the six figures, and
that many make millions of dollars a year speculating; it's the
kind of money that dazzles the young clerks, many of whom are high
school and college age.
</P>
<P>
   ``My girlfriend works in the bond pits and her boss made $12
million last year,'' said one clerk pacing the agriculture floor.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   On any given day, there are about 100 high-energy traders in the
corn pit. They say they love the crowds and the sounds there,
including the gong that signals the opening of trading. Many also
love the hours, which let them head home by 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Many are skeptics when it comes to electronic trading. There are
some things that a computer cannot do, they say. Chaotic as the
current system appears, they note that it has worked for
generations. ``This is something that cannot be replicated
electronically,'' said Jacob J. Morowitz, a longtime soybean
trader. ``On the computer it's a single file, and the thing is much
more susceptible to being dominated by the bigger players.''
</P>
<P>
   They also worry about the cost. One day a few weeks ago, Whitey
King stepped out of the pit holding a copy of The Chicago
Sun-Times. A small article said the Board of Trade was planning to
spend $100 million over the next decade on trading technology.
</P>
<P>
   Some members are already grousing about higher fees they would
have to pay to the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are we going to pay for that?'' King said, pointing to the
article.
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, though, many people here know that the computer is
coming. They fear that they will not be able to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have talents, they might be minimized on the screen,''
says Jeff Nicolaus, a trader in the corn pit. ``It might become how
fast you can press a button. Sometimes here, opportunity is
location, location, location. You won't find that on a computer
screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a theory here that these bodies down here are
lubricants; it's a whole different style of trading on computer.
People go upstairs and they miss the feel of the pit; there's
emotion here.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he turned his back and jumped into the pit to execute a
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some traders are making the transition. John Pietrzak is
trading overnight on Project A, the Board's modest attempt at
electronic trading. Terry Cullerton's sons, Terry Jr. and Jaime,
both in their '20s, are also trading after-hours on Project A,
preparing for the time when everything may be electronic.
</P>
<P>
   Like Chip Combs, many people here know that something has to
happen. Even if the floor survives, everyone knows that it won't be
the same; it's too antiquated.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure couldn't have come at a worse time. With volume
down 9 percent this year, in part because the federal government is
selling fewer Treasury bonds, the Board of Trade has now fallen
into third place among derivatives exchanges in Chicago, behind the
Chicago Board Options Exchange and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Baldwin, a legendary bond trader here, quit a few months
ago after 20 years on the floor. He earned millions by trading up
to 5 percent of the pit volume. But in recent months, that activity
has slowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was standing in the bond pits just wasting my time,'' he
said in a recent interview. ``I'm definitely leaving the bond pits.
I'm trading Nasdaq stocks. I'm staring at a computer screen right
now. This is where it's at now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sensing bad times ahead, Merrill Lynch decided last January to
close its agricultural futures operation and vacate a prime spot at
the exchange's landmark Art Deco building.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the times, that space is now being rented by
Yestrader.com, a high-technology start-up run by a former pit
trader who is developing trading software for those who want to
make the leap into the wired world.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Trade is making its own leap by forming the
alliance with Eurex. The Board will scrap Project A later this
month and use Eurex technology to allow traders to sell futures
online. But some members worry that the exchange is already far
behind. Instead of investing heavily in technology a few years ago,
the board spent $182 million to build the giant trading floor that
opened in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with talk about trading floors around the country being
shuttered, the Board is trying to cut costs and pay down a mounting
debt load.
</P>
<P>
   Les Rosenthal, a former head of the Board of Trade, says the
exchange erred in building the new trading floor and in failing to
develop its own technology. But it made another mistake, he said,
in failing to team up with its sister exchanges in Chicago, a move
that he said would allow the three big exchanges here to share
technology and back-office expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is survival time, and they're doing it all the wrong
way,'' he said. ``The basic plan should be the Merc, the CBOE and
the Board should be united on a single plan. But they'd rather make
alliances with people overseas than across the street. They're
going on these divergent paths and they're all going to end up
dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago _ long considered a center of innovation _ still has a
chance, the experts say. After all, it was the city that created
the concept of financial futures and exported it to the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Sandor said Chicago could be saved by a resilient, risk-taking
set of people.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Melamed, the former chairman of the Merc and the man
credited with introducing financial futures, says the members must
wake up to the fact that new opportunities can come from
technology, including a larger pool of investors and online
traders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys who want open outcry are looking at the back end of
the telescope because they've made money in the past,'' Melamed
said. ``But the past doesn't hold a candle to what's going to be
made in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The message may be getting through to the pits. There was talk
one late July day about more traders taking computer courses. While
few think that the floor will disappear in the next few months,
many are looking ahead by trading online through Project A _
learning the language of the computer.
</P>
<P>
   For Chip Combs, that means getting up at 3:45 a.m. to trade in
the after-hours market. He is beginning to get a sense of a wider
market waiting to be tapped through the keyboard _ albeit
reluctantly.
</P>
<P>
   In the office, he and his father agree. The history of the floor
is great, the elder Earl said, but it may just go the way of the
buggy whip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Businesses can't succeed on nostalgia,'' he said, pondering
the floor's fate. ``If it's electronic, so be it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
