<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FAST-SIDE0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Monday.
 &HT;    Fastest pitcher in baseball never made it to the majorsBy Jack
Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The fastest pitcher in baseball was Steve Dalkowski.
</P>
<P>
   A Baltimore farmhand phenom, Dalkowski signed with the Orioles
in 1957. He never reached Class AAA but was part of baseball lore
by his release in the mid-'60s.
</P>
<P>
   Dalkowski was stocky, just under six feet tall, and was
nicknamed ''Moon Man'' for the thick, round eyeglasses he wore.
Dalkowski came out of Connecticut with a reputation as a high
school left-hander who routinely struck out 17, 18 batters a game
and walked perhaps as many. In a word, wild.
</P>
<P>
   John Schuerholz, who broke into baseball in 1966 with Baltimore,
remembers hearing tales of a tiny ballpark in Bluefield, W.Va. When
Dalkowski pitched, the fans who usually sat behind home plate moved
to safer seating. Supposedly, Dalkowski once had thrown a pitch
right through the chicken-wire backstop.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hit a grand slam off of him,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cox was playing for Reno in the California League in 1960 when
he faced Dalkowski's Stockton team. Reno manager Tom Saffell had
strict rules when Dalkowski pitched.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had to take two strikes before we could swing at him,'' Cox
said. ''He had walked the bases loaded and was ready to strike me
out for the fourth time.'' Somehow, Cox homered.
</P>
<P>
   ''He could throw a bullet from one foul line to the other,''
said Cox. ''It was hilarious watching guys trying to catch him,
(to) warm him up in the Cal League where the lights went hiss,
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves bench coach Pat Corrales faced Dalkowski in 1962 in the
Eastern League. ''I didn't want to go to the plate. He was stupid
wild,'' Corrales said. ''I didn't do nothing against him. Didn't
want to get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Ted Williams, who stepped into the batter's box one
spring training to get a closeup look at Dalkowski's fastball.
After one heater, Williams put down his bat and announced he would
face Dalkowski only in a real game, when he had to.
</P>
<P>
   Most Orioles wouldn't face him, either. The club could not help
him develop control, but fans still flocked to see Dalkowski pitch,
sometimes approaching after games merely to touch his golden left
arm.
</P>
<P>
   One legend had it that Dalkowski tore off a batter's ear with a
fastball. In another, a heater supposedly broke an umpire's mask
and put the ump into the hospital for three days with a concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Once, the Orioles tried to measure such speed. Even though
Dalkowski had pitched the night before, gone out afterward to
celebrate and had been throwing for 40 minutes on flat ground, he
clocked at 93.5 mph. The consensus was that if he had been pitching
at peak form and on a mound his fastball would have exceeded 110.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams never had to face him in the majors, and neither
did anyone else. Dalkowski did not make it. After his release, he
drifted to California and wound up a migrant farm worker.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
