<HEADER>
A2958 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-UNILEVER-DIVIDE-NYT &LR;      08-04 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNILEVER-DIVIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR REORGANIZATION FOR UNILEVER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Unilever PLC, the global consumer goods giant that has
been on a buying spree in the United States, announced a major
reorganization of top management Friday. The move would split the
company into two divisions, one focused on food brands like Lipton
Tea and Ragu spaghetti sauce and the other on consumer products
like Dove soap and Elizabeth Arden cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement revived speculation among analysts that the
company, which has this year acquired Bestfoods, Slim-Fast and Ben
&AMP; Jerry's in the United States in a quest for growth, planned a
full split into two companies. But, as it reported a
higher-than-expected 7 percent rise in second-quarter profit, the
company denied that it was taking its reorganization that far.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a precursor to splitting Unilever, it is a
realignment of the business bringing the strategic and operational
functions closer,'' Mike Haines, a company spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   The split into two divisions capped a relatively fast-moving
series of changes at the sprawling, cumbersome giant. Unilever's
ability to change course has often been compared to that of a
supertanker.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 22, the company announced a $5 billion program to slash
10 percent of its 250,000 global work force, close 100 factories
and winnow its 1,600 brands down to 400 top sellers.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later it began a series of acquisitions in the
United States, committing a combined $2.6 billion in a single day
in April to acquire Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade and Slim-Fast Foods,
before sealing its $20.3 billion takeover of Bestfoods in June. The
Bestfoods deal was its biggest acquisition ever.
</P>
<P>
   By adding Bestfoods brands like Knorr soups and Hellman's
mayonnaise, Unilever hoped to strengthen profitability to catch up
with rivals like France's Danone SA.
</P>
<P>
   The organizational changes at Unilever, an Anglo-Dutch
corporation with headquarters in both Britain and the Netherlands,
will not affect the positions of Unilever's co-chairmen, Niall
Fitzgerald in London and Anthony Burgmans in Rotterdam, the company
and analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   But, formalizing a de facto division of responsibilities, they
will oversee two new divisions run by Patrick Cescau, currently
chief financial officer in charge of food, and Keki B. Dadiseth,
former head of Hindustan Lever, a separately traded Indian
division. Dadiseth will head a home and personal-care products
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are putting people in charge of these categories with
much more clout than ever before,'' said David Lang, an analyst
with Investec Henderson Crosthwaite. The division between food and
home and personal care products, he said, is a traditional
``fault-line'' at Unilever, which has tried several experiments in
its management line-up over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   While analysts generally welcomed the second-quarter rise in
profitability, some expressed reservations about the company's
ability to absorb a major management shake-up at the same time it
is coping with its cost-saving measures and a string of
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Haines, the company spokesman, said the management
reorganization would begin in January ``and will happen
progressively in the course of next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The extent of Unilever's changes made a full split of the
company into two new companies less likely, said Lang at Investec.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have got such a huge agenda to put together _ the
acquisitions and then to sort out their brand portfolio _ that
stripping out at this stage seems premature,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the acquisitions of Slim-Fast and Ben &AMP; Jerry's
had contributed to increased second-quarter profit, while the
Bestfoods acquisition had yet to be completed.
</P>
<P>
   It said profit from operations rose to 768 million euros, or
$695 million, compared with 715 million euros one year earlier,
ahead of analysts' forecasts. The company's operating margin, with
one-time costs, grew to 13 percent from 11.8 percent in Europe and
to 9.8 percent from 9 percent in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Sales rose 3 percent to 10.9 billion euros, but most
significantly, the sales of its top brands _ the 400 on which it
wants to build its future _ rose 6 percent, with much of that
coming from acquisitions, the company said. Some analysts said the
better-than-expected figures reflected one-time circumstances and
would be hard to sustain.
</P>
<P>
   The higher-than-expected profit gain still trailed Danone, which
had recently reported a 12.6 percent increase in first-half profit.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever's share price closed at 4.31 pounds, or about $6.45, on
the London Stock Exchange, up 1 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
