<HEADER>
A2960 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-KIDS-FLOWERSHOP0805-C     08-04 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-FLOWERSHOP0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Garden wears the footprints of many grandkids
 &HT;    By Trish Widdows
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ We didn't know what it was called or
even exactly what we sold, all we knew is we had a flower shop and
it was the best flower shop anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   As kids, my older sister Kristi and I ran the shop together out
of our grandparents' back yard of lush green grass, trees of all
kinds, vegetables, berries, and most striking of all _ flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent hours in that garden,'' Kristi remembered. ``Time
stood still when we were out there.''
</P>
<P>
   We spent many afternoons walking along the garden paths talking
to our imaginary customers about the different flowers that were
available.
</P>
<P>
   We would take the longest routes possible, opening and closing
as many gates as possible, pulling our carts behind us full of our
customers' flowers.
</P>
<P>
   One of our favorite places to take customers was into our
freezer _ which was actually the dog kennel _ for the fresh flowers
we carried.
</P>
<P>
   When we tired of walking around, we would ring up our customer
at our cement cash register and send them on their happy way.
</P>
<P>
   Most of our customers were imaginary, except for our
grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Gram always had a pitcher of ice-cold lemonade waiting for us,
along with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   I remember drinking lemonade and talking with Gram while
swinging slowly on the big wooden swing that still hangs from an
old ash tree. I can still see her sitting there.
</P>
<P>
   Now I love to sit on that same swing and remember the annual
leaf parties in the fall with my cousins, the massive Easter egg
hunts in the spring, the family barbecues with homemade ice cream
and the badminton games where the cable wires that ran above the
yard were out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This yard has seen many grandchildren's feet,'' said my
granddad, Bill Widdows. ``The grandchildren always had the run of
the yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Our 14 feet covered the yard all right, and we all have many
memories contained in the flowers and trees that stood by watching
us grow up.
</P>
<P>
   To Jennifer, the paths along the flowers were her very own
secret garden, where Gram would help her pick pansies for a
bouquet.
</P>
<P>
   Dan remembers Granddad lighting fireworks out of a pipe near the
basement door in hopes of scaring an unsuspecting child,
``regardless of whether it was the Fourth of July or not, of
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff thinks of the times when he and Granddad would pull carrots
out of the ground on Thanksgiving Day. Granddad would save a second
crop of carrots for the fall and winter, when he would bury them
under the warmth of leaves.
</P>
<P>
   April and Jennifer used to twist the swings around each other
and fly through the air, being careful not to hit the big ash tree
nearby as they unwound.
</P>
<P>
   All of us grandchildren have launched ourselves off the swing
into a pile of leaves.
</P>
<P>
   We have all swung with a push from Gram or Granddad.
</P>
<P>
   I used to swing after a bad day at school. The swing is still
one of my favorite places to regain perspective.
</P>
<P>
   The swing was used, and the grass paid the toll.
</P>
<P>
   For 40 years, the round patch of dirt under the swing was the
only blunder in my grandfather's carefully groomed yard.
</P>
<P>
   By now the grass has long since grown back over the patch.
</P>
<P>
   As the youngest grandchild left in Grand Junction for several
years, I have intentionally tried to drag my feet under the swing
to keep the grass from covering over the patch, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   The patch was a part of the yard, just as much as the beds of
flowers, rows of vegetables, the rose garden, the raspberries along
the back fence that were made into jam each summer, the birdbath,
or even the swings themselves. It represented that grandchildren
had been there, family had been together, and all was well because
of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a comfortable place,'' my aunt Jane said,'' a place for
family.''
</P>
<P>
   The yard may have been the perfect backdrop, but all my cousins
would agree that Gram and Granddad are what made it so special for
each of us.
</P>
<P>
   We were just lucky enough to have the perfect back yard _ and
grandparents _ to grow up with.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
