<SLUG> BC-JOBS-SLOWDOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOBS SLOWDOWN SEEN AS SIGN OF COOLING ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 108,000 fewer Americans were working in July, the US
Department of Labor reported Friday. It was the first decline in
payrolls in more than four years and strong evidence the nation's
breakneck growth has moderated.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the payroll shrinkage can be explained by last month's
layoffs of temporary workers who were hired to collect US Census
data, a one-time event that bloated the jobs data in preceding
months.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the 2000 Census, however, there was continued
weakness in hiring, beginning in May and continuing into summer.
</P>
<P>
   The private sector added a total of about 138,000 new employees
in July. That was substantially below the 200,000-a-month pace in
the final months of 1999 and early this year, said John Youngdahl,
senior economist at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The layoff at Census was totally predictable, but the
private-sector employment growth has moderated substantially since
the beginning of the year,'' Youngdahl said. ``That (private-sector
slowdown) is what people need to focus on, in terms of what the
report is telling us.''
</P>
<P>
   A clear downward trend in the pace of job creation calmed
economists' fears that the nation was continuing to experience
blockbuster growth, which the Federal Reserve worries would spark
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Such fears were renewed by a recent report that the economy
posted 5.2 percent growth in the first quarter, an acceleration
from 4.8 percent growth in the prior quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Slower job growth is not necessarily good for workers _ the
jobless rate among blacks and Hispanics is no longer declining, for
instance _ but economists say it eases concerns about the economy
overheating. That virtually eliminates the need for the Federal
Reserve to again raise interest rates to rein in the economy and
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has increased rates six times since it began a campaign
in June 1999 to slow the economy. The Fed board that sets monetary
policy meets again Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an unsustainable pace of growth in the economy in
1999,'' said Fred Breimyer, chief economist for State Street Corp.
in Boston. The July jobs report, he said, ``makes it unlikely the
Federal Reserve would tighten'' the money supply by raising
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The nation, though, continues to enjoy the spoils of a
record-setting economic expansion that began more than nine years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Not since January 1996 has the Labor Department reported a
shrinking in total nonfarm payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   And in July, the US unemployment rate was unchanged, at 4
percent. The Massachusetts rate was 2.6 percent in June, the most
recent figure available.
</P>
<P>
   But a weaker job market dovetailed with other signs of slowing,
particularly in the housing and retail sectors. Economists
attributed the surge in second-quarter growth in part to higher
inflation, which padded the figures, and to a surge in workers'
productivity, which means the existing labor force can produce more
goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   Friday the financial markets sighed with relief at the moderate
job gains.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq Composite index, after a rocky week, rose 27.48, to
3787.36. The Dow Jones Industrial Average of blue chip stocks
posted a fifth day's gain, rising 61.17 to 10,767.75.
</P>
<P>
   After a blockbuster first quarter, job creation slowed sharply
in May and became more sluggish each month. In June, for example,
about 30,000 total nonfarm jobs were created, according to a
revised estimate by the Labor Department, which had reported that
payrolls expanded by only 11,000 in June. In contrast, January
payrolls expanded by 349,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're holding in place,'' Breimyer said. ``The demand and
supply of workers is in balance, so there's no additional
tightening of the labor market.
</P>
<P>
   Economists say the private-sector slowdown in hiring was partly
masked by the Census Bureau's hiring, which peaked in May, with
about 618,000 temporary workers on the government's payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Job growth in July was tepid or nonexistent in most industries
in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Notably, the traditionally strong services sector, which has
driven the economic expansion, shrank by 1,000 jobs in July _ a big
change from gains in service jobs of 97,000 a month, on average,
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Other sectors performed slightly better, notably manufacturing,
which added 46,000 jobs last month. The financial industry also
expanded payrolls, the Labor Department said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time since the begining of the year that
we've seen an increase'' in manufacturers' payrolls, said Walter
Marshall, a senior Labor Department economist. It was largely due
to gains in hiring by makers of electronic components, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Marshall described July's job growth as ``modest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
