<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWMAN-PREDECESSORS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEP YOUR EYES OPEN FOR THESE OTHER WORTHWHILE INVISIBLE-MAN-THEMED
MOVIES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By TODD CAMP 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to Hollywood's recent infatuation with
invisibility, there's actually a great deal more than meets the
eye.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Verhoeven's special effects-laden thriller ``Hollow Man,''
which arrives this weekend and stars Kevin Bacon as a brilliant
scientist driven mad by his irreversible invisibility, along with
the Sci-Fi Channel's new ``Invisible Man'' series, starring Vincent
Ventresca, are just the latest in a long line of
now-you-see-him-now-you-don't projects.
</P>
<P>
   The Sci-Fi Channel show is actually the third of its kind,
following a 1958 British series and a short-lived 1975 series from
writer/producer Stephen Bochco starring David McCallum.
</P>
<P>
   Larger screen efforts have been more successful, although widely
varying in quality. Some are terrific _ Universal's original
adaptation of H.G. Wells' novel ``The Invisible Man'' is still the
best. Some are mediocre _ ``Invisible Mom,'' ``Invisible Dad'' and
``Invisible Kid?'' And some are just pathetic. I'm still trying to
forget the unapologetically crass ``The Invisible Maniac.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of the transparent titles available on video that
we think are still worth, uh, seeing:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Invisible Man'' _ Director James Whale's initial Wells
adaptation remains the best of the invisibility subgenre. Whale's
signature black humor, and dynamite performances from leads Claude
Rains and Gloria Stuart, are enough to make it worth a look, but
John P. Fulton's groundbreaking effects work (this was 1933!) is
dazzling to this day. A new special edition DVD hits shelves Aug.
29.
</P>
<P>
   Invisible sequels: Universal followed the Whale film with four
sequels, none nearly as good, but still fun in their own right.
They were ``The Invisible Man Returns,'' starring Vincent Price in
1940 (the best of the sequels); ``The Invisible Woman'' with John
Barrymore and Virginia Bruce in 1941; the ``Invisible Agent'' with
Jon Hall and Peter Lorre in 1942; and ``The Invisible Man's
Revenge'' with Hall and John Carradine in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abbott and Costello Meet the Invisible Man'' (1951) _ This
1951 film was one of the better efforts in the
Bud-and-Lou-Meet-the-Monsters series, with great effects and Arthur
Franz as an invisible prize-fighter. New video edition hits shelves
Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Amazing Transparent Man'' _ This almost forgettable 1960
low-budgeter featuring a mad scientist who turns a convict
invisible to steal materials for him is worth seeing if only
because of its Dallas connection. Much of the film was shot on
location at the Texas State Fair using the futuristic exhibits as
backdrops. It arrives on video Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Memoirs of an Invisible Man'' (1992) _ John Carpenter's
predictable spy thriller featuring Chevy Chase as a securities
analyst accidentally rendered invisible is worth seeing only for
its vast amount of special effects. It's disappointing to think
what Carpenter's exceptional horror instincts might have brought to
the picture if he hadn't decided to play it for laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Invisible rarities: You probably won't be able to find any of
these titles at local video emporiums, but they might be worth
searching the bootleg bins for. The 1957 Mexican film ``El Hombre
Que Logro Ser Invisible'' (dubbed ``The New Invisible Man'' in the
States) is a loose adaptation of ``The Invisible Man Returns,''
with Arturo de Cordova pulling a disappearing act to solve a murder
he didn't commit. ``The Invisible Dr. Mabuse'' from 1961 stands out
as one of the best of the Mabuse series, with the evil doctor using
an invisibility formula to help take over the WORLD!
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is pop culture critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7691, or e-mail:
tcamp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
