A2971 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-DOTCOM-DEVELOPMENT-HN     08-04 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOTCOM-DEVELOPMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN FRANCISCO MAYOR MOVES TO REGULAT DOT-COMS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHUCK FINNIE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown, responding to
outcries over gentrification of the city's working-class
neighborhoods, is moving to bring dot-com developments firmly under
stringent growth-control regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's proposal would impose a moratorium on the
developments in the Mission District. Elsewhere, developers wishing
to convert old warehouses and industrial sites for use by
technology companies would need to go through special hearings and
possibly accept extra conditions to receive permits, sources
familiar with the plan said.
</P>
<P>
   It would specify that all dot-com developments be treated as
office construction, ending a loophole through which developers
sought approval for their projects by dubbing them manufacturing,
research and development or business services facilities, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's proposal, therefore, would mean dot-com developers
would have to abide by the city's 950,000-square-foot cap on new
office construction in any given year and compete for approvals
under that limit with builders of conventional office buildings,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a framework for a proposal that is being evaluated by
people who have previously given opinions to the mayor on this
topic,'' said Emilio Cruz, Brown's economic development chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable the proposal will not hamper the ability to
grow economically and create jobs, while at the same time help to
meet community and social goals.''
</P>
<P>
   In various ways, the mayor's proposal borrows from an initiative
that growth-control and affordable-housing advocates hoped to get
on the ballot in November or December as well as from alternatives
recommended to Brown by business interests.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Haaland, a tenant activist working on the initiative
drive, said he didn't think Brown was going far enough to regulate
the economic forces driving up real estate prices and driving out
old-line businesses, nonprofit social services and cultural groups,
and longtime residents.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative being pushed by growth-control and
affordable-housing advocates contains bans on dot-com and other
office development in the Mission, Potrero Hill and South of
Market, and a moratorium for Bayview-Hunters Point pending
completion of a planning study.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be extremely surprised, if Potrero Hill, SOMA and
Bayview-Hunters Point are left out, that there would be support
from our coalition,'' Haaland said of the mayor's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Romero, of the nonprofit Mission Housing Development
Corp., said it would be a mistake to accept a compromise that
provides only partial relief to one neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rise and fall in coalition,'' he said. ``We won't break
ranks to protect our small corner of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Business representatives, who had been urging Brown to craft an
alternative to the proposed initiative ordinance, applauded the
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like an excellent recommendation,'' said Mara
Brazer, president of the San Francisco Partnership, a
business-oriented nonprofit economic development group.
</P>
<P>
   Developers and technology-industry advocates opposed subjecting
dot-com projects across the board to office building growth
controls, saying many software, Internet and digital technology
companies and multimedia firms are similar to manufacturing
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe all dot-com is office,'' Brazer said. ``But
as long there's enough room for growth of new business and emerging
technologies, in appropriate neighborhoods, then I could live with
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is application of Proposition M, the city's 1986
voter-approved office building growth-control ordinance, to the
dot-com industry. Prop. M capped new office construction at 950,000
square feet a year.
</P>
<P>
   A reaction to the high-rise construction of the late 1970s and
early 1980s, Prop. M provided for ``banking'' allowable
construction from years of low demand for use in years of high
demand.
</P>
<P>
   In hot markets such as today, office developers compete in
``beauty contests'' for the right to build and can be forced to
shelve their plans until room is available under the Prop. M cap.
</P>
<P>
   Both the initiative ordinance by growth-control and
affordable-housing advocates and the proposals from business
interests called for more office construction by exempting certain
large projects, such as the planned federal government office
building at Seventh and Mission streets, or Lucas Films campus
planned for the Presidio.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's proposal, which sources said is being tweaked,
adopts that approach. In addition, it would exempt from the Prop. M
cap office buildings planned at Catellus Development Corp.'s
Mission Bay and redevelopment proposals before The City for Hunters
Point Naval Shipyard.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale for exempting Mission Bay and the shipyard is that
both projects would include housing - priced at and below market -
as well as schools and other public resources.
</P>
<P>
   The changes being contemplated must go before voters because
they would amend Prop. M, which passed with 51.3 percent of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has until Aug. 9 to draft a final proposal and place it on
the ballot Nov. 7, or he could wait and call a special election in
March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
