<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2977 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PLANE-GROUNDED-HNS &LR;      08-04 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANE-GROUNDED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ALASKA AIR GROUNDS 18 MD-80 PLANES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DEMIAN BULWA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Alaska Airlines has grounded 18 Boeing MD-80
airliners to further inspect the planes' jackscrews _ a part
implicated in January's crash of San Francisco-bound Flight 261
that killed 88 people off the Southern California coast.
</P>
<P>
   The move forced Alaska to cancel five flights Thursday at San
Francisco International Airport, along with 15 in other airports.
Oakland and San Jose airports were not affected, but they and San
Francisco could experience cancellations or delays Friday and
possibly through the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle-based Alaska told the Federal Aviation Administration on
Thursday that it would immediately start to inspect jackscrews on
18 of the 34 MD-80s in its 92-aircraft fleet through Saturday, said
company spokesman Don Conrard.
</P>
<P>
   The airline, like other carriers, has focused on jackscrews
since the crash.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent test, it found that a tool made in a company machine
shop could - if positioned improperly - produce different
measurements than if tools manufactured by Boeing were used.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers are allowed to use manufacturers' tools or an
equivalent, although it is now unclear whether the tool used by
Alaska - called a il,6p6,13l restraining fixture - was an
appropriate substitute, Alaska and the FAA said.
</P>
<P>
   The jackscrew assembly consists of a nut that rides up and down
a screw. It drives an airplane's horizontal stabilizer up and down
and limits its range of travel.
</P>
<P>
   The restraining fixture unloads the pressure on the horizontal
stabilizer and holds it in place so a measurement of the space
between the thread on the jackscrew and the nut that holds it in
place can be taken, Conrard said.
</P>
<P>
   In side-by-side tests using both company and Boeing restraining
fixtures, no discrepancies were found, Conrard said, but inspectors
saw the possibility for error. He stressed that the difference in
the tools may not have had any impact on the MD-80s.
</P>
<P>
   The machine-shop tool was used on the 18 grounded planes, and
was also used on Flight 261, Conrard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is up to the U.S. attorney's office and the (National
Transportation Safety Board) to determine if this tool is a problem
in their investigation,'' Alaska Airlines President Bill Ayer said
in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 MD-80s in the Alaska fleet that were not grounded were
tested with the Boeing tool, Conrard said, and thus do not need to
be inspected again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the possibility (of a discrepancy) exists, we're erring
on the side of caution,'' said Conrard, who added that the
company-made tool will no longer be used.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA praised on Thursday the voluntary inspections as ``the
right thing`` and went further, asking that all other airlines that
fly MD-80s determine what fixture tools have been used, and ensure
they made proper measurements.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA said it was notifying foreign operators, and that DC-9s
are also affected. The NTSB is investigating the issue with the
help of the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no indications of other problems, but in the
interests of safety the FAA will direct that other carriers move
quickly to make certain that is the case,'' the FAA said. The
agency said it would have no further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines Flight 261 plunged into the Pacific Ocean off
the California coast on a flight from Mexico on Jan. 31. The plane
was an MD-83 - an MD-80 variant.
</P>
<P>
   A criminal investigation into the crash focused on a mechanic's
decision not to replace a jackscrew assembly. The jackscrew had
been tested repeatedly and found to be nearly worn out, but was put
back into service after a second crew retested it a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the FAA announced that Alaska Airlines had made
sufficient improvements to continue maintaining its planes.
Earlier, the agency had given the airline seven days to make
changes and threatened to strip the airline of the right to perform
maintenance - a step that eventually could have grounded all its
planes.
</P>
<P>
   The Flight Standards Service division of the FAA said then that
regulators had ``serious concerns about critical processes,
including management effectiveness,`` after teams of inspectors in
Oakland and Seattle found almost 150 cases in which maintenance
required on Alaska aircraft couldn't be documented.
</P>
<P>
   Operations at the Oakland hangar have been the subject of a
criminal investigation by a federal grand jury in San Francisco
since 1998. There have been no indictments.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska also faces a bevy of lawsuits arising from the crash.
They will be heard at the U.S. District Court in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska urged travelers to check the status of flights through
the weekend by calling ahead or visiting the airline's Web site,
alaskaair.com. cq CQHundreds of stranded San Francisco travelers
were put up at hotels Thursday as the carrier tried to find
alternate flights.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska slowly is phasing out MD-80s, not because of safety
concerns but because it can save money by using a standard fleet
type - 737s, which have more cargo room in their bellies, among
other advantages, Conrard said.
</P>
</TEXT>
