<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2979 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-GORE-0806-COX     08-04 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-GORE-0806-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE'S STRATEGY: FIGHT THE ``RUSTED WAYS'' OF OLD GUARD
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now that the Republican National Convention is
history, Vice President Al Gore needs to counter its effects in two
main ways: Deliver an acceptance speech at the Democratic
convention that counters the style and substance of George W.
Bush's, and choose a running mate who compares well with Dick
Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, it appears, the Gore campaign will try to
reinforce the vice president's pre-convention message _ that Bush,
the son of former President George H.W. Bush, and Cheney, who
served as defense secretary in the elder Bush's cabinet, represent
``the old guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in his first campaign appearance after the conclusion of
the GOP convention, vowed to fight ``the rusted ways of the old
guard.'' He told 3,400 union firefighters in Chicago on Friday that
he would battle ``the big interests'' and ``powerful forces lined
up against'' working families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is going to take the campaign straight to the working
people and make it clear whose side he is on in this fight,'' said
campaign aide Doug Hattaway.
</P>
<P>
   And campaign spokesman Chris Lehane, in comments about the
upcoming announcement of Gore's running mate, said the choice will
be someone who ``represents the future and not the old guard like
Bush's choice'' of Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to reversing Bush's lead in the polls _ 19
percent in the bi-partisan Voter.com-Battleground poll of 1,000
likely voters taken immediately after the convention _ Gore has the
task of stepping out from the shadow of the president he serves,
Bill Clinton, the man the Bush-Cheney campaign often speaks of as
if he were Gore's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore strategists see the acceptance speech as the time that Gore
becomes his own person, politically _ a point Gore made Friday with
a retooled campaign stump speech that mixed biting criticism of
Bush with warm autobiographical anecdotes.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the confetti, fireworks and technical wizardry of the GOP
convention, Gore said, was ``an agenda of rising gas prices and
smog-filled skies that is of Big Oil, by Big Oil and for Big Oil.''
</P>
<P>
   And responding to Cheney's convention refrain _ ``It's time for
them to go,'' a line Gore used against the elder Bush in 1992 _
Gore said, ``Let me tell you what time it's not ... It is not
recession time in America like it was back in 1992.''
</P>
<P>
   While touting the ``prosperity and progress'' of the last seven
years under Clinton's economic policies, Gore also said he would
offer ``a new vision for the future'' in his acceptance speech.
``I'll be talking about the new heights America can reach if we
stay on the right track and make the right choices today,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And although he has been in public office for nearly a quarter
of a century, Gore wants to use his acceptance speech in much the
way that Bush did his _ to introduce himself to American voters who
are just beginning to pay attention to the presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the American people know him particularly
well,'' said Gore media adviser Bob Shrum.
</P>
<P>
   With wife Tipper and daughter Sarah, one of his four children,
at his side Friday, Gore told the firefighters that he wants the
American people ``to know me for who I am.'' And in an interview
with CNN, he said, ``I'm running on who I am. I'm running as my own
man.''
</P>
<P>
   To further dramatize Gore's independence from Clinton, the Gore
campaign has arranged for Clinton to give his farewell address to
the convention on the day it convenes, then fly to a battleground
state in the Midwest for a symbolic ``passing of the torch.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is scheduled to disclose his choice of a running mate
Tuesday in Nashville. The two will then campaign together nonstop
enroute to Los Angeles, where the Democratic National Convention
convenes Aug. 14 and where the party met in 1960 to nominate John
F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign has tried to add drama to the vice
presidential selection process _ and thereby counter the post-GOP
convention ``bounce'' for Bush in the polls _ by floating the idea
of a ``wild card'' possibility, someone who has not been frequently
mentioned in press accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Gore family and his most senior advisers know the vice
president's thinking on who he regards as the best candidate for
the No. 2 spot on the Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's mention of a ``wild card'' caused considerable
attention to fall on former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, Gore's
lone challenger for the Democratic presidential nomination this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic National Committee General Chairman Ed Rendell, the
former mayor of Philadelphia, spent much of the week of the GOP
convention in his hometown promoting Bradley. And Gore strategists
in Nashville spoke glowingly of the amiacable meeting Gore and
Bradley had in Wisconsin last month, when Bradley announced his
endorsement of his former rival.
</P>
<P>
   The other six reportedly on Gore's list of possible running
mates are Sens. John Kerry of Massachusetts, Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut, Evan Bayh of Indiana and John Edwards of North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt and New Hampshire Gov.
Jeanne Shaheen round out the list, along with what Gore said was
``an out-of-the-box possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
