<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2995 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SHEEP-ILLNESS-BOS &LR;      08-04 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEEP-ILLNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGIUM WANTS TO STUDY SHEEP SUSPECTED OF BEING INFECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (350 sheep is cq; a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERICA THESING  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking a reprieve for more than 350 sheep condemned to death in
Vermont, the Belgian government requested Friday that the flocks be
returned to Belgium for further testing.
</P>
<P>
   The flocks _ containing about 50 animals exported from Belgium
in 1996, and their offspring born in the United States _ were
ordered destroyed in July after four animals tested positive for a
disease resembling bovine spongiform encephalopathy, or mad cow
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Adriansens, agriculture consulate at the Belgian Embassy in
Washington, said Belgium and the European Union want the sheep
returned so scientists can conduct further tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The condition is from the European Union that the sheep can
come back for scientific purposes,'' he said. ``The conditions are
to send back the whole flock or nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of Agriculture Dan Glickman ordered the flocks'
destruction July 14. A federal judge ruled Tuesday that the sheep
should be killed to prevent the possibility of contaminating
American farm animals or food supplies.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the USDA said the agency needed a few days to
review Belgium's request.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our folks would need some time to look at it and see
what makes the best sense,'' said spokesman Patrick Collins.
``We're continuing to negotiate with the flock owners. We'd like to
resolve this as quickly as possible and hopefully we can do so with
the families.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said the agency might respond early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Preventing the sheep slaughter has become something of a cause
celebre in Vermont, where a Save the Sheep campaign active during
court hearings portrayed government officials as thugs protecting
domestic trade interests. Supporters of the sheep have also
travelled to the farm of one sheep owner to feast on his family's
cheese products and visit the condemned animals grazing in nearby
pastures.
</P>
<P>
   The sheeps' owners remain hopeful that their flocks will avoid
slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Faillace, daughter of East Warren flock owners Larry and
Linda Falliace, said her parents were unavailable for comment. They
were busy getting their passports renewed for a possible trip to
Belgium, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Faillace said her parents were excited about the idea of sending
the sheep back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would much rather do that than have them killed,'' she
said. ``We're going to try everything we can to have that done.''
</P>
<P>
   Houghton Freeman, who owns the remainder of the condemned sheep,
said he was partly responsible for the Belgian's request.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to find some way to prevent the sheep being
slaughtered,'' he said. ``It's in negotiation now. The two
governments are talking.''
</P>
<P>
   But Adriansens said he had not been able to contact anyone at
the USDA about the request. He said USDA officials were scheduled
for meetings Friday and did not have time to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that they will have an answer but I don't know when or
what,'' he said. ``We made the request. Now we are waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Adriansens said the Belgians and other European scientists are
interested in the Vermont flocks because they represent the first
known instance of sheep testing positive for the illness without
their parents testing postive as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``So for scientific purposes, they believe it would be better to
avoid the slaughter of those sheeps at this moment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The animals that tested positive for the sheep equivalent of mad
cow disease do not necessarily have the mad cow illness, American
scientists have said. But agriculture officials are concerned about
anything that might spread the feared disease, which killed 53
people in Great Britain in 1995, and nearly destroyed that
country's beef industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
