<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3010 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SPOT/FEATURE-BUDGET-B     08-04 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT/FEATURE-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (Eliminates Missiles-Postol, adds Busstop-Wedding)  
 For Release SATURDAY AMs, August 5, 2000  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-MUM (London) _ As Britain's beloved Queen Mum turns 100,
it seems as if the empire is in full bloom and Queen Victoria is
still driving through the streets in a horse-drawn carriage. By
Kevin Cullen. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-GORE (Chicago) _ Looking tanned and rested after returning
from a week's beach vacation, Al Gore delivers a blistering attack
on the GOP, accusing his foes of stealing his lines and pandering
to ``special interests.'' By Susan Milligan. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-PARTY (Los Angeles) _ The convention doesn't begin for more
than a week, but the party scene is already heating up in LA. By
Lynda Gorov. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BOUNCE (Philadelphia) _ Assessing the Bush bounce off the
convention, and the road ahead. By Curtis Wilkie and Anne E.
Kornblut. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSSTOP-WEDDING (Boston) _ Michael Gandolfi wasn't looking for
love at the bus stop where met Maria Martiniello. But, three years
after their meeting, they're getting married -- at the bus stop. By
Jamal Watson. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   SHEEP-ILLNESS (Undated) _ Belgium's agricultural minister wants
to repatriate 50 sheep under a federal death sentence in Vermont
for possibly being infected with an illness similar to mad cow
disease. By Erica Thesing. 600 words. (a and i coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-GOP (Undated) _ Some analysts say the broadcast networks
defined ``news'' so narrowly _ and cut back on coverage so
dramatically _ that they missed the deeper stories behind the GOP
convention. By Don Aucoin. 975 words. (e and p coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-TAXMAN (St. Petersburg) _ American James Beatty has taken
on one of the most challenging jobs in Russia: Helping foreign
businesses navigate one of the world's most notoriously corrupt and
complicated tax systems without going broke. By Brian Whitmore. 950
words. (f and i coding)
</P>
<P>
   JOBS-SLOWDOWN (Undated) _ US employment decreased by 108,000
jobs in July, the third month of weaker job growth and a strong
sign a slowdown desired by the Fed may be under way. By Kimberly
Blanton. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON-UNIONS (Undated) _ Two unions representing more than
85,000 customer service workers for Verizon Communications say the
workers will strike at midnight Sunday if contract talks don't
produce an agreement on wages and benefits. By Diane E. Lewis. 800
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-REDSOX-EVERETT (Boston) _ In the aftermath of Carl Everett's
angry confrontation with umpire Ronald Kulpa, which resulted in the
most severe penalty given a baseball player for an on-field
incident in 20 years, his behavior raises questions about future
problems. By Gordon Edes. 900 words.
</P>
