<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3011 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CONVENTION-WRAP0805-C     08-04 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTION-WRAP0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'We are a new Republican Party'
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA - Presidential nominee George W. Bush, who promised
a different kind of national convention, succeeded in serving up a
four-day event that was completely atypical for the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the parts that weren't.
</P>
<P>
   What was different was night after night of folks and faces you
wouldn't expect to see on a GOP stage, including Hispanic singers
and Chaka Khan, the Delfonics and enough black entertainers to give
the convention a Soul Train look, as long as you didn't pan the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a new Republican Party,'' Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge
told delegates on the closing night Thursday. ``And George W. Bush
is the founding father.''
</P>
<P>
   But while being different was the goal, the parts that were the
same played best on the packed convention floor. For all the talk
of a new era of bipartisan cooperation, nothing _ no song, no star
_ got the crowd rocking like the third verse of the tune the GOP
has been singing for eight years: Bill Clinton and Al Gore are
unfit to serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all of the shouting and all of the scandal. After all of
the bitterness and broken faith, we can begin again,'' Bush said in
his acceptance speech, drawing a wild reaction.
</P>
<P>
   His speech came a night after running mate Dick Cheney _ about
the last guy you would expect to incite a riot _ whipped the crowd
into near-frenzy with his attacks on Clinton-Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking for a slash-and-burn artist who is somebody
who can get up and give a stirring, tub-thumping stump speech, I'm
not your guy,'' Cheney had said prior to the convention.
</P>
<P>
   But it turned out that if you're looking for a guy who can use a
measured, board-room, I-mean-business tone to fire up the troops,
he is your guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came in together. Now let us see them off together,''
Cheney said of Clinton and Gore, drawing an impassioned response
from delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Woven into the wild enthusiasm for every negative word about
Clinton-Gore is a Bush campaign dilemma. This was a decidedly home
crowd made up of Republicans who believe the White House was stolen
from them by scoundrels.
</P>
<P>
   That feeling is out there among some Americans, and Bush and
Cheney want to play to it. But some of the swing states that will
decide the race, among them the industrial Midwest, include
undecided voters. Those are folks who _ despite the Clinton scandal
_ still have not decided to give up on the president's political
heir.
</P>
<P>
   Survey numbers released after Bush's acceptance speech indicate
the delicate nature of attack politics. Republicans, predictably,
loved the speech. But according to a Hart Research analysis of
responses from viewers who punched in their reactions on
SpeakOut.Com, independents were a bit queasy about the attacks on
Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush lost independents when he attacked Clinton and Gore,''
the analysis said. ``Here, the politics of negativism turned off
these people in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign officials moved quickly to take advantage of that
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took Bush only seven sentences before he first attacked
Vice President Gore,'' they noted. ``Despite all the happy
rhetoric, despite all the smiling faces, despite all the scripted
displays of inclusion, Bush-Cheney is the same old mean-spirited
and divisive Republican ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, Bush's top strategist, is aware of the balancing act
that comes with assailing Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will respond if attacked,'' Rove said. ``But I think the
American people, after the last eight years and for a lot of other
reasons, are at a point where they would prefer to learn more about
the candidates and their respective agendas. And trashball politics
is not particularly compelling or effective this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the shots at Clinton and Gore, the GOP ticket managed
to transform its convention into something out of the ordinary for
Republicans. Gone was the usual litany of patriotic music, replaced
this year by up-tempo tunes and toned-down rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion, a GOP hot-button issue, got little mention.
</P>
<P>
   The party platform, especially its more controversial planks,
was not part of the made-for-TV Republican Party offered up for
four nights. Though mostly ignored in the party's prime time hours,
the conservative GOP platform remained generally intact and
Democrats are likely to highlight that in the race to secure
support from minority voters.
</P>
<P>
   In the convention's most deftly performed double reverse,
retired Gen. Colin Powell got delegates to cheer, sort of, for
affirmative action, a concept he supports but Bush and the party
oppose.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, at the GOP convention in San Diego, Powell was
booed when he voiced support for affirmative action. This year, he
packaged it with a can't-miss shot at big-money politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some in our party miss no opportunity to roundly condemn
affirmative action that helped a few thousand black kids get an
education, but you hardly hear a whimper from them over affirmative
action for lobbyists who load our federal tax code with preferences
for special interests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd on the convention floor cheered. There was no way to
know whether the lobbyists and special interests, wining and dining
in the luxury boxes above, reacted similarly.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's message of inclusion played in events all around town,
though not always as effectively as he desired. His first
appearance in Philadelphia, a Hispanic rally on the famous steps at
the Philadelphia Museum of Art, was largely populated by
non-Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Down front were the Minnesota Young Republicans, a decidedly
Anglo group holding signs that said ``Latinos for Bush.'' One
Hispanic singer, noting the lack of reaction when he spoke to the
crowd in Spanish, asked, ``There's a few Latinos here, right?''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Bush got the different convention he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never seen this much dancing at a Republican
convention before,'' noted U.S. Rep. Henry Bonilla of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
