<P>
   CBOT-TRADE (Chicago) _ The explosion of computerized trading is
threatening to make century-old pit trading obsolete. Some believe
the ``open outcry'' method of shouting and flashing hand signals
into a trading pit is already doomed. And so too, they say, might
be the United States' oldest derivatives exchange, the Chicago
Board of Trade. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BIZ-POLAND (Legnica, Poland) _ Thousands of Poles, with
government aid, have worked to beat Soviet swords into a share of
post-Communist prosperity, an opportunity they have grabbed with
both hands. By Peter S. Green.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-RESERVATIONS (Undated) _ The restaurant industry has been
slow to catch on to the electronic reservations revolution, but
there are now a growing number of Web sites that allow diners in
major U.S. cities to reserve tables online. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ The wave of economic reforms that has
washed over Latin America first touched shore in Chile. That small
nation was the first to tear down import barriers, liberalize
exchange-rate policy, bolster the domestic savings rate and
otherwise whip itself into shape for the new global economy. Now it
wants to go further. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic)
</P>
<P>
   SENIORS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Books aimed at the growing, and
increasingly affluent, senior market are steadily filling bookstore
shelves around the country. By Fred Brock.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUTCARS-MERCEDES (Undated) _ The Mercedes-Benz brochure of the
1980s described the marque's philosophy thus: A Mercedes should not
inspire aggressive driving, but if you find yourself in a bind _
say, roaring into a tight turn too fast _ the car will get you
through. That, at least, was the gist. The Mercedes was an
automotive Clark Kent, serious and sedate, but ready to fling off
its eyeglasses and soar to the rescue. There is nothing
mild-mannered about the Mercedes-Benz of today. By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
