   LATIN-ROCK-MUSIC (Bogota, Colombia) _ Rock may have been born as
American music, but at middle age it is also the music of the
Americas, as quickly becomes apparent during an afternoon spent in
a recording studio here with Aterciopelados, Colombia's most
popular rock band. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   DIESKAU-MUSIC (Undated) _ Who would suspect, this late in the
game, that there were any crucial gaps left to fill in the
discography of Dietrich Fischer-Dieskau? Yet here comes Myto
Records, of Milan, advertising the first release ever of
Fischer-Dieskau's first-ever operatic appearance. By Matthew
Gurewitsch.
</P>
<P>
   AFFAIR-OF-LOVE-FILM (Undated) _ ``I lived a powerful love story,
I understood nothing about it, and I needed to delve into my
questions in a film,'' said the Belgian director Frederic Fonteyne,
by way of explaining his tender, unconventional and emotionally
charged movie about middle-aged romance, ``An Affair of Love.'' By
Laura Winters.
</P>
<P>
   AIMEE&AMP;JAGUAR-FILM (Undated) _ Felice Schragenheim was a
high-spirited, educated, sensual, witty and wily young lesbian,
whose dangerous misfortune was to have been born Jewish in
pre-World War II Germany. During the war she lived in Berlin under
an assumed name and worked at a Nazi newspaper, feeding information
to the underground resistance. Lilly Wust, the young wife of an SS
soldier, was the mother of four boys, and for her effort in
producing such strapping young specimens of Aryan youth, she was
awarded the Nazi's Maternal Cross in bronze. She had reportedly
once said that she could ``smell Jews,'' a comment that, when it
reached Felice via a mutual friend, challenged the playful Felice
to arrange a meeting with such a person. ``Aimee and Jaguar'' is
based on the true story of Felice Schragenheim and Lilly Wust. By
Nancy Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   AFRIQUE-DANCE (Undated) _ ``Le Coq Est Mort,'' an earnest but
problematic production that will open at the Jacob's Pillow Dance
Festival in Becket, Mass., sheds light on some of the tensions
inherent in working with people from other cultures, a practice
that is gaining favor among performing artists. By Christopher
Reardon.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SKYSCRAPER-REFORM (Undated) _ In the absence of alternatives,
there may be no more important project under way in New York right
now than David Childs' restoration of Lever House, the
International Style skyscraper on Park Avenue. Designed by Gordon
Bunshaft and completed in 1952, Lever House was the first glass
curtain wall tower to rise in New York. It remains among the 20th
century's major landmarks. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FAUST-THEATER (Hanover, Germany) _ There are two souls within
``Faust.'' ``Faust,'' Part 1, published in 1808 and a work of both
Goethe's youth and maturity, contains the well-known plot _ the
bargain of the learned Doctor Faust with Mephistopheles, the
seduction of the innocent Gretchen _ that has been echoed in
novels, movies, puppet shows and several operas. ``Faust,'' Part 2,
written in Goethe's old age and published shortly after his death
in 1832, is more abstract, disjunct, and hardly ever staged. So
when one of Germany's most celebrated theatrical directors, Peter
Stein, determined to mount a production of the complete uncut
``Faust,'' Parts 1 and 2, it became an event of national magnitude.
By Anne Midgette.
</P>
