<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3016 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ART-EXPLORATORIUM-1ST     08-04 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-EXPLORATORIUM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCIENCE MUSEUM EMBRACES ART THROUGH ANATOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Resending to correct headline)  
 (For release Sunday, August 6)  
 By TESSA DE CARLO    c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   SAN FRANCISCO
_ Since the Exploratorium was founded here 31 years ago as an
innovative ``museum of science, art and human perception,'' it has
taken pride in breaking traditional museum rules. Mixing science
exhibits and artworks with little concern about which is which, the
Exploratorium encourages a giddily high level of interactivity,
inviting visitors not just to stand and contemplate but to touch,
pump, spin or otherwise mess around with most of the 600-plus items
on display.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This summer, however, a few distinguished visitors are being
treated with decidedly old-fashioned formality.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is the ``Medical Venus,'' a lifesize and alarmingly
lifelike 18th-century Italian wax sculpture of a young beauty who
lies in a swoon on pink damask cushions. It's hardly surprising she
feels faint, since she's not only naked but cut open from stem to
stern to reveal her heart, liver and other viscera, as beautifully
made as the rest of her dainty person.
</P>
<P>
   The Venus, who hails from the Museo La Specola in Florence, is
making her first appearance in the United States as one of the star
turns in ``Revealing Bodies,'' which runs through Sept. 4. The show
uses an array of artifacts and artworks to demonstrate that our
view of human anatomy has always been informed as much by culture
as science.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in the Exploratorium's history, this
temporary exhibition has been given a traditional gallery-style
installation off to one side of the museum, acoustically and
visually segregated from the whirling, flashing, wiggling exhibits
on the cavernous main exhibition floor. Moreover, while dozens of
the exhibits in ``Revealing Bodies'' welcome participation, the
Venus and other items are tucked safely under glass _ no
interactivity allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our first attempt to do something like this, but
`Revealing Bodies' is where we're headed,'' said Kathleen McLean,
the Exploratorium's director of public programs. While more
traditional museums try to move toward greater interactivity and
livelier, less contemplative exhibitions, she said, for the
Exploratorium, doing something new and different means ``creating
more environments for focus and reflection and slowing down.''
</P>
<P>
   That strategy isn't sitting well with everyone. ``There's been a
lot of concern here among staff that we're going to slip into being
just another museum,'' McLean said. ``But I don't think very many
museums could have done the `Revealing Bodies' show.''
</P>
<P>
   For while ``Revealing Bodies'' may be straitlaced by
Exploratorium standards, its multicultural, cross-disciplinary
blend of art, science and participatory technologies is very much
in the institution's mold-breaking tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the ``Medical Venus,'' the show includes African
carved figures used in healing rituals, prosthetic legs from a
variety of eras and cultures, Ken Wilkes' elegant, horrifying
photographs of dissections, a screen that displays the heat
emanating from the viewer's body in vivid colors, historic and
contemporary X-rays and copies of astonishingly varied medical
drawings from 17th-century Persia, 16th-century Holland and 1920s
France.
</P>
<P>
   Within the relatively staid ``Revealing Bodies'' environment,
there's also plenty of hard science and a number of the kind of
interactive exhibits that the Exploratorium is famous for. For
example, visitors can draw their own silhouette, peer into the
inside of their own eyes or page through a giant flipbook-style
display of the ``Visible Humans,'' two corpses (one male, one
female) that were frozen, milled from the feet up removing a
paper-thin section at a time, photographed and reassembled as
stacks of digital images that look disturbingly like human-shaped
slices of headcheese.
</P>
<P>
   These days, when so much of contemporary art aims to subvert
rather than investigate the truth, it can be problematic to bring
art into a science museum. So if one source of internal controversy
about the ``Revealing Bodies'' show is its artiness, another is
that some of the artworks look too much like science, while turning
scientific realities topsy-turvy.
</P>
<P>
   One example is the ``Face Value'' machine created by the British
artist Alexa Wright and the computer scientist Alf Linney. ``Face
Value'' compares the viewer's face to a composite portrait of some
200 other visitors, then spits out a ``personal face reading'' that
purports to use that comparison to define character. The readings
are nonsense, of course, a commentary on our naive willingness to
trust both technology and first impressions. But Melissa Alexander,
the show's project director, said some Exploratorium staff worried
that visitors would assume that ``Face Value'' was as real as a
nearby exhibit that lets them hear their lungs at work.
</P>
<P>
   Another source of potential confusion is the New York artist
Scott Serrano's curiosity cabinet of drawings, artifacts and
photographs telling the story of a 19th-century anatomist, Wilson
Quain, a man so ``science-intoxicated'' that he took to dissecting
himself. Quain is a fiction, but on one recent afternoon several
visitors clearly believed he was a historical figure. ``How could
anyone do that to themselves?'' one mother exclaimed as she and her
child stared at a series of animated digital photographs of Quain
(played by Serrano) apparently peeling off his own face. They were
too horrified to notice that the photographs obviously dated from
the 21st rather than the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the show's juxtaposition of the fine and the
medical arts is stimulating on all fronts, highlighting the formal
beauty of the latter and the sometimes grim reality embedded in the
former. An artificial heart made of shiny metal and intricate
swirls of plastic could pass for a sinisterly futuristic sculpture.
Rosamund Purcell's stunning photograph of a dissected hand, which
on a conventional gallery wall might too easily be seen as merely
an arty novelty, becomes a moving reminder of all the ways the
living feed on the dead when it's juxtaposed with a set of three
dissected, mummified hands used as teaching aids a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The distinction between art and science didn't always exist in
our culture,'' Alexander said. ``The Venus is proof that they used
to be much closer together. And the Exploratorium was based on the
idea of not making any distinction.''
</P>
<P>
   That course was set by the museum's founder, Frank Oppenheimer,
a brilliant physicist and teacher who worked with his brother,
Robert, on the development of the atomic bomb. Where most museums
expected people to absorb information passively, like students
sitting in a lecture hall, Oppenheimer sought to create a place
that would emphasize play rather than pretension, where visitors
could do their own experiments and make their own educational
leaps. From the beginning, artists and scientists have worked side
by side in the museum's workshop, using scientific phenomena as the
basis for exhibits that inspire aesthetic delight as well as
curiosity about how the natural world works.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Exploratorium opened in 1969, its innovative ideas
have been adopted by museums all over the world. But Oppenheimer's
vision tended to scant the cultural side of the art-science
partnership, focusing more on science phenomena and less on their
social interpretations and ramifications. Moreover, the
institution's anti-museum environment _ dark, noisy and usually
full of excited children dashing from one activity to the next _
favors the didactic over the contemplative, and sometimes
hyperactivity over either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
