<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Aug. 5, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Breezes from the northwest will direct drier air into the
Northeast Saturday as high pressure builds southward from Canada.
After a cool start, abundant sunshine will cause temperatures to
rebound to near seasonal levels. Farther south, patchy clouds and
isolated thundershowers will surround a front stalled over the
Carolinas and in northern Florida. The rest of the Southeast will
be sultry with isolated mainly afternoon thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of thunderstorms will erupt over the northeast Plains
and upper Mississippi Valley as a surge of humid air intercepts a
jet stream disturbance passing overhead. Additional showers and
storms will form in the lower Ohio and Tennessee Valleys.
</P>
<P>
   The West Coast will be mainly sunny and warm, though patchy
clouds will shroud the coast. The interior West will stay hot with
isolated afternoon thundershowers.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: OUT OF AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Many of the hurricanes that strike the eastern United States are
born in Africa. In the summer and early fall dozens of clusters of
thunderstorms form in the strongly heated air near the Sahel. As
the clusters move westward, the chilly waters near Africa's west
coast are inhospitable territory for the disturbances. But, when
the high-level winds are favorable, the African disturbances can
reach the warmer waters to the west where hurricanes take shape. On
Friday, Tropical Storm Alberto sprang to life 200 miles south of
the Cape Verde Islands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
