<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3019 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV06-     08-04 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING: SHRUBS FOR BEAUTY AND HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 6)  
 (EDITORS: optional sidebar at end of article)  
 By TOVAH MARTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I once disdained cannas, but that was before I met Cleopatra.
And before encountering Aaron, I was among those who looked down on
caladiums.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we've all loosened up a bit, or perhaps summer bulbs have
improved their image. For whatever reason, summer bulbs are way
cool again.
</P>
<P>
   Until fairly recently, it seemed that cannas served mostly as
bull's eyes in the center of Victorian circles, those little
islands of blazing color stranded on the expansive lawn of the town
bank or post office.
</P>
<P>
   You saw them loitering in bedding displays, balancing their
eye-popping blossoms on top of long, spear-shaped green leaves.
But, back then, cannas were in the same category as marigolds,
bright red bedding geraniums and wax begonias.
</P>
<P>
   Well, all that has changed. Cannas are now downright trendy,
filling a new job description: punctuation marks in the perennial
garden. Polite society may still frown on parading cannas in ribbon
borders, but a well-placed canna or two as an accent among more
discreet perennials is usually applauded.
</P>
<P>
   With one little difference. Nowadays, many gardeners snip off
the bright orange, patriotic scarlet or school-bus-yellow blossoms.
Although the Victorians put considerable effort into breeding
low-maintenance orchid-size blossoms that drop off after they
bloom, that trait is no longer the main draw. Instead, it's the
side show that gardeners now find appealing. Somewhere back in the
19th century, one of the orchid-flowering cannas that became known
as Cleopatra had burgundy-striped leaves. It also had harlequin
yellow, red or spotted flowers side by side in the same umbel. The
Victorians liked that sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, breeders have enhanced the leaf colors, resulting
in such popular hybrids as Pretoria (alias Bengal Tiger) with
yellow-striped foliage. If a 6-foot plant is more than you can
handle, there are ``dwarf'' versions, like Striped Beauty and
Striata, with all the visual kicks but condensed to a relatively
compact 4 feet. Alice McGowan of Blue Meadow Farm in Montague
Center, Mass., which specializes in rare annuals and perennials,
said that Striata is a best seller in their catalog, second only to
Panache.
</P>
<P>
   Why is Panache popular? ``Because it has discreet, cream-colored
blossoms,'' she said. ``Some people still retain their longstanding
prejudice, but cannas are rising in popularity, just like coleus.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for several other summer bulbs. Take
colocasias, for example. Brent Heath of Brent &AMP; Becky's Bulbs in
Gloucester, Va., which specializes in bulbs for all seasons, said
colocasias are so popular now that they can't keep them in stock.
Commonly known as elephant's ear because of its enormous foliage,
which is deeply veined and billows in breezes, Colocasia esculenta
was another denizen of shady Victorian circles _ surrounded by
impatiens or ferns, perhaps. It is now used in containers,
especially the Cranberry Taro, with its dark red veins, and Black
Magic, with its lustrous purplish black leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Heath never met a bulb he didn't like. But he ranks caladiums
high on his roster of up-and-comers. Like colocasias, they have
seemed like too much of a good thing for many gardeners. These
shade-loving, heart-leaved plants were splashed, spangled and zoned
with several different colors.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the older varieties scorched easily. Recently,
the Florida series has produced thicker-leaved, light-tolerant
versions. In addition, many quieter hybrids are now on the market,
like the luminous white-veined Aaron and rose-veined Florida
Sweetheart.
</P>
<P>
   Flashy leaves are part of the lure, but flowers are definitely a
factor.
</P>
<P>
   Dahlias, too, have hit their stride again. But they're not quite
as buxom as the versions that were coddled in greenhouses a century
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lilies never really lagged in popularity, but calla lilies have
been subject to fashion's yo-yo. Perhaps for good reason: in
gardens north of New York, flowers rarely arrive before frost
threatens.
</P>
<P>
   New varieties, however, have intriguing leaves as well as a
blossom or two before the time comes to dig the bulbs up and
transform them into houseplants.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, tuberoses often fail to fit their cycle into our
growing season.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Heath's solution is to start them indoors in April on a
heat mat. ``All summer bulbs like warmth,'' he explained, ``and
most prefer moisture. Given that, they'll thrive.''
</P>
<P>
   Calla lilies and tuberoses aside, however, most bulbs perform
just when you need them to. Indeed, one reason for summer bulbs'
new popularity might be that most of them swing into action
immediately in hot weather, filling the gap when the garden is
mired in midsummer lull.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't mind the chore of digging the bulbs up in autumn
and bringing them into a frost-free place, few plants could be
easier to please than amaryllis-like crinums or spider-shaped
hymenocallis. For a splash of midseason color, just add a
crocosmia, with its long wands of bright tubular blossoms jutting
from iris-like leaves. If you yearn for fragrance as well, opt for
acidanthera, recently redesignated as Gladiolus callianthus, with
white maroon-marked nodding star-shaped blossoms on long spikes, a
19th-century heirloom that has slipped back into the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to another summer bulb that has yet to be
re-embraced: gladiolus. Tall, elegant, great for cut flowers and
easy to grow if you don't mind staking stately spires dense with
blossoms in all colors of the rainbow, gladioluses have one major
strike against them, which is that many people associate them with
funeral parlors.
</P>
<P>
   But the way I figure it, if cannas overcame the obstructions of
taste, can glads be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   THIS WEEK: Plan Future Blooms &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By PATRICIA JONAS
</P>
<P>
   Bearded iris should be divided every four years after flowering;
this can be done through early August. Cut out and discard any
sections damaged by rot or iris borer. Dip healthy three- to 4-inch
pieces of rhizome in a mild bleach solution or dust with fungicide
and replant so that the top of the rhizome is just covered with
soil.
</P>
<P>
   It is not too late to order Autumn crocus (Colchicum) for fall
bloom: Colchicum speciosum Album, a large weather-resistant white,
and C. Waterlily, with double pinkish lilac flowers that do right
by their name, are two to try.
</P>
<P>
   Autumn crocus also refers to the true crocuses that bloom then,
including Saffron crocus (Crocus sativus). They require full sun
and are generally more persnickety about being well drained than
Colchicum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
