<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3020 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ORPHANED-BRANDS-ART-8     08-04 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORPHANED-BRANDS-ART-865(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETING AGAINST A GIANT WITH ITS DISCARDED BRAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KRUTI TRIVEDI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Todd Wichmann and Richard Owen barreled into the
Procter &AMP; Gamble headquarters last month and were about to head
upstairs when the security guard stopped them.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for permission to enter a place where they had worked
almost all their adult lives felt ``bizarre-weird,'' Wichmann
(pronounced WICK-man) said as he fiddled with his red visitor's
badge.
</P>
<P>
   He and Owen had just quit their jobs at P&AMP;G to form Redox Brands
Inc., a company that specializes in buying once-famous laundry and
cleaning brands that giants like their former employer are
discarding. Their first _ and so far only _ purchase was Procter &AMP;
Gamble's Oxydol laundry detergent brand, in a deal that calls for
P&AMP;G to continue to be involved in the product. The financial terms
of the deal have not been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Redox's timing could not be better: Behemoths like
P&AMP;G, hoping to assuage Wall Street's anxiety over sagging earnings,
are becoming more aggressive in dropping brands that are no longer
among the market leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But building a strong company out of a collection of jilted
labels is tough going. Other companies, notably in the food
industry, have tried; few have succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying an orphaned brand isn't necessarily a challenge,'' said
David A. Goldman, director of equity research at SunTrust Equitable
Securities. ``Consolidating them into one entity that makes sense,
has operational efficiencies, and has critical mass, well, that's
another matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, many industry experts say, giants like Procter &AMP; Gamble
do not shed brands unless they have a good reason to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Although P&AMP;G would not comment on its relationship with Redox or
the specifics of the deal, it said in a prepared statement that
Oxydol, which represented a minute portion of company sales, ``no
longer provided a strategic fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Oxydol was P&AMP;G's oldest brand of laundry detergent, introduced
in 1927. While it has a long history _ it even sponsored the ``Ma
Perkins'' radio show, the first so-called soap opera, in 1933 _
naysayers doubt that a rich heritage convinces consumers to buy a
detergent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is: Is Oxydol such an ancient brand that it is
valueless and not worth it to revive it?'' said Clive Chajet of
Chajet Consultancy, a branding consultant in New York. ``As far as
I'm concerned, they're starting from scratch in a category where
it's hard to differentiate one brand from another.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Oxydol have been sinking over the decade and are
dwarfed by those of the market leader, P&AMP;G's Tide.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all this, Wichmann, 30, and Owen, 31, are convinced they
will succeed. Their aim is to increase Oxydol's share of the $6
billion market for liquid and powdered detergent to 2 percent in
the next five years from its current 0.1 percent. (By comparison,
Wichmann said, Tide now has around 35 percent of the market.)
</P>
<P>
   Though they are dealing in an old-economy business, they say,
they are helped by some new-economy factors. The expansion of
contract sales makes it easier for them to hire a company to sell
their products. Internet technology allows them to hold ``virtual''
meetings with business contacts, slashing travel costs.
</P>
<P>
   And as companies like Procter &AMP; Gamble and Unilever scramble to
shed old brands, Wichmann and Owen have a steady stream of product
offerings from which to choose. In addition to Oxydol, for example,
P&AMP;G recently put Biz, a bleach detergent, up for sale. (Wichmann
and Owen would not comment on whether Redox was considering
acquiring it.)
</P>
<P>
   Wichmann, the Redox president, and Owen, the chief operating
officer, also say they have two distinct tactical advantages.
</P>
<P>
   First, instead of buying the leader in small markets _ a model
exemplified by Aurora Foods Inc., which has bought brands including
Duncan Hines, Log Cabin and Van de Kamp's, with some success _ they
will buy small brands in large markets. That way, they can focus on
competing for customers rather than trying to expand a market.
</P>
<P>
   Second, they can tailor their packaging and pricing to fit the
needs of smaller retailers, something that larger, bureaucratized
companies cannot do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago or even five years ago, there was no way to
do what we're doing,'' Wichmann said. ``We want to be a virtual
organization. We don't want any plants. We don't want any money
going to fixed assets.''
</P>
<P>
   He can make such a bold statement in part because he has P&AMP;G in
his corner.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Procter &AMP; Gamble, arguably the American
consumer-products company with the greatest influence among
retailers, will still take care of the ordering, shipping and
billing systems used for Oxydol, which will continue to be made at
a P&AMP;G plant. It also has an undisclosed minority stake in the
company. Redox, based in the Cincinnati suburb of West Chester,
Ohio, will be making the strategic decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Wichmann and Owen acknowledge that their former employer
influences their decisions. ``Our relationship with P&AMP;G is very
important and we do live by their rules,'' Wichmann said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Though bitten early by the entrepreneurial bug, the two men
were, after all, trained by the company whose employees are widely
known as ``Proctoids,'' distinguished by their efficiency and
obedience.
</P>
<P>
   Owen and Wichmann met as interns at the company in the summer of
1991, both researching laundry detergents. They cemented their
relationship when they returned after graduating the next year.
Though both started at P&AMP;G as chemical engineers, Wichmann, who
worked on Oxydol early, later went into marketing while Owen joined
the sales and finance side.
</P>
<P>
   They started business school together in 1994, attending Xavier
University at night. For their final project, the pair designed
American Detergent Corp., a hypothetical company that bought Oxydol
from Procter &AMP; Gamble _ a brand they said they chose somewhat
randomly.
</P>
<P>
   Their professor, Sandy Eustis, was impressed by their enthusiasm
but did not like their business plan. He voiced concerns that have
since been echoed by Redox's critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Why would you want to go into a business that's
dominated by huge players?''' recalled Eustis, who is now executive
director of the Center for Adaptive Management, a nonprofit
research group in Cincinnati. ``It's a slow-growth, mature industry
dominated by large players who spend huge sums of money on consumer
marketing and advertising, and that presents real difficulties for
a smaller, entrepreneurial company.''
</P>
<P>
   The two were not deterred. When the announcement of the Oxydol
sale popped up on the office intranet in March, Wichmann knew he
had to talk to Owen.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G had long neglected Oxydol; the detergent did not even have
the company's fixture of a brand manager to baby-sit the product.
Though P&AMP;G did not see much of a future for the brand, the two men
did.
</P>
<P>
   While he drove home on the night of the announcement, Wichmann
called Owen from his cell phone. All he needed to say was ``Hey
Rich, American Detergent Corporation might be in business.''
</P>
<P>
   As they hatched their plans over the weekend, Wichmann said,
they found themselves in a chicken-and-egg scenario.
</P>
<P>
   They had to convince P&AMP;G to sell the brand to them instead of to
an established company with deep pockets. ``We knew we needed to
have a big angle for Procter &AMP; Gamble to want to do this,'' Owen
said. ``This thing had to be much bigger than just Oxydol.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that, they needed to assure P&AMP;G that they had strong
backers. But to get those backers, they had to convince venture
capitalists that P&AMP;G was intent on completing the sale. They also
needed to keep their identity a secret so that if the deal did not
go through, they would still have their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really was this covert operation going on,'' Owen said.
Wichmann decided they needed some outside help, so he called
Eustis, who referred him to Robert Buechner, a childhood basketball
buddy and Cincinnati lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer was intrigued with their idea. He helped them write
an anonymous bid and began introducing them to venture capitalists,
bankers and accountants.
</P>
<P>
   During their lunch breaks and before and after work, Wichmann
and Owen would meet with potential backers. They decided to wear
khakis and shirts, the unofficial Procter &AMP; Gamble uniform, to
those meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you wear a suit at Procter and Gamble, that's a sign you're
interviewing,'' Wichmann said. ``I didn't want to tip my hand.''
</P>
<P>
   After two months of sub rosa maneuvering they had to reveal that
they were the anonymous bidders for Oxydol at P&AMP;G's demand. The two
made a point of telling their respective bosses on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually had one of my bosses say, `Rich, have you thought
this through?'' Owen said. ```What happens if Procter &AMP; Gamble
considers you a competitor?' I thought, I've got my family and my
resume.''
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G was impressed by their plan. Company officials even spoke to
venture capitalists on their behalf, the pair said, and a group of
investors led by Meriwether Capital Corp. in New York agreed to
finance Redox. The deal for Oxydol was completed in a month, and
both men were allowed to keep their jobs until it was done.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Owen and Wichmann have been busy preparing Oxydol for
the first Redox ship date this September. And in a recent
conference call, they discovered some of the difficulties of being
so closely tied to Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   For every 600 boxes sold, the two men want to give retailers 300
boxes free. P&AMP;G's system is not configured to handle free boxes, so
they have to find another way to distribute them. They are also
working on formulating a liquid detergent, and preparing a radio
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, they are trying to establish their own identity,
separate from Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Their first trip back to P&AMP;G went well. Former colleagues kept
dropping by, curious about how Owen and Wichmann were making out in
what they call ``the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   While they were getting ready to leave their meeting, Owen
noticed a small green packet of Oxydol on the shelf. ``You guys
were supposed to turn over all of the product!'' he teased the P&AMP;G
representative. She and the partners shared a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked toward the elevator, Owen slipped the Oxydol packet
into his back pocket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
