<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3026 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CONCORDE-NYT &LR;      08-04 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCORDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCORDE BRINGS AIRLINES ADVANTAGES THAT ARE HARD TO QUANTIFY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: See also CONCORDE-CRASH.)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The crash of the Air France supersonic Concorde brought
down a plane that by common measurements can hardly be profitable,
given its high maintenance costs, daunting fuel bills, little
passenger space, and no cargo. Yet any decision to permanently
ground the Concorde could have deep financial implications for the
two airlines that run it.
</P>
<P>
   Airline industry analysts say the Concorde is part of a sweeping
strategy, particularly by British Airways, to lure high-end
corporate travelers, the favored target of airlines, to the
Concorde's speedy flights between the financial capitals of London
and New York, and to connecting flights on slower aircraft beyond.
Its loss, they say, would divert these customers to other airlines,
notably in the United States, or to corporate jet travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps to tie in your very high-end customers,'' said Damien
Horth, an analyst at ABN-Amro in London.
</P>
<P>
   Neither airline has suggested it would quit flying the Concorde
because of the crash, the first deadly accident in the plane's
25-year history. But talk that the Concorde has outlived its
usefulness has persisted, and no other supersonic jetliners are in
development.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris Friday, Air France employees called on the airline to
resume flying the remaining six Concordes, which were grounded by
the French transport ministry until experts can clarify the cause
of the crash July 25 that killed 113 people.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways resumed its Concorde flights the day after the
crash, but its Concordes have been flying half empty since then,
and mechanical and safety issues have haunted nearly every flight.
On Tuesday, for instance, the London-New York flight was delayed 75
minutes because of an engine problem and the passengers had to
board a second Concorde, losing most of the time they would have
gained because of the plane's high speed.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from the Concorde is estimated to account for only 1
percent to 2 percent of the total at Air France, and slightly more
at British Airways. Yet Robin Horne, an analyst at HSBC Securities
in London, says neither airline is entirely open about the
Concorde's financial performance, and he believes that the planes
``don't make much money.''
</P>
<P>
   Depreciation _ the decreased value of something because of wear
and tear _ has never been a factor in accounting for the operating
cost of the Concorde, as it is for other aircraft. The reason is
that the planes were in effect given to the airlines by the British
and French governments, which footed the bill for their
development.
</P>
<P>
   Yet almost alone among commercial jetliners, the Concorde
carries a cockpit crew of three instead of two, and it lacks cargo
capacity. Crew members work fewer hours than on subsonic planes,
and their training is almost twice as long as that of other pilots,
and hence more costly.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Concorde is more expensive to maintain. British
Airways says its seven Concordes get up to 57 hours of maintenance
for every hour in the air, far more than what is accorded subsonic
aircraft. Fuel consumption, too, makes them expensive to run. The
Concorde burns about 4,670 gallons of kerosene for every hour of
flight, compared with 2,340 gallons for the Boeing 747-400,
Boeing's biggest aircraft. Yet the 747 carries roughly 400
passengers, four times that of the Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, many analysts believe that a modern Boeing 747 or 777,
with several dozen first-class passengers, who pay only about 20
percent less than on the Concorde, easily earns as much as or more
than a Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure how profitable they are,'' said Matthew Stainer,
an analyst at SG Securities. Given its gas-guzzling habits, he
added, the Concorde has felt the brunt of recent increases in
airline fuel prices ``more than most of the fleet.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, despite its marginal profitability, analysts say the
Concorde more than earns its keep, at least for British Airways, by
its ability to draw large numbers of first-class and business-class
travelers, who pay high premiums. Cutting the Concorde out of the
fleet, said Daniel Solon, director of Avmark International, a
London airline consulting firm, would expose the airlines to a
``double hazard.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it is hard to quantify, as economies globalized and New
York and London emerged in recent years as the world's principal
financial centers, British Airways has capitalized on increased
traffic between Wall Street and the City, London's financial
district _ effectively using the Concorde to lure what some
analysts refer to as the ``Goldman Sachs crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly on westbound traffic, analysts said, the Concorde
is attractive to corporate executives and investment bankers since
it enables them to cheat the clock, arriving in New York at an
earlier local hour than they left London or Paris.
</P>
<P>
   A further inducement to the premium traveler has been the
Concorde service's preferential treatment of passengers that
expedites them through customs, passport control and baggage
checking, and offers them a traveling environment closer to that of
a corporate jet, yet at supersonic speed.
</P>
<P>
   But both British Airways and Air France have also been able to
attract premium travelers from farther afield, enabling customers
from, say, Dubai or Moscow, to travel to London or Paris, then take
the Concorde on to New York. ``Concorde is a fantastic marketing
tool for BA,'' said HSBC's Horne.
</P>
<P>
   Without the Concorde, to be sure, some of these travelers would
shift to subsonic flights offered by British Airways or Air France.
But experts like Solon believe many would instead use corporate
jets. Others, particularly Americans, would desert British Airways
and Air France, preferring to fly their customary United States
airline, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
