   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ American companies added fewer new jobs
in July than economists had expected, further lessening the chances
that the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates when it meets
later this month. In the latest sign that economic growth is
slowing, the nation's unemployment rate remained unchanged at 4
percent as private sector payrolls grew by 138,000, about half the
number that most analysts had predicted. The employment numbers
offered the first picture of the economy's performance in July, and
economists predicted that the Federal Reserve's policy-making
committee will decide on Aug. 22 that it does not need to raise
interest rates in order to cool the economy. By David Leonhardt.
