   BARNEYS-QUESTROM (Undated) _ When troubled retailer J.C. Penney
announced last week that Allen L. Questrom would be its new chief
executive, Wall Street was euphoric. Investor enthusiasm stems in
large part from the work that Questrom did reviving ailing public
companies like Federated Department Stores and Macy's, which
Federated acquired under his leadership. But in the most recent
chapter of his career, as chairman and chief executive of Barney's
New York Inc., it is less clear that the veteran turnaround man has
spun straw into gold. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   Here are tonight's columns and regular features:
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks ended higher Friday after the
government reported that private job growth was slower than
expected last month. The data appears to make an interest rate
increase by the Federal Reserve later this month less likely. And
the slowing job growth helps confirm the belief of some analysts
that the central bank will not need any more rate increases later
this year to slow economic growth to a non-inflationary pace. By
Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Digest of the day's financial stories.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
