<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3029 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-MUM-BOS &LR;      08-04 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITONS, FETING QUEEN MUM, 100, RECALL THE EMPIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Goodness, what will they do if the Queen Mother makes
it to 101 next year?
</P>
<P>
   Friday, as Britain's beloved Queen Mum turned 100, it seemed as
if the Empire was in full bloom and Queen Victoria was still riding
through London's streets in a horse-drawn carriage.
</P>
<P>
   But those days are gone, so it was left to the Queen Mum, by far
the most popular royal and the first member of her family to reach
the century mark, to wave from her open carriage as she journeyed
from her home at Clarence House down The Mall to Buckingham Palace
for her birthday lunch with her daughter, Queen Elizabeth II.
</P>
<P>
   Police said 40,000 people lined the route, then serenaded the
Queen Mum with a chorus of ``Happy Birthday'' when she stepped onto
the palace balcony, surrounded by four generations of a royal
family that has survived a turbulent century.
</P>
<P>
   For all the hoopla, the most recent polls show that support for
the monarchy is slipping, as Britons become less bound by the
long-held traditions. While the republican ideal of abolishing the
monarchy and installing an elected head of state still seems a long
way off, neither is the monarchy anywhere as secure as when
Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon, the Queen Mum, was born in the last year of
Queen Victoria's reign.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrations, capping a month of commemorations, seemed as
much about shoring up the monarchy as they were about the birthday
golden girl.
</P>
<P>
   The Queen Mum embodies many admired qualities of the British:
stoicism in the face of overwhelming circumstances,
straightforwardness, fierce loyalty to king and country. One
brother was killed in World War I; another was taken prisoner. She
never complained.
</P>
<P>
   When her husband had to assume the throne after his brother,
King Edward VIII, abdicated to marry American divorcee Wallis
Simpson, the Queen Mum helped the stuttering new king by holding
his hand and calming him. But, despite her trademark smile, the
Queen Mum was a formidable enemy. It was she who insisted that
Edward and Simpson remain in exile.
</P>
<P>
   The Queen Mum won the enduring admiration of Britons when she
refused to seek refuge outside London during the Blitz. She also
refused to ship off her two daughters to escape the war's
hardships. Her visits to bombed-out Londoners, standing in high
heels amid the rubble of the East End, were extraordinary
propaganda during the darkest days of World War II. Recognizing
this perhaps, Adolf Hilter once called her ``the most dangerous
woman in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   But being so rooted in something that occurred more than a half
century ago also explains why a growing number of Britons don't
care about the Queen Mum, much less the rest of the royals. On
Thursday a 17-year-old who pleaded guilty to trashing a McDonald's
restaurant in London during an anti-capitalism demonstration three
months ago appeared in court wearing a T-shirt emblazoned with the
slogan, ``Queen Mum, hurry up and die.'' The teen attended Eton,
the exclusive school that has educated many an aristocrat and whose
current students include Princes William and Harry, the sons of the
late Diana, Princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
   Such disrespect would have been unthinkable just a generation
ago, especially from an Eton student. But Britain is changing, even
if, it appears, the Queen Mum never did.
</P>
<P>
   The divisions between traditionalists and reformers is reflected
in how newspapers have handled the Queen Mum's birthday. The
conservative Daily Telegraph has run story after story, and picture
after picture, as part of its exhaustive coverage of the Queen Mum.
It has been rare to pick up a Telegraph over the last year and not
find a photograph or story about the Queen Mum.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Telegraph, the Times, the other conservative
broadsheet, published a supplement with numerous photographs of and
stories about the Queen Mum, who has given only one interview in
her 100 years on earth, in 1923.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, The Guardian, the leading liberal newspaper, which
makes no secret of its wish to ditch the monarchy, ran a story to
celebrate the 11 other Britons who turned 100 Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Preston, the Guardian's former editor, recently wrote a
novel predicting the demise of the monarchy, suggesting Elizabeth
II will be the last monarch.
</P>
<P>
   Such republican sentiments seemed overly optimistic as the
British, some of whom spent the night in sleeping bags outside
Buckingham Palace to get a good seat, cheered the Queen Mum. She
rewarded them with her trademark wave and smile. That smile reveals
a set of ungainly teeth, untouched by cosmetic dental work,
evidence of the lack of pretense that endears her to millions of
ordinary Britons.
</P>
<P>
   At the Queen's annual garden party at the rear of Buckingham
Palace last summer, the Queen and her husband, Philip, the Duke of
Edinburgh, were politely applauded as they walked through the
assembled masses of guests. But when the Queen Mum, still
recovering from hip surgery, gamely made her way across the great
lawn with a cane, the applause grew louder and everyone smiled. The
applause for the Queen was perfunctory; the applause for her mother
was heartfelt.
</P>
<P>
   The Queen Mum has no secret to her longevity, though she is fond
of a gin and Dubonnet before lunch. She is a horse racing fanatic,
and devours the novels of Dick Francis, the jockey-turned-author
who makes sure she gets the first copy of his racetrack thrillers.
She is, according to those who know her, a formidable woman of
considered opinions. With palace approval, the Telegraph recently
ran a collection of those opinions.
</P>
<P>
   On hearing the national anthem on television, she urged a
companion to turn it off, saying, ``So embarrassing unless one is
there. Like hearing the Lord's Prayer when playing canasta.''
</P>
<P>
   She was unimpressed when T.S. Eliot gave her and her family a
private reading of his poem ``The Waste Land.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had this rather lugubrious man in a suit, and he read a
poem _ I think it was called The Desert _ and first the girls got
the giggles, and then I did, and then even the king. Such a gloomy
man,'' she said of Eliot. ``Looked as though he worked in a bank,
and we didn't understand a word.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, when she learned that her supper would be late because
the kitchen staff, some of whom are gay, were having an argument,
she icily replied, ``My compliments to the old queens down there,
but this old queen is hungry and wants her dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she was said to never have been overbearing, she remains
a mother as much as a Queen Mum. When the Queen once asked for a
second glass of wine with her lunch, the Queen Mum shot her a look
and a subtle admonishment: ``You know you have to reign all
afternoon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
