<SLUG> BC-BUSSTOP-WEDDING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S A BUS STOP FOR? A WEDDING, OF COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMAL E. WATSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He was standing in the pouring rain at the corner of
Massachusetts Avenue and St. Stephen Street on March 14, 1997
waiting for MBTA bus number one to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   As his eyes wandered in search of his ride home, he spotted her
_ a woman in a dark raincoat with a warm, wide smile and long,
lovely black hair.
</P>
<P>
   She, too, was waiting for the bus. They started talking, mostly
about music, and there was a hint of a spark. So they exchanged
telephone numbers. He called and slowly, over strolls through the
Back Bay and concerts at Symphony Hall, they fell in love.
</P>
<P>
   Now, three years and five months after a chance encounter on a
gloomy winter's day, Michael Gandolfi, 44, and Maria Martinello,
38, are about to become husband and wife.
</P>
<P>
   But when they exchange vows Sunday, it won't be inside a church
or at city hall. No, there is really only one place where it could
happen: The same bus stop in the shadow of Symphony Hall where they
met.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immediately after I asked Maria to marry me, I had this crazy
idea that we should get married at the bus stop,'' said Gandolfi, a
music composer and teacher at the New England Conservatory of Music
who also has composed for the Boston Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Martinello said she quickly embraced her finace's untraditional
idea for their nuptials, inspired by Gandolfi's passion for the
work of Luis Bunuel, the Spanish-Mexican surrealist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted this to be done in the right spirit,'' said
Martinello, a graduate student at Harvard University. ``We wanted
to have fun with what we're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   So instead of the usual hoity-toity, expensive invitations, the
couple sent computer-generated bus tickets to family and friends
asking them to make their reservations early.
</P>
<P>
   The 45 guests will arrive for the wedding by bus, of course. And
while a real MBTA bus could not be procured, the chartered bus
picking up guests in Watertown, will be decorated to look like the
familiar yellow and white public buses.
</P>
<P>
   The bus company even found an MBTA bus driver who agreed to don
his uniform and transport the bride and groom to the wedding and to
the reception in Watertown.
</P>
<P>
   When the bus arrives at the stop where he met his bride,
Gandolfi will emerge in a tuxedo. Martinello, who will wear a white
wedding dress, will ride to the ceremony in a separate car.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Gandolfi's close friends will be by his side as he wraps
a flower around the bus stop sign, signaling to Martinello to begin
the processional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll walk up Massachusetts Avenue, wait for the red light, and
cross at Huntington Avenue,'' Martinello said. ``I'll come up to
the bus stop and Michael will be waiting for me. Everyone on the
bus will be able to see me through the windows.''
</P>
<P>
   Once united at the stop, the two will step on board the faux
number one bus and be united by Osvaldo Golijov
</P>
<P>
   Golijov is neither a preacher nor a judge, but was granted
special authority by Governor Paul Cellucci to preside over the
ceremony under a state policy that allows anyone to perform a
wedding. The policy involves a long application process and gives a
person permission to officiate at a state-sanctioned wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little nervous,'' said Golijov, a composer and a close
friend of Gandolfi. ``This is the first time that I've performed a
wedding, but I think this is so beautiful. It's like giving
significance to something that is very significant to them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Gandolfi underwent an ``instant transformation'' after
meeting Martinello. ``You would have to witness it to believe it,''
he said. ``He's so excited.''
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony will be be conducted in English and Spanish
Martinello is from Venezuela.) and will last about 10 minutes _
less time than it usually takes to wait for the number one bus.
</P>
<P>
   The lovers will read poems they have written for the occassion.
The obvious musical selection should be the Hollies hit, ``Bus
Stop,'' about meeting the girl of one's dreams at a bus stop.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Martinello's friend will sing a song she composed about
a man and a woman who discover each other at the bus stop.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday will be special not only for Martinello but also for her
80-year-old mother, who flew from Venezuela to see her daughter
marry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first told her, she paused for a long minute and then
she said, `Oh, I think that's OK,' '' Martinello said.
</P>
<P>
   Gandolfi, who has planned a honeymoon in Rio de Janeiro, two
days after the wedding, interjected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait for Sunday to get here,'' he said. ``It's the
incongrunity of this that I just love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
