<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV06-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LOSERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 06, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In handling the GOP's extremists so effectively last week,
George W. Bush set forth a vision of the Republican party as he
wants it to be eight years from now, not the way it is today. It
may gain him the opportunity to try to make it so.
</P>
<P>
   All the bitter divisions that made it possible for Bill Clinton
and the Democrats to govern for eight years were glossed over, for
a time. Tax cranks, culture warriors, isolationsts, Clinton haters:
the tempestuous souls who made such a shambles of Republican
conventions for the last 12 years simply were excluded from a
convention role.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, Jack Kemp, Pete Wilson, Ross Perot, Newt Gingrich,
Henry Hyde, Kenneth Starr, Bill Bennett, Pat Buchanan, Jerry
Falwell, Pat Robertson, were scarcely to be seen. Even campaign
finance-reformer John McCain, accorded a prime-time speaking spot
Tuesday night, was banished on the final day to Washington -- until
Bush staffers called him back.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush is elected, he'll get a chance to try to keep his
factions in line. At the very least, he dispelled any lingering
doubts that he is not in charge. Before passing on to the
Democrats, however, let's take a look at how the Losers (at least
the opinion-makers among them) spent the week.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bartley passed the evenings doing on-line chats with
readers of the editorial page of the Wall Street Journal on its new
web site, www.opinionjournal.com. The editor of the page since
1972, Bartley attacked Bill Clinton with implacable fury from the
very first. But this spring the editor-for-life moved on to a
weekly column.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, deputy Daniel Henninger has taken over much daily
management, and the page is adulterating the purity of its views in
some interesting ways. It still permitted itself an outraged wheeze
last week on behalf of ``the missing managers'' -- Henry Hyde and
the other leaders of the impeachment trial, who were forbidden any
role in the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Amity Shlaes, a Journal editorial page alumna who now writes a
column for the Financial Times, attended a rump Republican
convention in a seaside New Jersey town. There, she reported, a
hundred ``furious'' congressmen, local activists, think-tank
authors and donors did ``what Republicans do when no cameras are
around: grumble, roar and plot revolt.''
</P>
<P>
   They also listened to Schlaes' theory of why the party does best
when operating with a bunker mentality. ``The Democrats enjoy
support from America's unions,'' she wrote. ``In contrast,
Republicans have no automatic electoral base, and must convince
voters anew in every campaign. Nothing works better to achieve this
than firebreathing.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the party of Big Business.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in the conservative ``Weekly Standard,'' executive
editor Fred Barnes explained why ``California Doesn't Matter any
More.'' The short answer is that it's gone Democratic. With one
fifth of the electoral votes necessary to win the presidency, only
a landslide for Bush will put it in the Republican column --in
which case the candidate doesn't need it. The election will be won
in the Midwest, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. The longer hypothesis of California's supposed
irrelevance was little less convincing. Barnes has determined that
the future no longer happens in California. ``Until the 1990s, the
state previewed practically everything that happened in America,
both socially and politically,'' he wrote. Urban violence. White
backlash. Tax-cut fever. Term limits. Richard Nixon. Ronald Reagan.
They all began in California.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1996 governor Pete Wilson sought to become the third
California Republican to make it to the White House on a new,
cutting-edge platform: anti-affirmative action, anti-immigration,
anti-gay.
</P>
<P>
   He never made it past the first round of primaries, and the
Republican party in California was crushed. From 40 percent of the
Latino vote in 1994, the GOP share of the California vote dropped
to 17 percent in 1998. Blacks and gays similarly turned away.
</P>
<P>
   The California disaster _ Congressional redistricting in 2002
may by itself to return control of the House of Representatives to
the Democrats -- had more to do than any other factor with the
resolutely inclusive tone of last week's Republican convention. The
country's Latino population is skyrocketing. The Republicans cannot
afford to ignore, much less alienate, what had previously been a
relatively conservative bloc of votes.
</P>
<P>
   There is, in fact, still plenty of radicalism in the mainstream
Republican Party. Its economists have declared war on the mixed
economy, taking aim at Social Security in particular. But that is
another story.
</P>
<P>
   By showing that he can handle his party's zealots, George W.
Bush has given himself a good chance to win the presidency. But the
strategy is not without its risks. As William Safire of the New
York Times _ another of the big Losers _ put it last week, ``If
Bush's smiling-in-lockstep strategy backfires, the next GOP
convention may be much livelier.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough. But if Gore wins _ or even if the GOP Losers escape
from the purdah to which Bush has sent them _ the next Republican
convention may not matter very much either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3035 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-TALISMAN-CHIC-ART-$AD     08-04 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALISMAN-CHIC-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVIL BEGONE! MY JEWELRY SAYS SO! 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Aug. 6) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By RUTH LA FERLA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until recently, Nadja Swarovski wore a bracelet of rose quartz
beads said to bring the wearer luck in love. ``But it was no use at
all,'' she complained. So these days Swarovski, the New York
representative of an Austrian crystal company founded by her
family, puts her faith in a wide mesh cuff that might have come
straight out of ``Gladiator.''
</P>
<P>
   In her arsenal of charms, the outsize bauble is an item of heavy
artillery. ``It makes me think of Wonder Woman _ I find it very
empowering,'' said Swarovski, who wears the cuff in the hope it
will give her an aura of Glamazonian invulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   When Estelle Leeds, a New York photo agent, needs a little boost
from the spirit world, she piles on jade bracelets, whose soothing
green hue is believed in the Far East to possess healing qualities.
The magic of such amulets may be mostly in the wearer's mind, but
don't tell that to Leeds. ``Jade has had a good effect on my
business,'' she insisted. ``Since I've worn it, I seem to get a lot
more work.''
</P>
<P>
   Both women are members of the vastly expanding tribe of New
Yorkers who, trusting nothing to chance, attempt to ward off evil
or beguile the gods by draping themselves in exotic beads and
talismans. Beetles and Buddhas, scarabs, pentagrams and pale pink
quartz _ any of these may function as a symbol of sincere religious
belief. But in the age of Spirituality Lite, they are also likely
to attest to the wearer's inner grooviness, just as her Jimmy Choo
mules speak of her up-to-date chic.
</P>
<P>
   Which might go a way toward explaining why they have lately cast
their spell not just on neo-hippies, religious seekers and the
doggedly contrarian souls who first gave them cachet in the 1960s,
but also on fashion addicts and otherwise conventional types with
no particular New Age creed.
</P>
<P>
   So ubiquitous is the second group that a random survey in Times
Square the other day turned up no fewer than one in four passersby
wearing some interpretation of a charm or amulet _ jewelry believed
by some cultures to be imbued with magic to ward off evil or bring
good luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``You certainly see a lot of this jewelry _ everything from
Egyptian ankhs to Celtic and Druid symbols,'' said Richard Leonard,
a vice president at the Zandl Group, a New York youth-marketing
firm, whose clients include the Limited. ``Whether people are
buying them for their aesthetic value or their spiritual heritage
I'm not sure, but talismans and charms have definitely crossed into
the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   At boutiques and gift shops, in airports and on street corners,
charm vendors are springing up like ragweed, selling Mideastern
Hands of Fatima and miniature Chinese turtles, alongside knockoffs
of last year's wildly popular crystal-beaded power bracelet.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;M, the cheap-chic emporium on Fifth Avenue, peddles a version
of the power bracelet that is so cheap ($2) that shoppers buy them
by the fistful. The store also offers geometric-beaded chokers and
feathered necklaces that look as if they had been pilfered from a
Native American burial ground.
</P>
<P>
   Kirna Zabete, MZ Wallace and Hedra Prue are among the downtown
Manhattan purveyors of hip who keep reinventing the lucky charm
genre. Their inventory includes crystal drop ``energy'' earrings
and pendants, and the latest twist on the power bracelet, a slender
piece of rawhide or scarlet ribbon meant to stay knotted on the
wrist until the wearer's wish comes true.
</P>
<P>
   Kamuti Kiteme, the president and co-founder of Polyverse, an
Internet company, rarely removes his Buddha pendant, a small gold
charm that was a gift from his kick-boxing partner. ``Call it a
luck charm, if you will,'' he said. ``It keeps bad things from
happening to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Desmond Morris, the social anthropologist and author of ``Body
Guards'' (Elements, 1999), a coffee-table book about amulets, said
in an interview that, judging by the masses of New Yorkers and
Londoners he has seen sporting charms, a great many people feel the
world is a menacing place, and they need protection from the spirit
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can laugh, but I blame TV news,'' Morris, said, emitting a
small groan. ``Every time you turn it on, you see another disaster.
You can't escape.''
</P>
<P>
   Amulets can also symbolize an aversion to technology, said
Leonard, the marketing consultant. ``All these new tools that
people are using but don't understand _ that's what's fueling
contemplation of greater powers.''
</P>
<P>
   In an increasingly complex and artificial world, ``people find
comfort in something that is natural,'' said Kazuko, a
first-name-only designer of raw-crystal-and-gold-wire jewelry sold
at Barneys New York (devotees include Bianca Jagger and Sue
Mengers, the Hollywood agent).
</P>
<P>
   Michele Quan and Robin Renzi, who own Me &AMP; Ro, a New
Age-inspired line of jewelry, are offering silver cuffs and bangles
with Sanskrit inscriptions from the Bhagavad-Gita. And when Aurora
Lopez and Steven Alan open Borealis, a jewelry boutique, in NoLIta
this month, they will showcase silver amulets by a Mexican jewelry
designer, Beth Orduna, and handbags by Jade Jagger embroidered with
trident symbols. ``All these things resonate magic,'' Lopez
declared.
</P>
<P>
   For some designers, they also resonate healing powers. Zoe
Metro, the designer for Stella Pace, one of the companies that
spawned last summer's power bracelet mania, is packaging her latest
collection of gold and lapis, bronze and onyx beads in plastic
prescription-drug vials. The labels say things like ``prescribed to
infuse your being with love,'' and ``Career Queen . . . glass
ceilings beware.''
</P>
<P>
   Even fashion and beauty heavyweights like MAC, the cosmetics
maker, and Danskin, of leotard fame, now use charms to promote or
enhance their products. MAC is offering an amulet with a groove
designed to hold its fragrances. And Danskin recently sent fashion
editors samples of its new ``Zen'' yoga togs, packaged with
polished, quarter-size pebbles. The pebbles are meant to be rubbed
between forefinger and thumb _ a Zen-inspired variation on worry
beads.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing amulets, the more outlandish the better, is partly a
legacy of the '60s. During that decade, spiritual and cultural
sampling became the order of the day. Many people took a kind of
supermarket approach to religion, shopping from a variety of
choices before finding a faith that suited them.
</P>
<P>
   The wearing of charms today suggests a similar mind-set. ``Some
people feel that amulets attract or bring forward the power they
represent,'' said Joe Zuchowski, who manages Enchantments, a
Manhattan boutique for aspiring Wiccans, or modern-day witches.
``But,'' he added offhandedly, ``other people might wear them
because they go with their outfit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, wearing charms attests to nothing more than a gauzy
wishful thinking. On a recent trip to Hawaii, Ally Tomi, a creative
director at Coty International, the cosmetics giant, bought a chain
with a pendant that reads ``Aloha.'' She wears it wherever she
goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps me create my own little aura and gets me through my
New York life,'' Tomi said. ``Sure, the taxi driver is screaming at
me, but I'm thinking `aloha,''' she said, pronouncing the word with
a lilt. ``It creates a sense of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm wearing this for myself, not for other people,'' she said.
``Still, when they read `aloha,' their mood might change, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
