<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3038 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-04 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ADVANCE FOR SUNDAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    IT ISN'T HIS FATHER BUSH MOST RESEMBLES POLITICALLY
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JANE ELY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Just as George W. Bush was moving to accept the
Republican presidential nomination here last week, Bill Clinton,
the lame-duck Democrat who won the presidency by defeating Bush's
father in 1992, derided the younger Bush. Clinton contended Bush's
campaign is much based on the fact his ``daddy was president.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Clinton wanted to more correctly characterize Bush the
Younger's 2000 campaign against Clinton's vice president, Al Gore,
he would have been much more on the money comparing it to his own
campaign in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, the general Democratic view of GWB much more
resembles that which the Democrats had of the elder Bush's
predecessor, Ronald Reagan, than it does of former President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   While neither comparison _ particularly the former _ likely
would please Clinton, if he's honest he'll acknowledge its
veracity. So, too, would that be true for the Texas governor, whose
nearly hourlong acceptance speech Thursday night got much _ if not
most _ of its length from interruptions for cheering, standing
ovations and widespread acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton won the 1992 Democratic presidential nomination
primarily because American Democrats wanted so desperately to
regain the White House from the Republicans' 12-year-occupancy of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly one of Bush the Younger's greatest political appeals
to his fellow GOPers is their widespread conviction he can win _
can defeat Gore in November.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, GWB may have an even greater edge in 2000 than Clinton
had in 1992. On the whole, Bush is far better liked personally by
the vast majority in the activist ranks of his party than Clinton
was in his.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to suggest Clinton was widely disliked back then,
but there was a pretty great clump of Dems _ notably those
officeholders in Washington _ who didn't much like Clinton but
accepted him because he was their best shot at regaining the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, when it was time to start mounting a campaign for the
Dem nomination in 1992, not many Dems were willing to plunge in
against Bush the Elder, who was riding fantastically high
politically after the then-recognized enormous success of Desert
Storm.
</P>
<P>
   By the time of New Hampshire, however, when it became apparent
Bush was prime for a political slide and Clinton's personal life
and veracity were being widely questioned, the so-called Democratic
establishment was about standing on its head trying to come up with
a way and an alternative to oppose Clinton's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   While it is true, GOP congressfolk generally would appreciate
less Washington bashing from Bush _ even would like, at the least,
some campaign aid from him _ they also generally like him, as,
certainly, do the assortment of those stretched across the gamut of
GOP conservative philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   It is in this sense that Bush tends far more to resemble former
President Reagan than he does his daddy. Great sort-of down-home
likability in Republicans seems not only a trait Dems, for obvious
reasons, dislike, it is a characteristic they seem compelled to
disdain politically.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Reagan served two terms, thus twice winning the
presidency, there still were Democrats out there who just couldn't
deal with the reality. That some Dems may have been partisan _ and
maybe politically gullible _ enough to have held to the end in 1980
convinced Reagan would do something really dumb and lose is one
thing.
</P>
<P>
   That just as many, if not more, actually believed the same thing
in Reagan's quite successful 1984 re-election campaign is another.
</P>
<P>
   As for those still sure it only was a series of quirks that
explained Reagan's political success, GWB ought to be delighted if
they do _ as many seem _ believe the same of him.
</P>
<P>
   If you're convinced the opponent will lose, then you have far
less inclination to work hard to elect your party's candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore not only has a strong element of this working against him
this year, he also is going to be the standard bearer fr a party
that seems to have forgotten the gnawing political hunger that sent
Democrats to campaign hard across the land to win the White House _
not so much for Bill Clinton as for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The GOPers, on the other political hand, not only are suffering
the gnawing political hunger that well could drive GWB to the White
House, they like him. They really like him.
</P>
<P>
   If George W. Bush wins the presidency in November, he, of
course, will be a Bush. But, he also will be a little bit of Bill
Clinton and a good dab of Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
