<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot settles suit
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot has agreed to pay $500,000 to a New Jersey
couple whose 6-year-old son was injured in a 1997 store accident,
according to the Philadelphia Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon Ryan, then 3, suffered a concussion when at least nine
boxes of vinyl siding fell on him at a store in Mount Laurel, the
newspaper said. At least one of the boxes, which fell from an
8-foot high shelf, hit the toddler in the head.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement includes $100,000 for the father, James Ryan, who
claimed he suffered emotional distress after witnessing the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Atlanta-based Home Depot confirmed the company
had agreed to settle the case but cited a policy not to discuss
details of settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
