<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3044 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-CREDIT-CARDS0805-COX     08-04 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-CARDS0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gold, platinum cards are old hat
 &HT;    By Peralte C. Paul
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As president of Business Travel in Norcross, Ga., Bill
Mayes remembers the days when plunking down a gold or platinum
credit card at the lunch table was a conversation stopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you'd go out with clients to business lunches, if they
pulled out a platinum card, you were expected to notice,'' Mayes
said of the early 1990s when such cards began popping up in
American wallets.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they get nary a glance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have college students now with platinum cards,'' Mayes
said.
</P>
<P>
   Card issuers did relax credit standards to get more of the cards
into circulation, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 506 million bank cards in circulation in the U.S., about
29 percent, or 150 million, are gold or platinum, according to
Frederick, Md.-based Cardweb.com, which tracks the industry.
</P>
<P>
   When first introduced in 1983, a consumer typically had to earn
$25,000 to $30,000 in annual income to get a gold Visa or
MasterCard with a minimum credit line of $5,000, said Robert B.
McKinley, Cardweb.com's chief executive officer. Today, a gold
cardholder can earn as little as $10,000 a year to qualify for it,
and the limit is $5,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You introduce it to the high end of the market and it waters
down to the lower end of the market,'' said Frank Martien, a senior
consultant with First Annapolis Consulting in Linthicum, Md. ``The
associations and the issuers just have a factory going.''
</P>
<P>
   Perks got curtailed or cut altogether when banks began
eliminating annual fees to attract high-end credit users, said
Moshe Orenbuch, a research analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as the fees went away, the services got cut,''
Orenbuch said. ``Gold and platinum are just colors.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the higher-level cardholders used to enjoy lower
interest rates, that's no longer the case, said Greg McBride, a
financial analyst at Bankrate.com in North Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The average interest rate on a variable platinum card in July
was 16.72 percent, McBride said. That was only 0.58 percentage
points less than the average 17.3 percent consumers were being
charged on regular cards.
</P>
<P>
   But card issuers such as American Express Co., MBNA America and
even Direct Merchants Bank, which specializes in accounts for
consumers who've had past credit issues, say gold and platinum
still has value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all consumers are alike; they want different products and
services,'' said Michelle Shepherd, MBNA's vice chairwoman of
advertising and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   So, banking executives reason, one consumer might be satisfied
with getting the auto collision insurance that comes with their
gold card, but another might want the perks that come with platinum
such as double frequent flier miles or upgrades at posh hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Some card issuers including American Express and MBNA, are now
offering by-invitation-only cards to appeal to upmarket consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The target market for the ``super cards'' are folks with perfect
credit who have minimum annual incomes of $70,000 and travel
frequently, McKinley said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the roughly 185 million Americans who carry credit cards,
only about 10 million would qualify for the most exclusive cards,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In June, MBNA launched the Quantum card, which comes with a
minimum line of $15,000 and a maximum limit of $250,000 to $1
million.
</P>
<P>
   American Express, which created the platinum concept in 1984
with its $300-a-year card, unveiled its Centurion card in October.
</P>
<P>
   Designed with such services as free upgrades to British Airways'
Concorde fleet, an assigned personal travel counselor and
complimentary cellular phones anywhere in the world, the
black-colored Centurion has a $1,000 annual fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really introduced Centurion in response to discussions with
our customers,'' said Judy Tenzer, an American Express spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Both Visa and MasterCard also have established new categories
that are designed to go after the upmarket consumer. Visa has the
Signature level, and MasterCard has the World category.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Shaifer, managing partner at Seyfarth Shaw's law offices
in Atlanta, gets an average of five offers a week from card issuers
touting the power of these upmarket cards and platinum cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them really don't provide anything that's materially
different,'' the American Express gold cardholder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain number of people who will always want to
have the most prestigious thing available. That, for me, frankly,
is not important,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
