<SLUG> BC-BOX-JUDAH-MILLETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDAH, MILLETT KO POLITICS WITH FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNCASVILLE, Conn. _ Saturday night, recess will finally be over.
</P>
<P>
   In a scenario that only could happen in boxing, International
Boxing Federation junior welterweight champion Zab Judah will
defend his title against IBF junior welterweight champion Terronn
Millett at the Mohegan Sun casino with the winner declared the IBF
junior welterweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   Say what? Say boxing politics.
</P>
<P>
   Millett (22-1-1, 17 KO's) won the 140-pound title from Vince
Phillips in five rounds last year and has never lost it. He
successfully defended it once by stopping Virgil McClendon in the
12th round after being knocked down early in that fight. Later,
Millett learned he had broken his right hand and asked for a
postponement of an already scheduled December defense against
Judah, who was then the IBF's No. 1 contender.
</P>
<P>
   IBF president Bob Lee ruled Millett could have an extension so
he could have the hand operated on and the fight would be scheduled
after it had healed. But after Lee was indicted on bribery and
racketeering charges _ he is currently waiting for a federal jury
in Newark to decide if the $300,000 he took from promoters in
exchange for selling out his own ratings was bribery or rental fees
_ and Hiawatha Knight was appointed interim president, the IBF
reversed course. At the behest of Judah's promoters, the IBF ruled
Judah and a stiff named Jan Bergman could fight for the suddenly
``vacant'' title because Millett was ``unavailable.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, after the fists flew, the lawsuits flew and
the IBF reversed itself again, declaring Millett ``champion in
recess,'' Judah ``interim'' champion, and mandating the two fight
for the true title, which is what Millett planned to do as soon as
his hand healed.
</P>
<P>
   Judah (23-0, 17 KO's) had one ``title'' defense in June against
Junior Witter, who spent 36 minutes running.
</P>
<P>
   So, finally, the two champions will meet to end a recess period
that has become interminable for Millett. ``At first there was some
kind of animosity toward him. But then I thought about it and said
if they gave me as much as they've given him, I don't think I would
have said anything, either,'' Millett said. ``I would have accepted
it and rolled with it, too. I can't blame Zab. I guess I can say
I'm upset at the IBF.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zab's management (Main Events) played a big part in me being
stripped. The IBF changes its rules any time it feels like. They
said I was the champion in recess and the No. 1 contender. I can't
understand that. I refuse to understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   What Millett won't refuse is the opportunity to take his
frustrations out on Judah, a hot 22-year-old prospect from New York
who has been a disciple of Pernell Whitaker since his amateur days.
Because of that style and his often stunning quickness, putting a
fist in Judah's face is complicated by the difficulty of finding
it.
</P>
<P>
   Judah spent his formative years as a professional training with
Whitaker. Judah learned much from that experience, both about
boxing and about the reality of his sport. He brings that to the
ring for what he understands is his first real test as a
professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really looking at this fight as being my world title
fight,'' Judah said. ``I'm the best that ever did it and I'm going
to show the world. I never had a problem with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   That may include the 32-year-old Millett, who, though a powerful
puncher, was KO'd in the first round in 1995 when he challenged
then WBA champion Sharmba Mitchell and was in trouble against
McClendon before rallying. A fast starter by inclination, Millett
is expected to pressure Judah early to test his mettle. It is a
test Judah seems sure he will pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the heat of battle,'' Judah said. ``I am going to go in
there and handle my business.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does that the way manager Lou Duva expects, recess will be
over for Zab Judah . . . and school will be out for Terronn
Millett.
</P>
</TEXT>
