u i BC-ARAFAT-ARABS-800(2TAK     08-04 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARAFAT-ARABS-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAB NATIONS' VIEW OF PALESTINIANS MAY BE SHIFTING 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ On the face of it, Arab support for the
Palestinians has never been so unified. One after the other, Arab
kings and presidents have said they stand behind Yasser Arafat's
claim to East Jerusalem and the right of return for Palestinian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the uncompromising public statements, more pragmatic
approaches to those thorniest of issues are being discussed
seriously among Arab leaders for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   There have even been signs of subtle shifts in the once
monolithic Arab public opinion that Arab Muslims should have
exclusive sovereignty over East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10 days since the Camp David talks broke down, on this
and other previously taboo issues, Arab leaders have been absorbed
in their most intense consultations ever on how to find a swift,
workable deal that would combine both symbol and substance for both
sides.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, the Palestinian leader, has shuttled around the region.
President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt has received a string of Arab
leaders at his summer palace in Alexandria, where Prime Minister
Ehud Barak of Israel arrived for talks on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And Edward S. Walker Jr., a former U.S. ambassador to Egypt and
Israel and now an assistant secretary of state, has gone to Saudi
Arabia as part of his tour of Arab nations that rely to some degree
on U.S. money or military backing.
</P>
<P>
   A new Arab consensus on these issues could ultimately make an
agreement between the Israelis and the Palestinians possible,
analysts and diplomats say, if Israel also compromises at least in
symbolic ways on viewing Jerusalem as its eternal undivided capital
and on Palestinian refugees as a resettlement problem for the rest
of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jews and Muslims are in a Catholic marriage with no
possibility of divorce,'' said Kamel Abu Jaber, a former Jordanian
foreign minister who led the first joint Jordanian-Palestinian
delegation to the Madrid peace conference in 1991. ``Everyone
realizes that the problem now is how to engineer arrangements to
satisfy at least the minimum requirements of both sides to live
together.''
</P>
<P>
   The concept of making ``arrangements'' along the way to peace is
relatively new in the 52-year-old Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
   For seven years since direct talks between the Israelis and the
Palestinians began in earnest, negotiations have focused almost
exclusively on step-by-step arrangements that have allowed most
Arab leaders to remain on the sidelines, talking of a comprehensive
peace settlement in absolute terms.
</P>
<P>
   But with the rush of expectation that came with last month's
15-day Camp David talks, Arab leaders are facing internal and
external pressure to play a role in forging a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that both of the most contentious issues on the
table _ Jerusalem and refugees _ carry implications for leaders
other than Arafat and for peoples other than the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is home to more Palestinian refugees than any other Arab
country. Egypt is a leading U.S. ally in the region and has the
status of the only Arab state to have reached a peace agreement
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   And the approval of Saudi Arabia, as the keeper of Islam's
holiest sites outside Jerusalem, is essential to any shift, no
matter how subtle, in the Arab position on the Holy City.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Arafat is alone negotiating with the Israelis, he is too
weak to make concessions,'' said Labib Kamhawi, a
Palestinian-Jordanian political analyst. ``But if a third party is
involved, the third party is like a facilitator. So I think,
ultimately, an Arab umbrella will be given to Arafat.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason is that most Arab nations, if not impatient for a
settlement, have become at least used to the idea that a settlement
would bring much-needed economic benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a growing linkage in the region between having
conditions of peace and the possibility of development,'' said
Abdel Moneim Said, director of the Al Ahram Center for Political
and Strategic Studies in Cairo. ``In addition, there is no one in
the Arab world, except for some fundamentalists, who would deny any
more the legitimacy of Israel. So we are all transferring from an
existential conflict of `us or them' to how we are going to be
living with them.'
</P>
<P>
   Before the Camp David peace negotiations, reflections on how to
finesse issues like Jerusalem were never seriously broached in Arab
countries. But proposals for dividing administrative and religious
control of the city, made at Camp David by Barak and President
Clinton, have lifted a curtain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are ways of dealing with it without saying that Israel
is sovereign over East Jerusalem,'' said Said. ``Certain things
could happen de facto, if we have an agreement that settles the
issue of East Jerusalem and left aside the question of the Old
City.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Arab control over the Haram al Sharif, the complex in the Old
City known to Jews as the Temple Mount, which contains two of the
holiest mosques in Islam, remains a fixed demand. It cannot be
relinquished, Arab officials have said, without stirring the wrath
of Muslim militants in the region and Muslims all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of Arab officials and commentators, even in the
most religiously conservative country of Saudi Arabia, have
recently talked of the need to cool tempers over Jerusalem and of
making a distinction between political and religious sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerusalem has a very important religious value, but its
political importance is just as great,'' said a Saudi official,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``Maybe both sides could agree
on joint administration according to certain arrangements.''
Postponing either Jerusalem or further negotiations is not an
option, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have already wasted 52 years and we do not need to waste
more time,'' the official said. ``We have to take what we can now _
anything that is possible or is the remnant of the possible.''
</P>
<P>
   From another quarter, Fahmi Howeidi, an Egyptian commentator
with close ties to the Islamic fundamentalist movement, also
suggested that Arabs are focusing too much attention on the
mosques. Instead, he wrote recently in Al Ahram newspaper, they
should emphasize the issue of right of return for Palestinian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The importance of the human being is more important than a
place, even if this place is the Haram al Sharif,'' Howeidi wrote,
adding that God would protect the Jerusalem mosques.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of the return of refugees, a number of Arab
officials have also said that an arrangement is possible if Israel
only accepts the principle that Palestinians have a right to return
if they fled or were forced from their homes in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Israel has said only that it might accept some
100,000 refugees under a family reunification plan. About 3.2
million Palestinians are registered with the United Nations as
refugees who fled or were forced from their homes at the time of
Israel's creation in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Another 300,000 are considered displaced persons from the 1967
Israeli occupation of the West Bank. Some of the more flexible
statements have come from Jordan, where officials and others of
Palestinian descent say they doubt that many people will take
advantage of a right to return, which would mean accepting Israeli
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say you agree to theoretical language that refugees have the
possibility of the right of return,'' said Marwan Dudin, a
Jordanian senator who was born in Beersheva, in what is now Israel,
and represented Jordan in multilateral talks with Israel about
Palestinian refugees. ``It could take two to three generations to
implement. But you at least make something that smells like an
acknowledgment of the right of return.''
</P>
<P>
   Kamhawi, the Jordanian political analyst, agreed. ``At a
minimum, Israel should uphold this right and then sit down and see
if it's practical or not,'' he said. ``First the principle; then
the details.''
</P>
</TEXT>
