<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AETNA-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      08-04 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AETNA-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AETNA CITES 17 PERCENT DROP IN 2ND-QUARTER EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aetna, the nation's largest health insurer, reported a 17
percent drop in second-quarter profits Friday as more people sought
increasingly costly treatment. But it said it was moving along on
sweeping changes aimed at improving business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that we must remake our model to better serve
employers and consumers and improve relationships with physicians
and hospitals,'' said William H. Donaldson, Aetna's chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson said Aetna had begun increasing prices for managed
care coverage and giving regional managers greater authority in
dealing with costs and pricing. For consumers, he said, Aetna was
trying to make its services easier to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intent,'' Donaldson said, ``is to eliminate those policies
and procedures that may have no positive effect in terms of either
monitoring quality or managing costs _ the so-called hassle
factor.''
</P>
<P>
   The earnings for the second quarter, excluding charges, fell to
$134 million, or 94 cents a share, down from $160.9 million or
$1.03 a share in the same quarter a year earlier. Aetna attributed
the decline mainly to higher-than-expected costs for treating
patients.
</P>
<P>
   The results were better than the lowered average profit
predictions by analysts of 88 cents a share, but far worse than the
original consensus estimate of $1.20 before Aetna said in mid-July
that it would not meet that target.
</P>
<P>
   Investors responded by bidding up share prices $1.187, to
$59.50.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But whether Aetna, which last month sold its financial services
and international units, can pull itself together as a purely
health care company and prosper over the long run in an extremely
competitive business is a matter of debate among those who follow
the company closely.
</P>
<P>
   Todd B. Richter, an analyst at Banc of America Securities, says
Aetna is doing too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are starting to do things now that other people in the
business have been doing over a long period of time,'' Richter
said. ``And doing this stuff today is much more difficult than it
was several years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts say that Aetna is relying heavily on increases
in prices to turn the company around.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business needs to be shrunk and then rebuilt,'' Richter
said. ``Trying to fix a business with price increases is not a
panacea.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, price increases poorly executed can be
self-defeating. ``Unless price increases are implemented with
surgical precision,'' he said, ``they can destroy the risk pool of
an insurer, meaning in any book of insurance business you've got
customers that are very profitable and customers that lose money
for you. If you raise prices too aggressively on those profitable
customers, they will leave and you will be left with only the
unprofitable customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Studying the same data, Tom Burnett, the president of Merger
Insight, a financial research firm in New York, reaches a far
different conclusion. ``The way we see it,'' he said, ``Aetna is
beginning to get is arms around the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   A big part of the problem has been the integration of three big
health insurance companies _ U.S. Healthcare, Nylcare and
Prudential Health Care _ into one smoothly running machine. With
investors angry about the company's poor results and lagging share
prices, Richard L. Huber, the architect of the acquisition
strategy, stepped down in last February.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson, one of the founding partners of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, has been overseeing the company since. He acknowledges
that is no health care expert. But he negotiated the sale of the
nonhealth care units to the big Dutch banking and insurance
company, ING, and he is leading the search for a chief operating
officer. He has also begun implementing fundamental changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They recognize their problems,'' Burnett said. And, having
sold off the business that have nothing to do with health
insurance, he said, ``they're going to be able to mount a
dedicated, focused effort toward improving their health care
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts Friday, Aetna said it had
narrowed its search for a new chief executive to a ``short list.''
One person under consideration, according to people close to the
search, is John W. Rowe, the president and chief executive of Mount
Sinai NYU Health. Neither Aetna nor Mount Sinai would comment.
</P>
<P>
   But even a new boss at Aetna would not be enough to cheer some
analysts. ``One guy is not going to fix this,'' Richter said.
</P>
</TEXT>
