<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVANGELICAL-CONFERENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
7,000 EVANGELISTS GATHER IN THE NETHERLANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UTRECHT, Netherlands _ In a vast and utilitarian exhibition
center, 7,000 people have assembled in what is probably one of the
most ethnically diverse, but purposefully homogenous, encampments
on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Temporarily living inside the Jaarbeurs Exposition Center, a
warehouse-like space within sight of the Utrecht train station, are
people from Africa, Asia, the Caribbean, Europe, Latin America, the
South Pacific and the United States. Two hundred nations and
territories are represented, and dozens of languages are spoken.
But everyone here is a Christian evangelist.
</P>
<P>
   They sleep in bunk beds, dine at long tables and form groups
each morning at 7 a.m. to board chartered trains for the half-hour
ride and a conference arranged by the Billy Graham Evangelistic
Association, which _ at the cost of millions of dollars _ is paying
for their transportation and housing here. The nine-day event, also
attended by 3,000 others flush enough to stay in hotels, concludes
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The organizational scope is close to breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're building a city inside a building,'' said John Drake,
the Graham association's man in charge here, who works the rest of
the year as an official with the YMCA in England. ``For some people
who come here, we've built a city bigger than their hometown _ and
that includes some of the Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Drake is a crew of 700 volunteers, themselves an
international group, who wear bright blue vests identifying them as
``stewards'' at the event, called Amsterdam 2000, and sometimes
cruise the vast expanse of Jaarbeurs on roller skates.
</P>
<P>
   The Graham organization has divided the evangelists in residence
into five groups, with each assigned a color _ blue, green, gray,
purple or red. That color determines their wristband, dining table,
train for Amsterdam and the color of the carpet that leads to their
bunk beds _ carefully identified by number _ at night. The sleeping
quarters for the overwhelmingly male population of this temporary
global village are strictly segregated by sex.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the measure of the quiet logistical efficiency here is
that the worst problem for the director of security _ Ted Cornell,
a graduate of the Julliard School of Music who directs choirs at
events led by Franklin Graham, Billy Graham's eldest son _ was some
cash that was misplaced until ``the guy found it.''
</P>
<P>
   With security apparently assured and at least seven doctors and
40 nurses on hand to deal with any medical problems, delegates have
been able to concentrate on one of the purposes of the gathering:
meeting other evangelists from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some of the mingling unites compatriots long
separated by distance. Louis Girardin, 33, an evangelist from the
Haitian capital, Port-au-Prince, sat across the breakfast table one
morning from Gregory Toussaint, 26, a Haitian-born resident of New
York City and a student, who was exulting in finding 50 or so
Haitians here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful place,'' Girardin said. ``We are one spirit,
the spirit of the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   For others, the sheer internationalism of this gathering impels
them to reach out to any new face and nationality, albeit with
smiles and gestures if a language barrier precludes more intense
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I meet people, I talk,'' said Taher Abu Chowdury, 43, who
came here from Chittagong in his native Bangladesh, and marveled at
being surrounded by hundreds of Europeans, Africans and Americans.
``When I think someone is smiling at me, I try to talk with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Edward Enim, 44, director of an organization called
Coast for Christ Baptist Ministries in Ghana, said that in his
sleeping area alone, he had met people from Madagascar, India and
the United States. ``We've been exchanging ideas, we've been
exchanging strategies for ministries,'' he said, conceding that, at
first, the Jaarbeurs center did not strike him as particularly
impressive. ``But when you're inside, it's like a city. It's
unbelievable!''
</P>
<P>
   Enim was among the few visitors to remark on the Dutch hosts of
the meeting, whom he praised for their efficiency and friendliness,
but admonished for spiritual laxity. Visiting Amsterdam, he said,
``has given me more of a burden to pray for Holland,'' adding,
``people have so much, they don't know what they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in history, he said, ``the Netherlands were a launching pad
for missions.'' But, Enim said, the country appears since to have
strayed from its historic faith. ``They need to come back,'' he
said. ``But they are lovely people.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Americans spoke of quite specific cross-cultural
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no walls to encase the noise,'' said William Petree,
28, a student at Golden Gate Baptist Theological Seminary in San
Francisco. ``You know, a lot of people sing themselves to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Are they singing hymns? ``It's not in English, so you don't
know,'' he said. ``But this morning, one person was singing, `His
eye is on the sparrow, so I know he watches me,' and people chimed
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Kolbert, 43, another student at Golden Gate, noted that
the sense of religious purpose transcended any differences here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not speak the same languages,'' he said, ``but we have
Jesus in our hearts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
