<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3051 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SAFRICA-BUS-DRIVERS-(     08-04 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-BUS-DRIVERS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA'S BUS DRIVERS AND COMMUTERS BRAVE GANTLET OF TERROR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KHAYELITSHA, South Africa _ Every day when Oscar Picane heads
off to work, he leaves behind a wife who worries that she will
never see him again. He is not a police officer or a soldier or a
miner, or even a gangster. He is a bus driver here in this
sprawling township south of Cape Town, doing a job that has become,
for the moment at least, the deadliest occupation in a country with
no shortage of dangerous jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Buses like the one Picane drives for Golden Arrow Bus Services
are under fire here in the Cape Flats, as the townships are
collectively known. Stoned, shot at and firebombed, the drivers are
the targets of a campaign of urban terror apparently orchestrated
by criminal elements in the rival minibus taxi industry, who
believe their business is threatened by the big bus company and the
cheaper fares it offers the poor here.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks and acts of intimidation, which began five months
ago and now number nearly 60, have so far killed four drivers and
two passengers, wounded dozens and shaken a community caught
between the brazen violence and the limp response of the local and
national governments.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is a share of the scarce resources of a desperate,
long-neglected place that, like so many in South Africa, was
founded to house black workers as far away as possible from the
white people they work for.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the worst violence unfolded late last week with a driver
and a passenger dying in a spate of attacks. This week, under
increasing pressure, the authorities took the most significant
steps so far to curb the violence. More than a dozen suspects were
arrested, and hundreds of police officers drawn from elite units
around the country were sent in.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Picane, 32, who has been a driver for Golden Arrow for
almost four years, has heard all the talk before _ the forceful
denunciations of the violence and the promises of swift, decisive
action.
</P>
<P>
   Little changes, and the attacks continue. Indeed, late Wednesday
night, a disabled bus was firebombed in Nyanga, a neighboring
township. No one was injured, but that is scant comfort to Picane.
</P>
<P>
   When he leaves for work each morning shortly before 5, he does
so driven by the same economic realities that leave his passengers
with little choice but to board his bus, as they begin doing
shortly after 5:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I am scared,'' he said as he guided his 68-seat bus
down the N2 Highway, through the fog-dusted darkness toward
Khayelitsha. ``But I am working for my family, so I have to work.
My mother and father, they don't know why I'm still working. But
I'm the breadwinner. Even my wife, she was crying, `Why are you
still going to work?'''
</P>
<P>
   But in a country where millions are unemployed and the economy
is barely growing, work is work, and a job is not easily
relinquished, even if risking your life is the only way to keep it.
David Tyantsi, a 50-year-old father of five, said that after the
latest violence, his family begged him to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them jobs are scarce,'' he said as he and a few other
drivers huddled in the early morning cold during a break at a
vacant lot that serves as a terminal in one township neighborhood.
``I haven't got anywhere to go to get a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Konana, as a passenger, is in the same situation. A
factory machinist in Durbanville, north of here, he spends about $5
a week on his bus ticket. Taking a taxi to work would cost him
another $3 to $4, a dear premium for someone like Konana, who makes
about $40 a week. ``I'm scared, but I've got no other choice,
because the buses are cheaper than the taxis,'' he said a few
minutes after boarding Picane's bus, which was northbound for
Bellville.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A seemingly endless sea of shanties southeast of Cape Town,
Khayelitsha lies miles away from the cities and towns where many of
its residents work. Transporting them to Cape Town and the other
urban centers has always been a lucrative and competitive
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   But rarely, if ever, has the fare battle between taxis and buses
been so violent _ and part of that could be attributed to a recent
national government effort to reshape the bloated, poorly regulated
taxi industry. Tactics common among rival taxi operators are now in
some instances being turned on the bus company, a convenient target
for taxi drivers' fear and anger with government plans.
</P>
<P>
   Taxi fleets are to be trimmed by tens of thousands, and an aging
collection of vans is to be replaced with larger, more suitable
minibuses. A crackdown is also planned on the unlicensed operators
who have saturated the market.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on whom you ask, the response from the authorities has
been inadequate, inept or both. The provincial government and the
national government have argued about who is ultimately responsible
for controlling the situation, even as the violence persists and
the perpetrators disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations between the bus company and the taxi industry have
been fruitless, and hours after the two most recent killings, they
broke down altogether. The local minister of security quit last
week, saying the national government, which controls the police and
army, had given him little power to act.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The handling of the crisis has left the bus drivers indignant.
``The national government had to intervene long ago,'' said Yaasien
Abrahams, the shop steward for the South African Transport and
Allied Workers Union.
</P>
<P>
   A driver for 13 years and shop steward for the last nine,
Abrahams says he is a marked man. He and his family were in hiding
for three weeks, he said, after the authorities learned that an
attempt was likely to be made on his life. He resurfaced a few days
ago and now wears a bulletproof vest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if it's safe for me now, but I don't know how
long a man can run,'' he said. ``Unfortunately, these people
negotiate through the barrel of a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most drivers and passengers, Abrahams is not white, and he
wonders how the crisis might otherwise have been handled here in
the only province where whites have retained control of the local
political machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm positive that if this had happened in Sea Point or the
suburbs,'' he said, referring to the fashionable neighborhood on
Cape Town's waterfront, ``it would have been resolved. But it's
only black people who are dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Until something changes, people like Elizabeth Letsie will have
to live with fear. ``We were on the bus that was shot last
Thursday,'' Letsie, a domestic worker, said as she sat with her
13-year-old son, Emmanuel, one row from where they were when shots
rang out last week. ``We were sitting right there. We were both
shaking. We were afraid, but we have no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   A man of the townships himself, Picane knows how much his
neighbors depend on him and his colleagues, and that, too, brings
him back each day. Every so often, he pulls his white-faced
wristwatch from his jacket pocket and steals a quick look.
Shootings or no shootings, a schedule is a schedule.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
