<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3054 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-04 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PONDERING JIMYOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Come with me to the manager's office. The skipper is
about to start his daily pregame rendition of of ``Meet The
Press.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Got Brogna, sent Burkhart,'' Jimy Williams says.
</P>
<P>
   No need to waste words. He knew we all knew what he's talking
about. Rico Brogna is here, and he will be in the lineup, batting
eighth. Morgan Burkhart, a veteran of the I-95 Shuffle, will be
joining his old friends in Pawtucket once again.
</P>
<P>
   You probably listen to talk radio. You've probably been
listening to people behind the microphone whine about the Jimy
approach to interviews. You've probably heard them say he's
useless, that he's combative and that he absolutely refuses to give
the reporter anything he or she can use.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, people shouldn't deal in absolutes. ``Always'' and
``never'' are two dangerous words to employ. Secondly, just because
a guy isn't 100 percent forthcoming doesn't mean he can't be a
little entertaining. And Jimy Williams at 4 in the afternoon is
nothing if not entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   The skipper watches Globe scribe Larry Whiteside walk in and
seat himself. ``Of all the people I know,'' Jimy purrs, ``you're
one of 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Dennis Miller, it ain't. But it's a clue that the mentor
is in a playful mood.
</P>
<P>
   The topic shifts back to the new man. ``He's in the lineup,''
Jimy says. ``He's in the lineup. First base tonight.'
</P>
<P>
   ``What about tomorrow?'' someone inquires. ``And will he used as
a DH, too?''
</P>
<P>
   ``First base, tonight,'' Jimy repeats. ``Got a game tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   This is classic Jimy. We are 590 regular season and 14
postseason games into the Jimy Williams era, and we should know the
rules. The day he most regularly acknowledges is today. His
favorite tense is the present. He gets out of bed thinking about
the game he will manage that afternoon or evening, and just about
nothing else. Oh, sure, every manager has certain long-range
considerations he must acknowledge (pitching, certainly), but, more
than most managers, Williams chooses to focus on the here and now.
He doesn't like ``What-Ifs?'' and ``Supposes'' and the like. He
truly is Mr. One Game At A Time.
</P>
<P>
   There is a little more talk about Brogna. ``I haven't seen him
in a while,'' Jimy says. ``I do know he is an outstanding defensive
first baseman, and I've seen him hit very well when he was with the
Mets. That was a long time ago, before he was with the Phillies.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett's name comes up. Yup, he'll be in the lineup
tomorrow, and yup, his wrist is fine.
</P>
<P>
   Now we're going to have some fun. Our beat man Bob Hohler feeds
Jimy a breaking ball. He tells Jimy he's managed 47 players this
season. He asks him how he feels about dealing with such a large
number.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably wouldn't have met 'em any other way,'' Jimy
deadpans, and I mean deadpans. ``I never would have had a chance to
meet 'em. I like ballplayers.''
</P>
<P>
   C'mon. Is that delibarately fouling off the pitch, or what? That
was classic Nellie Fox or Wade Boggs, right there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty-seven, huh?'' Jimy says, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   In all probability, this really is news to Jimy. He simply has
not thought about it. All he knows is that he likes to have 25 at
his disposal, and that this is a nightly goal that hasn't always
been met. But of 37 or 47 or 147, Jimy knows not.
</P>
<P>
   This leads to a discussion of chemistry. For some reason, he
bites on this one, even though it is borderline philosophy and Jimy
would prefer to deal with the concrete.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won a couple of tough games on the road with people who
haven't been here (long),'' he decides. Jimy then ponders whether
happiness breeds winning or winning breeds happiness. ``When you
win,'' he concludes, ``they say you've got chemistry. When you
don't, they say, well, what do they say? What's the opposite?''
</P>
<P>
   A four-letter word is suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``And re-arrange the letters and you've got `this,' '' he points
out. ``So I guess you can say you've got chemistry or you've got
`this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. Have you ever heard any better descriptions of
the phenomenon?
</P>
<P>
   There is a lull in the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saberhagen's still pitching tomorrow in Syracuse,'' Jimy
offers.
</P>
<P>
   Well, news is news.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of pitchers, the next name introduced into the
conversation is Pedro. Someone wants to know if, given the
circumstances (coming off a tough loss, the bullpen shot, etc.),
and considering the methodology (eschewing strikeouts in favor of a
more pitch-conscious approach), this was as impressive as anything
the amazing No. 45 has done all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say the least,'' Jimy concurs. ``Huge. And to have a game
like that offensively, getting four runs in the first. We can talk
about the way he pitched and the defense, but those runs were
important. But what Pedro did was very, very impressive, after what
happened to us in the two previous games and having won the first
game with eight innings of relief.''
</P>
<P>
   He turns his attention back to Mr. Whiteside, who is wearing a
baseball cap proclaiming his alma mater, Drake University. Jimy
grills him on Drake. Where is it? How'd you get there? Etc. And
then he asks who's the best basketball player that ever came out of
Drake. Whiteside throws out the name of Red Murrell. Someone else
references Willie Wise, the ``Dave DeBusschere of the ABA.'' In
case you didn't know, Jimy does love his basketball.
</P>
<P>
   And that's pretty much it. The veteran Jimyologists say it's a
typical pregame session. Some days there's more news than this;
some days there isn't. But the tone, the informality, the slightly
askew, but hardly bumpkinish, flavor is pure Jimy. You can pretty
much count on leaving the office having smiled at least once. You
might even have laughed out loud.
</P>
<P>
   He's not Joe Morgan. No one is, or ever will be. But he's just
as informative as Don Zimmer (in that context only; Zimmy has
always been very good in pure story-telling circumstances) and John
McNamara (not exactly Mr. Belly Laugh) and he is infinitely better
than Butch Hobson, the most obtuse and informationally barren Red
Sox manager in modern history. And let's not even discuss Kevin
Kennedy and his sad I-me discourses.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe it's not Bobby Valentine. But it's definitely better
than `this.'
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by email at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
