<HEADER>
A3055 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-MILES0805     08-04 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-MILES0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DBy Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Dave Campo calls it a business trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys have not gone to Japan to sample Far East
cuisine or climb Mount Fuji. The only thing on Campo's mind is
improving a football team that hardly resembled world-beaters in
their preseason opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I call a real road game,'' Campo said, referring
to the American Bowl game against the Atlanta Falcons tonight at
the Tokyo Dome.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had better get used to traveling. No team will fly
more miles this season than the Cowboys, the unofficial ambassadors
of the NFL. Including preseason, the Cowboys will travel 31,020
miles.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is second with 30,218 and San Francisco third at 29,928.
By contrast, Tennessee travels a league-low 8,498 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas will always be among the NFL leaders in travel miles,
partly because they have an owner who likes to market his team
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   This marks the team's seventh American Bowl in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are expected to play preseason games in Mexico the
next three seasons, perhaps longer, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling has become an issue with the Dallas coaches, who
figure trips to Tokyo and Mexico City are distracting. In this
case, they will miss six training camp days in Wichita Falls.
</P>
<P>
   This marks the eighth time the Cowboys have been chosen to play
in an American Bowl game. Their record: 0-6-1. Atlanta is playing
on foreign turf for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Campo, perhaps knowing that his boss is listening, said this
week's trip is ``positive.'' It enables the 88-player roster, which
has been blistered during two weeks of training camp, will get some
much-needed rest.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Troy Aikman did not looked enthused, saying he's
been on the 12,000-mile round trip to Tokyo three or four times and
has seen everything he's wanted to see.
</P>
<P>
   Jones looks at the business side of such trips. By playing in
places like Tokyo, London and Mexico City, the Cowboys play before
fans who might never have an opportunity to see them in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The most important market is Mexico, Jones said. By agreeing to
play in Tokyo this year, Jones said the NFL has assured him that
Dallas will be scheduled to return to Mexico for future games.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has been interested in marketing his team to a large
Hispanic audience. The Cowboys already have played three American
Bowls in Mexico and played two exhibitions in El Paso. All five
games drew overflow crowds, including an NFL-record 112,000 in 1994
in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation that Jones would like to move
training camp from Wichita Falls to the Rio Grande Valley, where
the Cowboys likely would draw many fans from across the border.
</P>
<P>
   As for tonight's game, Campo will have his eyes focused on
several positions. After Sunday's 38-10 loss to Pittsburgh, several
questions emerged at several key positions:
</P>
<P>
   Rookie cornerbacks Mario Edwards and Dwayne Goodrich were thrown
into the fire for the first times as pros, _ and got burned. It's
doubtful that either will play significantly during the regular
season, but injuries to Ryan McNeil or Kevin Smith will force them
in.
</P>
<P>
   Campo wants a better look at his tight ends. David LaFleur
(groin) did not play against the Steelers, and Mike Lucky (torn
knee ligaments) suffered a season-ending injury. The Cowboys
promise that the tight ends will have a bigger role in the offense
this season, and it's important to see how LaFleur and newcomer
Jackie Harris respond when the ball is thrown their way.
</P>
<P>
   Third-team quarterback Paul Justin had a horrific showing
against Pittsburgh, throwing three interceptions in the second
quarter. Campo said Justin, who did not have the benefit of playing
with first-team players, deserves another chance. If he does not
improve, No. 4 quarterback Clint Stoerner will take his job.
</P>
<P>
   After rushing for only 78 yards Sunday, it was clear the Cowboys
need work on their running game. Emmitt Smith's return should help,
but it's unclear whether rookies Michael Wiley or Troy Hambrick or
second-year player Michael Black are prepared for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   At 9 tonight, some of these questions could be answered.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
