<HEADER>
A3065 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-04 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FOR GERALD FORD 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The posturings and hypocrisies of the Republican
Convention were pushed aside, in my mind, by the news that
President Ford had suffered a small stroke. It made all the talk in
Philadelphia seem even emptier.
</P>
<P>
   One of my greatest regrets as a newspaper columnist is how I
underrated Gerald Ford when he was in the White House. It is time,
past time, to say what a model of decency and respect for law he
has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our long national nightmare is over,'' he said when he took
office after Richard Nixon's resignation on Aug. 9, 1974. ``Our
Constitution works; our great Republic is a government of laws and
not of men.''
</P>
<P>
   Those too young to have experienced Watergate may find it hard
to understand how much those few simple words meant. Here was a
president who trusted our system instead of conniving against it.
And not just Ford's words but the plain sincerity of the man who
uttered them. We needed someone we could believe.
</P>
<P>
   Belief was wounded when Ford pardoned Nixon a month later. I was
harshly critical of the pardon. So it is only right to say that I
am less sure now. I believed him in 1998 when he wrote, on The New
York Times Op-Ed page: ``In the end I listened to only one voice,
that of my conscience. I didn't issue the pardon for Nixon's sake,
but for the country's.''
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, as a former president, Ford took part in one of those
constitutional seminars that Fred Friendly put on, in which
panelists played roles in prickly scenarios. The issue at one point
was whether a president should take an action he deemed vital for
national security even though Congress had forbidden it.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyer, on the panel, urged him to ignore the
congressional restriction. But Ford rejected the advice. A
president, he said, had to follow the law, however inconvenient.
</P>
<P>
   When he entered the White House, two of Nixon's attorneys
general had been sentenced for crimes. The Justice Department,
crucial to the legal climate of the country, was in a terrible
state.
</P>
<P>
   Ford had to choose a new attorney general. He appointed Edward
Levi, president of the University of Chicago, who was revered by
lawyers across the country. When Levi died earlier this year, Ford
spoke at his memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know his politics when I appointed him,'' Ford said.
``All I knew was that he shared my reverence for the Constitution
....
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to Ed Levi, American citizens protesting the policies
of their government no longer had to fear illegal surveillance,
improper wiretaps or outright harassment .... In recommending John
Paul Stevens for the Supreme Court, Ed ... promoted one of the
nation's most distinguished jurists ....''
</P>
<P>
   But of course Edward Levi could not have done what he did
without a president secure enough in his own character to have such
an independent-minded attorney general. How many presidents would
appoint an attorney general without knowing his politics, and
resolutely support him whatever the political cost? That takes real
courage.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering what Gerald Ford did as president takes us back to
Philadelphia. For the convention made clear, despite its
papered-over unity, what a hard time George W. Bush would have
dealing with his party if he was elected president _ how much he
would need the courage and independence of Gerald Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Bush speaks of wanting to carry on the fight against racism in
this country. But what would he do about the Republican senators
who have refused to confirm a single black nominee to the 4th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, which has more black citizens than any
other circuit?
</P>
<P>
   Is it the Republican Party of Colin Powell? Or is it the party
of Sen. Trent Lott and Rep. Tom DeLay? When Republicans push
through environmental ripper bills drafted by polluting companies,
would George W. Bush have the courage to veto them as President
Clinton did?
</P>
<P>
   Most important, would Bush be ready to do what he has not done
as governor of Texas _ think seriously about the American legal
tradition and what it demands? Would he follow Gerald Ford in
putting politics second to respect for law?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
