<SLUG> BC-INVEST-SIX-FLAGS-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A RAINY SUMMER, CLOUDS OVER SIX FLAGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, August 6) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHELLE LEDER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six Flags amusement parks are best known for their scary roller
coasters that turn riders upside-down, and this summer investors
may well feel that they have been along for the ride. The stock has
had a negative total return of 43.29 percent so far this year, and
its price has fallen to $16.375 from its 52-week high of $39.1875,
set last August.
</P>
<P>
   Even more frightening, much of that slump has happened since the
start of July _ at the height of the parks' season _ and two
leading Wall Street analysts say the cool, rainy summer weather in
the Northeast and Midwest has further dampened the company's
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The company's results for the second quarter are to be released
this week. But investors are much more on edge about the outlook
for the remainder of the summer, particularly after word on July 21
from Six Flags' smaller rival, Cedar Fair L.P., that attendance at
its five parks has been below expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies are the only publicly traded regional
amusement park operators; they have several parks in the same
geographic regions. Six Flags Inc., which changed its name last
month from Premier Parks, operates 27 amusement and water parks in
the United States, 7 in Europe and 1 in Mexico. Cedar Fair has four
water parks in addition to its five amusement parks.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's problem, analysts and institutional investors
say, has been the weather. Parts of the New York metropolitan area
had 10 consecutive rainy days extending into last week, putting a
damper on one of Six Flags' largest and most profitable operations,
a cluster of three parks in central New Jersey _ Great Adventure,
Wild Safari and Hurricane Harbor. After that rainy stretch,
analysts at Merrill Lynch and Salomon Smith Barney lowered their
estimates for 2000 operating income for the company, as well as
their price targets for the stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone delayed visiting the park in June, we thought they
would make it up in July because a visit is usually delayed instead
of canceled,'' said Hayley Kissel, the Merrill analyst. ``But the
last week of July was an absolute washout, and that's making it
harder and harder to make it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Kissel lowered her estimate for 2000 earnings before
interest, tax, depreciation and amortization, or Ebitda, to about
$400 million, or about $2.28 a share, from her earlier one of $435
million, or $2.47 a share. Still, she maintains a buy rating on the
stock, but has lowered her 52-week price target to $27 from $34.
``They've had severe weather, but that doesn't change the
fundamentals or the operating model,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two years, the company has developed a reputation
as an amusement park consolidator, buying older, underperforming
parks cheaply, spending money to add attractions and spruce them up
and branding them with the well-recognized Six Flags name. That has
helped the company increase cash flow steeply, said Cliff
Greenberg, portfolio manager for the Baron Small Cap fund, which
owns about a million shares of Six Flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, they're going to buy additional parks in the U.S. and
do the same thing,'' Greenberg said, adding that there are ``also
opportunities in Mexico and Europe.'' He said that at six to seven
times 2001 Ebitda estimates, the stock was attractive. ``It's not
just about this year, but next year and the prospects beyond,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But some large investors are clearly skittish. On July 25, just
after Cedar Fair's warning, 3.77 million shares of Six Flags traded
hands, and the stock fell to a 52-week low of $13.93. And short
interest in the stock, which stood at 5.37 million shares as of
July 10, remains high.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts criticized Six Flags executives for not doing
more to allay investors' fears. But others say that considering the
importance of any given weekend, management could not have done
much before announcing second-quarter numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conclusion is that if Cedar Fair lowered their guidance
then Six Flags will probably do the same,'' said Kathy Styponias,
senior entertainment analyst at Prudential Securities. ``But at
this point, it's unclear if that will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Styponias said she believed that any bad news was priced into
the stock, which she rates as a strong buy with a 52-week target of
$48.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
