<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3071 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      08-04 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODEST JOB GROWTH HELPS MAJOR MARKET INDEXES RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks ended higher Friday after the Labor Department
reported that private job growth had been slower than expected in
July.
</P>
<P>
   The data appears to make an interest rate increase by the
Federal Reserve later this month less likely. And the restrained
job growth helps confirm the belief of some analysts that the
central bank will not need any more rate increases later this year
to slow economic growth to a noninflationary pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said one more rate hike,'' Robert J. Barbera, chief
economist at Hoenig &AMP; Co. in Rye Brook, N.Y., said. ``These numbers
make me look wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there is some concern about corporate
earnings. Second-quarter earnings have been stronger than expected,
increasing 21.2 percent so far, according to First Call/Thomson
Financial. But a lot of companies have announced that they do not
expect to meet earnings forecasts for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still in a period of trying to rationalize very high
earnings expectations,'' said Richard E. Cripps, chief market
strategist at Legg Mason Wood Walker in Baltimore. ``If you think
that the economy is going to grow at 3.5 percent instead of 4.5
percent, you are too high. You've got to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Federal Reserve policy-makers have other important
July economic data to review before they meet on Aug. 22, including
retail sales and the Consumer Price Index. If retail sales are
unexpectedly strong, which would signal a rebound in spending,
rate-increase fears would presumably revive.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices moved up and down all day Friday. Early on, the
Nasdaq composite index was up 87 points, or 2.3 percent. But it
reversed and at one time was down 8 points. The Nasdaq finished the
day up 27.48 points, or 0.73 percent, at 3,787.36.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 61.17 points, or 0.57
percent, to 10,767.75. Early in the day, the Dow was off 41 points.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index climbed 10.37 points, or 0.71
percent, to 1,462.93. Market breadth was positive.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of Dow industrial stocks showed how the
optimistic outlook for interest rates versus the concern about
earnings, especially in technology, played out Friday. The Dow was
led higher by financial stocks including J.P. Morgan and American
Express, which would be hurt by higher rates. Drags on the Dow
included the technology giants Intel and Microsoft, as well as
Eastman Kodak, which told investors in July that it was losing
market share.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices and yields also bounced around Friday as investors
tried to understand the import of the new jobs data. By late
afternoon, the price of the 10-year Treasury note had climbed
13/32, to 104 12/32. The yield, which moves in the opposite
direction, fell to 5.89 percent from 5.95 percent on Thursday, the
lowest since April. The yield on the 30-year bond fell to 5.71
percent from 5.74 percent. Next week, the Treasury will sell $25
billion in new securities.
</P>
<P>
   The employment data showed that private-sector jobs rose by
138,000 in July, less than in June and less than the 182,000
average for the first six months of the year. Analysts said the
291,000 increase in the pool of available workers indicated there
might be some slack developing in a very tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   Barbera of Hoenig said that the most important matter facing
investors is not whether there will be one more interest rate
increase by the Fed. What is more important, he maintained, is that
corporate earnings are probably going to slow more than even
worried investors expect.
</P>
<P>
   The strong earnings growth in the first and second quarters, he
argued, was the peak. He said investors were focusing more on the
positive expectation that the Fed could guide the economy to a soft
landing, avoiding recession, than the effect that a slowdown in
growth would presumably have on corporate earnings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
