u p BC-NAACP-CAMPAIGN-NYT &LR;      08-04 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAACP PLANS MAJOR VOTER REGISTRATION DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People, seeking to play a more active role in the
presidential elections this year, is planning to mount a
multimillion-dollar campaign to mobilize and register black voters.
</P>
<P>
   The association plans to spend about $7 million on a
wide-ranging campaign that is likely to include television, radio
and newspaper advertising, direct mailings, phone banks, pamphlets,
faxes and other tactics, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The amount earmarked for the effort is relatively small compared
with the costly standards of today's political campaigns. But it is
a significant sum for an organization like the NAACP, with an
annual budget of $19 million. Its previous efforts have been
largely limited to grass-roots voter education and registration,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Pringle, a spokeswoman for the NAACP's National Voter
Fund, said the group would not endorse candidates in its drive to
increase black voter participation.
</P>
<P>
   But she said the effort would highlight the records of
presidential and congressional candidates on issues that are
important to blacks, Hispanics and other racial and ethnic
minorities. Those issues, she said, include education, health care,
civil rights and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot at stake'' in the November elections, Pringle
said, adding: ``This is based on the NAACP's belief that an
informed voter is an empowered voter.'' The drive, she said, will
be kicked off in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP's campaign comes as some of its members have warned
that the outcome of the presidential election in November could
have a major impact on the course of civil rights. In particular,
the members have voiced concern that another conservative member on
the Supreme Court could be a major setback for that cause.
</P>
<P>
   Black voters now make up 15 percent of the electorate, and they
usually provide overwhelming support for Democrats. But Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, the Republican presidential nominee, has been
campaigning in black and Hispanic communities, in an effort to
underscore his message of inclusiveness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 2019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
