<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3074 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BODY-FARM0805-COX     08-04 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BODY-FARM0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Macabre `farm' helps solve crimes
 &HT;    By Ken Mink
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ At ``the Body Farm,'' corpses are left lying
in a field for study. And one of the directors thinks it would be
great if medical officials in Atlanta, Miami and elsewhere would
start doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Murray Marks, the associate director of the University
of Tennessee Medical Center's Anthropological Research Facility,
said ``a lot more criminal cases would be solved and victims
identified if there were more such research facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medical science needs to know more about how differing
environmental conditions affect the decomposition of bodies,'' he
said. ``The differences in the heat, humidity, cold, rain, snow,
ice and so forth are major factors. We have only the climate in
East Tennessee to guide us right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Marks, 44, admits the idea of placing bodies around a field
and chronicling their decomposition is probably too macabre to win
approval anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our facility is the only one in America, and perhaps the only
one in the world, where this kind of study is going on,'' he said.
``I seriously doubt any other locality would ever approve such a
program. In fact, because of the highly-charged political climate,
I don't think we could even get one approved here if we had to
start over.'' Center founder William Bass III and UT medical school
officials have managed to convince legislators of the scientific
value of the program, which provides practical training for
students seeking to become forensic scientists. Law enforcement
agencies, including the FBI, use the facility for training.
</P>
<P>
   The school has turned out more forensic experts than any school
in the country, said Marks, a graduate of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Another graduate, William Rodriguez, is chief deputy in the
Armed Forces Medical Examiner's Office and was co-leader of the
team of U.S. forensic experts that investigated sites of alleged
massacres in Kosovo. Officials from the Body Farm went to Waco,
Texas, at the request of the federal government to identify the
skull of David Koresh, leader of the Branch Davidian group whose
members died in a fire after a standoff with government agents.
</P>
<P>
   The Body Farm name was popularized by author Patricia Cornwell
of Charlottesville, Va., who wrote a 1994 book by that title. In
her story, a crime-fighting forensic doctor ran experiments on dead
bodies for the book's main character, Dr. Kay Scarpetta. Cornwell
has said the UT Body Farm program inspired her to write the novel.
</P>
<P>
   The research facility has survived several attempts to close it.
Tennessee state Sen. Tommy Haun in 1995-96 led a campaign to cut
state financing for the Body Farm, saying some veterans groups had
complained that veterans might be among the paupers studied at the
site. A Knoxville citizens group, called Solutions to Issues of
Concern to Knoxvillians, once picketed The Body Farm with signs
reading, ``This makes me sick.'' But there have been no citizen
protests in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Bass, 71, retired as director of the program a few months ago,
and Richard Jantz and Marks took the reins.
</P>
<P>
   The program began in 1972. ``When I found body decomposition in
Tennessee was a lot different than in Kansas, where I was a teacher
for 11 years before coming to UT,'' Bass said, ``I decided science
needed better knowledge about this for identification and
crime-solving purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, some 300 bodies have been studied at the
facility, Marks said. Bodies have been placed in the trunk of an
old car, submerged in water, partly buried and left lying in the
open.
</P>
<P>
   The Body Farm covers about three acres on a hillside near the UT
Medical Center. It is an unmarked area surrounded by two fences,
one with razor wire to keep out curiosity-seekers.
</P>
<P>
   Bodies for the facility come from three sources: Unclaimed
paupers (saving the state the $700 cost of burial), people who
donate their bodies for general scientific study, and people who
sign up to have their bodies sent specifically to the Body Farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more than 200 people who have signed up with us to
take over their bodies when they die,'' Bass said.
</P>
<P>
   Bass said he, too, is considering donating his body to the
program. ``I lost two wives to cancer, and now I am married for the
third time. If my current wife agrees, I would like to have my body
made a part of the program. Why waste a perfectly good skeleton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
