u f BC-VERIZON-LABOR-NYT &LR;      08-04 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERIZON'S PROPOSAL TO UNIONS NOT LIKELY TO AVERT STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Verizon Communications, the nation's largest wireless and local
telephone company, moved to avoid a strike by more than 86,000
telephone workers from Maine to Virginia by submitting a proposal
Friday addressing some of its unions' main contractual concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the possibility of a walkout may have increased after
Verizon skirted other important issues, like its wireless work
force organizing a union, the contracting out of some labor and the
loss or migration of jobs as a result of mergers in the last
several years.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the company and the unions agree on issues by 12:01 a.m.
Sunday or agree to extend discussions _ 72,000 members of the
Communications Workers of America and 14,700 members of
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers will walk out on
Verizon, the new name of the company formed when Bell Atlantic
acquired GTE.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to win assurances from Verizon making it easier to
organize employees into unions in the wireless division are at the
heart of the dispute. Unlike their counterparts in more traditional
areas of the telecommunications industry, wireless workers are
generally not union members.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few dozen of the 32,000 employees in Verizon's wireless
division are union members, compared with nearly 80 percent of the
120,000 employees in the company's local telephone operations.
Concerned that the wireless division is growing much faster than
the rest of the company, the union membership of Verizon's work
force is threatening to walk out.
</P>
<P>
   If the unions do strike, the telephone network would probably
not be disrupted, the company said. But about 25 million businesses
and households on the East Coast, could be inconvenienced by delays
in requests to repair or install phone service, make
operator-assisted calls and have questions answered about telephone
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency services like 911 would not be disrupted in the event
of a walkout, according to Verizon officials. The company also said
it would give communications for hospitals and other health care
operations priority. The company said it did not yet know if it
would create hotlines or special telephone numbers for customers
inconvenienced by a possible work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to avoid a strike, Verizon made its proposal Friday
morning addressing wage, pension and job security. Representatives
from the two unions and Verizon discussed the proposal at length
Friday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, Verizon would increase wages by 3 percent to
4 percent per year for unionized employees, improve pension plans
for active employees and offer some job security, although details
of this part of the proposal were not clear Friday night, according
to Eric Rabe, a spokesman for Verizon.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company plans to offer increased financing for
day care programs, improved medical benefits for new employees and
an adoption reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to the communications workers union, the proposal
did not address concerns about forced overtime, the movement of
work locations as a result of the merger, or the contracting out of
some services to nonunion companies in areas, including the
installation of high-speed Internet lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the company would rather farm out work this means one
company installs the line on the outside of the building, which is
us, and another on the inside, which is them,'' said Ed Mcgowan, a
Verizon employee who installs digital service lines in midtown
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This results in a big headache for the customer, who has to be
at home for two days instead of one, and a loss of income to a
nonunion company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side appeared optimistic about the chances of reaching
an agreement before the strike deadline Sunday, people close to the
talks said. The involvement of senior company and union officials
in negotiations, which could change their direction, is only
expected on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the talks between the unions and Verizon are
likely to have repercussions throughout the entire wireless
communications industry. Verizon Wireless, which Verizon owns in an
alliance with Vodafone AirTouch of Britain, is the nation's largest
wireless company with 26 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the wireless industry has not organized into unions,
although some companies, like SBC Communications and BellSouth,
which together operate the nation's second-largest wireless
carrier, make organizing efforts easier by allowing employees to
join a union if a majority of employees at a given site agree to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   ``If unions can tap into a key area like wireless, it means much
more than simple wage increases or better pensions,'' said Stanley
Aronowitz, a sociology professor at the City University of New
York. ``This is about questioning who benefits from wealth creation
in the new economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on figures before the company became Verizon last spring,
Bell Atlantic's wireless division outstripped its traditional
land-line operations in generating revenue, according to the
communications workers union.
</P>
<P>
   For example, each wireless employee generates $325,000 a year in
revenue, or 230 percent more than counterparts in regular telephone
operations. And the company's wireless operations generate $532 a
year in revenue from each customer, compared with $324 a year for
each telephone company customer.
</P>
<P>
   A Verizon spokesman said the company was wary of discussing the
organization of its wireless work force into a union because
Verizon Wireless operates as a separate company from Verizon
Communications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
