<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3079 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-SOUTHCO-CRISIS0805-CO     08-04 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHCO-CRISIS0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern Co. hit by California electricity crisis
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ California's electricity crisis is proving to be one
big headache for Southern Co.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesale price caps, imposed this week after prices
skyrocketed, are affecting revenue for the company's San Francisco
Bay Area power plants that sell electricity in wholesale markets.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the prospect that regulators might now reverse the
state's landmark electricity deregulation law has raised questions
about the timing, at least, of Southern's plans to build more
generators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bought these plants in good faith based on an understanding
of how the market was set up,'' said Randy Harrison, chief
executive officer of Southern Energy California, the company's West
Coast subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the rules are constantly changing, and there's the threat
of re-regulation. We're watching things very carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern Energy Inc. became the primary power producer in the
Bay Area in April 1999 after purchasing three power plant complexes
from Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric for $801 million. The San Francisco
utility company divested itself of the units as part of
California's electric utility deregulation, enacted by the state
Legislature in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Co. subsidiary announced plans in September to add
``state of the art'' natural gas-fueled generators in the city of
San Francisco and Contra Costa County at a cost of between $400
million and $600 million, to be completed in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   But California's power grid strained to the breaking point this
week when temperatures topped 100 degrees. Monthly power bills for
homes and businesses in Southern California have more than doubled,
in part due to a shortage of electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Ramped-up air conditioners sent wholesale prices to the legal
limit of $500 a megawatt hour, and the California Independent
System Operator reduced the cap to $250. Earlier this summer, the
cap was reduced from $750 to $500.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison said that Southern anticipated a $750 cap this summer,
the most profitable period of the year for power producers. ``We
make our money in hot weather for a few days,'' he said. Southern
had expected price caps to be eliminated entirely in November.
``Now, it's a question mark,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison declined to say how much the lower prices are costing
the company. Credit Suisse First Boston estimated last year that
the California power plants, not including any expansion, would add
$50 million in net income this year.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison also said Southern will have to decide during the next
90 days whether to proceed with construction of the San Francisco
plant. In the long run, he expects the problems to be straightened
out and for Southern and other companies to build new generators.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
