<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3080 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-NYT &LR;      08-04 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SLOWER JOB GROWTH FOR JULY EASES FEAR OF FED RATE HIKE  (ART ADV:
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American companies added fewer jobs in July than economists had
expected, reducing the chances that the Federal Reserve will raise
interest rates when it meets later this month.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that economic growth is slowing, the unemployment rate
remained unchanged at 4 percent in July as private-sector payrolls
grew by 138,000, about half the number that most analysts had
predicted. Overall employment fell by 108,000 last month because of
the large number of temporary government workers who finished
collecting census data in June, the Department of Labor reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an economy that has gone from spectacular growth to
steady and solid growth,'' Labor Secretary Alexis Herman said.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing companies and restaurants accounted for more than
two-thirds of the job growth last month, and other sectors _ such
as real estate, construction, and insurance _ hired relatively few
new workers. In what may be a sign that businesses expect sales to
slow, the number of people working for temporary employment and job
placement firms fell, and overall growth in that sector so far this
year is now less than half what it was in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is slowly losing altitude,'' said James Glassman,
a senior economist at Chase Manhattan Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The employment numbers offered the first broad picture of the
economy's performance in July, and are leading economists to
predict that the Federal Reserve's policy-making committee will
decide on Aug. 22 that it does not need to raise interest rates in
order to slow growth. Last week, Alan Greenspan, the Federal
Reserve chairman, told members of Congress that the jobs data, as
well as upcoming reports on inflation and productivity, would have
``a significant effect upon what action the committee chooses to
take.''
</P>
<P>
   Since June 1999, the Fed has raised its benchmark short-term
interest rate six times to 6.5 percent, from 4.75 percent, in an
attempt to ward off inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The one sign of inflationary pressure in Friday's report was a
mild one: Hourly wages for production employees, who make up about
three-fourths of the work force, rose by 6 cents, to $13.76. Since
the start of the year, wages have risen at an annual rate of 4
percent, up from 3.2 percent in the second half of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Other labor costs, such as benefits and bonuses, appear to be
growing more quickly, said Ken Matheny, a senior economist at
Macroeconomic Advisers, a consulting firm in St. Louis. The
government will report official compensation numbers next week.
</P>
<P>
   Productivity gains also appear to be strong, allowing companies
to increase their workers' pay without raising prices to maintain
profits, analysts said. That, combined with the moderate
private-sector job growth, has left both economists and investors
confident that the Fed let the interest rates stand, just as it did
at its most recent meeting in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report was the final nail in the coffin,'' said William
Dudley, the chief domestic economist at Goldman, Sachs. The
investment bank told clients Friday that it was changing its
forecast and no longer expects a rate climb in August or for the
rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   All of the major stock market indexes closed higher Friday, as
investors' confidence about the stability of the interest rates
outweighed tepid profit announcements in the drug and semiconductor
industries.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists think a rate increase is still possible, if not
in August then at the following meeting of the committee, in
October. Factory orders and consumer confidence have both risen
recently, and the gross domestic product grew at a surprisingly
fast 5.2 percent annual pace in the second quarter. But most
analysts agree the odds of action by the Fed has fallen in recent
weeks. Aside from the spike in gas prices, inflation remains
slight, and recent statistics on consumer spending and home sales
have indicated that the economy is growing more slowly in its 10th
year of expansion.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of June, almost 90 percent of economists surveyed by
Macroeconomic Advisers, thought the Fed would raise interest rates
in August or October. By last week, the number had fallen just
below 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's report depicted a job market that has changed little
over the last nine months, as employment growth has slowed.
Private-sectors payrolls did fall significantly in May, but modest
increases during the other months of the year have made up for the
decline. The unemployment rate has stood between 3.9 percent and
4.1 percent since October, and the portion of Americans over the
age of 16 who are working was the same as it had been in July 1999
_ 64.2 percent. Over all, 134.7 million people in the United States
hold jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate for black Americans fell 0.2 percent last
month, to 7.7 percent, but remains slightly higher than it was
earlier in the year. The rate for whites and Hispanics showed
almost no change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
