<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3081 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-BIASCASE0805-COX     08-04 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-BIASCASE0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke settlement following strict timetable
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Attorneys should be finished with the written version
of the June 14 settlement in the Coca-Cola discrimination suit
within a few weeks and can report on its status by early September,
the court-appointed mediator in the case said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But it will still be late October at the earliest before some
2,000 current and former black employees of Coke can expect to see
copies of the proposed final agreement, including details of
monetary awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The schedule that was announced remains in place,'' said
Hunter R. Hughes, an attorney with Rogers &AMP; Hardin, who mediated
the settlement process.
</P>
<P>
   If U.S. District Judge Richard Story makes a preliminary
determination that the deal is fair, the proposed settlement would
then be mailed to class members in late October or early November.
</P>
<P>
   Four African-American plaintiffs filed suit against Coke,
alleging that the company treated them and other black employees
unfairly in pay and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Hughes said attorneys for Coke and the
plaintiffs have been ``working diligently to reduce that agreement
to writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is expected that this process will be concluded within the
next few weeks, and that in early September, the parties will be in
a position to provide a further status report on the matter,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Coke spokesman Scott Jacobson said that status report may
include a written description of the initial June 14 agreement. He
said the process has not been accelerated. ``There is a federal
court order that does not allow us to step out of the process for
this,'' he said. ``We cannot unilaterally step out of the process
and make it faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes issued his statement about the 51-day-old process on the
same day that Larry Jones, a former Coke manager and founder of the
Committee For Corporate Justice, speculated that the two sides
hadn't actually reached an agreement in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``On June 14, I don't believe that they had much of anything,''
said Jones during a Friday press conference and protest in front of
Coke's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   He said releasing the settlement details in September or later
is ``unacceptable,'' and makes it more likely that potential
members of a class-action suit will accept smaller monetary awards
than they might have agreed to earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Jones' concerns, Hughes said the two sides ``did reach
an agreement in principle on June 14, and that agreement in
principle reflects the parties' resolution of the material elements
of the dispute.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
