<HEADER>
A3082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-R-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-ART-5     08-04 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIDING CONVENTION MOMENTUM, BUSH LAUNCHES CAMPAIGN TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to clarify status of story; this is a 1STLD writethru of
the earlier BUSH-CAMPAIGN story from Philadelphia.)   (ART ADV: Photos NYT7 and 12 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Gov. George W. Bush came roaring out of the Republican
National Convention on Friday by plane, train and automobile,
intent on sustaining whatever momentum he seized from the four-day
political extravaganza in Philadelphia and focused on a group of
swing states that Democrats won in both of the last two
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor, now officially the Republican presidential
nominee, traveled from Pennsylvania to Michigan, with several stops
in Ohio in between, to reiterate his vow to bring a new harmony and
integrity to Washington, rejoice in the unity that he said the
Republican Party had achieved and just plain grin. It was clear
that Bush had been pleased with the convention, and with his own
performance there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how energized I am,'' Bush told a crowd of
hundreds along a stretch of train tracks near downtown Pittsburgh,
where he began the westward whistlestop tour that consumed the bulk
of his day. In a classic campaign tableau, he stood on a kind of
balcony, draped in red, white and blue bunting, at the back of the
rear car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be long now,'' Bush said, repeating a line from his
convention speech that forecast the ouster of President Clinton and
Vice President Al Gore and the arrival of a Republican
administration in their stead. ``Give us a chance to change America
for the better, and it won't be long now.''
</P>
<P>
   Like some portions of his convention speech, this was a clearly
partisan appeal that belied his exhortations for across-the-aisle
amity, and the crowd duly chanted, ``No more Gore! No more Gore!''
</P>
<P>
   And like much of the convention itself, Bush was trying to have
it several ways at once. At a prayer breakfast Friday morning in
Philadelphia, he made a point of saying that ``the gateway to
heaven has many different paths.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also listened politely as one of the invited guests,
Cardinal Anthony Bevilacqua of Philadelphia, explicitly railed
against abortion and implicitly indicted marriage between
homosexuals, saying that ``millions of children have been
slaughtered'' and that society was plagued by ``sexually unbridled
permissiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said repeatedly that he wanted to change the tone in
Washington. But his own voice had vinegar mixed with the honey.
</P>
<P>
   On his campaign plane Friday, Bush said that he was not
indulging in negative campaigning, against either Clinton or Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I say I'm going to bring honor and dignity to the White
House,'' Bush said, ``that's what I'm going to do. And if people
draw conclusions other than that, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to some pointed jokes about Gore in his convention
speech, Bush added: ``The idea of needling the opponent with good
humor _ that's what American politics should be about, as opposed
to trying to tear people down and distort. And I'm going to
continue pointing up differences, and I will do so in a respectful
way and occasionally put a needle out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Several polls taken toward the end of the convention suggested
that Bush had latched onto an effective strategy and was enjoying a
better ``bounce'' from the event, and from the attention that it
garnered, than candidates sometimes do.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A bipartisan survey conducted during the convention by Voter.com
found a 10-point bounce for Bush, leaving him with 49 percent and
Gore with 31 percent. Ralph Nader, the Green Party candidate, had 6
percent, and Pat Buchanan, the likely Reform Party candidate, had 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because those polls were so promising, the Bush campaign
actually sought to soft-pedal them, so that Republicans would not
be lulled into an outsize optimism about Bush's prospects, and so
that the inevitable tightening of the race between Bush and Gore
would not be portrayed as a downturn for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said, ``Listen, there's going to be all kinds of polls and
speculation between now and Election Day and I understand that and
that's why I think it's so important for us to be patient and keep
our eye on the finish line.''
</P>
<P>
   A campaign spokesman, Ari Fleischer, said, ``You've got to wait
a few days, let the bounce settle. Al Gore has much more room to
bounce.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Bush campaign's confidence was evident in its itinerary:
just as Bush had traveled to the convention by visiting a series of
states that Republicans had not won in a presidential election
since 1988, it was traveling out of the convention in the same
fashion. After stops over the next few days in Ohio, Michigan and
Illinois, the campaign is heading next week to California, Oregon
and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   To help hold onto the sense of momentousness from the
convention, Bush traveled with his wife, Laura; his running mate,
Dick Cheney; Cheney's wife, Lynne, and a larger group of his senior
advisers than he typically does. And he hit eight cities, nine of
them while on the train, which started in Pittsburgh and ended in
Akron, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The stops came as frequently as every 15 to 20 minutes, and Bush
kept his remarks extremely brief, electing general expressions of
emotion over specific allusions to policy. Time and again, he
reflected that his favorite moment of the convention was the speech
by Laura Bush on Monday night, and he remarked on what a beautiful
smile she had.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
