<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service has moved the following
entertainment/arts, travel, business and style articles this week
for release Sunday, August 6, 2000. Week in review articles will
move Saturday morning. If you have questions about stories, call
888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (moving in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-MUSIC (Undated) _ Last year was a great year for Latin
music, and by extension Latin culture, in the United States, if one
accepts that the enthusiastic reception of Latin music by
non-Latinos was a true indication of the music's health. By Peter
Watrous.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-ROCK-MUSIC (Bogota, Colombia) _ Rock may have been born as
American music, but at middle age it is also the music of the
Americas, as quickly becomes apparent during an afternoon spent in
a recording studio here with Aterciopelados, Colombia's most
popular rock band. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   DIESKAU-MUSIC (Undated) _ Who would suspect, this late in the
game, that there were any crucial gaps left to fill in the
discography of Dietrich Fischer-Dieskau? Yet here comes Myto
Records, of Milan, advertising the first release ever of
Fischer-Dieskau's first-ever operatic appearance. By Matthew
Gurewitsch.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRONIC-MUSIC (Undated) _ The Lincoln Center Festival's
five-concert Electronic Evolution series last month surveyed the
history of electronic music, starting with the 1920 invention of
the theremin, the electronic instrument that looks like a radio
transmitter and was once a staple of sci-fi movie soundtracks.
These rewarding concerts showed where electronic music has come
from. But a free preconcert event in the Low Library at Columbia
University showed where electronic music, maybe music as a whole,
could be going. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AFFAIR-OF-LOVE-FILM (Undated) _ ``I lived a powerful love story,
I understood nothing about it, and I needed to delve into my
questions in a film,'' said the Belgian director Frederic Fonteyne,
by way of explaining his tender, unconventional and emotionally
charged movie about middle-aged romance, ``An Affair of Love.''
Written by his longtime friend and collaborator Philippe Blasband,
it depicts a 40-something woman and a slightly younger man who meet
in Paris through a personals ad that the woman has placed in order
to fulfill a particular sexual fantasy. The characters never tell
each other their names, nor do they (or we) have any information
about their respective backgrounds. By Laura Winters.
</P>
<P>
   AIMEE&AMP;JAGUAR-FILM (Undated) _ Felice Schragenheim was a
high-spirited, educated, sensual, witty and wily young lesbian,
whose dangerous misfortune was to have been born Jewish in
pre-World War II Germany. During the war she lived in Berlin under
an assumed name and worked at a Nazi newspaper, feeding information
to the underground resistance. Lilly Wust, the young wife of an SS
soldier, was the mother of four boys, and for her effort in
producing such strapping young specimens of Aryan youth, she was
awarded the Nazi's Maternal Cross in bronze. She had reportedly
once said that she could ``smell Jews,'' a comment that, when it
reached Felice via a mutual friend, challenged the playful Felice
to arrange a meeting with such a person. ``Aimee and Jaguar,''
which opens August 11, is based on the true story of Felice
Schragenheim and Lilly Wust. By Nancy Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JEWISH-TV (New York) _ You don't get much banter in the four
Hebrew horse operas being screened August 8 at the Jewish Museum in
Manhattan. Billed as ``Wild Wild West: The Jewish Experience,'' the
program is comprised of hourlong TV episodes with Jewish themes,
including a 1963 episode of the historically dubious ``Bonanza.''
``We want audiences to look critically at the way Jewish ethnicity
has been represented on TV,'' said Andrew Ingall, the museum's
broadcasting archivist. ``The Jewish characters on these shows are
basically stereotypes. But then, all four teleplays are products of
their time.'' By Franz Lidz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AFRIQUE-DANCE (Undated) _ ``Le Coq Est Mort,'' an earnest but
problematic production that will open on August 9 at the Jacob's
Pillow Dance Festival in Becket, Mass., sheds light on some of the
tensions inherent in working with people from other cultures, a
practice that is gaining favor among performing artists. By
Christopher Reardon.
</P>
<P>
   STREB-DANCE (Undated) _ At a recent dance forum, Elizabeth Streb
introduced herself with considered clarity: ``Ten years ago I
thought of myself as someone who had a dance company. Today I think
of myself as someone who creates wild actions and movement moments
in a show that I sell.'' Streb, artistic director of Streb, has
never been a typical choreographer. For her new show, ``Action
Heroes,'' Streb has pumped up the spectacle with a music-sound
score and at least the semblance of a story. Streb has gone Vegas.
Or, at least, that's where she's headed. By Ann Daly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART-ARCHITECTURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EXPLORATORIUM-ART (San Francisco) _ Since the Exploratorium was
founded here 31 years ago as an innovative ``museum of science, art
and human perception,'' it has taken pride in breaking traditional
museum rules. Mixing science exhibits and artworks with little
concern about which is which, the Exploratorium encourages a
giddily high level of interactivity, inviting visitors not just to
stand and contemplate but to touch, pump, spin or otherwise mess
around with most of the 600-plus items on display. This summer,
however, a few distinguished visitors are being treated with
decidedly old-fashioned formality. By Tessa DeCarlo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SKYSCRAPER-REFORM (Undated) _ In the absence of alternatives,
there may be no more important project under way in New York right
now than David Childs' restoration of Lever House, the
International Style skyscraper on Park Avenue. Designed by Gordon
Bunshaft and completed in 1952, Lever House was the first glass
curtain wall tower to rise in New York. It remains among the 20th
century's major landmarks. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FAUST-THEATER (Hanover, Germany) _ There are also two souls
within ``Faust.'' ``Faust,'' Part 1, published in 1808 and a work
of both Goethe's youth and maturity, contains the well-known plot _
the bargain of the learned Doctor Faust with Mephistopheles, the
seduction of the innocent Gretchen _ that has been echoed in
novels, movies, puppet shows and several operas. ``Faust,'' Part 2,
written in Goethe's old age and published shortly after his death
in 1832, is more abstract, disjunct, and hardly ever staged. So
when one of Germany's most celebrated theatrical directors, Peter
Stein, determined to mount a production of the complete uncut
``Faust,'' Parts 1 and 2, it became an event of national magnitude.
By Anne Midgette.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Editors: The city of Sydney, host of the 2000 Olympic Games, is
featured in this week's travel section:
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-OLY-TICKETS (Undated) _ Time, something that many Olympic
athletes compete against, has turned out to be a friend to
Americans thinking of going to the Summer Games in Sydney next
month. Those who have waited before buying package tours to the
Games, which officially open Sept. 15 and continue to Oct. 1, will
find cheaper plans than were available several months ago. In some
cases, the savings are about 50 percent. By Joseph Siano.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-OLY-SYDNEY-QUEENSTREET-ART (Undated) _ Visitors to the
Olympics who need an antidote to the events and the crowds can
spend a few hours wandering along Queen Street in Woollahra. The
quiet, tree-lined area is filled with antiques stores and a few
smart restaurants. Much of Sydney has become overwhelmed with new
building and brash architecture, but Woollahra, one of the early
settlements of the colonial city, has retained its original terrace
houses, shady trees and village atmosphere. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-OLY-SYDNEY-ARTS-ART (Undated) _ Australia has
well-deserved credentials as one of the great sporting nations of
the world, but its reputation in the arts is a more recent
phenomenon. For visitors to the Olympic Games, the Sydney Olympic
Arts Festival, with its roster of dance, music, art, theater and
film, offers an enticing bonus, a way to appreciate the rich and
diverse culture of this antipodean nation and place Australia's
artistic achievements in an international context. The
six-week-long festival actually starts a full month before the
Games commence, to set the stage and to showcase the full scope of
arts offerings. By Susan Gough Henly.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-OLY-SYDNEY-PORTSTEPHENS (Undated) _ Port Stephens, north
of Sydney, is a calm bay ringed by beaches. It is the kind of
getaway that even steady rain cannot spoil. By John Tierney.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-OLY-SYDNEY-GUIDES (Undated) _ The best of the latest
guides to Sydney offer real insights into the city. By Debbie
Seaman.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Stargazing in Oakland; Cruise problems
in Fiji; Deerhurst resort north of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Dancing in Paris; Hudson River Valley
drives; shipping golf clubs. By Ray Cormier.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ A lawsuit raises the issue of
wheelchairs on ships. By Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BARGAINS (Undated) _ Ferry bargains in British Columbia;
Yellowstone in Autumn; early-bird specials in Puerto Rico. By
Joseph Siano.
</P>
