<P>
   &UR; ON THE SECTION FRONT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COCA-COLA (Daingerfield, Texas) _ Drive around here in midsummer
and you begin to understand why it turned into prime territory for
the latest skirmish in the cola wars. It was here, in the state
courthouse, that lawyers for nine bottlers and distributors of
Royal Crown Cola squared off this spring against the Coca-Cola Co.
and its largest bottler, Coca-Cola Enterprises. The trial took
place six years after the Royal Crown group sued Coke and its
bottler. The plaintiffs contended that Coke, working with Coca-Cola
Enterprises, had tried unfairly since the early '90s to keep them
out of supermarkets and convenience stores. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CBOT-TRADE (Chicago) _ The explosion of computerized trading is
threatening to make century-old pit trading obsolete. Indeed, some
believe the ``open outcry'' method of shouting and flashing hand
signals into a trading pit is already doomed. And so too, they say,
might be this country's oldest derivatives exchange, the Chicago
Board of Trade. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-WATCH (Undated) _ Weekly Wall Street commentary. By
Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE THE SECTION: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TENET-HEALTHCARE (Undated) _ Jeffrey Barbakow of Tenet
Healthcare Corp. has taken a lot of heat for building the nation's
second largest for-profit hospital chain. Over the past seven
years, residents from Philadelphia to Los Angeles have watched
Tenet buy their long-standing community hospitals, streamline
operations, and downsize staff. How long, people wondered, before
Tenet would cut the hospital's traditional role of caring for the
poor? So far that hasn't happened _ despite a $205-billion-gash in
Medicare payments over the past two years. Instead, Barbakow has
managed to lift corporate profits in this battered industry while
maintaining and, sometimes improving, patient care. By Kathleen
Sharpe.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   DAVID-LINK-PROFILE (Undated) _ As David Link sees it, doctors
heal the body, ministers heal the soul and lawyers heal society. By
Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BIZ-POLAND (Legnica, Poland) _ Thousands of Poles, with
government aid, have worked to beat Soviet swords into a share of
post-Communist prosperity, an opportunity they have grabbed with
both hands. By Peter S. Green.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-RESERVATIONS (Undated) _ The restaurant industry has been
slow to catch on to the electronic reservations revolution, but
there is now a growing number of Web sites that allow diners in
major cities to reserve tables online. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INVESTING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-ENERGY-STOCKS (Houston) _ Will natural gas prices stay
high? Consumers hope not, but the Anadarko Petroleum Corp., for
one, is betting that they will. Prices at the wellhead have leapt
80 percent this year, to more than $4 per million British thermal
units. Further, if colder temperatures return after the
unseasonably warm winters of the last few years, supplies could be
squeezed tighter, sending prices even higher. But that may be just
the start, argue executives at Anadarko, one of the largest
independent oil and gas producers. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Jay Walker didn't play Kevin
Costner's dad in ``Field of Dreams.'' But Walker, the founder of
Priceline.com, knows all about ``if you build it, they will come.''
Essentially, that is what he has been saying since he started
Priceline. On Wall Street it's called a ``demand collection
system'' that allows people to name their price for things like
plane tickets and hotel rooms. But Walker has more building to do.
By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-SIMPSON-WMGROWTH (Undated) _ Like most people who live in
Seattle, David Simpson is never too far from Mt. Rainier, the
highest peak in the Northwest. But he is often closer than most. On
weekends and vacations, Simpson leads Alpine climbers over Mt.
Rainier's glaciers and rocks; on weekdays, he drives past the
mountain on his way to work managing the $721.1 million WM Growth
Fund of the Northwest. By Carole Gould.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-SIX-FLAGS (Undated) _ Their amusement parks are best
known for their daredevil roller coasters that jolt riders by 180
degrees. But investors in Six Flags Inc. have been shaken around in
a different way: the stock is trading near its 52-week lows, amidst
losses and restructurings. Is it a buy? By Michelle Leder.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL COMMENTARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONTRARIAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Natural used to be Roy Hobbs,
Bernard Malamud's mythic baseball player, but now it's an obsession
that many of us seem to share about a life we have somehow lost. By
Daniel Akst.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ The wave of economic reforms that has
washed over Latin America first touched shore in Chile. That small
nation, with an economy roughly the size of New Jersey's, was the
first to tear down import barriers, liberalize exchange-rate
policy, bolster the domestic savings rate and otherwise whip itself
into shape for the new global economy. Now it wants to go further.
By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   STRATEGIES-COLUMN (Undated) _ One the investment world's great
unsolved mysteries has been why the dividend yield model stopped
working about a decade ago. This model, based on stocks'
dividend-to-price ratios, used to be one of Wall Street's
most-respected valuation models. Not any more. Today's investors,
who are fixated on making a quick buck, are likely to wonder how
anyone could ever have been interested in something so obviously
irrelevant as dividends. By Mark Hulbert.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
