u p BC-GORE-SPEECH-NYT &LR;      08-04 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SPEECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SPENT PART OF VACATION WRITING SPEECH, ADVISERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore spent part of his beach vacation writing his own speech
for next week's Democratic convention, according to Gore's Harvard
professor and longtime friend Martin Peretz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been drafted to tell him he should show it to other
people sooner rather than later,'' Peretz, who is better known as
the owner of The New Republic, said. ``And I dread saying it
because I dread his response.''
</P>
<P>
   Peretz declined to say who had drafted him for the job, though
he hinted it was Karenna Gore Schiff, Gore's oldest daughter and
one of his closest advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff did not say whether she had asked Peretz to prod her
father into involving the professionals, but did confirm that her
father is working on the speech himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been writing his speech all week,'' she said, typing
into a laptop on the porch of the North Carolina beach house where
the Gores were vacationing until Friday. .
</P>
<P>
   One night, Schiff said, the entire family was at the dinner
table until nearly 10 p.m., nibbling on the remains of her dad's
favorite Chinese dish, Szechuan beef, and ``listening to him talk
through some of the paragraphs he had written.''
</P>
<P>
   After returning to New York, Schiff said, she spoke with her
father on the phone on Thursday, while he was still in North
Carolina. ``I could hear the ocean in the background and he was
sitting on the porch writing,'' she said. ``He read me a few new
paragraphs, which I thought were the best yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing a speech of this importance oneself is virtually unheard
of in presidential politics. George W. Bush, the Republican
nominee, put his speechwriters through 17 drafts, but like most
candidates did not do any of the writing himself.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, though, is a former newspaper reporter who by all accounts
wrote every word of his best-selling 1992 book, ``Earth in the
Balance.'' The eulogy he wrote for his father's funeral in 1998was
widely considered the best speech he ever gave.
</P>
<P>
   And it is hardly out of character for Gore, who often rejects
his staff's advice and does things his own way, to have taken on
the speechwriting duties. This is the candidate, after all, who
designed his own ``Gore 2000'' campaign logo.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, some aides have complained that Gore relies too
much on his own instincts, and only really listens to his family,
particularly his daughter Karenna, wife Tipper and brother-in-law
Frank Hunger, who tend to support him in his own views.
</P>
<P>
   Because this speech is considered crucial for Gore's election
effort, it is not surprising, either, that there might be concern
about making sure the vice president hears from the professionals.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Gore campaign declined to say anything about
the speech or who was involved in writing it.
</P>
<P>
   While still at the beach, Schiff was not only critiquing her
dad's efforts but also working a bit on the nominating speech she
is to give in Los Angeles. ``It feels like a really important toast
at a wedding,'' she said, ``and I have to dig through my head for
anecdotes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
