<HEADER>
A3091 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-NEXT-480&AMP;ADD     08-04 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-NEXT-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH GAINS POPULARITY AFTER CONVENTION, AND HOPES IT WILL LAST 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas got a clear bump
upward from his acceptance speech and the Republican convention
generally, but its dimensions and duration were uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians around the nation said Bush had succeeded in his
most immediate task, using his first big-audience national
appearance to begin the task of showing himself to be a serious,
plausible national leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked and sounded like a leader, a potential president,''
said Robert Teeter, a Republican pollster.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican stalwart, former Sen. John Danforth of Missouri,
said after watching the convention on television, ``I feel better
about my party than I have in a long, long time. It had just the
right tone. It's remarkable that Republicans staked out significant
issues that were the preserve of the Democrats, like Social
Security and education.''
</P>
<P>
   One overnight poll, conducted for NBC News, indicated that
Bush's lead over Vice President Al Gore had gone from 6 percentage
points to 11. Candidates almost always gain after a convention, and
Teeter, who conducted this poll with Peter Hart, a Democrat, called
it ``a normal, an average bounce.'' The other poll, by the Tarrance
Group, said the margin had gone from 8 points to 18.
</P>
<P>
   While the Tarrance Poll showed an especially big gain among
independents, there were indications in some focus-group studies
that Bush's attacks on Gore had played badly among such voters.
Frank Luntz, who conducted a convention-long focus group of 36
uncommitted voters for MSNBC, said ``virtually every criticism
received a negative reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a point hit hard for the Gore campaign by Bob Shrum, a
consultant who works on major speeches and television
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the speech will wear well,'' Shrum said,
``because he engaged in the kind of personal attacks that don't
work with independent voters and don't work with undecided
voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrum also struck a major Democratic theme when he said,
``Ultimately, people are going to come to the issues.'' Then, he
said, they will reject Bush's tax plan, which ``gives $50,000 a
year to a millionaire and a dollar a day to the working man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think their whole convention was an effort to mention issues
without debating them or explaining their real positions,'' Shrum
said.
</P>
<P>
   That will be a major theme of the Democratic convention,
contending that the Bush proposals on issues like Social Security,
taxes, education and health will not work and will favor only the
rich. Democrats will also strongly criticize his record in Texas on
the environment and health.
</P>
<P>
   But that tack, Luntz warned, carries risks of its own. He said
the universal anti-attack mode of his focus group suggested that
``we live in an age of pleasantry'' when attacks function like an
inward-facing ``circular firing squad'' and wound the attackers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Neither of the polls was able to pinpoint states where the
convention had most helped Bush. G. Terry Madonna, a pollster at
Millersville University, said that in Pennsylvania, a crucial swing
state, said, ``I don't really know that it moved a lot of suburban
voters, and in Pennsylvania, I am absolutely convinced that the
election depends on the suburbs.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBC poll gave Bush 47 percent compared with 36 percent for
Gore, 6 percent for Ralph Nader and 1 percent for Pat Buchanan.
Before the convention, it had 44 percent for Bush, 38 percent for
Gore, 6 percent for Nader and 2 percent for Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   The Tarrance Group poll, a two-day survey that was completed on
Thursday with only a few interviews after the governor's acceptance
speech, gave Bush 49 percent, Gore 31 percent, Nader 6 percent and
Buchanan 2 percent. When the convention began, the numbers were 46
percent for Bush, 38 percent for Gore, 3 percent for Nader and 2
percent for Buchanan. Ed Goeas of the Tarrance Group said that
Bush's gains were widespread among various demographic groups, and
that Gore lost strength among Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the extent of the Bush gain uncertain, it is also
unclear whether it will be lasting. Andrew Kohut, a pollster and
director of the Pew Research Center for the People and the Press,
said, ``Is it a blip or a bounce? There are as many blips in recent
elections as there are booms.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, for example, President Clinton got no spurt in
popularity after his convention and Bob Dole, the Republican
candidate, did gain, but it was brief.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, convention week was the best week of Dole's
campaign, but Republicans in Philadelphia were insisting this week
that they had held out no real hopes then, while this time they
expected to win.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania called the 1996 session in San
Diego ``a very respectful convention,'' where delegates loved Dole
and his running mate, Jack Kemp, because of their efforts to
campaign for Republicans over the years. But, he continued, the
delegates knew ``they had one hell of a steep climb'' to defeat
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans said the best comparison to a past convention
was with the 1980 gathering in Detroit. Michael Deaver, who worked
on Ronald Reagan's staff, said the task back then was to show the
seriousness of a ``governor from the West with no foreign policy
experience, who seemed maybe a little light, read from speech
cards, maybe didn't have an independent thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's situation in 2000, Deaver said, is similar to Reagan's in
1980. Then there were ``people not wanting to vote for Carter, but
not being quite sure that Reagan was up to the job,'' he said,
adding that Reagan's effective convention speech was a beginning
for that reassurance, which was capped when Reagan debated Carter
in October.
</P>
<P>
   The one convention that no one in Philadelphia wanted to
remember was the last one in that city, where Gov. Thomas E. Dewey
of New York, favored in the polls, strengthened his ticket with a
widely hailed running mate, Gov. Earl Warren of California. Dewey
spoke confidently of unity in an acceptance speech characterized by
his biographer, Richard Norton Smith in ``Thomas E. Dewey and His
Times,'' as short, dignified and ``the speech of a man already
elected.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 25, 1948, the Philadelphia Evening Bulletin's
front-page, end-of-convention headline proclaimed, ``Dewey Leaves,
Sure He'll Win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
