<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-JARRETT0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Top-10 finishes in past 10 races make Jarrett favorite
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ When Dale Jarrett won the Brickyard 400 last
year, he essentially clinched the 1999 Winston Cup championship.
With a repeat performance today, he could return to the top of the
Winston Cup points standings.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett will start fifth in today's event at Indianapolis Motor
Speedway. Ricky Rudd, Jarrett's teammate at Robert Yates Racing, is
the pole sitter and is surprisingly joined on the front row by
53-year old Darrell Waltrip.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jarrett is not starting first at Indy, he has been
mentioned by other drivers as the favorite to finish first today.
Jarrett is a two-time winner at the Brickyard, with the other
victory being in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we have the opportunity to win again, but I think
the competition has caught up (at) a lot of places, particularly
here,'' Jarrett said. ``But I think we have a very good shot at
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past three months, Jarrett has been on a torrid
streak. Beginning with the Fontana, Calif., race on April 30, he
has finished the past ten Winston Cup events in the top 10. Jarrett
had fallen all the way back to eighth in points in the spring but
has rallied with a smooth summer ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked all year about the `New Generation' Goodyear tire,
and that was the biggest factor in what we found early in the year
_ that we just weren't getting a handle on it,'' Jarrett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked hard (to) ensure what we are learning and know
what it takes to run with this tire and be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were struggling to be a top-10 car . . . that was like a
victory for us. Now we've got ourselves in the top five battling
for victories and as long as you run there, you're going to be able
to get some wins. So we're back on track, so to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   After crossing the line in fourth place in the Pennsylvania 500
at Pocono two weeks ago, Jarrett moved past Dale Earnhardt Sr. in
the points standings to second place. He trails leader Bobby
Labonte by 53 points with 15 races remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the championship comes down to the team that makes
the fewest mistakes,'' Jarrett said. ``You can't get overly excited
at any race track. You have to be patient and take the
opportunities when they present themselves to you.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jarrett wins today's event _ and Labonte finishes 15th or
higher _ he will become the points leader for the first time since
after the Feb. 27 race at Rockingham. Ironically, Labonte is one of
Jarrett's picks to win at the ``world's most famous track for auto
racing.''
</P>
<P>
   `` ``I hope (Labonte is) in the rearview mirror,'' Jarrett said.
I'm afraid I might be seeing him from my windshield. Bobby and his
team perform really well on flat race tracks. They do extremely
well here. I think he finished second here a couple of times. I
think it's just a matter of time before he's in victory lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, he and Tony (Stewart) both seem to have a lot of things
figured out on these flatter race tracks that make them both
perform extremely well. So I would look for those guys to be guys
we have to beat in order to win.''
</P>
<P>
   In last season's Brickyard 400, Jarrett put on the most dominant
display in the event's seven-year existence. Todd Parrott pulled a
fast one on the rest of the field by calling for only two fresh
tires on the final pit stop, allowing Jarrett to win by the
incredible margin of 3.351 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that you can ever have a perfect race, but (last
year) was as close as it could come because we did everything we
needed to do,'' said Jarrett, who will use the same car today.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett has a habit at peaking with driving skills at the
biggest races. His only other win was at the season-opening Daytona
500 last February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy the challenge knowing that everybody is here and at
Daytona with their very best equipment,'' Jarrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
