<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3098 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-NKOREA-ARMS-1205(2TAK     08-04 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-ARMS-1205(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARSE DATA ON NORTH KOREAN ARMS LED TO DISPUTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Exclusive) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Behind the growing debate over whether to build a
new national missile defense against countries like North Korea
lies an old and bitter dispute over how to interpret the
frustratingly limited intelligence on of one of the world's most
secretive nations.
</P>
<P>
   Witness this incident, not previously disclosed: Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright had just completed an upbeat, top-secret
briefing for the House leadership in July 1998 on the Clinton
administration's dealings with North Korea when one lawmaker posed
the question he had been waiting to ask.
</P>
<P>
   What was Albright's assessment of a recent intelligence report
suggesting that North Korea had built a storage installation that
housed components for nuclear warheads? How long had she known
about the report?
</P>
<P>
   Albright, according to several people who were present, replied
that she had learned of the evidence just two weeks earlier. In a
startling departure from the united front that top administration
officials usually present to Congress, Lt. Gen. Patrick Hughes,
director of the Defense Intelligence Agency, immediately
contradicted the secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Madam secretary, I have to correct the record,'' said Hughes,
whose agency had produced the report, according to others who were
there. ``You were briefed on that intelligence a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   That tart exchange offered an unusual glimpse of the depth of
the disagreements between the United States' senior diplomats and
the Pentagon's top intelligence officials over how to interpret the
few hard facts available about North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said the dispute spurred them to demand an independent
review of the evidence on North Korea, which the administration
eventually acceded to with the appointment of former Defense
Secretary William Perry as special adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the debate stems from arcane arguments over photos or
snippets of intelligence from agents. State Department officials
say the Pentagon intelligence agency, well known for its hawkish
outlook, has been painting far too dark a picture, surmising on
sketchy evidence that North Korea has up to 10 new installations
working on a covert nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department officials said their skepticism about the
quality of the Defense Intelligence Agency's work was deepened by a
1999 incident in which U.S. diplomats leaned heavily on the North
Koreans to allow inspections of a site that the intelligence agency
had said was part of the nuclear program. Nothing was found.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, intelligence analysts at DIA are said to believe
the State Department has been far too willing to overlook reports
of suspicious activity. In their view, the failure of a single
inspection does not mean the United States should stop pressing the
North Koreans about suspect facilities, including the intelligence
report about the storage building suspected of housing warhead
components.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis over North Korea's nuclear program began in 1993,
when analysts reviewing evidence captured by U.S. spy satellites
concluded that a North Korean nuclear reprocessing facility at
Yongbyon had gone ``hot'' _ had begun to process plutonium.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. intelligence analysts then watched as the North Koreans
dumped radioactive nuclear fuel out of the heavy-water reactor into
a cooling pool in order to replace it with fresh fuel rods. The
spent fuel rods contained enough plutonium for 10 nuclear warheads,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The activity at Yongbyon led to a diplomatic showdown, and after
months of talks the Clinton administration won a North Korean
pledge to freeze plutonium production at the site.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the United States, South Korea and Japan agreed to
give the North oil and technical assistance to build a peaceful
nuclear-power program. The agreement called for international
monitoring of the Yongbyon site, and Energy Department experts were
allowed to encase the spent fuel rods at the facility to ensure
that they could not be used for warheads.
</P>
<P>
   Before the production freeze, North Korea was able to produce
about 26 pounds of weapons-grade plutonium, U.S. intelligence
analysts agree. A consensus developed that North Korea could
produce one or two bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Political problems first surfaced when administration officials
began to declare that North Korea had agreed to freeze its entire
nuclear program. Eventually, however, the lawmakers realized that
the agreement covered only Yongbyon and did not preclude nuclear
activity at other sites. Suspicions immediately arose that the
North Koreans were in fact covertly continuing work on their
nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
   After the administration negotiated the freeze on activity at
Yongbyon, the Defense Intelligence Agency began to report that it
had detected a series of other secret sites, many of them
underground, that analysts suspected were related to an ongoing
nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1990s, DIA, working closely with the National
Imagery and Mapping Agency, which processes and analyzes
spy-satellite photographs, compiled a list of at least 10 such
sites.
</P>
<P>
   None, however was a ``smoking gun.'' One official termed them
``enigmas'': They raised suspicions, yet the United States did not
have enough evidence to prove their ties to a nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
   DIA analysts were most concerned about one facility that they
suspected of being a storage building for components of nuclear
warheads. The identity and exact location of the suspected storage
center, whose existence has not been previously made public, could
not be learned.
</P>
<P>
   Current and former officials say the intelligence on the storage
facility was obtained at least three years ago, and was based not
only on spy satellite photographs and intercepted communications,
but on ``human intelligence'' _ spies _ reporting to the DIA.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also detected another facility, at Kumchangri, that
was believed to house an underground nuclear reactor and plutonium
reprocessing operation. The existence of that underground facility
was publicly disclosed in The New York Times in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1999, the United States pressed North Korea to allow an
inspection of the Kumchangri facility. Before that visit, the DIA
provided senior officials with extensive briefings on Kumchangri,
complete with models of what DIA analysts believed the installation
contained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kumchangri had all the signatures you would look for if they
were putting a reactor underground,'' said one former U.S.
intelligence official. ``It had vast water supplies, and the belief
was that the reactor would be water-cooled.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the U.S. team arrived, they found nothing but a series
of narrow, empty tunnels, with no large underground chamber capable
of holding a nuclear reactor. The inspection was a bust, and an
``embarrassment'' to the United States, said an official familiar
with the inspection.
</P>
<P>
   The United States sent another inspection team to Kumchangri in
May of this year, but again they found nothing to indicate that it
was involved in a nuclear-weapons program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a joke,'' said one State Department official.
``The North Koreans really must have thought we were idiots.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some officials say that the United States gave North Korea far
too much advance warning of its interest in visiting the Kumchangri
site before inspecting the facility, making it possible for the
North Koreans to hide its purpose. They add that the Kumchangri
facility was still under construction when it was first detected by
U.S. intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``My best guess is that it was something bad on the nuclear
side, but no one knows,'' said an official familiar with the
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   But the inspections of Kumchangri seriously damaged DIA's
credibility with administration officials and analysts at the other
agencies, particularly the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   The skepticism deepened after U.S. officials discovered that
another installation that had fallen under DIA suspicion turned out
to be an underground storage site for the memorabilia of the North
Korean leadership.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the administration has become extremely reluctant
to pursue leads on other suspected facilities identified by the
DIA. The administration has never asked to inspect the secret
facility believed to be a warhead storage site, several U.S.
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a prime example of policy being driven by
intelligence, and at the end of the day it was wrong,'' said one
State Department official critical of the DIA's handling of the
Kumchangri case.
</P>
<P>
   After the failed inspections at Kumchangri, U.S. intelligence
officials debated whether to conduct a thorough review of the
available intelligence on the North Korean nuclear program and
produce what is known as a National Intelligence Estimate,
representing a government-wide consensus on the problem. But there
were so many inter-agency disagreements that no such estimate was
commissioned, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   At the DIA, meanwhile, the agency's inability to provide more
conclusive evidence has prompted it to take a more cautious tone in
its assessments, officials said. Adm. Thomas Wilson, Hughes'
successor, has not been as aggressive in pushing the issue,
officials say. ``DIA was driving this process,'' noted one
intelligence official. ``But there has been a change of leadership
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes retired in July 1999, a year after his showdown with
Albright.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said that Hughes
eventually apologized to Albright, who still maintains that she had
learned of the secret facility just two weeks before the hearing.
But Hughes said in an interview that while he did apologize to
Albright for ``causing her public embarrassment,'' he did not
apologize for correcting the record, because her testimony was not
accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt bad that I caused the secretary of state some
embarrassment,'' Hughes said. ``But on the other hand, I felt fine
about raising the issue, and still do today. I would have hated
going away from there with Congress thinking we hadn't properly
informed officials about the intelligence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
