<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-04 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: ARCHBISHOP OF CANTERBURY SPEAKS AT GRAHAM EVANGELICAL
GATHERING 
</HEADLINE>
   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands _ When the Billy Graham Evangelistic
Association planned a conference here this week for evangelists
from around the world, it signed up a raft of prominent speakers,
many of them very well known among evangelical Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone who took the podium came from the sort of
religious background that Graham represents: the itinerant
evangelist of Baptist background. In fact, one of the more
interesting and nuanced speeches came from the leader of a
hierarchical and liturgical church _ the archbishop of Canterbury,
George Carey, spiritual leader of the Church of England and first
among equals among bishops of Anglican churches worldwide, a group
that includes the Episcopal Church in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Carey came to talk about effective Christian preaching in a
``broken'' and sinful world. And he began by praising some words of
the French existentialist Albert Camus _ not the sort of figure one
would expect to hear quoted at an evangelists' conference. Yet, the
archbishop said, Camus, in his book ``The Fall,'' which is set in
Amsterdam, had given a moving appraisal of human sinfulness. He
called the book a great one.
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop urged that churches preach a ``committed faith in
Christ'' as the singular savior, an argument for the uniqueness of
Christianity's claims in a world increasingly conscious of
religious pluralism. But he also said _ in fact, said twice _ that
he held no brief for fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christ whom we follow is one who allows people to think,
argue, dispute and doubt,'' Carey said. ``Authentic Christian faith
is not afraid of scholarship or the critical study of the
Scriptures.''
</P>
<P>
   He also called on evangelicals to embrace an ecumenical spirit
in the name of presenting a common faith, and to be involved in
society to combat social evils. In supporting ecumenism, he was
endorsing both the example set by Graham, who has long tried to
bring together as many different churches as he can at his
preaching events, and also the various Anglican churches, which
have lately entered into formal alliances with other denominations,
as Episcopalians have with Evangelical Lutherans in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Carey's speech to the conference, which concludes on Sunday, was
reported and favorably commented upon in the British press. But
much of the focus was on a limited part of it, in particular, his
criticism of human attempts to replace religious faith with total
reliance on therapy, education or the pursuit of wealth. He had
good things to say about therapy and education, but indicated that
he worried that too many sermons had adopted a therapeutic message
and missed ``an appeal to a holy God and his call to us to turn to
him in repentance and faith.''
</P>
<P>
   What some reports on his speech overlooked, too, was the note of
optimism he struck, unlike those who would preach doom and gloom.
The archbishop called the world a good place, even wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   ``No true Christian ever despises the world,'' he said. ``We
love it, we exalt it, we cherish it. And we love humanity made in
God's image. Fallen, yes _ but always loved by Almighty God and
therefore loved by us.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the conference began, its organizers predicted it would
be attended by 10,000 evangelists from 190 nations and territories.
The estimates turned out to be accurate. After the event began,
Graham's association reported that 10,287 people, representing 209
nations and territories, had registered for it.
</P>
<P>
   Half those attending came from either North America or Africa.
After the United States, with 2,767 people, the largest delegations
came from India (495 people), Ghana (249), Kenya (204) and South
Africa (182).
</P>
<P>
   Many brought pamphlets with them, to spread the word about their
particular efforts. Thus, one information table carried stacks of
fliers describing groups probably little known outside their
immediate regions: India Youth for Christ, the Evangelical Alliance
of Sri Lanka, Christ Total Gospel Ministries International of
Nigeria, and many, many others.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Graham, Billy Graham's eldest son and designated
successor as head of the Graham organization, was also among the
conference's speakers, taking the podium Thursday after flying from
Philadelphia, where he had offered a prayer at the Republican
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   His stated theme was evangelism and compassion, but he seemed
more inclined to offer his audience a lesson about preaching to win
converts. Make sure, he told the crowd, that people know in advance
that you are going to make an altar call, so the unconverted know
they will have the opportunity to come down to the front of the
event and declare a born-again faith in Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Like Carey, Graham spoke about sin, but from the perspective of
one who wants to tell people just what it is. ``People today,
especially in Western society, don't even know what sin is,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   To clear up the ignorance, he said, he often goes to the 10
Commandments. ``Telling a lie is a sin, sex outside of marriage is
a sin,'' Graham said. ``But I'm very careful to say God loves
you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3103 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GOP-REACT-ART-4TAKES-     08-04 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-REACT-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATCHING, LISTENING, HOPING FOR A PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Calif., Wis., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 14, 15 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tamara Allen wanted to like what she saw. She was in
the market for a president. She voted for Bill Clinton in two
elections, and for Ronald Reagan before that. But she reacted to
the Republican National Convention with disappointment and venom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was astounded at the falsity, the facade of it all,'' said
Allen, an executive assistant for Hands On Atlanta, a nonprofit
service organization.
</P>
<P>
   Watching from her home in Grant Park, a predominantly black,
gentrifying neighborhood of Atlanta, Allen, who is black, was
heartened at first by the number of women and those belonging to
minorities on stage in Philadelphia. But then, she said, she went
``from being disappointed to being angry.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Republican Party hoped that assembling a festival of
diversity on the convention podium would convince voters that its
party had a grand new diverse face, conversations with voters in
four places in America this week indicated that it was not entirely
succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   Voters interviewed here and in New York, Milwaukee and Los
Angeles had a wide array of reactions to the convention. Some found
things to approve of, like the gathering's patriotic fervor or what
they saw as Gov. George W. Bush's ``presidential stature.''
</P>
<P>
   But the one theme that ran consistently through many of their
observations was that they did not necessarily accept at face value
the rainbow image the Republicans were projecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like this mega-infomercial, but not nearly as
entertaining,'' Allen said. ``Give me Ginzu knives.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, over four days of intermittent convention viewing in their
homes, three women undecided about their votes were less than sold
on Bush and were waiting to see whether the Democrats in Los
Angeles would be more captivating.
</P>
<P>
   Another of the women, Latara Jackson, 19, who will vote for
president this year for the first time, was at the end leaning,
however slightly, in the Democrats' direction. An intern with the
U.S. Department of Labor, she is a student who describes herself as
having conservative views. But after watching the convention's
opening night, she found herself leaning away from the Republican
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a last attempt to basically come out as just
very tolerant,'' Jackson said. ``It was like they were trying too
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, an admirer of retired Gen. Colin L. Powell, was
disappointed by his speech, which she found insincere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a last-ditch effort, and I was kind of
disappointed that he would be a part of that,'' said Jackson, who,
like Powell, is black.
</P>
<P>
   She did not appreciate what she described as Bush`s rude remarks
about Vice President Al Gore's personality and character: ``He kind
of made personal jabs at him. I think he did that to kind of get
away from the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's vow to prohibit the kind of late-term procedure that
opponents call partial-birth abortion left Jackson feeling his
stance had been watered down. ``In reality, we know he thinks all
abortion is wrong,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole convention dealt with no issues at all,''
she said. ``Any attempt to deal with any issues was very weak, just
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   While she believed Bush appeared presidential, if she had to
vote tomorrow, Jackson would select Gore for what she saw as his
sincerity and his drive to try to do what he thinks is best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would define myself more as a Republican than a Democrat,''
she said. ``But I just couldn't vote for this Republican,'' mostly
because of the remarks he made against his opponent, but also
because of the Philadelphia celebration's efforts to include
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really late, like at the last minute,'' she said. ``It
was a really bad attempt.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Jane Kruzan, 72, a retired director of a volunteer
placement agency, said she was beginning to think she could forget
about some of the issues she felt strongly about, in order to vote
Republican, as she often does.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environment, gun control and campaign finance are
certainly not being answered in these three days, but I'm impressed
with the types of people promoting Governor Bush,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really looking forward to the debates,'' said Kruzan, who
is white and lives in Decatur, an Atlanta suburb. ``I'm not ready
for the ballot box. I would not feel comfortable going tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   She felt the same after hearing Bush's acceptance speech, which
she found comprehensive and impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he certainly articulated his views very well,'' she
said, ``but I will have to admit that the truth is in the
details.''
</P>
<P>
   She was glad he mentioned the environment, though it was too low
on his priority list for her, and she was not impressed by his plan
to enforce existing gun-control laws rather than push for stronger
ones.
</P>
<P>
   In all, she said, her opinion of the candidate rose during the
convention, particularly after she saw people who might serve in
his Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday night, Allen sat back from the television and
played with her hair pensively. ``Today I'm just sad about my
choices,'' she said. ``I'm concerned now. Yesterday I was still
kind of waffling, but today I'm really sad. I don't know who I'm
going to vote for, and I love voting.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, when Bush vowed to support a ban on the abortion
procedure, Allen, who is in her mid-30s, said he lost her vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There you go,'' she said. ``OK, so, it's over for me. He just
told me I don't control me. He just told me that I don't count.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'll wait and I'll see what Gore has to say,'' Allen
said Thursday. ``He better be honest. I mean just real stuff, not
all of this kind of `rockets' red glare,' lyrics from the anthem,
fields of waving grass and grain.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the convention had pushed her away from voting for
Ralph Nader, whom she admires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have voted for Nader before I saw this, but seeing
Cheney made me so afraid,'' she said. ``He doesn't represent half
the people or a quarter, he represents the upper echelon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I came out of this with anything, it's that I want a
debate. Bad. I can taste it I want it so bad,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Milwaukee &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Watching the Republican National Convention from his living
room, James Greer, a 54-year-old lawyer and an independent, found
himself awash in pleasantness.
</P>
<P>
   It was Laura Bush, the wife of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who
set the tone. ``She has a softer way,'' Greer said. ``She's really
a plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Like movie critics, or perhaps Olympic judges, Greer and six
other Milwaukee residents watched the Republican convention this
week, giving marks for style and substance, ready to catch any
stumbles.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, all of them _ a die-hard Republican, a devoted
Democrat and varying shades of independents _ agreed that while the
convention was lacking in suspense, it was also free of missteps.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, one resident, Brian Colon, 27, a computer
programmer, found comfort in retired Gen. Colin L. Powell's message
that many Americans deserved help.
</P>
<P>
   Another resident, Chiquita Lee, a 63-year-old homemaker and a
Republican, who is black, found it pleasing to watch Republicans
``of different colors _ this convention was really reaching out.''
</P>
<P>
   Paris Wright, a 36-year-old computer systems analyst, also
expressed approval that Republicans ``realize that demographics are
changing, and that they need to widen the umbrella.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Kathleen Wyman, a 59-year-old real estate
agent, found the Republican efforts at racial diversity a bit
forced. ``Are these people really representative of the new
Republicans?'' Wyman said, muffling a chuckle. ``Of course they're
not.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Carolyn Castore, 47, the feel-good tenor of the opening
night was lacking in substance. ``It's like baby food,'' Castore
said, ``no flavor, no texture and designed to be easily
swallowed.''
</P>
<P>
   On the convention's second night, Greer offered praise as he
listened to speeches by Sen. John McCain of Arizona and Condoleezza
Rice, Bush's chief international affairs adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing Republicans do well is patriotism,'' he said. ``They
have a knack for waving the flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Colon, so impressed by McCain, exclaimed: ``I wish I had this on
tape!''
</P>
<P>
   But others were not convinced that McCain was speaking from his
heart. ``McCain gives a very good speech,'' Wyman said, ``but I
would bet that in his heart of hearts, he doesn't believe what he
says about Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee was taken with Lynne Cheney, the wife of Dick Cheney, the
vice-presidential candidate. ``She showed her devotion and love for
her husband,'' she said, ``while still showing that she was her own
person.''
</P>
<P>
   For Wright, it was the videotape of past presidents, especially
Ronald Reagan, that rang bells. ``It was really very moving,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, when Cheney introduced himself to voters,
the reviews from the Milwaukee residents were mostly favorable but
hardly inspired.
</P>
<P>
   Lee found Cheney's speech to be a bit heavy on cliches. ``I
think he has to grow on you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Colon said, ``It was just a speech, not so good, not so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wyman found Cheney's talk to be ``rational and to the
point.'' ``I can see this ticket being very attractive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Castore said Cheney's role was to shore up the conservative
base. ``Until he spoke, the messages had been so progressive, that
I was starting to feel sorry for the Republicans,'' she said. ``But
Cheney, with the whole morality issue, seemed to be bringing back
the base.''
</P>
<P>
   The Milwaukee residents paid most attention, not surprisingly,
to the speech by Bush on Thursday night. Most of them considered
the speech a success.
</P>
<P>
   Bush ``looked presidential,'' Wyman said, and he ``comes across
better than his father ever did.''
</P>
<P>
   In some places, she said, it was almost Reaganesque, ``the way
he talked about real people and made things very clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer noted that Bush ``didn't have his smirk,'' and said the
candidate scored points by presenting himself ``as a human,''
especially when making references to his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Lee remarked on Bush's ``charisma, the friend-next-door
appeal,'' and applauded his plans on education.
</P>
<P>
   For Castore, the praise was grudging. ``As a speech it was OK,
but I thought his attacks on Gore fell flat,'' she said, referring
to Vice President Al Gore. ``A lot of what he said, it sounded
good. But I don't know what it means. It lacked so many
specifics.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Colon, who had started the week not certain whether he
would vote for Bush or not, the speech was a clincher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just loved it,'' Colon said. ``I'm ready to march right out
and vote for him.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; DIRK JOHNSON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Los Angeles &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Vanegas is precisely the kind of person George W. Bush
has been straining to speak to this past week. He is a Latino and a
small-business owner, he hews to the political center, and he is
undecided about his vote this November. But after watching the
Republican convention, Vanegas is also a skeptic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mr. Bush is very noble and he wants to do the right
thing,'' said Vanegas, who is 31 and operates transportation and
real estate businesses. ``But as far as making me want to vote for
him, I'm still not there. As a Latino immigrant, being a bigger
superpower isn't something that appeals to me, and I don't mind
paying taxes or worry about a big tax cut. We just want opportunity
and a country with a big heart.''
</P>
<P>
   When Condoleezza Rice, a foreign policy expert, spoke on Tuesday
night, Vanegas said, he found her engaging but peripheral. ``How
much stronger do we need to be as a superpower?'' he asked. ``As a
Latino and an immigrant, that isn't something that appeals to me.''
</P>
<P>
   When Dick Cheney was introduced by his wife, Lynne, who
mentioned his interest in fly fishing, Vanegas was turned off.
``How many of us even thought about going fly fishing?'' he asked.
``I don't think many of us have the luxury of thinking about that.
I'm interested in work.''
</P>
<P>
   Another immigrant, Mario Matute, 40, who is voting in his first
presidential election, said he was impressed that Bush spoke some
Spanish and was at least interested in wooing Latinos. Matute
emigrated from El Salvador and runs a job development program.
</P>
<P>
   But after the convention appearances of two black speakers,
retired Gen. Colin Powell on Tuesday and Rice on Wednesday, Matute
said, he paid more attention to the color of the faces of the
delegates. ``Powell sounded mainly on the side of the Democrats by
addressing education and the racism that still exists in the
country,'' Matute said. ``They scored high with that. I think he
spoke from the heart, but if you looked at the faces there, it
didn't match. That was a disappointment for me.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the convention, which he described as generally
impressive, he said: ``I want to believe that they are a new party
and more inclusive, but it didn't look real to me, especially when
it came to policies. I wanted to hear more about immigration policy
and jobs, not tax cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   With its white majority long gone, a soaring immigrant
population and a heavy reliance on small businesses, Los Angeles is
the kind of nascent metropolis of the future that both parties need
to capture to win the White House. Conversations with a handful of
residents found that most of them, even ardent Democrats, had been
impressed by Bush's sense of optimism. But there were also
questions about how new the party could be with its conservative
core intact _ a core that is still perceived by many people here to
be less sympathetic than the Democrats to immigrants and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Inouye, a mortgage banker, said that she had been turned off
by what she perceived to be a lack of moral rectitude in the
Clinton White House and that she had found much to like in the
Republican platform, even though she supports abortion rights. But
in response to Cheney's sometimes harsh speech, she said that some
of the attacks had been inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics shouldn't be so polarized,'' she said. ``Bush was
confident and optimistic, not negative. That may be his edge.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention itself was a spectacle that left many cold. Some
people who work in Hollywood, of course, saw it as a cynical act of
manipulation, and they had their own suggestions for appealing to a
broader audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they should lock everybody in the convention hall like
`Survivor,''' said Robin Schiff, a television producer and
screenwriter. ``The last person alive is the candidate. It's
Republican `Survivor.' Now that's a convention I would watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim O'Doherty, a television producer, is that rarity in
Hollywood, an avowed Republican. His views evolved throughout the
week. Early on, he expressed concerns about his party's chances. He
said he had been very impressed by Sen. John McCain's speech, but
that it had only emphasized what he perceived as a lack of talent
elsewhere in the party. ``I'm very frustrated because we have some
real problems with our image,'' he said. ``There's a charisma
problem. We don't have the most exciting A-list talent pool.''
</P>
<P>
   By week's end, however, O'Doherty expressed enthusiasm for the
convention as a successful show. He said he felt that Cheney's
speech had energized the convention for the first time. He
applauded Bush as a leader with good ideas in his speech, and he
said the party had focused on the positive with a high moral tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did exactly what his mission was,'' O'Doherty said of
Bush's speech on Thursday night. ``He had to convince the swing
voters to come over, and that's what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Doherty's writing partner, David Israel, is a Democrat, but he
found some common ground. ``I think the biggest thing he had to do
was to not appear smug, and he did that,'' Israel said. ``I think
he's a likable guy, and he didn't say anything you could disagree
with. But I still don't know what he's really going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; JAMES STERNGOLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New York &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Political science students at New York University recognize
obscure de Toqueville quotations and argue the merits of the
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty vs. the Strategic Defense Initiative.
So when the Republican Convention rolled around they were an astute
audience, eager to analyze what George W. Bush set out to
accomplish and how well he succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   The students _ four from the undergraduate honors program and
three doctoral candidates _ differed on whether the convention was
``brilliant marketing,'' in the words of one, or ``insulting
propaganda,'' in the words of another. But all agreed it was a
textbook example of ``median voter theory'' and ``triangulation,''
insider jargon for capturing swing voters by show-casing the
popular issues of the opposition and burying the unpopular issues
of its own fringe, as Bill Clinton's Democrats did in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the theme of inclusion is a blatant plea to
nontraditional Republican voters,'' said Ramsey J. Green, 20, as he
watched a rainbow coalition of speakers cross the podium in
Philadelphia. ``It seems as though they have finally realized that
their reputation as white, wealthy and Christian will not appeal to
socially liberal suburban voters and therefore prevent them from
enjoying the policies of a Republican president.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, who will vote in his first presidential election, most
likely for Al Gore, veered between calling the tactic a ``sick
Republican scheme'' and saying that the convention had ``gone
extremely well'' for the party. Green argued with himself about
whether the Republicans were ``trying to pull the wool over my
eyes'' or ``making a serious attempt to change the party's
traditional ethnic and financial makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicted, as Gov. Bush completed his acceptance speech to a
hail of confetti, that the candidate had probably ``cajoled'' many
non-Republicans to vote for him in November. But he said they would
probably ``be let down come the implementation of the real policies
of a Bush administration,'' which would revert to form. But Green
said that the tone of the convention was a healthy development for
the party and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   From the other side of the political aisle, Costas Panagopolous,
a doctoral student who ran unsuccessfully for the Massachusetts
Legislature while a Harvard undergraduate, also saw the Republican
show of inclusion as a plus.
</P>
<P>
   Panagopolous, 28, who ran as a Republican but has since
re-registered as an Independent, said that ``I do think it's a
strategy _ for now. But if they win the election, they'll know it
works and this will have been a first step. It has to start
somewhere. And there comes a point where perception becomes
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Panagopolous, with his experience as a candidate and a resume
filled with jobs in marketing, seemed to unnerve other students
with his unabashed admiration for the ``rebranding'' by the
Republican party. ``It's no different than repositioning Hush Puppy
shoes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sona Nadenicheck, a doctoral candidate devoted to academic
research, not the hurly-burly of politics, gasped: ``But that's not
who they really are!''
</P>
<P>
   Nadenicheck's husband and fellow student, Matt Golder, jumped
in. ``The goal is to get elected,'' he said, soothingly, comparing
the Republicans to the Labor Party in his British homeland. ``It
took the Labor Party 10 years to change their image,'' Golder said,
declaring by the end of the convention that the Republicans had
surely ``been effective at winning over some undecided voters.''
</P>
<P>
   The students were not equally engaged by the four-day
proceedings. Alissa Elliott, a 20-year-old with a bent for
international relations, watched hours of C-Span each night, as she
cooked dinner, ironed and answered e-mail and took detailed
exception to the foreign policy positions of several speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Panagopolous, also a nightly devotee, dissected the
ramifications of Bush's proposed tax cuts and lamented the
candidate's silence on international trade and domestic economic
indicators. Green seemed to have seen virtually every speaker,
Republican National Committee video and mariachi or Motown band.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Martin Wolf, 19, skipped the first night because a
broken fish tank had shorted out his television set, and he
considered Bush's speech, which he grudgingly watched, a ``waste of
my time.'' Nadenichek, 28, said she would have ignored the Bush
speech and worked on a conference paper were it not for her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt had the TV on and we have a small one-bedroom
apartment,'' Nadenichek said. She was scornful of the Republican
performance throughout, but said it was more interesting than it
might have been because Golder brought a fresh eye to this American
spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   All of the students noted, admiringly, the Republicans finesse
at highlighting the improprieties, sexual and otherwise, of the
Clinton White House and tarnishing Gore in the process. They also
thought it deft to call attention to the nation's prosperity, the
Democrat's crowning achievement in the past eight years, while
characterizing it as an opportunity wasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush tried to point out what is morally wrong with the
executive administration today while pointing out what is right
with the economy,'' Green said. ``Theoretically, I guess this means
all Bush has to do is win the election, move into the White House,
do no harm to the economy and remain faithful to his wife. Sounds
like a pretty easy job.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; JANE GROSS &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
