<SLUG> BC-FILM-BLACKLIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKLISTED SCREENWRITERS GET CREDITS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The Writers Guild has announced that the writing
credits on 14 films released from 1951 to 1964 will be corrected to
include the names of several screenwriters blacklisted by Hollywood
studios. The current credits on the films either omitted a
blacklisted writer's name or used a pseudonym.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years the Writers Guild of America, West, has
corrected the writing credits on 95 such films.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of writers as well as actors, directors, agents and
producers found themselves blacklisted in the 1950s following
efforts by the House Committee on Un-American Activities to find
suspected Communists in the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those on the blacklist refused to name names, declined
to discuss their political beliefs, were singled out by informers
or were simply liberals who were friendly with Communists. Many of
the blacklisted writers started using ``fronts'' or pseudonyms,
while others fled to Europe to find work. Careers were damaged, if
not shattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hollywood blacklist destroyed the careers and lives of
numerous Americans _ not only artists but also those in government,
in academia and the unions,'' the Writers Guild said on Thursday.
The Guild said that ``because of the unchecked zealousness of HUAC,
the list also managed to include non-Communist liberals and even
victims of mistaken identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the films whose credits will be revised are ``He Ran All
the Way,'' a 1951 drama. The corrected credit reads Dalton Trumbo
and Hugh Butler, both blacklisted writers.
</P>
<P>
   Other blacklisted writers whose names have been added to films
included Carl Foreman (``Born for Trouble,'' 1955), Ben Barzman
(``Stranger on the Prowl,'' 1952, and ``It Happened in Paris,''
1953), Cyril Endfield (``The Master Plan,'' 1954), Bernard Gordon
(``Circus World,'' 1964) and Paul Jarrico (``The Man Who Watched
Trains Go By,'' 1952).
</P>
<P>
   Trumbo, a well-known screenwriter in the 1950s, whose films
included ``Exodus'' and ``Spartacus,'' was given new credits on a
handful of others, the Writers Guild said.
</P>
<P>
   These included ``The Green-Eyed Blonde,'' 1958; ``Terror in a
Texas Town,'' 1958; ``The Brave One,'' 1956, in which Trumbo shared
credit with Harry S. Franklin and Merrill G. White; ``The Boss,''
1956; ``Cowboy,'' 1958, sharing credit with Edmond H. North, and
``The Prowler,'' 1951. That film, also known as ``The High Cost of
Living,'' is also credited to Hugo Butler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
