<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3111 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-870     08-04 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-870(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH REPUBLICAN CONVENTION OVER, GORE COMES OUT SWINGING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.C., Mich, Pa., Ohio)   (Eds: ``Fire Fighters for Gore'' is cq) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 and NYT2 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ After suffering days of Republican barbs in silence,
Vice President Al Gore returned from vacation Friday swinging back
hard, accusing the Republicans of running a showy, but
insubstantial convention and strongly claiming credit for having
helped create the nation's roaring economy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had spent the week with his family on a North Carolina
beach while the newly minted Republican ticket of Gov. George W.
Bush, the presidential nominee, and his running mate, Dick Cheney,
used center stage in Philadelphia to portray the Clinton
administration as timid, ineffectual and lacking vision.
</P>
<P>
   The two Republican nominees zoomed out of the convention city in
a day filled by campaign trips by plane, train and car to stops in
Pennsylvania, Michigan and Ohio, as Bush continued his own
synthesis of conservative policies described in words likely to
appeal to swing voters. But he also showed a lift of his own after
the convention. Bush told a crowd of hundreds along downtown train
tracks in Pittsburgh, ``I can't tell you how energized I am.'' In
Chicago, Gore answered the Republican criticisms Friday by slinging
arrows of his own, without mentioning Bush or Cheney by name while
accusing the Republicans of trying to paper over empty promises and
harsh policies with a feel-good, slickly choreographed convention
that offered little more than ``confetti and klieg lights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to political pageantry, I've got to hand it to
the other side,'' Gore told a cheering throng of more than 3,000
representatives of the International Association of Fire Fighters.
``But you and I both know that a slogan never put out a raging
fire. A sound bite never saved a child from a burning building. And
political positioning will never heal sick children who don't have
health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing the role he seems most comfortable with, the
counterpuncher, Gore seemed to relish reusing a line of his own
from the 1992 campaign that Cheney had appropriated in
Philadelphia: ``It's time for them to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two nights ago at the convention, we heard their view of what
time it is,'' Gore told the firefighters. ``That was a familiar
line wasn't it? I remember that one. Well let me tell you what time
it's not. It's not time to give in to the big drug companies. It is
not time to give in to big insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``And our opponents may not like to hear it, but it is not
recession time in America like it was back in 1992,'' he continued
to loud cheers. ``It's not deficit time in America like it was in
1992.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore entered the Chicago hotel Friday morning looking like a
gladiator on an adrenaline high, pumping his fists as he led a
march of chanting firefighters dressed in yellow T-shirts
emblazoned with the words, ``Fire Fighters for Gore.'' Inside the
ballroom, he spent nearly 10 minutes wending his way through the
crowded aisle toward the stage, slapping high-fives, grabbing every
outstretched hand and cradling an infant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we're starting out behind,'' he said. ``I'm here today
to serve notice: This is Day 1 of the fight for working families.
And with your help, we're going to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers are hoping to fill the coming 10 days with
events like the one Friday, first to dampen any post-convention
bounce in the polls the Republicans are likely to receive, and then
to build enthusiasm for Gore's own triumphal entrance into the
Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles on Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Later Sunday, Gore spoke here before more than 8,000 letter
carriers, and on Saturday he will address a convention of the
National Association of Police Organizations in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's speeches offered a preview of the themes Gore will
emphasize in the coming week and at the convention. He fired
populist attacks against the Republicans, describing their
convention as ``a masquerade ball for special interests'' and
repeating the refrain, ``They're for the powerful, and we're for
the people.''
</P>
<P>
   He pledged to oppose tax cuts for the rich, bolster Social
Security, improve public schools, provide targeted tax breaks for
the middle class, raise the minimum wage by a dollar and make it
easier for workers to form unions.
</P>
<P>
   And, as if to answer critics within his own party who contend he
has not done enough to reveal his personal side to voters, he
salted his speech Friday with more biography than usual, saying,
``I also want the American people to know me for who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   He then dwelt heavily on his time in Vietnam as an army
journalist, offering an implicit contrast to Bush, who served in
the Texas Air National Guard during the war, never leaving the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in Vietnam, I didn't do the most or run the
greatest danger,'' Gore said. ``But I volunteered and enlisted
because I loved my country, and I knew that if I didn't go, I knew
that someone else from my home town of Carthage, Tennessee, would
have to go in my place.''
</P>
<P>
   Left out of that explanation are two other possible reasons for
his decision to volunteer: His desire to help insulate his father,
an anti-war senator from Tennessee at the time, from Republican
criticism, and his own interest in broadening his resume for a
future political campaign.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was accompanied by his wife, Tipper, who
aides said was likely to spend significantly more time campaigning
for her husband in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to one of Bush's harsher attacks _ that the Clinton
administration had coasted through eight years of prosperity,
choosing ``the path of least resistance'' _ Gore said: ``What
planet have they been on?''
</P>
<P>
   He then claimed partial credit for starting the nation's
economic recovery by casting a tie-breaking vote in the Senate for
the president's 1993 economic stimulus plan. And he recalled the
efforts of the Republican-controlled Congress, led by Speaker Newt
Gingrich, to shut down the government in 1995, which polls showed
to be highly unpopular with voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish there had been less resistance,'' he said. ``I broke
the tie when every Republican voted no on the economic change that
has brought about this prosperity. I wish there had been less
resistance and that they didn't shut down the government twice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
