<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-TV-RATINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV AUDIENCE FOR BUSH'S SPEECH SLIGHTLY HIGHER THAN DOLE'S IN '96 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 18 million people watched the coverage of George W.
Bush's acceptance speech on ABC, CBS and NBC on Thursday night,
compared with the 17.8 million who watched the coverage of Bob
Dole's on those networks on the final night of the 1996 Republican
convention, according to Nielsen Media Research data.
</P>
<P>
   Viewership was bolstered by a particularly strong showing by
ABC, which ran an episode of ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''
before its coverage began and scored the highest ratings of the
night among the major broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   On cable television, CNN, with 2.3 million viewers, saw its
final-night audience drop 22 percent from the level of 1996. Some
of those viewers clearly went to its new competitors. Fox News
Channel, which was not in existence during the last convention, was
watched by 1.7 million viewers. MSNBC, which was too small to be
rated in the summer of 1996, was watched by 579,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the stronger showing on its last night, the average
television audience over the convention's four nights was down,
compared with the audience in 1996, statisticians say. Nielsen
experts said that it is difficult to compare the size of the
audience for the two conventions because of the varying amounts of
coverage and the new 24-hour cable channels. But, based on a rough
analysis, they believe the audience possibly dropped by as much as
12 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
