<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3120 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BARNEYS-QUESTROM-NYT &LR;      08-04 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNEYS-QUESTROM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNAROUND EXPERT MAY NOT HAVE SPUN GOLD AT BARNEY'S 
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When troubled retailer J.C. Penney announced last
week that Allen L. Questrom would be its new chief executive, Wall
Street was euphoric.
</P>
<P>
   Penney, which has been dogged by disappointing sales at its
department stores, saw its stock rise 16.5 percent on the day. And
Questrom's credentials led four of the 12 analysts that cover the
company to upgrade the stock, according to First Call/Thomson
Financial.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to be a huge improvement at J.C. Penney,'' said
George Strachan, an analyst at Goldman Sachs, who raised his rating
to market outperform from market perform. ``He's got a lot of
charisma and is very decisive.''
</P>
<P>
   Investor enthusiasm stems in large part from the work that
Questrom did reviving ailing public companies like Federated
Department Stores and Macy's, which Federated acquired under his
leadership. But in the most recent chapter of his career, as
chairman and chief executive of Barney's New York Inc., it is less
clear that the veteran turnaround man has spun straw into gold.
</P>
<P>
   While Barney's has seen robust sales growth, its cash flow and
earnings have not been nearly as strong as the company had
predicted they would be in documents filed with the court to emerge
from bankruptcy protection and to entice investors. This combined
with a less forgiving investor environment has dashed any chance of
a quick return to public ownership. In addition, the glitzy
retailer has been hemorrhaging staff at an alarming rate.
</P>
<P>
   Questrom, a flawlessly groomed executive, arrived in May 1999 at
Barney's, famous for dressing men in the finest suits and their
social X-ray wives in the newest European designs. The company had
come out of bankruptcy in January, and Questrom was not responsible
for the earlier plan, filed with the court in November 1998. That
was done by Barney's majority owners, two vulture funds, Bar
Harbour Management and Whipporwill Associates Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Teitlebaum of Bar Harbour and David Strumwasser of
Whipporwill Associates Inc. say that the numbers in the filing were
based on the projections of previous management, under the
leadership of chief executive Tom Shull. When Questrom came aboard,
they formulated a more conservative plan, the owners say, and the
company is exceeding its new targets, though they declined to
disclose those numbers.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his arrival, Questrom was heralded as an
executive who could generate dynamic growth _ growth essential for
Barney's to pay off its looming and substantial debts.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Tarkenton, a bankruptcy lawyer at Womble, Carylyle,
Sandridge &AMP; Rice in Washington, D.C., said he had not studied the
Barney's situation, but added, ``like any company that misses
projections significantly, it is a sign that reorganization might
be failing.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea that his yearlong tenure at Barney's has been anything
less than spectacular makes Questrom's eyes flash. He says what
really matters for a retailer just out of bankruptcy is to earn the
trust of vendors, and there he surpassed expectations. When he took
Barney's helm, 80 percent of vendors were asking to be prepaid, he
says, and today less than 8 percent do _ and those are mostly small
suppliers who have no choice.
</P>
<P>
   Barney's stores have experienced double-digit sales growth since
Questrom arrived. In fact, much of the luxury market, including
Saks Fifth Avenue and Neiman Marcus, has benefited from a strong
economy. Questrom, though, takes credit for helping Barney's
partake in the boom by training the notoriously snooty sales force
to be more friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these solid accomplishments, there have been troubling
signs at the retailer, most notably staff turnover at Barney's
flagship Madison Avenue store since Questrom arrived. In just the
last three months, the company has lost six executives at the level
of divisional vice president and above, a creative director, a vice
president of communications and the Madison Avenue store manager,
or roughly nine out of 16 senior staff members.
</P>
<P>
   The turnover would not be a concern at a large chain of stores.
At a small, high-end operation like Barney's, though, experienced
service people and discerning fashion buyers are vital.
</P>
<P>
   A common theme among departing employees was that they did not
like the change to Questrom's more corporate manner from the
family-style management dating back to the Pressman clan that owned
Barney's before bankruptcy. The executive was repeatedly described
as ``cold.'' He earned ill will by demanding that his staff pass
basic retail math tests _ an exercise one former staffer described
as ``degrading.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Questrom's effort could justly be defended as needed
professionalism for a famously high-flying, high-spending
operation, staffers felt his bottom-line emphasis was not in line
with Barney's overall luxury shopping experience.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he shifted Barney's away from its traditional
emphasis on the most cutting-edge designers. ``He was focused on
business volume makers, not on nurturing the young and upcoming
designers,'' said Emilia Fabricant, formerly the senior vice
president responsible for the women's co-op and outlet division,
who said she left because she was looking for a new creative
environment. ``I thought he was maybe losing the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Another possible reason for staff departures is that Barney's is
in no position to make a public offering of stock anytime soon.
Since Barney's emerged from bankruptcy with an estimated value of
$240 million, the market valuations of public retailers have
collapsed. Most now trade at less than their annual sales. Neiman
Marcus Group, a luxury retailer on solid footing, had 1999 sales of
$2.6 billion and sports a market cap of roughly 60 percent of that
amount. Given sales last year of $385 million and its distressed
history, Barney's public value might be less than $200 million in
the current environment.
</P>
<P>
   Even Questrom's decision to move on may relate to the fact that
there was probably little short-term upside in his staying. When he
joined, his employment agreement called for him to be paid entirely
in stock. The company now says that Questrom will get an
undisclosed sum of stock as well as a salary for the year he was
the top executive. He will remain chairman after joining Penney.
</P>
<P>
   Barney's majority owners say they don't pay attention to
short-term valuations and that theirs is a long-term investment.
</P>
<P>
   Back in its 1998 filing with the court, the company projected a
net loss of $614,000 for the fiscal year ended January 2000 and net
income of $5 million for the year ending in January 2001. Instead,
the company posted a $5.3 million loss last year and expects just
to break even this year.
</P>
<P>
   The shortfall is significant because Barney's has two important
pools of debt coming due in 2003. A person very familiar with the
company's balance sheet says that the shortfall already endangers
the company's ability to meet these obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Teitlebaum and Strumwasser vigorously deny that they will have
any trouble meeting their debts.
</P>
<P>
   Shull, who saw Barney's through bankruptcy and helped build its
cash flow from negative $2 million to positive $20 million, and who
knows the company well, says that if the retailer does not start
meeting plan it will not be able to pay its debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for them to make their financial commitments in two
years the company would have to achieve an EBITDA of over $70
million,'' he said, using the term that refers to earnings before
interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization. ``At this stage,
barring significant additional investment, that would seem to be
virtually impossible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
