<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3121 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-GAY-PRIESTS0805-COX     08-04 1558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-PRIESTS0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gay couple followed a policy of selective disclosure
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ They're not going to Vermont in
September for a quick ceremony in front of a justice of the peace
to make it ``official.'' They're not throwing a huge party _ or
even a small one _ to mark the day. There will be no invitations.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nolan and Bob Pingpank are not flashy men. They're
pragmatic, salt-of-the-earth New Englanders; Connecticut Yankees
through and through. So next month when they celebrate the 45th
anniversary of the day they met during their freshman orientation
at Trinity College in Connecticut, they will do it with the reserve
that has marked their lives. They will celebrate at home, with
their two Cavalier King Charles Spaniels and maybe a bottle of
wine.
</P>
<P>
   If their names were Rich and Barbara or Bob and Renee this story
might end here, with a hearty Happy Anniversary and a piece of
cake. But these are two men, a retired Episcopal priest and a
retired high school math teacher. And to some, their carefully
ordered world, filled with concerts at the Kravis and movies on
HBO, represents the breakdown of American society and a
disintegration of the church as the country's moral compass.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the civil rights era in the 1950s and '60s have
America's religious communities struggled so mightily with a single
issue as they have with gay rights. In the past five months, five
of the country's largest denominations have taken crucial votes on
policies toward homosexuality and gay marriages. The United
Methodist Church and the Presbyterian Church voted to maintain bans
on same-sex ceremonies. The Episcopal Church and the Reform branch
of Judaism voted to open the door wider to gay unions. And the
Southern Baptist Convention in June condemned homosexuality as
immoral.
</P>
<P>
   The feared consequence of normalizing the status of
homosexuality? A slippery slope ``to Sodom and Gomorrah where fire
fell out of heaven and (the cities) burnt to ashes,'' says the Rev.
Gene Walton of Grace Christian Fellowship Church in West Palm
Beach. ``The acceptance of the homosexual lifestyle will trigger
God's judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   NOT MUCH CONTROVERSY HERE
</P>
<P>
   Which leads us back to Nolan and Pingpank _ aka, the triggers.
Somehow all this high-octane controversy swirling around them seems
a touch displaced because by any standard other than their
sexuality there's nothing controversial about them. They are two
button-down 63-year-olds with button-down concerns and button-down
lives. They read a lot, take their dogs on walks, confer on what to
eat for dinner and occasionally say to hell with their cholesterol
count and splurge on Kentucky Fried Chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Like any other longtime pair they have divided the chores:
Pingpank takes care of household maintenance and dog walking. Nolan
takes care of cooking and shopping. Need directions to their
suburban West Palm Beach home? ``Hold the phone a second,'' Nolan
says. ``That's Bob's department.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty boring,'' Pingpank says.
</P>
<P>
   And that, Nolan says, is the point: We blend in. We are your
neighbors, your friends, your teachers, even your priests.
</P>
<P>
   In half a century, a gay ``married'' minister may not raise
eyebrows in some denominations, but that's not today. This article,
for instance, was held for a week so Nolan could finish a series of
sermons at a church in Wellington where he has been a guest
speaker. He thinks some congregants are going to be pretty ticked
off when his relationship with Pingpank is known and the
congregation realizes they were being preached to about morality by
a homosexual. The rest of his career as a substitute minister will
be over as well, he suspects. If that's the case, so be it, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida is 25 to 50 years behind Connecticut,'' he says.
``This is a don't-rock-the-boat diocese. . . One rector said they
pretty much wish the issue would just go away and I think that's
representative.''
</P>
<P>
   ONCE DEEMED A MENTAL ILLNESS
</P>
<P>
   A little adversity is nothing new. A quarter century ago Nolan
and Pingpank consistently ``fine tuned'' their lives so they could
live as they pleased without making waves. They came of age at a
time when homosexuality was considered a mental illness by the
medical establishment, a sin by the church and a perversion by
society.
</P>
<P>
   Their house in Connecticut, for instance, was divided into two
apartments with two kitchens, two bedrooms and two mailing
addresses in case the neighbors thought it odd that two grown men
were living together. It was all a ruse. They shared the same
bedroom, the rest was kept strictly for appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never hugged in front of the picture window, but OK, we can
live with that,'' Nolan says.
</P>
<P>
   On Sundays, Pingpank would drive to church in a separate car in
case anybody wondered why he and the pastor were always together.
When the principal's job came open while Pingpank was head of the
math department at the public high school where he taught, he
didn't apply in case his sexuality _ known to just a handful of
people in the community _ was used against him.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they hold no grudges against the society that pressured
them to keep the closet door mostly shut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come a long, long way in a very short time,'' Nolan
says. ``These things take time.''
</P>
<P>
   NOLAN A CRADLE EPISCOPALIAN
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps patience is part of the bargain when you're gay and you
want to serve God. Nolan knew from the third grade he wanted to be
a minister. About the same time he realized he was ``different.''
Being a cradle Episcopalian, there was no question what kind of
minister he would be.
</P>
<P>
   And he was ahead of his time as far as liberal theology goes.
While the Episcopal Church had a ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy
in effect, Nolan never believed that his sexual orientation was
sinful _ as conservative Christians believed _ because he never
thought of the church as infallible. ``If homosexuality is a sin
then someone's saying God made a mistake,'' Nolan said. ``And I
don't think he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Nolan's first vocational interview when he was a
sophomore in college. After driving to Boston with Pingpank and
being interviewed in the morning, the now inseparable pair saw the
priest who conducted the interview at a gay bar later that same
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he saw me I think he could sense I was nervous because he
said, `Don't worry, Richard, I'm going to recommend you very
highly,' '' Nolan laughs. ``He was probably nervous too.''
</P>
<P>
   That was four decades ago. It was just last month that the
Episcopal Church endorsed a new policy acknowledging that there are
Episcopal couples ``acting in good conscience,'' in lifelong
committed relationships outside of marriage that should receive
``prayerful support, encouragement and pastoral care.'' They don't
specify whether those ``couples'' are homosexual or heterosexual,
leaving some to believe the language is a purposefully vague
endorsement of long-standing homosexual relationships.
</P>
<P>
   FINALLY, THE CHURCH'S BLESSING
</P>
<P>
   At this point does the church's blessing even matter? ``Not
really,'' Nolan says. ``It effects us only in the sense that it's
affirming. It's admitting that we've been right all along. Now,
that can sound awfully smug and arrogant, but I can't help it if
sounds that way. The church has caught up to what we had already
known and experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career as a professor of philosophy and a priest
Nolan has been ``out'' to varying degrees within the church and
community. ``It's been a selective sharing, where we thought it was
appropriate,'' Nolan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to live as gay people but just as people,''
Pingpank said.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent that meant overt omissions. Though at different
times they took care of all four of their parents in their old age
(''Every parent should be so lucky to have a gay son,'' Nolan
says), none of their parents ever discussed their son's sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``People know at the level they are capable of knowing,'' Nolan
says. ``Besides, by then my father had Alzheimer's and my mother,
well, my mother was from Boston.'' All four of their parents are
now dead, enabling them to speak publicly about their lives
together.
</P>
<P>
   CRITICISM FROM GAY GROUPS
</P>
<P>
   That sort of compromised openness about their sexuality has
occasionally prompted the younger generation of gays to consider
them Uncle Toms. They can live with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been several times when we have been considered not
gay enough for different groups and we weren't asked to speak,''
Nolan said. ``Times change.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, all of that _ the denominational votes, the social
attitudes, the severed speaking engagements _ mean little to either
of them. In the end, theirs is a love story. ``I know my
relationship with Bob has fueled my capacity to be a pastor,''
Nolan says. ``People ask, if I could have pushed a button and
become straight, would I? And what flashes into my life is not
straight or gay, but Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask us, wouldn't we like to get married in a church and
have God bless our relationship,'' Pingpank says. ``The answer is,
he already did, 45 years ago, the day we met.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
