<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3122 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-RICH-COLUMN-2TAKES-NY     08-04 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE GOP'S AGE OF AQUARIUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: please replace double parentheses (( )) with single
brackets)  
 By FRANK RICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Who says the GOP is against welfare? The show it
put on here was nothing if not a bountiful assistance program,
providing food, drink and shelter for 15,000 journalists who found
themselves seriously underemployed at a political convention
without fisticuffs. In keeping with Republican orthodoxy, the bill
for this welfare program was picked up by the private sector _ the
journalists' employers _ and not the taxpayer. What is
compassionate conservatism if not life on an expense account?
</P>
<P>
   Alas, not all the recipients of this largess were grateful. Some
journalists drifted into a kind of catatonia in which they said
over and over to anyone who would listen how boring the GOP
infomercial was and how they longed for that happy time when Pat
Buchanan would give a Nazi speech and all three major networks
would leap to broadcast it. But not many were listening to this
nostalgic reverie _ or anything else emanating from the city of
brotherly inclusion. On Tuesday night, lowest-rated MSNBC had only
390,000 viewers _ a national audience slightly exceeding the
population of Wichita.
</P>
<P>
   As such grim reports from the outside world infiltrated the
media bubble, there was much public and private soul-searching. Are
the political parties killing democracy by staging canned pageants
that TV networks don't want to broadcast and Americans don't want
to watch? Or is the press itself the culprit? Should the
underemployed masses of journalists at a convention be forced to
work no matter what _ call it welfare reform _ and provide
prime-time wall-to-wall coverage like the good old days, even if
nothing is happening and no one is tuning in?
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Heyward, president of CBS News, found himself almost
pilloried for cutting back his convention programming to a bare
minimum, anticipating the day when the networks cover the
presidential candidates' acceptance speeches and little else.
</P>
<P>
   I'm with Heyward. The political parties have the right to stage
any kind of convention they choose to sell their candidate, and the
networks have every right not to broadcast it in its entirety. As
this Republican convention illustrated more clearly than any other
to date, political parties are in step with the rest of the
branding-crazed American corporate culture. They roll out their
homogenized products just as The Gap introduces its new line of
khakis or Hollywood its summer blockbusters.
</P>
<P>
   Elections _ the primaries and the general _ are still
spontaneous and do demand full journalistic employment. But as long
as conventions are tightly scripted exercises in friction-free
salesmanship, they no more merit a full media army than an auto
show. They are chapters in the history of American merchandising,
not democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there were some real stories here that, for all the
excessive size of the press contingent, did not always get the
attention lavished on George P.'s looks, Gerald Ford's health, the
rise of Internet journalism and the latest image makeover of
Arianna Huffington.
</P>
<P>
   The true shadow convention in Philadelphia (as it will be at the
Democratic convention) was the one almost impossible for the media
to penetrate _ the one put on by big money. ``Democracy is now
lobbyists and fund-raisers,'' as a Republican operative put it to
me. Instead of providing wall-to-wall coverage of the official
doings in the First Union Center, some enterprising cable network
or Web site might have more aptly set up a hidden 24/7 camera in
the lobby of the new Ritz-Carlton Hotel, situated in what used to
be the Girard-Mellon Bank buildings, if only to keep track of the
fat cats hoping to buy influence.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts of ABC News' Brian Ross to infiltrate corporate
festivities here _ which usually led to his and his cameraman's
being body-blocked _ were more revealing than anything that
happened on the convention floor. A front-page New York Times story
by Don Van Natta and John Broder reporting that a mere 739
contributors are responsible for two-thirds of the $137 million in
soft-money contributions to the GOP gave new, if unsavory, meaning
to the heretofore empty slogan ``prosperity with a purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Another shadow convention _ or perhaps more correctly, closet
convention _ began when Dick Cheney's perennially angry wife,
Lynne, predictably became the only big-name Republican in the
entire convention to go off-script. That moment occurred last
Sunday morning when, in an interview on ABC, Cokie Roberts said to
her, ``You have a daughter who has now declared that she is openly
gay.'' Lynne Cheney snapped back, ``Mary has never declared such a
thing,'' and then chastised Roberts for bringing the subject up.
``I simply am not going to talk about ((my daughters')) personal
lives,'' Cheney barked, cowing Roberts into retreat.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In tone and language, Cheney thus conveyed that (a) her daughter
is not openly gay; (b) to be gay is a frightful ``thing''; and (c)
Roberts was revealing a Cheney family secret.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Mary Cheney, who is 31, has by many media accounts been
openly gay for close to a decade, lives with a partner, and until
this spring worked as the corporate-relations representative from
Coors Brewing Co. to the gay and lesbian market, often appearing as
Coors' spokeswoman on its gay philanthropy and promotional events.
</P>
<P>
   So it was preposterous to insinuate, as Lynne Cheney did, that
Roberts had outed Mary Cheney. It was equally preposterous for
Lynne Cheney to claim that she would not be talking about her
family in the campaign. She dragged her daughters into her speech
introducing her husband to the convention just three days later,
and throughout the week here wielded her heterosexual daughter's
young child as a political prop.
</P>
<P>
   So what made Lynne Cheney lose it? The fact is that for all the
minorities paraded across the convention stage, homosexuals are
still at best seen and not heard in the GOP. At a reception for gay
Republicans here, the honoree was Mary Matalin, an honorary
lesbian, in the words of her jokey introducer, rather than, God
forbid, an actual lesbian. The obligatory AIDS speaker at the
convention itself was not gay, while the one openly gay speaker to
appear, Rep. Jim Kolbe of Arizona, was permitted to talk about
anything except being gay.
</P>
<P>
   Though George W. Bush was able to soften or remove the
traditional hard-line GOP platform boilerplate on almost every
issue _ he even got rid of the plank calling for the abolition of
the National Endowment for the Arts _ he let stand the party's
draconian positions on both gay civil rights and abortion rights.
Had he really wanted those stances altered, they certainly would
have been.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to the most important story here _ the political
prowess of Bush. For all the ridicule lavished on this
touchy-feely, pseudo-multicultural, neo-Clintonesque convention _
exactly the lockstep exercise in political correctness that the
political right professes to abhor _ the medium really was the
message. That message is not the official one, that the GOP has
overnight transformed itself into a haven for minorities. It
hasn't. The real message is simply that Bush had the iron-fist
skills, the team and the imagination to persuade his party to
convey that benign image, however synthetic some of it was.
Everyone from pro-choice Republican women in pearls to Pat
Robertson devotees to the most rabid Clinton-haters bit their
tongues rather than frighten any of those few independents or
Democrats watching. There were no mentions of impeachment; no ``it
takes a village'' cracks about Hillary Clinton. Republican heavies
from Richard Nixon to Newt Gingrich to Henry Hyde were erased from
history with Stalinist efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   It was all so lulling _ except for Bush's ingeniously crafted
acceptance speech _ that it looked easy. But it couldn't have been.
The big news here, and it's far from boring, is that the GOP
nominee proved, as neither his father nor Bob Dole could, that he
is capable of taming, uniting and, if you will, leading what has
been for a decade a notoriously unruly and obstreperous party.
Democrats are kidding themselves if they deny that Bush is far
closer than he was a week ago to making the sale that he can govern
the country as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
