<HEADER>
A3124 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      08-04 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   C.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Growth in Employment Less than Forecast
</P>
<P>
   U.S. companies added fewer jobs in July than economists had
expected, further reducing the chances that the Federal Reserve
will raise interest rates when it meets later this month. In the
latest sign that economic growth is slowing, the unemployment rate
remained unchanged at 4 percent in July as private-sector payrolls
grew by 138,000, about half the number that most analysts had
predicted. Overall unemployment fell by 108,000 last month because
of the large number of temporary government workers who finished
collecting census data in June, the Department of Labor reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Major Market Indexes Rise on Slower Job Growth Data
</P>
<P>
   After an early morning decline, the Dow Jones industrial average
rose 61.17 points, or 0.6 percent, to 10,767.75. The Dow is down
6.3 percent so far this year. Other markets also rose with the
Nasdaq composite index rising 27.48 points, or 0.7 percent, to
3,787.36 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index climbing 10.37
points, or 0.7 percent, to 1,462.93. Stocks ended higher after the
Department of Labor reported that private job growth had been
slower than expected last month. The data appears to make an
interest rate increase by the Federal Reserve later this month less
likely.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon Tries to Stave Off Strike
</P>
<P>
   Verizon Communications moved to avoid a strike by more than
86,000 telephone workers by submitting a proposal on Friday
addressing concerns over issues including wages, benefits and job
security. Still, the company avoided unions' central concern of
unionizing the wireless work force, increasing the possibility of a
walkout. Unless the company and unions agree on several issues by
12:01 a.m. Sunday or agree to extend discussions, 72,000 members of
the Communications Workers of America and 14,700 members of the
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers will walk out on
Verizon.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna Reports 17 Percent Drop in Profits
</P>
<P>
   Aetna, the nation's largest health insurer, reported a 17
percent decrease in second-quarter profits as more people sought
increasingly costlier treatment. But it said it was moving along on
sweeping changes aimed at improving business.
</P>
<P>
   8 Wall St. Firms Settle Charges
</P>
<P>
   Banc One Capital Markets and seven other securities dealers have
agreed to pay a total of $13.5 million to settle the latest federal
case accusing firms of overcharging municipalities for Treasury
securities in a practice known as yield burning.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever to Split Into 2 Divisions
</P>
<P>
   Unilever, the global consumer goods giant that has been on a
buying spree in the United States, announced a major reorganization
of top management. The move would reorganize the company into two
divisions, one focused on food brands like Lipton Tea and Ragu
spaghetti sauce and the other on consumer products like Dove soap
and Elizabeth Arden cosmetics. The news revived speculation that
the company planned a full split in two.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE Sues Online Impersonators
</P>
<P>
   The New York Stock Exchange filed a lawsuit against 10
unidentified people on charges of impersonating its chairman and
chief executive, Richard A. Grasso, on a popular Internet message
board. In the suit, lodged in Federal District Court in Manhattan,
the exchange contends that the John Does, using aliases like
RichAGrasso, impersonated Grasso on the Ragingbull.com Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Role Seems to Remain for Concorde
</P>
<P>
   The July 25 crash of the Air France supersonic Concorde brought
down a plane that by common measurements can hardly be profitable,
given its high maintenance costs, daunting fuel bills, little
passenger space and no cargo. Yet any decision to ground the
Concorde permanently could have deep financial implications for Air
France and British Airways, the two airlines that run it. Its loss
would divert high-end corporate travelers to other airlines,
notably in the United States, or to corporate jet travel.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa in Deal to Expand in Europe
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa said it had bought Baco Consumer Products of London for an
undisclosed price to increase its sale of household plastic wrap
and aluminum foil in Europe. The company is Britain's biggest
seller of aluminum foil and plastic bags.
</P>
<P>
   Rio Tinto Wins Battle for North
</P>
<P>
   Anglo American ended its bid to acquire North, the Australian
mining company that is one of the world's biggest producers of iron
ore. A rival, Rio Tinto, countered Anglo American's $1.8 billion
bid with one that was 11 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
   GE to Get Air Force Contract
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin said it had selected General Electric to provide
engines for an updated version of its Galaxy transport aircraft for
the Air Force, a contract that could be valued at up to $2.6
billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
