<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIA: A STAR'S PLEA
</P>
<P>
   In a tape cassette sent through an emissary, the kidnapped movie
star Rajkumar asked the police not to try an armed rescue to free
him from the forested redoubt of the bandit Veerappan. He also
asked his fans not to resort to street violence to protest his
abduction.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: KASHMIR GROUP ACCUSED
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to parliament, Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee said
that arms and ammunition recovered from the scene of several
massacres this week in Kashmir establish that the militant group
Lashkar-i-Toiba was responsible. The group has denied any role in
the attacks, which took 98 lives.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA: MEDIA TOUR
</P>
<P>
   In the latest sign that North Korea is shedding its reclusive
ways, the heads of major South Korean newspapers and broadcast
stations will visit Pyongyang on Saturday at the invitation of
North Korea's leader, Kim Jong Il. During their weeklong visit, the
South Korean delegation plans to meet with North Korean media
representatives to discuss exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: FARMERS SUE
</P>
<P>
   The Commercial Farmers Union went to court to block the
government's planned acquisition of 2 million acres of white-owned
farmland. The union, which represents the nation's 4,000 white
farmers, had agreed that underutilized land should be distributed
to black peasants but now says the process is moving too hastily.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
