<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3127 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-EDWARDS-PROFILE0805-C     08-04 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDWARDS-PROFILE0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. senator on Gore's list
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ Republican politician John Blust would love
to see North Carolina's first-term senator, John Edwards, tapped
Tuesday as Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore's running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say he'd be like Dan Quayle,'' Blust said
referring to the President George Bush's little-known running mate
in 1988. ``But I don't think Edwards has the experience in
government and politics to become president if Gore were to die in
office.''
</P>
<P>
   But in eastern North Carolina, state Sen. R.C. Soles, a Democrat
from Tabor City, said Edwards as the party's vice presidential
candidate ``may be a stroke of genius.''
</P>
<P>
   He described the 47-year-old millionaire trial lawyer from
Raleigh as ``bright and competent and hard working'' and
``certainly more charismatic than Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only criticism they might say about him is he has not had
a lot of experience on Capitol Hill,'' Soles said. ``From a
political standpoint, I'm not sure that is too negative.''
</P>
<P>
   As Gore, campaigning Friday in Chicago, kept people guessing
about his running mate, and Edwards, visiting Raleigh, dodged the
topic, North Carolinians debated the prospect of two Southern
Democrats winning the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards has emerged out of the blue as the only Southerner on
Gore's short list. In his 17 months in the Senate, Edwards has
impressed some important Capitol Hill Democrats, including Senate
Democratic Leader Tom Daschle, who have touted him to Gore's
campaign advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Gore's closest advisers _ political consultant Robert
Shrum and pollster Harrison Hickman _ were involved in Edwards'
upset win against incumbent Republican Sen. Lauch Faircloth two
years ago. Also reportedly touting Edwards is Charlotte banker
Erskine Bowles, who served as President Clinton's White House chief
of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was among the people who called Edwards in 1998 on the
night of his victory over Faircloth.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the speculation that Edwards might be Gore's choice is
the fact that Gore spent last week at the home of Greenville, N.C.,
businessman Park Overton on Figure Eight Island, where Edwards also
has a home. However, one of the guests at Edwards' house was Sen.
Evan Bayh of Indiana, another name mentioned prominently as a
possible Gore choice.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Edwards returned to Washington from Raleigh, where he
hosted an Internet privacy forum. A day earlier, in a visit to
Greenville and Rocky Mount, where he viewed areas still recovering
from Hurricane Floyd, Edwards characterized the sudden interest in
him as ``a real compliment to the people of North Carolina. I think
it shows how important North Carolina is to the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Although North Carolina has a relatively small number of
electoral votes _ 14 _ Edwards could help the Democrat ticket win
the state for the first time since Jimmy Carter and Walter Mondale
took it in 1976. Edwards also might influence votes in other
Southern states that, according to polls, have been leaning toward
Republican George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney of Wyoming, who served as President George Bush's
secretary of defense, is the Texas governor's running mate. Gore,
from Tennessee, on Friday numbered his contenders as ``six, plus an
out-of-the-box possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles a week
away, Gore has said he will announce his choice for running mate on
Tuesday in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   The leading prospects are all from the Senate: John Kerry of
Massachusetts, Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, Bayh and Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Edwards) would give a further youthful,
forward-looking image to the ticket, and I think that might work
against the Bush-Cheney ticket,'' said East Carolina University
political science professor Tinsley Yarbrough.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards was a political novice in 1998 when he defeated
incumbent Faircloth, an Eastern North Carolina farmer and ally of
North Carolina's senior senator, Republican Jesse Helms.
</P>
<P>
   He entered the bruising race relatively late and survived
Faircloth ads attacking him as a Clinton clone.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards refused to take money from PACs or Washington lobbyists.
Rather, spending $3.2 million of his own money, he ran ads about
his views and background. He drew criticism for suggesting that he
was born in North Carolina, when he was actually born in South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a textile mill supervisor, he was the first in his
family to go to college, attending North Carolina State University
and then the University of North Carolina Law School.
</P>
<P>
   He became a successful plaintiffs' personal injury lawyer,
gaining attention with cases that included North Carolina's largest
personal-injury verdict. He won $25 million in compensatory damages
in 1997 when he represented a 9-year-old girl from Cary who was
badly injured by the suction of a faulty swimming pool drain. He
showed that another 13 children had suffered similar injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In all, he won verdicts totaling $152 million, allowing him to
build a fortune estimated as high as $50 million, according to the
Almanac of American Politics 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Faircloth seemed to be cruising to re-election until
Edwards stepped forward, some Democrats expressed reservations
about Edwards, saying at that time that he had not paid his
political dues. Even now, some long-time Democrats aren't quite
sure what to make of Edwards, or his vice presidential prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't know enough about Edwards to say what the truth
is,'' said R.V. Owens, campaign finance chairman for state Attorney
General Mike Easley, the Democratic candidate for governor of North
Carolina. In 1998, Owens supported Faircloth.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards made two admissions in the 1998 campaign that Blust, a
former state senator from Greensboro who is seeking a state House
seat, said could haunt him if he becomes the vice presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards conceded that he had not voted in every election and
that he didn't remember whether he had first registered as a
Republican or a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am sitting back as a Republican strategist, here is a guy
who has not been in the political process for even two years,''
Blust said. ``He didn't even vote in some elections.''
</P>
<P>
   But political analyst Yarbrough said Edwards' imperfect voting
record might actually appeal to independent voters and ``people
whose party leanings are marginal.''
</P>
<P>
   Soles, the state senator who likes Edwards chances, said, ``I
have serious doubts that everybody has voted in every election.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
