<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3128 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-RELIGION-SAMESEX0805     08-04 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-SAMESEX0805 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Episcopalians honor non-married couples
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The proverbial Wisdom of Solomon is
often needed for the Church to honor its traditions and do the
right thing.
</P>
<P>
   Splitting hairs, but not their church, Episcopalians have done
just that.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates meeting at the national convention of their church in
July decided to honor matrimony and also recognize couples who are
not married, including same-sex relationships.
</P>
<P>
   After years of bitter struggle, it seems so simple.
Episcopalians acknowledged that the hand of God might figure in
evolving human relationships. The church could both honor ancient
beliefs and remain open to the next thing God might be up to.
</P>
<P>
   That's the tricky part of the Christian faith. Many churches try
to be obedient to a God they know from his past activities and
teaching. But their obedience often prevents them from seeing what
God is doing now.
</P>
<P>
   That keeps them from serving a God who could be about radically
new things.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that many churches behave like dusty museums
preserving a glorious past when they are called to be partners with
God in making all things new.
</P>
<P>
   Still, honoring the past and building the future with such a God
means walking a tightrope between obedience and risk.
</P>
<P>
   Episcopalians took the risk. Delegates voted to affirm the
church's traditional teaching on the sanctity of marriage and
respectfully recognize lifelong, committed, non-married
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   The convention denounced promiscuity, exploitation and
abusiveness in all relationships, thereby honoring the teaching of
God.
</P>
<P>
   But delegates recognized that some couples disagree with the
church's traditional teaching on sexual behavior and act in
contradiction to it. That courageous admission accepts the risk
that God may be helping us understand another form of intimacy for
some of his children.
</P>
<P>
   The convention decided, for the time being, not to prepare
liturgical services to bless unmarried couples. A majority of
delegates feared that some parishes might leave the Episcopal fold
in protest and that schism was possible were the church to bless
such unions.
</P>
<P>
   Others argued that blessing same-sex unions would enhance the
church's deplorable practice of blessing virtually anything. The
church blesses yachts, tanks, animals, houses and countless other
things.
</P>
<P>
   The Episcopal bishop of Maryland, Robert Ihlof, reminded
delegates that the church blesses the hunt in his state, including
a divine nod to the hounds whose duty is to harass and terrify the
fox.
</P>
<P>
   One day the church will bless same-sex unions. But already, the
Episcopal Church recognizes that God may be involved in new forms
of human relationships.
</P>
<P>
   That suggests the church rightly believes that God has more to
teach us than has heretofore been found in the pages of Scripture.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
