<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 08/04/00. Database in
Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 213-237-4577
or PressLink at 800-888-6195. Non-clients can make individual
purchases by calling (888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- Aug. 4, 2000 -- ORPHANED-BRANDS-2 -- Is
now a good time to try to make a business out of someone else's
jilted labels? The business of reviving  so-called ghost or orphaned
brands has    its risks. But for two former Procter &AMP; Gamble
employees who have acquired the company's Oxydol laundry detergent,
the challenge is how much life they can squeeze out of the
73-year-old brand. A scene from an old Oxydol television commercial.
(The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) DENVER -- Aug. 4, 2000 -- REFORM-HAGELIN -- John
Hagelin, 46, who received his master's and doctorate degrees from
Harvard University and spent nearly 20 years as a research scientist,
is immersed in a nasty primary fight with Patrick J. Buchanan, the
loquacious former television commentator, to win the Reform Party's
nomination to run as a presidential candidate. (Kevin Moloney/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MILWAUKEE, Wisc. -- Aug. 4, 2000 -- GOP-REACT-2 ---
Undecided voters huddled in small groups around television sets
across the country to watch Gov. George W. Bush deliver his speech to
the Republican National Convention accepting his party's nomination
for president. Costas Panagopoulos, left with Sona Nadenicheik, both
studying political science at New York University, talk about Bush's
speech as it was televised Thursday night. (James Estrin/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MILWAUKEE, Wisc. -- Aug. 4, 2000 -- GOP-REACT-1 ---
Undecided voters huddled in small groups around television sets
across the country to watch Gov. George W. Bush deliver his speech to
the Republican National Convention accepting his party's nomination
for president. Chiquita Lee and her husband Arthur Lee, Sr. watch
Bush's acceptance speech Thursday night. (Steve Kagan/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SOUHWEST HARBOR, Maine  -- Aug. 4, 2000 --
LOBSTER-BOATS-BOS -- Ralph Stanley with a lobster boat, built in
1963, that he refurbished for  a Southwest Harbor, Maine, resident.
Stanley is the dean of Maine's wooden  boat builders. (Wendy
Maeda/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 4, 2000 -- BUSH-CAMPAIGN-2 --
Gov. George W. Bush, center, the Republican presidential candidate,
addresses a crowd at the Northeast Philadelphia Airport just prior to
departing on a campaign swing through western Pennsylvania, Ohio and
Michigan, Friday. Looking on from left are Lynne and Dick Cheney and
Bush's wife Laura. After a hearty send-off in Philadelphia, Bush and
Cheney, his runningmate embarked Friday on a three-day air and rail
tour of battleground states.  (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Aug. 4, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 6 --
TALISMAN-CHIC-2 -- There is a vastly expanding tribe of New Yorkers
who, trusting nothing to chance, attempt to ward off evil or beguile
the gods by draping themselves in exotic beads and talismans. A
collection of such objects. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Aug. 4, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 6 --
TALISMAN-CHIC -- There is a vastly expanding tribe of New Yorkers
who, trusting nothing to chance, attempt to ward off evil or beguile
the gods by draping themselves in exotic beads and talismans. Kamuti
Kitemi shows off his Buddha amulet and bracelets. (David Corio/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Aug. 4, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 6 --
MARGARET-CHO -- Comedian Margaret Cho reacts to the television show
"Survivor" in her hotel room earlier this week.  Cho speaks honestly
about other things in her new one-woman film, ``I'm the One that I
Want,'' based on her stage show, about her trials with weight loss,
and overindulgence in alcohol and other mind altering substances.
(David Corio/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Aug. 4, 2000 -- BKW-COACHING-WOMEN --
Richie Adubato, coach of the New York Liberty, who, with four games
until playoffs, are the top team in the Eastern Conference of the
Women's National Basketball Association. After 19 years as an
up-and-down coach in the National Basketball Association, Adubato
says he has been rejuvenated by his gutsy team of women. (Chester
Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PHILADELPHIA -- Aug. 4, 2000 -- BUSH-CAMPAIGN -- Gov.
George W. Bush, right, the Republican presidential candidate, signs
autographs as his runningmate, Dick Cheney, looks on at left, Friday.
After a hearty send-off in Philadelphia, Bush and Cheney embarked
Friday on a three-day air and rail tour of battleground states.
(Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Aug. 4, 2000 -- OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN --
Little did Dawn Ellerbe know, when they handed her a strange metal
contraption featuring a ball and a chain, that they were giving her a
chance to be an Olympian. Ellerbe, of the U.S., in in line to be a
medal contender as the woman's hammer throw makes its Olympic debut.
(/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SEATTLE -- Aug. 4, 2000 -- ANANCHY-REVIVED --
Anarchism, broadly construed, is becoming fashionable. "With the
decline of socialism, you have seen anarchism go through a revival as
an easy way to oppose global capitalism," said Paul Avrich, a leading
historian of anarchism who teaches at Queens College in New York.
Members of a group of self-proclaimed anarchists raise a modified
jolly roger atop a warehouse they occupied in December, 1999, during
the World Trade Organization.. (Dan Lamont/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SEATTLE -- Dec. 2, 1999 -- TRADE-PROTEST-1, 12-02 --
Members of a group of self-proclaimed anarchists raise a modified
jolly roger atop a warehouse they are occupying, Thursday. The group
took over the privately owned, vacant warehouse, which they now call
'The Squat,' last week. Wary of a violent confrontation, the police
have so far held off from storming the building. (Dan Lamont/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
