<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3140 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS-JAPAN0805     08-04 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-JAPAN0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trip to Japan expanding Falcons' horizons
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Morten Andersen has seen a lot of things in a lot of
places, but Friday afternoon was special.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 11 million people in this city, but for a
few minutes on Friday afternoon, nobody stood out like his Atlanta
Falcons teammate, Adriano Belli, the rookie free-agent Italian
defensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   Nevermind that there were Japanese people in every direction.
For Belli, there was something liberating about travel that made it
feel like, well, like 'Karaoke night' back in his native Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a guy with a megaphone advertising, and (Belli) says,
`Can I borrow your megaphone?' `` said Andersen, the Falcons'
kicker/world traveller, who was born in Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy was reluctant, but he finally gives it up, and Belli
starts singing, `Copa Cobana.' That was beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   For a couple of minutes, a small portion of the population in
one of the world's biggest cities might have other opinions.
</P>
<P>
   This is a culture of staid people, and while karaoke is big
here, folks aren't used to it next to the subway, being performed
by a 6-foot-5, 290-pound Caucasian.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have made a dent on Tokyo, however, small, and the
city has made a dent on them.
</P>
<P>
   Having never played on international soil, team president Taylor
Smith said at an official NFL gathering Friday night that he was
honored to represent the league, the Falcons, and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great,'' he said, addressing the crowd. ``It's just
two good ol' Southern boys (he and Dallas owner Jerry Jones of
Arkansas), getting together playing . . . like the Hatfields and
McCoys.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Tim Dwight, who grew up in Iowa City, as a blur in
massive Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' he said. ``I started liking sushi when I
came to Atlanta, and it sort of brought me up on a bigger city.
Now, you come here and we're such a minority. I'm into this bowing
thing . . . it's cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from Iowa, and being half way around the world . . .
you see if you can apply what you've learned out in the real world.
Just using the bathroom, you've got to figure out what all these
buttons are.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, the toilets.
</P>
<P>
   If you hit the wrong button, or the right button, you'll get
sprayed.
</P>
<P>
   That's OK.
</P>
<P>
   For all the grumbling players might have done before their
21-hour bus ride-flight-and-bus ride from training camp in
Greenville, S.C., just to play a preseason game against the Dallas
Cowboys tonight, things are pretty cool.
</P>
<P>
   That's other than the effects of sake that will hit some this
morning, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Former Georgia linebackers Whit Marshall, a Falcon, and Brandon
Tolbert, the Villa Rica native who was briefly with the Falcons in
1998 and now is on the Dallas roster, were shooting the breeze on
one side of the room.
</P>
<P>
   On the other, the world famous Dallas Cowboys cheerleaders were
strolling down the stairs, with locals videotaping every minute of
it.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons finally got past their jet lag late Friday, being 13
hours ahead of Atlanta and Greenville, and started having a good
time. The game will be at 10 p.m. tonight, 11 a.m. Sunday morning
in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the longest time, I never even left Georgia,'' said coach
Dan Reeves, a native of Americus who has been overseas now for five
NFL preseason games in Tokyo, Berlin and London.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, I went to college (at South Carolina) and my horizons
expanded. Then, in the NFL they expanded more. And now the NFL is
going around the globe. It's really amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Shane Dronett, an Orange, Texas, native, got
over the flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people here are incredibly nice,'' he said. ``The hardest
thing, always, is the flight. But it's amazing how safe the city
is. You go to a lot of countries where they have a lot of turmoil,
and then you look at how thin the newspaper is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like they use crime to sell newspapers in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Running back Jamal Anderson, who's coming back from surgery on
his right knee, isn't expected to play tonight, but he's here,
practicing.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, of course, believes he's international, like the NFL's
Michael Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Last week at Furman University, when Japanese media visited to
cover temporary Falcons player Nachi Abe of Japan, Anderson told
them he was, ''Larger than Godzilla in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving here, he was given a Godzilla doll.
</P>
<P>
   His role in Saturday afternoon's fan festival, in which he
signed more autographs than he might back in the U.S., was unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going overseas is great, especially a game of this magnitude,
the first game overseas for our organization,'' he said. ``You work
this hard, and prepare, and you really want to play. But at the
same time, what's best for me and my knee is the most important.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this is all good for the NFL and the Atlanta Falcons.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumping around Friday afternoon in Akibahara, Tokyo's,
``Electric City,'' players were buying scads of electronic goods in
what looked like a giant, very colorful arcade of multiple stores.
</P>
<P>
   It was all part of an experience that will broaden horizons.
</P>
<P>
   These guys might have BMWs, Mercedes and expensive SUVs back in
the U.S. , but in Tokyo, they were relegated to the subway, with
millions of Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   For some, in a way, it was a trip back to their roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travel purifies you,'' Andersen said. ``It humbles you,
purifies you, and makes you realize how fortunate we are to live in
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're jaded by material goods, the way we sometimes greet each
other and act. When you travel, you're totally exposed. It's an
away game of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It educates me more than any book I could read. My phrase has
always been, 'To travel is to live.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
