<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3142 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CYBERFRAUD0805-COX     08-04 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERFRAUD0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Colleague arrested in cyber trickery
 &HT;    By Brad Schrade
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was a high-tech dirty trick that experts say could
happen to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Needham, 51, of Mableton, Ga., was stunned when he arrived
at work two days after Christmas at ING Investment Management,
where he was a technology operations manager making six figures. He
was told he would be fired for a stinging e-mail that maligned his
supervisor's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `What . . . are you talking about?' '' Needham
recalled. ``I hadn't even had my first cup of coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Police say this is what happened: Needham didn't write the
e-mail that carried his name. Instead, a co-worker created an
e-mail account on the free service Hotmail.com using Needham's
name. On Dec. 26, the co-worker used the account to send the
inflammatory e-mail to his supervisor's boss.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, police issued an arrest warrant for Mark Cohen on a
computer fraud charge.
</P>
<P>
   This type of fraud, combining the relative anonymity of the
Internet with the politics of the corporate world, has become
common with the growth of the Internet, experts say. But while the
medium is new, the tactics are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this had been 25 years ago, it's possible he would have
typed a letter or sent a note on his personal stationery,''
speculated Frank Prince of Forrester Research. The Massachusetts
firm studies the impact of technology on business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology aside, all the good and evil, beauty and ugliness
we see in everyday life gets played out on the Internet,'' Prince
said.
</P>
<P>
   In this particular case, the lengthy e-mail sent to the
supervisor's boss uses professional language to criticize the
supervisor's performance and to suggest that Needham could do his
job better without him. ``I am very concerned that he is on the
verge . . . of destroying everything I have strived to build,'' the
e-mail said.
</P>
<P>
   After Needham got fired, he went to the police, who had created
a high-tech crime unit in November to combat Internet fraud and
other computer-related crimes. Using phone records and information
provided by Hotmail, Detective Joel Horne was led to Cohen, who
worked with a consulting firm at Needham's company.
</P>
<P>
   Police speculate Cohen sent the e-mail because Needham was
critical of Cohen's firm's performance. Needham says he doesn't
know the reason.
</P>
<P>
   Needham, whose wife left him after he was fired, is now working
in a similar job earning six figures for another company. Even
though his name has been cleared, he says, he doesn't want his old
job back. He has retained a lawyer and wants ING to pay him for the
three months he was out of work. Attempts to reach the company
Friday for comment were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Prince said there is little one can do to protect against such a
cyber attack. But as employers become more familiar with the
Internet, they may not make such quick judgments, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Needham hopes employers take heed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a pretty tech-savvy engineer. If it can happen to me, the
poor guy out there who has no knowledge is really in trouble,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
