<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3144 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH0805-COX     08-04 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush takes message to key swing states
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ A triumphant Gov. George W. Bush headed for
Pittsburgh Friday where he kicked off a whistle stop train tour
through four key swing states fresh off his speech before the
Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Standing with running mate Dick Cheney at the back of the
Victory 2,000 Express, Bush asked a crowd of cheering supporters
for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our party has a message. It says give us a chance,'' Bush
said, echoing the refrain of his Thursday speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be long now. Give us a chance. Give us a chance to
change America for the better. It won't be long now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney promised the crowd: ``We will prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, at a meeting in Philadelphia of the Republican National
Committee, Cheney cautioned against taking the race for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a tough campaign . . .,'' he said. ``We're going to
take our campaign right to the heart of the key swing states,
battleground states.''
</P>
<P>
   The information technology company Electronic Data Systems
Corp., announced Friday that Cheney has left its board to pursue
the vice presidency. There are no immediate plans for his
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Secure with GOP base voters, Bush and Cheney are traveling with
their wives, Laura and Lynne, to towns in Pennsylvania, Ohio,
Michigan and Illinois _ states packed with the Democrats and
independents they will need to win the White House in November.
</P>
<P>
   Riding a 16-car train with American flags waving at the front,
they launched the trip in Pittsburgh and traveled through a handful
of Pennsylvania towns before arriving in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough campaign, it is,'' Bush told about
100 people at one stop. ``That's why we're here in Wampum,
Pennsylvania. We're taking no votes for granted. I want you to
remind your friends and neighbors when voting time comes who came
and asked. We're here asking.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Bush told reporters aboard his campaign plane that
delivering the speech was a turning point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt different yesterday when I went on the stage and I
became the official nominee of the party,'' Bush said. ``I've got a
responsibility to uphold and I'm going to uphold it and I think
we've got a good chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, there's going to be all kinds of polls and speculation
between now and Election Day and I understand that. That's why . .
. it's so important for us to be patient and keep our eye on the
finish line. We've got a strategy in place the entire time.''
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, Bush's lead over Gore had reached 19 points _ 50
percent to 31 percent _ in a bipartisan Voter.com-Battleground
tracking poll of 1,000 likely voters taken Wednesday and Thursday.
The poll has a 3 percentage point error margin. Bush had a 20-point
lead among independents and a slight lead among women, two groups
where he and Gore previously had been tied. Bush led in every
region of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was not trying to provoke Vice President Al Gore
with the speech, but to, ``speak to the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Bush accused Gore and President Clinton of
squandering their eight years leading the nation. He mocked Gore as
a fearful naysayer who labels Bush's proposals, ``risky schemes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of needling the opponent with good humor, that's what
American politics should be about ...,'' he said. ``I'm going to
continue pointing up differences and I will do so in a respectful
way and occasionally put a needle out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it was the most negative speech he has given as a
candidate, Bush said: ``I don't feel that was the case at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to draw the distinction and I need to make the case
that this is a wasted moment in American history,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
