<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3146 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CONVENTION-ANALYSIS-H     08-04 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTION-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH MUST SUBSTANTIATE HIS ATTACKS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Drawing morning-after praise, even from Democrats, for his GOP
acceptance speech, George W. Bush now must substantiate his attacks
on his opponent and convince more voters that he's equipped for the
presidency, political experts said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, however, wasted no time in belittling
the Texas governor's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know our opponents put on quite a show in Philadelphia,
but political positioning will never heal sick children or give
senior citizens the medications they need,'' Gore said in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, an NBC News poll conducted in the final hours of the
four-day convention said the upbeat GOP gathering sent Bush's
approval numbers up considerably.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly he helped himself on a personal front,'' said
Democratic pollster Peter D. Hart of Washington, D.C., who
conducted the survey for NBC and the Wall Street Journal in
conjunction with GOP pollster Robert Teeter.
</P>
<P>
   Before the convention, the pollsters said Bush drew favorable
ratings from 52 percent of the public, but as it closed, the number
was 58 percent. Meanwhile, Bush's negative rating, which was 32
percent before the gathering, dropped to 24 percent, Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, with a 4.4 percent margin of error, placed Bush ahead
of Gore by 11 percentage points (47 to 36 percent) up from a
six-point spread before the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I would call a conventional convention bump. It's
perfectly normal and understandable. This falls right in the
mid-range of what one expects from a good convention,'' Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is, personal attitudes toward Bush climbed
considerably,'' Hart said, even among people who didn't follow the
convention and missed Bush's acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight tracking polls taken Wednesday and Thursday showed
Bush had gained a convention bounce of 10 percentage points among
likely voters, almost twice the historical average for candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In the NBC poll of 511 registered voters, Bush picked up support
with older voters in the Midwest and with independents nationwide,
the pollster said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush bolstered perceptions that he is the ``compassionate
conservative'' he claims and has more of a vision for the future
than Gore, Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the central question that people had going in, they still
have going out: Is he knowledgeable and experienced enough to
handle the presidency? Going in, Gore had an advantage of 36-30 on
that quality; coming out, it's 41-37,'' Hart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in a good Bush week, he still has something to prove to
the voters,'' Hart said. For example, on the subject of the tax
cuts proposed by Bush, ``it's not a question of how big your tax
cut is, it's how responsible it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond satisfying those types of concerns, Bush also must be
prepared to answer harsh Democratic attacks in answer to his own
verbal salvos, said University of Texas at Arlington political
scientist Allen Saxe.
</P>
<P>
   He described Bush's address as ``the smoothest speech I've ever
heard him make.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But now the Democrats are going to come out swinging and the
Republicans know it,'' Saxe said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will Bush's federal policies be assailed when the
Democrats meet in Los Angeles on Aug. 14, but Bush's Texas record
is in for unrelenting scrutiny, the professor said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, quoting his friend, the late Democratic Lt. Gov. Bob
Bullock, warned critics, ``Don't mess with Texas.'' Saxe said it
isn't likely the Democrats will heed that.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to mess with Texas. That's what the
Democratic party is going to do now _ show that it's really not the
compassionate conservative party that Bush talked about in his
speech. It's really the same old conservative party that we've
always known,'' Saxe said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Jano Cabrera downplayed the NBC poll, saying it
reflect the ``wild'' fluctuations common during the convention
season. More telling, he claimed, was Bush's attack on the
Clinton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering that he promised to have an attack-free convention
and then broke his word to the American people, his whole speech
was offensive,'' Cabrera said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of having a substantive discussion on the issues, he
attacked Al Gore,'' Cabrera said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
