<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TAKES WINNERS LAP THROUGH 4 KEY STATES 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Enjoying a post-convention campaign bounce and a
bumpy railway ride, newly anointed Republican presidential nominee
George W. Bush boarded the ``Victory 2000 Express'' train Friday
for a three-day winner's lap through four battleground states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our party has a message: It says give us a chance. It won't be
long now. Give us a chance to change America for the better,'' Bush
said while standing on the rear platform of a red Norfolk Southern
railway car, addressing a crowd of about 3,000 supporters in
Station Square.
</P>
<P>
   The train of 16 antique cars, pulled by two engines bearing two
wind-whipped American flags, carried Bush away from the Republican
National Convention in Philadelphia and the most triumphant moment
in his quest for the White House. Bush's railroad tour had stops
scheduled in Pennsylvania, Ohio, Michigan and Illinois between
Friday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight tracking polls taken Wednesday and Thursday showed
Bush had gained a convention bounce of 10 percentage points among
likely voters, almost twice the historical average for candidates.
The largest convention bounce was the 13 percentage points gained
by Ronald Reagan in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The Battleground 2000 poll for Voter.com ended before Bush had
delivered his nationally televised acceptance speech Thursday
night. A final day of polling Friday is expected to measure the
impact of Bush's speech.
</P>
<P>
   The poll was conducted by Democratic pollster Celinda Lake and
Republican pollster Ed Goeas. It surveyed 1,000 likely voters
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Gore can expect his own bounce from the Democratic National
Convention that begins Aug. 14, but Bush's lead puts Gore in the
position of having to make up ground with voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be all kinds of polls and speculation between
now and Election Day and I understand that,'' Bush said. ``That's
why it's so important for us to be patient and keep our eye on the
finish line.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said issues are ``going to win this campaign and I'm going
to keep talking about issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush dismissed Democratic criticism that he and other convention
speakers had masqueraded as moderates for national television to
hide a conservative record that is out of the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he will keep hitting on the themes of his acceptance
speech: tax relief, strengthening the military, reforming Social
Security and improving education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to keep saying it over and over again, so should I
become the president, I will be able to stand up in front of the
Congress and say, `The American people heard what I said. They've
endorsed the platform. Now, let's get it done,' '' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush defended the aggressive tone of his convention speech,
saying it was not too harsh against Gore or President Clinton.
Denying that his deadpan joke about Gore inventing the Internet was
a personal attack, Bush said, ``I'm sure he's used to that by now.
I doubt he even watched it, would be my guess.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor said there is nothing wrong with teasing an
opponent or drawing a distinction between records or political
positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of needling the opponent with good humor, that's what
American politics should be about as opposed to the kind where you
tear people down and distort,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm going to continue pointing up differences, and I'm
going to do so in a respectful way. And occasionally put a needle
out there. But as some of you may know by now, I like to needle.
Right, Pancho?'' Bush said, teasing a reporter for The New York
Times by using his nickname.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he enjoyed delivering his convention speech and was
not nervous. The toughest moment, he said, was when he was talking
about his family, including his father, the former president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I got through those paragraphs, I knew I was in pretty
good shape,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The best audience response, Bush said, came from the refrain,
``They had their chance. They haven't led. We will.'' He said the
delegates began to understand that he was laying out a case that
Clinton's legacy should not be continued through Gore.
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, Bush said he returned to his room at the
Marriott Hotel in Philadelphia and celebrated with his sister and
two of his three brothers.
</P>
<P>
   He said his bedtime probably ``set a modern-day record for me,
1:30 in the morning.'' Bush's usual bedtime is 9:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The nominee and his running mate, Dick Cheney, began Friday at a
prayer breakfast, followed by a visit to the Republican National
Committee. Cheney told the RNC not to become complacent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the polls look great. The opposition is obviously
shell-shocked. It will be a tough campaign. This crew is not likely
to steal off into the sunset,'' Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   At an airport rally attended by about 500 people, Bush praised
Philadelphia and the convention that nominated him for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sure glad we came to Philadelphia,'' Bush said. ``We
leave this city of brotherly love energized and united and focused
on victory.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bushes and the Cheneys rode a pair of 1928 sister train cars
on their whistle-stop tour, the Virginia and the Carolina. One is
an office car, and the other is a sleeper.
</P>
<P>
   The train trip was not constant; the entourage planned to get
off and fly to the next state every day while a train crew
deadheaded to the next day's starting point.
</P>
<P>
   At stops along his train trip, Bush greeted small groups of 100
to 300 well-wishers in western Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a tough campaign. That's why we're here in
Wampum, Pa.,'' Bush told one crowd of about 100 people. ``We're
taking no votes for granted. I want you to remind your friends and
neighbors when voting time comes who came and asked. We're here
asking.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
