<HEADER>
A3161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CONCORDE-CRASH-1STLD-     08-04 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCORDE-CRASH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH INVESTIGATORS FIND UNIDENTIFIED STRIP OF METAL ON RUNWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Rewrites 4th graf to identify investigating agency. Changes
``Concordes'' to ``the French Concordes'' in 2nd-last graf.)  
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Investigators looking into last week's crash of the Air
France Concorde said Friday that they had found a 16-inch strip of
metal on the runway that did not belong to the plane, and that they
have also found a ``large gash'' in a piece of tire debris.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators have so far been unable to explain why the jet
caught fire on take off and crashed into a small wooden hotel, just
north of Paris, killing 114.
</P>
<P>
   Without any theories, French transportation officials have
continued to keep Air France's remaining Concorde planes out of
service.
</P>
<P>
   But a statement released Friday by the BEA, the French agency
that investigates air crashes, suggested that investigators might
be considering the possibility that a problem that had nothing to
do with the plane's mechanics had caused the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Since the disaster on July 25, speculation has largely focused
on the possibility that a tire suffered a blow out and debris from
it or a wheel sliced through fuel lines or fuel tanks, triggering a
fire. But investigators have yet to offer their opinion. The metal
strip could explain how the tire was damaged.
</P>
<P>
   But in their statement, the investigators continued to steer
clear of theories. They offered a smattering of new facts without
explaining how any of them might fit together. They have said that
a preliminary report will not be ready before the end of the month,
and a final report could take 18 months to complete.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators said that one of the plane's left side tires
was changed before take off and survived the crash intact. Debris
from another tire on the left side was found on the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Tire marks on the runway also showed that the plane had veered
to the left before taking off. Traces of soot, pieces of water
deflectors above the tire and debris from a fuel tank were also on
the runway.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, a water deflector on a British Airways Concorde broke
off and punctured a fuel tank. The British airline later modified
the deflector so that could not happen again. But Air France
officials have said they did not install the same modifications.
</P>
<P>
   Some Air France employees on Friday sent an open letter to the
airline to organize a special Concorde test flight to show that
they still have confidence in the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason to keep it on the ground,'' said Gilles
Belliard, spokesman for the National Union of Civil Aviation
Mechanics. Belliard said mechanics and other employees would
volunteer to board the special flight.
</P>
<P>
   But Air France officials said no such flight would take place
before the Transportation Ministry ruled that the French Concordes
could fly again.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways briefly suspended its Concorde flights but went
back to regular service the day after the crash, which killed all
100 passengers and nine crew members and five people who were on
the ground in the town of Gonesse, where the plane crashed in a
ball of fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 2214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
