<HEADLINE>
ALASKA AIRLINES GROUNDS JETS TO RECHECK TAIL MECHANISMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Alaska Airlines said Friday that it had canceled 48
flights in the past two days after grounding 17 of its 34 MD-80
aircraft for inspections. Those planes are the same model as the
one that crashed off the Southern California coast in January,
killing 88 people, when a part in the tail section malfunctioned.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska said it acted after finding that a measurement tool made
by the airline to monitor wear on the tail part had produced
inconsistent readings, meaning that it might have failed to detect
unacceptable wear in a control mechanism called a jackscrew. A
factor in the January crash is believed to have been problems with
the plane's jackscrew, which had been checked with a tool made by
the airline.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Alaska, Dave Marriott, said that as of late
Friday afternoon, the airline had checked all 17 of the grounded
planes with a measurement tool made by Boeing, the plane's
manufacturer, and had found the tail parts to be within acceptable
tolerances. The planes were returned to service by Friday evening,
Marriott said.
</P>
<P>
   The airline canceled 19 flights on Thursday night and 29 Friday,
and rebooked passengers on other flights or other airlines. Alaska,
based in Seattle, averages 500 flights a day and is a major carrier
between the Pacific Northwest and cities in California.
</P>
<P>
   The airline has 92 aircraft, 34 of which are MD-80s. Another
Alaska spokesman, Jack Evans, said half of the MD-80s had been
recently inspected using tools made by Boeing, and were not
grounded. The MD-80 maintenance manual says that motion in the
jackscrew should be measured using a tool made by the aircraft
manufacturer or an ``equivalent substitute.'' Alaska mechanics had
inspected several of the other MD-80s using a tool made in the
carrier's machine shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airline found that the measurements could vary if the
carrier's tool was improperly positioned,'' Alaska said Friday in a
news release. The airline said it had notified the Federal Aviation
Administration and had begun ``reinspecting the jackscrews on the
affected aircraft using the tool made by the aircraft
manufacturer.'' The airline suggested there was uncertainty as to
whether its tool was considered an ``equivalent substitute.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman at the FAA, Diane Spitalieri, said that checks had
determined that other airlines were using a mix of tools, some
built by the McDonnell Douglas division of Boeing, and others made
by the airlines. Spitalieri said the agency had not found any tools
that produced inconsistent results, but more tools remained to be
checked.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing assumed production of the MD-80, which is a more recent
variant of the DC-9, after it took over McDonnell Douglas three
years ago in a $16.3 billion merger. There are roughly 2,000 MD-80s
and DC-9s in service around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
