u a BC-NY-KOSHER-LAW-NYT &LR;      08-04 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KOSHER-LAW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. COURT VOIDS N.Y. STATE'S AUTHORITY TO ENFORCE KOSHER RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A ruling by a federal judge that New York state's
kosher food laws are unconstitutional highlights the intersection
of centuries-old biblical and rabbinical strictures with modern
state sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Under the laws, state inspectors would visit supermarkets to
ensure that kosher meat and dairy products were not mingled, would
step into the kitchens of kosher restaurants that serve meat to
make sure that vegetable dips did not contain cheese or other dairy
products, and would even stick their hands into the water used to
defeather chickens in poultry plants to determine whether it was
too hot to permit the birds' blood to fully drain.
</P>
<P>
   If the inspectors discovered forbidden activities the violators
could be fined or, in the case where intentional deception was
charged, could face criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in declaring the laws unconstitutional, Judge Nina
Gershon of U.S. District Court in Brooklyn held that they ``foster
excessive entanglements'' between religion and the state, in
violation of the First Amendment. The ruling came in a suit in
which the owners of a kosher butcher shop in Commack on Long Island
challenged the laws after being cited for numerous violations under
them.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Gov. George Pataki said he had directed the state's
Department of Agriculture and Markets, which enforces the laws, to
appeal Gershon's decision as well as to seek a stay of the decision
pending the outcome of the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``These laws protect New Yorkers from consumer fraud,'' Pataki
said, adding that such protection was necessary to make sure that
``food represented as kosher'' really was.
</P>
<P>
   But in her ruling, Gershon said that the laws in question, first
written in the late 19th century, ``advance religion because they
require the state to affirmatively assume ongoing obligations of
enforcement of purely religious laws, inevitably requiring the
state to rely on religious authority and interpretation to properly
enforce them.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners of Commack Self-Service Kosher Meats had also argued
that in defining kosher food as ``prepared in accordance with
Orthodox Hebrew religious requirements'' the laws impermissibly
violated the rights of Jews who were not Orthodox and often had
different standards of kosher. The suit further claimed that the
laws were too vague because they failed to define ``orthodox Hebrew
religious requirements.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say that a major deficiency of the state laws is
their failure to take into account varying views among Jews of what
kosher means in certain situations.
</P>
<P>
   One Conservative Jewish leader who said he thought Gershon had
made the right decision said that the differences were not only
between Orthodox and other Jews, but often within the Orthodox
branch itself.
</P>
<P>
   That explains why there are ``so many different rabbis who
certify what is kosher'' within that branch, said the Conservative
leader, Rabbi Jerome Epstein, executive vice president of the
United Synagogue of Conservative Judaism, which represents nearly
800 congregations in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Wiesenfeld, a former member of Pataki's staff who served as
his liaison on Jewish matters, contended Friday that the reason the
laws had run into trouble was that for a time in recent years they
were being improperly enforced under the ``higher level'' of kosher
``required by the Orthodox.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
