<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TACOMA-DEVELOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TACOMA JOURNAL : AIR CLEANED, TECH HIGH, A CITY REBOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TACOMA, Wash. _ When EssentialMarkets.com was looking for a
place to establish headquarters a year and a half ago, executives
at the Internet start-up thought first of the better-known software
capitals of the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat down and the general feeling was, I guess we should
look in Seattle, or maybe Bellevue or Redmond,'' recalled David M.
Boitano, chief operating officer of the company, which helps
businesses sell their products online. ``But the more we talked
about Tacoma, the more we thought, Well, why not Tacoma? I mean,
we're an Internet company. We can be anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's decision to locate here is just one piece in the
much larger story of a renaissance for Tacoma, which long suffered
from image problems as a gritty mill town living very much in the
shadow of Seattle, its more glamorous sister 30 miles to the north.
For years the noxious fumes from pulp plants here were so powerful
that people in the region spoke of the ``Tacoma aroma.'' The city
even seemed a bit of an afterthought in the name of the region's
major point of entry, Seattle-Tacoma International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   But, lured by office rents and housing prices roughly half
Seattle's, 100 high-technology companies have started up, relocated
or expanded in the downtown area in the last two years, according
to the city's Economic Development Department.
</P>
<P>
   Tacoma's revival is evident not just in the new companies coming
here. The Tacoma Art Museum is expanding into a new building, and a
convention center three times the size of the existing one is
rising downtown. The famous smell is gone, a result of mill
closings and cleanups, and the air is much cleaner, yielding
spectacular views of Mount Rainier, the Olympic Mountains and Puget
Sound that rival those in Seattle. Traffic congestion, a major
complaint in Seattle and its high-tech suburbs to the east, is not
a big problem here in this city of 187,000 people _ not yet,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in Tacoma, you can still choose whether you want to
live in an urban, suburban or rural area, and it simply doesn't
take long to get around,'' said Eric Cederstrand, a developer here
who has built or renovated several downtown buildings that are now
home to high-tech companies. ``You can be out in the countryside in
half an hour. In Seattle these days, it can take you half an hour
to drive three blocks.''
</P>
<P>
   The revival can be traced in part to municipal officials'
decision a few years ago to invest $100 million to stretch
fiber-optic lines through much of the city, offering a high-speed
data network attractive to technology companies. Tacoma's is one of
the largest publicly owned telecommunications infrastructures in
the nation, prompting the city to market itself with the theme
``America's No. 1 Wired City.''
</P>
<P>
   Tacoma also has an impressive stock of turn-of-the-century and
Art Deco buildings that were largely in disrepair or even abandoned
in recent decades, lending a ghost-town air to parts of downtown.
Many of those are being renovated, offering the kind of ``fun,
creative space,'' in Cederstrand's description, that lots of
technology companies crave.
</P>
<P>
   One of his clients, Y3K Inc., a sort of Internet mall that helps
small businesses sell products over the World Wide Web, is taking a
floor and a half in a 1910 building downtown that has exposed brick
walls, high ceilings, sandblasted beams and impressive views.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cox, chief operating officer at Y3K, which will move from
another Tacoma location to the renovated building this fall, said
he discerned no problems in being a bit outside the Seattle-Redmond
orbit that is home to giants like the Microsoft Corp. and
Amazon.com, and to many lesser-known high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are advantages here,'' Cox said. ``In Seattle, I
think, there's a danger that a new company can feel lost in the
shuffle. The feeling is, Well, it's just another Internet company.
Here, it's a bigger deal. And there's a lot of support from the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Grenley, chief executive of IDmicro, a 25-employee
company based here that designs several kinds of wireless tracking
devices, also said he saw advantages to being a ``bigger fish in a
smaller pond.''
</P>
<P>
   Grenley, who grew up in the area, said he would have ``laughed
out loud'' if he had heard someone predict Tacoma's resurgence 15
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Downtown was decayed, empty, bombed-out,'' he said. ``Parts of
it looked like Dresden or something. You were scared to be
downtown. And it physically smelled bad. Today it's completely
different. It's amazing what's happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   Boitano, at EssentialMarkets, which is planning to grow from 105
employees &UR;  &LR; to 250 over the next eight months and is leasing new
office space downtown, said attracting people to the area was not a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put them in a car and drive them around,'' he said, ``show
them the mountains, the water, the quality of housing that's
available, the recreation. It's not a hard sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Juli Wilkerson, the city's director of economic development,
said there was plenty of talent available locally, noting that 22
percent of the work force from Tacoma and surrounding Pierce County
still commuted to jobs in the Seattle area. ``They would love to
avoid that commute if they could,'' Wilkerson said.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan A. Wright, marketing director at IDmicro, moved from
Seattle in February with some trepidation, but was pleasantly
surprised. ``Now I'd say, Why put up with the hassle? Here I've got
a seven-minute commute. The views are great, there's a lot going
on, but Tacoma's still got a small-town feel to it, too. I'd take
this any day of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
