<SLUG> BC-DRUGBUST0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dragnet locates 1,015 high-level drug fugitives
 &HT;    By Monika Gonzalez Mesa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A police task force formed to corral ``the highest
level'' of drug organization fugitives has made 1,015 arrests,
including a Fort Pierce, Fla., man suspected in the slaying of a
government witness, federal authorities announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Deputy Marshals, working with state and local police
agencies, also seized more than $1 million in property in the
four-month effort to round up felons on the run, federal
authorities said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1,015 arrested internationally, 532 were wanted under
indictments linking them to the organized drug crime industry. And
119 were high-level drug dealers from Florida and the Caribbean who
had been indicted but never were arrested, and ones who had jumped
bail.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. marshals estimated the task force, dubbed Operation Sort 1,
arrested about 25 people in Palm Beach, Martin, St. Lucie,
Highlands, Indian River and Okeechobee counties.
</P>
<P>
   Edner St. Louis, 36, a suspected lieutenant in a Haitian crack
cocaine ring, was arrested April 5 in Fort Pierce on charges of
distributing crack cocaine, said U.S. Marshals Warrant Coordinator
Lou Vega. St. Louis also is a suspect in the shooting of two
government witnesses, but has not been charged with those crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Vega said the drug investigation of St. Louis began in 1994 when
the Florida Highway patrol stopped him in Indian River County.
There were three people in the car and 10 ounces of cocaine
obtained in Fort Pierce, Vega said.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Pierce police later informed the Drug Enforcement Agency
that they were investigating the May 1994 death of Brian Wright,
who had died after being shot multiple times at the house where the
men allegedly had been storing the drugs. Federal agents considered
Wright a witness.
</P>
<P>
   Another Fort Pierce man, Tim White, was shot five times but
survived, as did two bystanders who were injured, Vega said. The
triggermen in that shooting told investigators they were hired to
shoot Wright for stealing from a drug house.
</P>
<P>
   The Drug Enforcement Agency later indicted six people in the
drug ring for conspiracy to distribute crack, including St. Louis.
Several months later, in January 1999, Tim White, a witness in the
case was shot again and killed.
</P>
<P>
   Vega said that when St. Louis was arrested in April, he had
three knives by his bed, a Colt .357 in the oven, and a Haitian
passport and a driver license bearing his photo and a false name.
</P>
<P>
   The federal officials used the announcement to ask for more
money from Congress for similar operations.
</P>
<P>
   Katharine Armentrout, director of the U.S. Justice Department's
Organized Crime Drug Enforcement Task Force, said the seizures from
the arrests had added up to nearly twice as much as was spent to
conduct the roundup. Armentrout emphasized that the average cost of
each arrest was $623.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to show we need more money to go find them,''
Deputy U.S. Marshal John Amat said. ``Unfortunately, informants are
a major part of investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   The operation also led to the May 5 capture of Felix Fermin, 36,
who U.S. Marshals said led a major Colombian heroin smuggling
organization operating in South Florida, New York and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   And it led to the arrest of Santiago Mendoza who was arrested in
May in connection with a first degree murder indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Elias, 37, had been wanted since DEA agents raided a
marijuana grow house in 1997. Deputy U.S. Marshals from the West
Palm Beach office arrested him in La Jolla, Calif., in April along
with former Palm Beach County residents Stanley Hough and uncle
Larry Hough, Vega said. Vega said their search for Elias also led
to the search of a home in Alpine, Calif., where deputies
discovered an elaborate indoor marijuana growing operation in a
detatched garage big enough for two motorhomes. The garage was
double-walled so that air-conditioned air shielded the building
from heat sensors used by police . It was capable of growing more
than $2.5 million in marijuana a year, Vega said, adding he saw
nearly 1,000 plants. The home had been bought for nearly $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Michael Salnick, who is defending Elias, said the
government is overstating their effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``They happened to stumble upon Mr. Elias,'' Salnick said. ``Law
enforcement has made it much larger than it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Salnick said Elias left Boca Raton before he was indicted and
wasn't trying to evade authorities. He also denied that Elias is a
high-level drug trafficker; a trial date is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
