</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-RECORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BUSH CREATES NEW SYNTHESIS TO APPEAL TO MODERATES  

</HEADLINE>
   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ With his speech at the GOP convention Thursday,
Gov. George W. Bush created a synthesis new to Republican politics:
conservative policies described in ways that his campaign believes
swing voters will love.
</P>
<P>
   So his $1.3 trillion, 10-year tax cut _ more sweeping than
congressional Republicans ever tried _ became an effort to bring
``common sense and fairness to the tax code.'' His plan to divert
some Social Security payroll taxes to private investment accounts
amounts, he said, to giving ``American workers security and
independence that no politician can ever take away.''
</P>
<P>
   The language was positively Clintonian, but as many
conservatives were quick to note, Bush had not actually changed any
of the Republican Party's core principles _ from its opposition to
abortion, to its support for large tax cuts, to its backing of a
vast missile defense system, to its search for conservative Supreme
Court justices.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has packaged the traditional conservative positions with
completely new covering,'' said Marshall Wittmann, a policy analyst
at the Heritage Foundation, a conservative policy group in
Washington. ``It's not necessarily a new Republicanism in quite the
way that Clinton was a new Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   This synthesis is central to Bush's effort to assemble a winning
coalition. The Bush campaign wants to hold its conservative base
through its policy proposals, and then pick up the moderate middle
through Bush's conciliatory language and willingness to speak about
issues that Democrats long dominated.
</P>
<P>
   The question for the fall campaign is whether Bush can
convincingly keep up his balancing act as the Democrats try to home
in on the details of policy proposals and his record back in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Where Bush describes a tax cut that helps people at the bottom
of the economic ladder, the Democrats see a tax cut that helps the
rich. While Bush promises to strengthen Social Security, the
Democrats say he could reduce retirement benefits. For all the time
Bush spent delivering policy addresses this spring, a number of his
proposals lack specifics.
</P>
<P>
   And for some, Bush's record does not always square with his
rhetoric. ``An informed voter is their worst nightmare,'' said
Douglas Hattaway, a spokesman for presumed Democratic nominee Vice
President Al Gore, referring to the Bush campaign. The Democrats
have already begun a barrage of ads trying to challenge Bush's
commitment on issues like the environment.
</P>
<P>
   With the Democrats running against the high cost of prescription
drugs, Bush's aides say they are already debating whether the Texas
governor needs to draw up a plan to show how he would pay for
prescription drug coverage. In his nomination speech, Bush said he
would ``make prescription drugs available and affordable for every
senior who needs them.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has never said how he would do that and has never devoted
a major address to the issue. He has spoken approvingly of one
bipartisan plan floated in Congress that would allow Medicare
recipients to choose a plan with a prescription drug benefit. And
when House Republicans passed their own prescription drug plan,
Bush avoided taking a position on it.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing Social Security Thursday night in his speech at the
GOP convention accepting the nomination, Bush sought credit for his
willingness to take a stand on the issue. He promised that he would
strengthen the program ``for the greatest generation and
generations to come.''
</P>
<P>
   But while he has called for some portion of the Social Security
payroll tax to be diverted to individual investment accounts for
young workers, he has not said what percentage, and has been silent
on many related issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not said whether he would raise the retirement age, or
specified how he would deal with the diminished payroll tax that
would come into Social Security if a portion were diverted into
individual investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The New Century Foundation, which characterizes itself as a
nonpartisan and nonprofit research foundation based in New York,
published a study _ disputed by the Bush campaign _ that has said a
plan like Bush's could result in retirement incomes 20 percent
lower than the levels projected under the current Social Security
system.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's tax cut can also be portrayed in different ways. Bush
focused on how he would help the people at the bottom of the
economic ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``On principle, those in the greatest need should receive the
greatest help,'' he said Thursday night. ``So we will lower the
bottom rate from 15 percent to 10 percent and double the child tax
credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats contend, like all tax cuts that sweeping, Bush's plan
helps people at the top of the economic ladder the most. The Gore
campaign, in a statement, calls Bush ``compassionate for the rich
and conservative for everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   In one case on Thursday night, Bush's language was designed to
keep conservatives from becoming alarmed over one area of policy
where he is directly breaking with his party's past.
</P>
<P>
   ``One size does not fit all when it comes to educating our
children,'' Bush said, ``so local people should control local
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a version of one of his biggest applause lines on the
campaign trail _ his insistence that he does not want to be the
federal superintendent of education.
</P>
<P>
   But, he has proposed using federal funds as a lever to encourage
states to give standardized tests in reading and math to all
students in grades three through eight. Any state that refused
would lose 5 percent of its federal education money.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers seem to acknowledge that to some extent Bush is
using issues to create the impression that he is a bold leader. The
fact, they say, that Bush has been willing to take stands that
challenge the status quo makes voters think he is up to the job of
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues form a composite of the candidate that's bigger
than the issues themselves,'' said one senior adviser to Bush. ``We
have and want to be seen as confronting the hard issues, not
avoiding them, and doing so in ways that are innovative for a
Republican to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Garin, a Democratic pollster, said that in recent focus
groups he had run, ``people did not feel that on the level of
issues there is a lot at stake in this election.'' He found that
the voters are focusing much more on the character of the
candidates and their moral authority.
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, the Republicans are confident that Bush has
made conservatism attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that Al Gore can win this election,'' said Gov.
Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin. ``I think George Bush can lose it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
