<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE BELITTLES GOP CONVENTION 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Smarting from the drubbing he took in his opponent's
convention speech, Democratic presidential hopeful Al Gore returned
to the campaign trail Friday to belittle the Republican National
Convention as a ``masquerade ball,'' with hosts that would return
the United States to recession and high deficits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that our opposition put on quite a show in
Philadelphia,'' Gore told about 3,400 cheering members of the
International Association of Firefighters. ``When it comes to
political pageantry, I've got to hand it to the other side. When it
comes to nice sounding slogans and sound bites, I'll give credit
where credit is due.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you and I know political positioning will never heal sick
children who don't have health care, or help senior citizens afford
the medicines they need,'' Gore said. ``If you ask me, the
Republican National Convention was kind of like a masquerade ball
for special interests, with a purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spent the last week vacationing on the coast of North
Carolina, following the tradition of laying low during the
opposition party's convention. But he used the Democrat stronghold
of Chicago to stage a downtown-marching, placard-waving,
high-fiving return to the fray.
</P>
<P>
   GOP nominee George W. Bush's acceptance speech Thursday before
the Republican National Convention painted the Clinton-Gore
administration as an embarrassment _ a failed partnership that
squandered its opportunity to lead. His attacks on Gore were his
sharpest and most personal to date, suggesting the vice president
was afraid to take risks and willing to retool himself to fit his
pollsters' image of what Americans want.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not need to take your pulse before I know my own mind,''
Bush said. ``I know my own mind. I do not reinvent myself at every
turn. I am not running in borrowed clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore described the GOP's televised embrace of traditionally
Democratic themes as an act _ albeit a clever one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind the balloons and bunting is a massive, budget busting,
tax giveaway primarily benefiting the wealthy in this country,''
Gore said. ``Behind the flashing video wall is an agenda of rising
gas prices and smog-filled skies that is of big oil, by big oil and
for big oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're for the powerful, we're for the people,'' Gore
repeated as punctuation to a litany of complaints against the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   A large share of Gore's message was aimed at debunking the GOP
convention message of a failed Clinton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to get real,'' Gore said. ``I heard our opposition
in Philadelphia talking about the past eight years. They said it
was a time of lost opportunity, that we were just coasting, taking
the path of least resistance. I have to ask what planet have they
been on?''
</P>
<P>
   Citing GOP budget stalemates that shut down the government twice
and Republican opposition to campaign finance reform, Gore said,
``I wish there had been less resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   When they turned out a Republican administration in 1992, Gore
reminded his audience, they inherited a recession and large
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have seen in last eight years is leadership to stand
with American families,'' Gore said. ``Instead of the biggest
deficit, we have the biggest surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   Countering the GOP message that the Clinton administration was
marred by moral failures, Tipper Gore introduced the vice president
as ``a man who continues to be a terrific husband. A man who's
always been there for every member of our family, and what that
says is he'll be there for your family.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gore, too, sought to underscore a certain distance from
Clinton, mentioning his service as an Army correspondent in Vietnam
as a contrast to Clinton's efforts to avoid the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in Vietnam, I didn't do the most, or suffer the
most danger,'' Gore said.``But I knew if I didn't go, someone else
from my hometown of Carthage would have to go in my place.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he ultimately decided he could no more turn away from
public service at home, ``than I could turn away from service in
Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also spoke to letter carriers in Chicago before flying back
to Washington for two fund-raising events. He will travel to upper
New York state today before heading to Tennessee, where he plans to
announce his running mate Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign has leaked a short list of those potential running
mates, including Sens. John Kerry of Massachusetts, Joseph
Lieberman of Connecticut, John Edwards of North Carolina and Evan
Bayh of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeanne Shaheen of New Hampshire and Rep. Richard Gephardt
of Missouri also are on the short list, though they have said they
do not want the job.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Gore said there is a ``wild card'' on his short
list _ an individual he described to reporters Friday morning as
``an out-of-the-box possibility.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
