<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3180 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-EARNHARDTS0805-CO     08-04 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-EARNHARDTS0805-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The son also rises; both Earnhardts on a roll
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Dale Earnhardt was holding court in a room off
Gasoline Alley at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway when the door
opened and in walked Dale Jr. _ the one they call Little E.
</P>
<P>
   As his son joined him, Earnhardt leaned back from the microphone
and said quietly, ``So, you decided to take a little vacation?''
</P>
<P>
   Little E nodded sheepishly about his absence during the two-week
break since the last Winston Cup race: ``Yeah, I just forgot to
tell you. Went to Cancun.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt sized up the kid everyone says is a chip off the old
engine block and quickly focused on Little E's two-tone hairstyle.
Naturally dark and clipped close on the sides, it exploded into a
parted-down-the-middle top thatch that was bleached the blondest of
blondes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Cancun sun do that to your hair?'' Earnhardt smirked.
</P>
<P>
   Little E grinned: ``Nope . . . from a bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying hard to hide his own smile, Earnhardt got up, shook his
head and said, ``It's your turn. Enjoy yourself in here, but be
careful of these (media) guys.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 49-year-old Earnhardt _ who has worked so hard to
cultivate his image of The Intimidator, a no-nonsense enforcer who
dressed in black, drove a black car and wore a perpetual scowl
beneath his ever-present black shades _ peroxide progeny was a
little unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in their lives, Earnhardt and his 25-year-old
son are spending their weekends together. But instead of
arm-around-the-shoulders embrace, this bond has been built
bumper-to-bumper at 190 mph. Today, Little E will start the
Brickyard 400 on the outside of Row 3. His dad will start directly
behind him on the outside of Row 4.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt _ a come-to-life character from one of those rowdy
Hank Jr. songs _ is a certified legend in Winston Cup racing. He's
won 75 races _ including the Brickyard 400 in 1995 _ and seven
driving titles, a mark that ties him with stock car icon Richard
Petty. Little E _ a Winston Cup rookie who has the driving style of
his give-no-quarter dad and his NASCAR pioneering grandfather _ is
seen both as Winston Cup's future and a vibrant link to the sport's
past.
</P>
<P>
   But if you think this season is simply about passing the torch,
you better think again. ``If someone tells you I'm riding my years
out,'' Earnhardt spit, ``they're not payin' attention.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Earnhardt won the Cracker Barrel 500 in Atlanta, has
15 top 10 finishes in 21 races and stands third in Winston Cup
points standings. Little E has won at Texas Motor Speedway,
Richmond and the non-points Winston all-star race at Charlotte and
is 14th in the points standings.
</P>
<P>
   Both drivers are bull-headed competitors and for the rest of us,
it's made for a family affair that's been fun to watch. While they
are father and son, they also are Felix and Oscar _ the Odd Couple.
</P>
<P>
   Little E wears baggy jeans that hang from his hips, boxy polo
shirts and shades propped atop his head. He's into music big time,
with a massive collection of CDs and stereos in every room of his
house. His tastes run from Pearl Jam to the Foo Fighters and he
financially backs his friends' band called Bridge. He's played the
drums with them on stage and written lyrics for one of their songs.
He also pens poetry about love and has said one day he might like
to be a disc jockey or a music critic.
</P>
<P>
   His dad _ don't call him Dale Sr., he hates that _ is into
Loretta Lynn and Brooks and Dunn. Not much for rhyme, he is, at
times, even more adverse to reason. He's made a career out of good
ol' boy crankiness, but that unyielding nature and honest grit have
made him endearing to blue collar dreamers fighting the bosses and
bureaucracy of life.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt earned his hard-edged stripes. He was the son of Ralph
Earnhardt, the hard-scrabble short track racer who was nicknamed
Ironheart for his undaunted approach _ right up to the day he died
of heart failure at age 45.
</P>
<P>
   Having quit school after the eighth grade to go racing,
Earnhardt struggled. By 17 he was married, had a son and ``probably
should've been on welfare.'' He'd race on the weekend, so he could
buy groceries on Monday. Soon after he was divorced and after that
allowed his ex-wife and her new husband to adopt his son, Kerry,
because, as he once told writer Ed Hinton, ``I couldn't afford to
make child support payments.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jr. and daughter Kelly were the products of his second
marriage and soon after he was married a third time, to current
wife Teresa, who has given him a fourth child and with whom he has
forged a business empire _ Dale Earnhardt Inc. _ that a couple of
years ago had an estimated net worth of $20 million in annual
endorsements and souvenir sales.
</P>
<P>
   With the means came new methods, including sending Dale Jr. off
to military school during his teen years. After that, he gave him a
job changing oil at his massive race shop, now known as ``The
Garage Mahal.''
</P>
<P>
   While Little E talks of earning his way, his dad is quick to add
a qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent my money until I was broke,'' Earnhardt said recently.
``I didn't have nothing. It's a little different for him. Things
are there for him. His team, his sponsors, things like that I
didn't have that when I started. He always says he had to work for
it. He worked for it in the driving department and the paying
attention department, but he hasn't had to WORK for it and get it
like we did.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is _ and the Earnhardt fans who have embraced the son
as the Second Coming would be loathe to admit it _ Little E
probably has more in common with Jeff Gordon than his dad.
</P>
<P>
   He's another GenX driver who _ after proving himself in the
Busch Series, where he won two driving titles _ came into Winston
Cup with top equipment provided by his dad and a 5-year, $50
million sponsorship by Budweiser. Little E also got a built-in fan
base. Earnhardt followers hope he is the guy who will finally put
Gordon in his place and NASCAR brass prays that becomes the perfect
marque match-up for the future.
</P>
<P>
   As much as he grumbles, Earnhardt wants to take care ofr this
month at Michigan International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say the kids get carte blanche. Earnhardt expects
them to drive to a standard and when Little E didn't hook up with
him to draft toward the front of the pack at this year's Daytona
500, Earnhardt pulled behind the kid and gave him a corrective
high-speed bump.
</P>
<P>
   When Little E crashed early this year in an IROC race _ the
series Earnhardt won Friday at IMS with a second place finish to
Mark Martin _ his dad minced no words afterward: ``It looked to me
like his plan was to run wide open 'til he hit something.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends say that in private Earnhardt is relishing his son's
success and, at times, has literally gushed, but publicly _ as he
did again Friday _ he doesn't mind occasionally chiding his
namesake: ``He listens OK, but he's still a little hard-headed.
It's harder to give him advice since he's won a race and a couple
of titles.''
</P>
<P>
   Little E just laughed at such talk: ``Yeah, well he's no easier
to get along with either.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually that's not true and Little E should know it.
</P>
<P>
   When he was just six, his dad decided to teach him to water ski
by tying a rope to his pick-up truck and then driving along the
bank pulling his son. And the better the kid did, the more enthused
the old man got _ until he drove too fast on one run, yanked Little
E out of the water and straight into a boat house.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt shrugged off that story with a grin: ``Yeah, but he
learned how to ski.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
