<HEADER>
A3182 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BERGER-MILOSEVIC-NYT &LR;      08-04 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERGER-MILOSEVIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADMINISTRATION AND NATO FEAR MILOSEVIC MAY MOVE AGAINST
MONTENEGRO 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States is increasingly worried the
Yugoslav leader, Slobodan Milosevic, will move militarily against
Montenegro, the junior republic in Yugoslavia, forcing Washington
and NATO into the awkward position of deciding how to react,
Clinton administration officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's possible use of his Yugoslav army troops and special
forces stationed in Montenegro to undermine Montenegro's president,
Milo Djukanovic, or even strike against him, was discussed at a
White House meeting this week and at NATO headquarters 10 days ago,
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The fears about Milosevic's intentions toward Montenegro have
become more acute since he unilaterally changed the constitution to
arrange presidential, parliamentary and local elections for Sept.
24.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic, who for more than a year has forged a path in
opposition to Milosevic, has refused to take part in the elections
and has rebuffed pleas from Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
to participate in them.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has called the elections in an effort to remain in
power for another eight years. Albright has been eager for
Djukanovic's Democratic Party of Socialists to participate in the
elections, partly to increase the chances of Milosevic's defeat and
partly to minimize the risk of Milosevic's using force. Montenegro
has been receiving American financial assistance for the last year.
</P>
<P>
   If Djukanovic refuses to participate _ and both he and the
United States have called the elections illegal _ then Milosevic
will be more tempted to move against him, administration officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   About 15,000 soldiers of the Yugoslav army are based in
Montenegro, along with about 1,000 men of the seventh military
police battalion. Arrayed against these forces are 15,000
Montenegro police officers reportedly loyal to Djukanovic.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic put the Yugoslav army units on ``high alert'' last
month while he was changing the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a reminder of their ability to act with little or no
warning,'' a NATO official said.
</P>
<P>
   As far as timing a move, the Yugoslav leader has several
options, all potentially embarrassing to the Clinton administration
during the fall presidential campaign. Some kind of military action
against Djukanovic after the Sept. 24 elections would be most
likely, administration officials say.
</P>
<P>
   At the North Atlantic Council last week, Milosevic's designs on
Montenegro were discussed at length, a NATO official said. However,
none of the 19 alliance members had much enthusiasm for any sort of
action against Milosevic if he acted against Montenegro, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO members said they saw few parallels between Montenegro
today and Kosovo last year. They could not cite a legal basis for
intervention, officials said, unlike NATO action on Kosovo, where
the humanitarian crisis was used as the rationale.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. national security adviser, Sandy Berger, said Friday
that he would not speculate about what the Clinton administration
or NATO would do if Milosevic moved against Djukanovic in
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support Djukanovic, we believe he has broad support in
NATO,'' Berger said, adding that ``it would be another mistake for
Milosevic'' to move against Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Berger stressed that he believed it was important for the
opposition parties in Serbia to run as effective a campaign as
possible against Milosevic. Then, if Milosevic stole the election,
the opposition would have a reason to mobilize street
demonstrations against him, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remind you of Marcos, that was the beginning of the end,''
Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Ferdinand Marcos, the authoritarian leader of the
Philippines, claimed victory in rigged elections and was eventually
toppled through street protests.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has tried to enlist the help of
Russia, which traditionally has close ties with Serbia, the main
republic in Yugoslavia, to dampen Milosevic's ambitions in
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the Russian president, Vladimir Putin, was
persuaded last month at the G-8 conference in Okinawa, Japan, to
sign a communique expressing concern about the legality of the
elections.
</P>
<P>
   In addition the secretary-general of NATO, Lord Robertson, wrote
to Putin asking him to dissuade Milosevic from moving against
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   So far the Russians have not been cooperative. A NATO official
said Friday that the Russian ambassador to NATO, Sergei Kislyak,
told Lord Robertson that Putin's agreement to the communique in
Okinawa did not guarantee Russian support for it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
