u i BC-BRITAIN-QUEEN-MOTHER-     08-04 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-QUEEN-MOTHER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN CELEBRATES 100TH BIRTHDAY OF QUEEN MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite and expand by 375 words.)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Surrounded by three generations of the royal family,
Queen Elizabeth the Queen Mother celebrated her 100th birthday
Friday, waving to cheering well-wishers from the Buckingham Palace
balcony where she had marked the end of World War II and helped
lead national rejoicing on other occasions.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40,000 people thronged the Mall as she rode by in a
horse-drawn carriage garlanded with flowers in the gold and blue
colors of her stable. Clutching small Union Jacks, many of them
took up vantage points on the pedestal of the Victoria Memorial,
which honors the woman who was queen on Aug. 4, 1900, when
Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon was born in Glamis Castle in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Her grandson, Charles, the Prince of Wales, 51, sat by her side
as the coach entered the palace grounds to the sound of a 41-gun
salute and the strains of ``God Save the Queen.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later the band of the Coldstream Guards struck up
``Happy Birthday to You,'' and she emerged from the darkness of the
curtained doorway onto the sunny balcony hung with gold and
burgundy draping with her daughters Queen Elizabeth II, 74, and
Princess Margaret, 69, and 25 other members of her immediate
family, including her two great-grandsons, Princes William, 18, and
Harry, 15.
</P>
<P>
   Her day had begun with the arrival of a royal postman at her
Clarence House residence just off the Mall, bearing a ceremonial
card that the queen daily sends to her subjects who are turning
100. One of 12 such cards delivered across the country Friday, the
queen mother's was the only one to carry a personal greeting and to
be signed not with the formal ``Elizabeth R'' but with ``Lilibet,''
the queen's family name since childhood.
</P>
<P>
   The festivities capped weeks of commemorations that have
included full-dress parades, Royal Air Force flyovers and ``God
Bless You Ma'am'' tabloid headlines. Editorials have credited her
with saving the monarchy from perils ranging from the abdication of
her brother-in-law Edward VIII in 1936 to the bombing of Buckingham
Palace during World War II to the dysfunctional family behavior of
modern-day Windsors.
</P>
<P>
   Her first duty as queen was taming the stammering rages of her
husband, the newly crowned King George VI, and it set the tone for
her job ever since _ steadying the pulse of the crisis-prone royal
family.
</P>
<P>
   She is generally regarded as the most popular royal, and it is
difficult to imagine the image-makers who have been hard at work
combating the declining popularity of the other family members
spinning any better presentation of the queen mother than the one
she herself created over 75 years of being in the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   There is no more endearing sight to tradition-minded Britons
than her tilted head, ready smile and girlish waves. She is seen as
a favorite grandmother, surrounded by her pet corgis, open and
approachable, with a love of the blustery British outdoors, a
knowing eye for the daily racing form and a famous fancy for gin
and mischievous chatter.
</P>
<P>
   She lives in high style in Clarence House with a staff of 50,
and while her spending habits have provoked some grousing, they
have continued unchecked. ``Who would want to be the Coutts bank
manager who forecloses on a centenarian national institution?''
explained Andrew Roberts, an author of political histories.
</P>
<P>
   While she never gave interviews or otherwise let the outside
world into her life, she became a figure the public embraced,
particularly during the blitz when she visited London's East End to
observe the damage for herself and to try to lift the spirits of
besieged Londoners. In an oft-cited comment, she inspected the
debris of some Buckingham Palace buildings that had been hit by
Nazi planes and said: ``I'm glad we have been bombed. It makes me
feel I can look the East End in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   The king and queen became symbols of the resistance, she
negotiating the rubble in high heels and pearls, and he dauntingly
military in his navy officer's uniform. She proclaimed the family's
intention to ride out the war in Britain, and she let the palace
information minister put out word that she was practicing shooting
a revolver. Today she remains a living link to a time that is
legendary in British history.
</P>
<P>
   George VI died of lung cancer in 1952 at age 56, and Elizabeth,
then 51, had to adjust to becoming the mother of a monarch rather
than the wife of one. A steely traditionalist, she forcefully moved
to end the love affair between Princess Margaret and Group Capt.
Peter Townsend, a palace equerry who was in the process of divorce.
More recently, she sided with Charles in his marital dispute with
Princess Diana. Diana retaliated for the queen mother's disdain by
telling a biographer that she was ``the chief leper in the leper
colony.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth was born to wealth and privilege, daughter of the 14th
Earl of Strathmore, and the medieval family castle in Scotland was
the setting for much of Macbeth. She was married in 1923 to Albert,
known as ``Bertie,'' and the couple became the Duke and Duchess of
York. His older brother David was the heir to the throne and would
become the future Edward VIII. Though the brothers lived strikingly
different lives _ one at home with his wife and two daughters, the
other out on the town in silken evening wear _ they were close
friends until the arrival of Wallis Simpson, the American divorcee
who was to cause the soon-to-be King Edward to abdicate 11 months
into his reign in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth was never to forgive Wallis Simpson, years later
frostily referring to her as ``the lowest of the low,'' and
insisting that she and her husband, by then the Duke of Windsor,
spend the rest of their lives in exile. But her primary
preoccupation was restoring the good name of the monarchy and
shoring up her husband after he became king, helping him overcome
his crippling stutter and gain the confidence to make public
addresses.
</P>
<P>
   The queen mother is credited with trying to associate the royal
family with the common British family, laying the foundation for
the current effort to make the monarchy less remote and more
personable. She was the first royal to stroll up to crowd barriers
and greet the public in what has now become the common practice
called ``walkabout.''
</P>
<P>
   She moved gingerly through Friday's ceremonies, helping herself
along with two walking sticks, beaming her signature smile and
continually waving at the festive crowds.
</P>
<P>
   As at so many occasions involving British royalty, many of the
most enthusiastic celebrators Friday were Americans. One of them,
Connie Missinger, 47, a librarian from St. Louis, said: ``I came
here especially for the birthday. I came here last year and had
such a wonderful time that I thought I would love to come again.
She is a very special person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
