<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DOCTORS-LOANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RAW DEAL FOR DOCTORS IN POOR AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Aug. 5: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The federal program that pays doctors saddled with huge student
loans a bonus to practice in poor rural and urban areas needs a
major redesign or millions more dollars. What Congress should not
tolerate is a repeat of this year, when more than 90 percent of the
doctors who joined understaffed clinics were told in midyear,
without warning, that the program had run out of money and that
they would receive nothing beyond their meager salaries. The
administrative blunder threatens to undermine the worthy program by
driving away future applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Last year 771 doctors took new positions in underserved areas
and applied for a federal bonus of up to $50,000 to repay student
loans. The program awarded 469 bonuses to new applicants at a cost
of about $37 million. But this year the authorities changed the
rules and awarded bonuses to only 48 new applicants, less than 10
percent of the 715 new applicants. The decision traps hundreds of
doctors who would otherwise have received a bonus in lower-paying
jobs they cannot afford to keep. Many of these doctors rejected
higher-paying positions in the expectation, based on recent
experience, that the government would help them pay off their
loans.
</P>
<P>
   The administration did not crack down out of malice or
callousness. But neither was it adroit in handling the program's
financial problems. Without notice, the authorities shifted $7
million out of the bonus program into a program that provides
scholarships to medical students who agree to practice in medically
underserved areas after they graduate. The shift was made because
the administration had allowed spending on the scholarships to fall
below Congressionally mandated levels. Then the administration
decided to spend the shrunken pool of bonus money in a way that
gave priority to doctors who started work at approved clinics last
year rather than the doctors who started this year. These two
decisions explain the fall from 469 new bonuses last year to 48
this year.
</P>
<P>
   A program that rejects 93 percent of its applicants will not
draw many applicants in the future. Congress could address the
problem by spending an extra $7 million or more. The money would be
well spent because the approved clinics are woefully understaffed.
The administration also plans to switch its priority to new
applicants, making this year's losers permanent. But the
administration might also fix the core problem. It should be
possible for doctors to learn before they pick up and move to a
clinic whether they will in fact receive a bonus to repay their
loans. The certainty would not only make the program fairer to the
doctors, but also attract more high-quality applicants. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
