r s BC-BKL-SPARKS-PREVIEW-LA     08-04 0280
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT SPARKS IN PHOENIX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Sparks can win at least a share of the Western Conference
title today when they play Phoenix at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It would be the first for the Sparks, who already have set a
number of franchise records this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks (26-3) set a league record with 10 consecutive road
wins after holding off the Detroit Shock on Wednesday, narrowly
escaping with an 84-81 victory. L.A. has won 10 games in a row
overall, two short of their previous franchise high before a loss
to Portland last month.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks center Lisa Leslie, a leading candidate for league most
valuable player along with Houston's Sheryl Swoopes, had 27 points
against the Shock before fouling out with a minute to play. She is
leading the team with 17.8 points and 9.4 rebounds. Tamecka Dixon
had 17 points. The Sparks won despite being outrebounded 38-19.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks begin the playoffs on the road Friday and might again
play the Mercury (19-10), which is jostling with Sacramento for the
third and fourth Western Conference berths. The Sparks will host
the next two playoff games at the Forum on Aug. 13 and Aug. 15, if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury is coming off a hot shooting night. They set a
league record Thursday with a 63.6 percent field-goal effort in
their 85-63 victory over the Seattle Storm. Phoenix got balanced
scoring from Jennifer Gillom (14 points) and Brandy Reed (11
points).
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks have beaten the Mercury in the previous meetings
between the teams, 76-57 in Los Angeles and 74-68 in Phoenix. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
