<SLUG> BC-NY-PHILIPPINES-CHARITY-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO SOME SHE'S A GIVER, TO OTHERS A THIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fidela Caparas, 54, was driven to generosity. She was
the head bookkeeper for a Manhattan magazine publisher, and she
managed to wire millions to her native land, the Philippines, to
help hospitals, churches and others in need. But prosecutors say
she was most generous to herself, using phony paychecks to steal
over $10 million from her employer.
</P>
<P>
   Caparas worked 30 years for Harris Publications, a publisher of
magazines on hunting and weaponry. At some point, she began to
write herself a few company checks, a habit that escalated in
recent years, according to Manhattan prosecutors and Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Since she stopped collecting paychecks in April, when she was
fired, her luck has gone steadily downhill. She was indicted in May
for grand larceny, and she is being held on Rikers Island without
bail.
</P>
<P>
   And worse, while she is a beloved figure in her hometown of
Cavitenos, prosecutors contend that her generosity was simply a
quick way to dispose of ill-gotten gain.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a Manhattan judge refused to reconsider her bail
application, even though she surrendered her U.S. passport and
argued that despite a ``palatial home'' that prosecutors say she is
building in the Philippines, her ties are now here. She denies the
charges against her.
</P>
<P>
   Her bail was initially set at $750,000 after her arrest in May.
But the judge withdrew the bail offer after prosecutors said that
she had a Philippine passport that she had failed to mention, and
that she might have stolen $9 million more than they had originally
thought.
</P>
<P>
   Caparas' lawyer, Stephen Zissou, said that prosecutors had
grossly exaggerated the amount of money she gave away. He argued
that the court had been unfair in its refusal to release her on
bail, pointing out that she had been charged with a nonviolent
offense and had no prior criminal record. And as for the contention
that Caparas was a flight risk because she had ties to a foreign
country, he said, ``Like 180 million Americans do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hers was an immigrant success story. With only a college degree
in commerce from Far Eastern University in Manila, she made her way
to New Jersey, became a citizen and worked her way up in classic
fashion, her two sons attending college here.
</P>
<P>
   By 1970 she had joined Harris Publications. There she eventually
oversaw the payroll and expenses for all employees. She earned
$150,000 a year and was soon dabbling in philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be fair to say that she has engaged in substantial
philanthropic endeavors,'' said her lawyer, Zissou.
</P>
<P>
   But according to prosecutors, a preliminary audit found that she
had inserted her name on the payee line of more than 50 checks that
ranged from $15,000 to $75,000.
</P>
<P>
   She spent the money on cars, antiques and expensive homes in New
Jersey, California and Florida, as well as real estate in the
Philippines, prosecutors said. She also used it for an
entertainment and production company that she headed, they said.
</P>
<P>
   When her employer confronted her, she admitted to stealing
$800,000, prosecutors said. But the day after she was arrested,
they said, she diverted $120,000 from her bank account through wire
transfers to relatives in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI helped assess the damage to Harris, and the first
estimate that $800,000 had been stolen was soon revised.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Llambelis, an assistant district attorney in Manhattan,
told a judge that bank records that had been subpoenaed ``reveal
that the amount of theft is far, far greater than was previously
estimated.''
</P>
<P>
   The final tally came to over $10 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Harris executives could not be reached for comment, but
prosecutors said it was very unlikely that the company could
recover its money. Llambelis told a judge: ``She knows what she
stole. She knows where she's hidden it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 100 community members wrote letters to the judge, pleading
for leniency. Most cited Caparas' outstanding generosity.
</P>
<P>
   Her son Jeremy Jason Caparas wrote: ``One time, she even rented
out a whole church and hall on Christmas for the mentally disabled
home, bought all of them presents, and gave them a party with Santa
and made them feel loved. No matter the cost, she was there for
anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
