<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 23:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3211 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-MOTO-BRICKYARD400-HNS     08-04 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTO-BRICKYARD400-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three stand out in Winston race
</P>
<P>
   By TERRY BLOUNT
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ It is down to the stretch run now, which may be
the toughest 16 weeks in auto racing.
</P>
<P>
   The NASCAR Winston Cup drivers will race in 15 events across 14
states, from Loudon, N.H., to Miami, from Watkins Glen, N.Y., to
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   It is a grueling schedule that includes races on 12 consecutive
weekends, starting today with the prestigious and lucrative
Brickyard 400.
</P>
<P>
   Seven drivers are within 300 points of front-runner Bobby
Labonte, but realistically, it is a three-man battle for the 2000
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, seeking his first Winston Cup title, is trying to hold
off two veteran drivers who know what it takes to win a
championship _ Dale Jarrett and Dale Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett is the defending champion, and Earnhardt hopes to become
the first man to win eight titles. That would be enough to
intimidate any driver, but Labonte believes he is up to the
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of racing to do, but we're happy where we are,''
Labonte said. ``We've been leading the points for a long time, but
I have two fierce competitors right behind me. We just have to keep
plugging along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to think about the points situation. The only time I
really think about it is when people bring it up to me. We have
some races coming up that have been good for us, so we're looking
forward with confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte has won at five of the tracks remaining on the schedule,
including four last year _ Michigan, Dover, Talladega and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis is one of the places where he hasn't won, but
Labonte has been painfully close the last three years. He was
second in 1997 and 1999 and third in 1998 at the Brickyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had great runs here, but we just can't seem to break
through and win it,'' Labonte said. ``We ran up front with the
leaders, but when it came down to the late stages of the race, we
weren't the best car on the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could look at it two ways. I could be discouraged that we
haven't won and find things to blame it on, or I can be optimistic
that we've been very good here in the past. I choose to be
optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte is only 53 points ahead of Jarrett, who has moved up
four positions in the standings in the last seven races.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some problems early getting adjusted to the new
Goodyear tires,'' Jarrett said. ``But we gradually have started to
figure things out and have put ourselves in position to battle
Bobby and Dale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about our chances. We're not going to be
conservative. That's not the way to catch up. We've learned a lot,
but we are going to have to win a couple of races to get to the
top.''
</P>
<P>
   Indy would be a likely place to start, since Jarrett is a
two-time winner of the Brickyard 400. He also was third in 1995 and
'97 and was leading the race in 1998 when his crew miscalculated on
fuel, and he had to coast into the pits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a track where you need a lot of horsepower, and that's
why the Robert Yates teams have done well here,'' Jarrett said.
``But you have to be able to get through the corners to utilize
that horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always test here because we work very hard to get our cars
to go through the corners as fast as we can to use the two long
straightaways. That's the key to this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt knows that as well as anyone. He won the event in
1995, when he finished second to Jeff Gordon in the Winston Cup
championship. This is the closest Earnhardt has been to a title
since that season. He is only 107 points behind Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to keep chipping away at them,'' Earnhardt said.
``We have the team to race for it. I'm 49, but I'm healthier than
I've been in years. If someone tells you I'm just riding out my
time, they aren't paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett has been paying attention all season to Earnhardt's
resurgence in the No. 3 Goodwrench Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as feisty as ever,'' Jarrett said. ``Obviously, Dale has
a lot more experience at this stuff than Bobby or myself.''
</P>
<P>
   All three contenders will be starting close to the front today.
Jarrett will start fifth in the No. 88 Quality Care Ford, and
Earnhardt will start eighth _ directly behind his son, Dale
Earnhardt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough track, and you have to know your way around,''
the elder Earnhardt said. ``But (starting position) really doesn't
matter to me that much because I know I have a great race car.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte will start on the inside of row 2 in the No. 18
Interstate Batteries Pontiac, which he hopes is a sign of good
things to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best starting spot we've had here,'' Labonte said.
``Maybe that's an omen. Maybe luck is on our side this time.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
