A3293 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-LAZIO-SOFT-MONEY-N     08-04 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-SOFT-MONEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO SAYS IF MRS. CLINTON REFUSES SOFT MONEY, HE WOULD, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELVILLE, N.Y. _ With Sen. John McCain at his side, Rep. Rick
Lazio pledged on Friday that he would pick up the senator's
signature issue, campaign finance reform, and refuse the largely
unregulated campaign contributions known as soft money _ if Hillary
Rodham Clinton, his opponent, made the same pledge beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, the Republican Senate nominee, took particular issue with
soft money used by independent groups to finance attack advertising
against him, but found himself accused of hypocrisy by Democrats
because similar groups have sponsored advertising for him.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio called on Clinton to abolish four financial accounts that
he said had raised millions of dollars in soft money contributions.
Such contributions have been criticized because it is often
difficult to detect their sources and because they effectively
allow candidates to circumvent legal limits on contributions by
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign, which laid claim to only two such accounts,
immediately responded by noting that Clinton had extended a similar
pledge to Lazio months ago, but was rebuffed. She also accused
Lazio of hypocrisy by complaining of soft money while deriving
benefit from it through independent groups supporting his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money by law is not supposed to be used to advocate a
candidacy directly; the funds are to be used for such things as
party building and voter registration drives. But critics, notably
McCain, have criticized the limitations as so loosely interpreted
that organizations do manage to influence campaigns and promote
candidates. Congress recently passed legislation _ sponsored by
McCain and backed by Lazio _ requiring certain political
organizations employing soft money to disclose their donors.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he was loath to refuse the help of soft money
unilaterally because Clinton and her supporters have raised much
more of it than he could hope to. He said his campaign had not
directly accepted any such contributions but would not refuse them,
either, until Clinton made the pledge.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who joined Lazio at a hotel here for a fund-raiser for
Joan Johnson, a Republican candidate for Lazio's congressional seat
in Suffolk County, backed up the congressman's position. ``You
can't expect him to unilaterally disarm,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, Clinton's spokesman, said only two of the four
accounts Lazio named accept soft money in a joint fund-raising
account the campaign maintains with independent organizations. Of
the other two, one is an account under the control of the state
Democratic Party and not the campaign, and the other is a campaign
account that does not accept soft money contributions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson ridiculed Lazio for not disavowing independent groups
that have benefited his campaign with advertising. ``Just because
you don't have a joint account,'' Wolfson said, ``does not mean an
organization is not spending on your behalf.''
</P>
<P>
   De Blasio cited one group, the Republican Leadership Council,
which is running an advertisement featuring, against his wishes,
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who called it ``soft money fakery.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has said he had no control over the advertisement because
it was produced by an unrelated political group, but on Friday he
said he saw no contradiction in calling on Clinton to pull attack
advertising against him sponsored by a third party, the state
Democratic Party, using soft money. By law, neither candidate is
supposed to have involvement in the spending of such money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-04-00 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000804.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3305 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NY     08-04 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 2 SPOT FOR POSADA PAYS OFF FOR YANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The idea formed inside the timeworn skull of the
bench coach Don Zimmer as he and manager Joe Torre and the hitting
coach Chris Chambliss discussed the framework of the New York
Yankees' lineup Friday night. They determined that Derek Jeter
would lead off and, standing outside Torre's office, they were not
sure who would bat second.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer suggested Jorge Posada _ something the catcher had not
done since he was in Triple-A _ and they all nodded and smiled,
figuring that maybe the change would help him out of his slump.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer owns bragging rights now, for Posada had four hits and
four RBIs, inciting a couple of early rallies before driving in the
go-ahead run in the bottom of the seventh as the Yankees dumped the
Seattle Mariners, 13-6.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams hammered a three-run homer, leaving him one RBI
short of 100 for the season, and 31 shy of a switch-hitters' record
shared by Mickey Mantle.
</P>
<P>
   If the playoffs were to begin Saturday, the Yankees (59-45) and
the Mariners (62-46) would play in the first round. Posada would
probably not bat second. Chuck Knoblauch usually serves as the
lead-off hitter and Jeter bats second, but Knoblauch's sore right
elbow is not improving and Torre wants him to be able to throw
pain-free before he restores him as his regular second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   But Posada climbed high in the lineup _ so high, in fact, that
when he first glanced at the batting order posted in the Yankees'
clubhouse, he did not think he was playing at all. Posada looked at
the bottom half of the order, could not find his name in its usual
place and thought he had been benched.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually discovered his name almost at the top, however.
Other than a 4-for-4 outburst against Baltimore on July 28, Posada
had only two hits in his last 35 at-bats coming into Friday night's
game.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle scored three runs in the top of the first inning against
Andy Pettitte (12-6), but after Jeter flied out in the bottom of
the first, Posada pulled a double to left field.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill lined a single off the glove of third baseman
Carlos Guillen, Posada scampering to third when he saw the ball
roll. Bernie Williams was next, a big-time problem for Jamie Moyer,
Seattle's starting pitcher. Williams came into the game with 25
hits in 52 at-bats in his career against the left-hander, a .481
average.
</P>
<P>
   With a three-run lead, Moyer was obligated to throw strikes to
Williams, and when the count reached three balls and two strikes,
Williams drove one of those strikes into the left-field stands to
tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had two on and two out in the second inning, and
Posada dumped a single to score Tino Martinez; the Yankees led by a
run, and then two, after O'Neill doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Posada's working relationship with Pettitte has been imperfect,
with occasional disagreements over pitch selection, but never more
animated than in the fifth inning Friday night. After John Olerud
fouled off a ball in the fifth inning, with runners at second and
third and one out, Posada jogged to the mound to talk to Pettitte,
who subsequently shook off the next sign Posada flashed.
</P>
<P>
   After the inning ended, Posada moved toward Pettitte in front of
the dugout and raised both arms, as if to question him, and as
Pettitte pulled on his jacket, he appeared to snap back at the
catcher, jawing as he passed. Posada offered some retort. The
Mariners cut the lead to 5-4 in the third and tied the score at 5-5
in the seventh, when Olerud singled home Edgar Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Bellinger hit an easy roller to shortstop to open the
bottom of the seventh, but the Seattle shortstop Alex Rodriguez
fumbled the ball. One out later, Posada smashed a line drive to
left-center field, far out of the reach of Rickey Henderson, and
Bellinger got a good jump and scored easily, the Yankees moving
ahead, 6-5. The Yankees would add four more runs in the inning, the
last on Glenallen Hill's two-run homer off the reliever Jose Mesa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
