<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-04 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3308 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-GUERRERO-HNS &LR;      08-04 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GUERRERO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Guerrero has superstar credentials despite limited Exposure
</P>
<P>
   By SCOTT KAISER
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ After Vladimir Guerrero was signed by the Montreal
Expos in 1994, the 17-year-old was asked to fill out a routine
questionnaire. When reading the responses, the Expos should have
known they had a future superstar in their midst.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero wrote, among other things, that his winter occupation
was ``practicing baseball'' and his hobby was ``being a
ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Expos right fielder is a throwback to when players had
a passion for their profession. The 6-3, 205-pounder doesn't wear
batting gloves or jewelry, and he politely refuses most interview
requests. About the most you can get out of the shy Dominican
Republic native is his favorite quote: ``What I do is see the ball,
hit the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   When you ask others, one thing constantly mentioned about
Guerrero, 24, is he's a ``five-tool player.'' In other words, he
can hit, hit with power, run, field and throw, which makes him
arguably the best player in the game today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anybody with his kind of talent,'' Expos
manager Felipe Alou said. ``And not just the physical talent, but
also the mental toughness. He's dedicated to all-out hustle for
nine innings and is one of the best late-inning hitters I've ever
seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros manager Larry Dierker was asked to vote for the most
exciting player in the National League by a sports publication, and
he didn't have to think twice before naming Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays with a lot of enthusiasm and aggressiveness at the
plate, and I think he's going to be a superstar if he's not one
already,'' Dierker said. ``The scary thing is he's still young and
can get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering Friday's game against the Astros, Guerrero ranked
seventh or better in the National League in batting average (.351),
hits (130), total bases (245), triples (seven), RBIs (86),
intentional walks (17), slugging percentage (.662), on-base
percentage (.425) and multihit games (39). In addition, his 26 home
runs are ahead of last year's pace. He had 42 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   One team that didn't project those numbers is Los Angeles. The
Dodgers had Guerrero in camp for an extended tryout when he was 16,
but they decided against signing him. That surprised Astros
righthander Jose Lima, who pitched against the teen-ager in winter
ball in their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't the big stud that he is now, but I knew he was going
to be very good,'' Lima said. ``You know when a guy has the tools
to be a major-league player, and he's showing them now.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season Guerrero drove in 131 runs, had 84 extra-base hits,
a slugging percentage of .600, and a 31-game hitting streak. He is
the first player in major-league history to average .300, 40 home
runs and 120 RBIs over two seasons at the age of 23 or under.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a kid out there,'' Expos first baseman Lee Stevens
said. ``He has a great attitude every day, and every time you see
him he's smiling, but he plays hard. He's playing hurt right now
(with a hip flexor), and you don't see young kids with his talent
and potential who are willing to play hurt. Even the older players
around here can learn something from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his reputation among his peers and baseball personnel,
Guerrero isn't well known in the United States. One reason might be
his trouble speaking English, which limits his interview
opportunities. But Guerrero prefers to spend his pre-game time
playing video baseball games while listening to merengue music
through headphones than talking about himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to know about him because nobody does know
about him,'' Stevens said. ``He's up in Montreal, and the exposure
is not there, so people are intrigued about him because they're
always curious about the unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's quiet and not controversial, and he's not in the papers
every day saying something or doing something. He just quietly goes
about his business.''
</P>
<P>
   In the field, Guerrero sports a Dave Parker-like arm (seven
assists this season) and incredible range. But his prowess with the
bat earns Guerrero the most respect. If men are on base and
Guerrero is coming to the plate, a trip to the mound by the
opposing pitching coach or manager is likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a scouting report and try to come up with a plan
of how to pitch him, there really isn't one,'' Dierker said.
``There really isn't. You just say, `Throw it in and out and up and
down, and don't throw too many strikes, and hope he hits it to
somebody.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lima, who will face Guerrero in today's 7:05 p.m. game at Enron
Field, admits it's a waste of time trying to fool a player who has
power to all fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go out there and challenge him,'' Lima said. ``If
he hits you, he hits you, and if you get him out, you say, `Thank
you very much.' Like any big hitter, you're not allowed to make a
mistake, because he can hurt you. He swings at everything, so you
better be careful out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Guerrero is from Latin America, he is often compared to
former Pirates great Roberto Clemente. But Dierker says Guerrero
reminds him of another outstanding Expo, Andre Dawson.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those guys are great players, but physically he's more
like Dawson,'' Dierker said. ``Clemente was an aggressive hitter,
but I'm not sure he was as aggressive as Dawson or Guerrero. With
Dawson and Guerrero, you practically have to intentionally walk
them to walk them. Clemente did take at least a few walks.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point of his career, Guerrero's numbers are ahead of
those posted by Clemente, Dawson and Ken Griffey Jr. at a similar
stage in their careers. And they are close to Joe DiMaggio's.
Unless hit by a serious injury, a plaque in the Hall of Fame seems
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he can still get better and probably will,''
Stevens said. ``I don't know if the sky's the limit, but the
consistency's there already, and that's the important thing for a
guy who's only 24 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know how much higher his numbers will go, but you
know what you're going to get from him.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
