<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REALM OF MEDICARE IS KAFKAESQUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Just because Medicare's regulatory enforcers
say you're a crook doesn't mean that you're really a crook.
</P>
<P>
   This must be kept in mind when following the misfortunes of
members of the Kansas City health-care community whose lives and
careers are being devastated by questionable criminal prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   Unless these otherwise respectable citizens gain appellate
relief from their convictions, they face extensive prison time for
alleged crimes that many familiar with health-care business
relationships would contend aren't crimes at all.
</P>
<P>
   The charges essentially involve payments that prosecutors say
were bribes made to doctors by hospital executives in return for
referrals of Medicare patients. In a business in which referrals
are a cornerstone of relationships, those in the industry might say
what happened was merely business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this case remarkable, though, was how it brings to
light the Kafkaesque world created by byzantine Medicare
regulations, which are estimated to be more voluminous and complex
than the Internal Revenue Code.
</P>
<P>
   Only the defendants, of course, know in their heart of hearts
whether they set out to cut legal corners. Given the world in which
they operate, however, they deserve the benefit of the doubt.
Moreover, media coverage of the case certainly raises honest
questions about its merits.
</P>
<P>
   Uwe E. Reinhardt, a Princeton University political economist and
prominent expert on health-care economics, says the critical
problem isn't so much criminality or malfeasance as it is Medicare
regulations having become too complicated to understand.
</P>
<P>
   The necessary compromise, he explained in a recent analysis in
The Wall Street Journal, falls between two extremes: ``rules so
crude as to tolerate widespread abuse, and rules so finely honed as
to become impenetrable.''
</P>
<P>
   It can be argued that Medicare's system has gone too far in
evolving the impenetrable. As a result anyone can be transformed
into a crook because it's impossible to obey all the laws with
precision. Reinhardt noted that health-industry audit committees
often spend more time on compliance with ``ever-burgeoning Medicare
rules than on their own financial reports.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the way totalitarian regimes operate. Create enough laws
and it means everyone is always in violation of some law, which is
the source of all autocratic and authoritarian power.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the medical profession itself frowns on commission
payments to referring physicians as a matter of ethics, there is no
doubt that professional relationships over time produce positive
economic outcomes for those involved. Medicare makes out-and-out
kickbacks illegal, which leaves the door open to liberal
interpretation of what constitutes referral arrangements that may
violate the law.
</P>
<P>
   An important aspect of one defendant's appeal, in fact, has
turned on conflicting judicial interpretations of an arcane rule.
If the defendant loses his freedom, it probably will result more
from a subjective judgment than commission of an act most
reasonable minds would agree is criminal.
</P>
<P>
   For a society in which consistent application of the rule of law
is supposed to protect basic rights, this is an unsettling thing to
contemplate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
