<HEADER>
A3310 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-SIMPSON-WMGROW     08-04 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-SIMPSON-WMGROWTH-ART-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Attn:   Wash., Ore., Idaho, Mont.   and Alaska. ) 
(ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, August. 6)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like other people who live in Seattle, David W. Simpson is never
too far from Mount Rainier, the highest peak in the Northwest. But
he is often closer than most. On weekends and during vacations,
Simpson leads climbers over the Mount Rainier's glaciers and rocks;
on weekdays, he drives past the mountain on his way to work
managing the $721.1 million WM Growth Fund of the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   The mountain is also the polestar of the portfolio, whose
prospectus requires it to be at least 65 percent invested in
companies with headquarters in Washington, Oregon, Idaho, Montana
and Alaska. The remainder must be in companies doing business in
that region. The geographic area may be small, but it has been
fertile territory for investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're quite diversified in terms of industries, and we've
become something of a hotbed of technology,'' Simpson said from his
office overlooking Puget Sound. ``Many executives leave Microsoft
with enormous amounts of wealth that they use to finance new
businesses, seeding the region with start-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund returned 26.8 percent a year, on average, for the three
years through Thursday, versus 7.4 percent for its peers among
small blend funds, according to Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson, 41, can pluck almost any of the roughly 300 public
companies in those five states. He can find long-term capital
growth in start-ups or choose behemoths like Starbucks, Microsoft
and Nike. Small fry make up 60 percent of the portfolio; the
balance is split between midsize and large-cap companies.
</P>
<P>
   His style could be called eclectic. The fund may hold basic
materials companies in forestry and steel as well as red-hot
technology concerns. Unprofitable biotech businesses rub shoulders
with value plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a perception that regional funds are dependent on the
local economy,'' he said. ``But that's not true. What drives the
companies we buy are national and global markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson works with three equity analysts to pick the fund's 70
or so holdings. He aims to keep shares at least three to five
years; the turnover rate is 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   He does not use computer screens to scout out purchases. ``I
keep a hit list of new companies that I look at every day,'' he
said, ``and I pay attention to the local news and investment
analysts.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, he wants companies to have relatively low debt
and adequate working capital. Although working-capital needs vary
by industry, as a rule of thumb he wants companies with current
assets that exceed current liabilities, and the bigger the margin,
the better. He also checks a company's ``quick ratio,'' which
compares cash and accounts receivable to current liabilities;
again, bigger is better.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, he wants a company to have a price-to-earnings
multiple that is lower than its growth rate, although he will pay
more for technology companies and less for consumer cyclicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to identify a competitive advantage and make sure that
it is protected,'' he said. That advantage may be a brand name
(Starbucks), a technology (Intel or Microsoft) or domination of a
small market niche (Electro Scientific Industries).
</P>
<P>
   Solid management is vital. For big companies, he relies on Wall
Street research to evaluate management's record. ``I'm more active
talking to management of smaller companies,'' he said, ``because we
can gather information that's not well understood on the Street.''
</P>
<P>
   What does he look for? ``I like them to be able to articulate
business strategy in a sensible way,'' he said. ``And I prefer
management that can answer my detailed questions on the spot,
because it means they have their finger on the pulse of the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson recently added shares of Paccar Inc., a Bellevue, Wash.,
company that sells heavy-duty trucks. ``The stock was very
inexpensive, because an industry downturn is under way
domestically,'' he said. ``But the company is more global than
perceived.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has some debt but low fixed costs because it
assembles trucks from components rather than manufacturing them
from scratch, he added. That has helped earnings during the
downturn.
</P>
<P>
   He first bought shares in 1991 at $16.96 and recently added more
in the low 40s. They closed on Friday at $41.9375, or almost seven
times Wall Street's earnings estimate of $6.27 a share for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The fund also expanded its position in Monaco Coach, a
manufacturer of recreational vehicles in Coburg, Ore. ``We're
playing into a strong demographic trend,'' he said. ``Young
retirees love these things, and the market should be very strong as
baby boomers reach retirement age.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock price is down because of rising interest
rates and fuel prices, he said, but the company is debt-free and
management is adjusting production. He started buying in July 1999
and has paid an average of $12.94. The stock now trades at
$15.8125, or more than six times the consensus 2000 earnings
estimate of $2.48 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite is the Corixa Corp., which he bought at the
initial offering in 1997 at $13 a share. It closed on Friday at
$38.875. Corixa, a biotechnology company in Seattle, is developing
vaccines for cancer and autoimmune diseases. Its chairman and chief
executive, Steven Gillis, was co-founder of Immunex, another
biotechnology company in Seattle. Simpson said he had ``confidence
in his grasp of the business and science of managing a biotech
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Canadian regulators recently approved the company's melanoma
vaccine, and approval by the Food and Drug Administration is
expected by year-end, he said. Wall Street's consensus estimate is
that the company will lose $1.62 a share this year. Nevertheless,
Simpson is optimistic about the long-term prospects.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
